/* Per-state, per-year descriptions for the Atlas globe click popup (middle "year" column).
   window.COUNTRY_YEARS[lowercased state name][year] = a 2-3 sentence, fact-checked description of that state in that map-year.
   Generated + independently fact-checked; unverifiable entries were omitted (popup shows a dash). Load before app.js. */
window.COUNTRY_YEARS = {
  "accra": {"1900":"Accra was a coastal town on the Gold Coast that served as the capital of the British Gold Coast colony, having become so in 1877. By 1900 it was firmly under British colonial administration as the seat of government on the West African coast."},
  "afghanistan": {"1900":"Afghanistan was a monarchy ruled by Amir Abdur Rahman Khan, known as the \"Iron Amir,\" who had consolidated central authority through harsh campaigns since 1880. Its foreign relations were controlled by Britain under earlier agreements, making it effectively a buffer state between British India and the Russian Empire, though it remained internally sovereign.","1920":"Afghanistan was an independent kingdom ruled by Emir Amanullah Khan, who had come to power in 1919. Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War of 1919, Britain recognized Afghanistan's full control over its foreign affairs, and Amanullah pursued ties with Soviet Russia and other powers while beginning ambitious modernizing reforms.","1938":"Afghanistan was an independent kingdom ruled by Mohammed Zahir Shah, who had taken the throne in 1933 after the assassination of his father Nadir Shah. The country pursued a policy of cautious modernization and neutrality, with much real power held by the king's uncles. It maintained its independence between the British and Soviet spheres.","1960":"Afghanistan in 1960 was an independent kingdom ruled by King Mohammed Zahir Shah, with his cousin Mohammed Daoud Khan serving as prime minister. Daoud pursued modernization and accepted substantial Soviet economic and military aid while maintaining a policy of nonalignment, and tensions with Pakistan over the Pashtunistan question were acute around this time.","1994":"In 1994 Afghanistan was engulfed in civil war following the 1992 fall of the Soviet-backed Najibullah government, with rival mujahideen factions fighting for control of Kabul. Burhanuddin Rabbani held the contested presidency while forces loyal to Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and others shelled the capital. The Taliban movement emerged in the south around Kandahar in late 1994, beginning their rise to power.","2000":"In 2000 most of Afghanistan was controlled by the Taliban, whose Islamic Emirate held the capital Kabul and was recognized by only Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE. The opposition Northern Alliance under Ahmad Shah Massoud held territory in the northeast. The country was under UN sanctions, and Osama bin Laden and al-Qaeda were sheltering there.","2010":"In 2010 Afghanistan was an Islamic republic led by President Hamid Karzai, governing amid an intensifying insurgency by the Taliban. NATO's US-led International Security Assistance Force conducted a major troop surge that year, including the large Operation Moshtarak offensive in Helmand Province's Marjah area. The country remained one of the world's poorest and most conflict-affected states, with weak central authority outside major cities."},
  "akrotiri": {"2026":"Akrotiri, together with Dhekelia, is a Sovereign Base Area retained by the United Kingdom on the island of Cyprus since Cypriot independence in 1960, used as a British military installation. It remains under UK sovereignty and administration in 2026."},
  "albania": {"1920":"Albania in 1920 reasserted its independence at the Congress of Lushnjë, establishing a national government and capital at Tirana, after the country had been occupied and partly partitioned by foreign powers during and after World War I. Italian forces were pressured to withdraw following Albanian resistance in the Vlora War, and Albania was admitted to the League of Nations in December 1920, confirming international recognition of its sovereignty.","1938":"Albania was a kingdom under Zog I, who had proclaimed himself king in 1928. By 1938 the country had fallen heavily under Italian economic and political influence, with Mussolini's regime steadily increasing its dominance; Italy would invade and annex Albania in April 1939. In 1938 King Zog married Geraldine Apponyi.","1960":"Albania in 1960 was a one-party communist state led by Enver Hoxha's Party of Labour. During this period Albania was aligning itself with the People's Republic of China amid the deepening Sino-Soviet split, a realignment that culminated in its break with the Soviet Union.","1994":"In 1994 Albania was a republic under President Sali Berisha and his Democratic Party, having emerged from decades of isolated communist rule that ended in 1991-1992. The country was undergoing a difficult transition to a market economy amid widespread poverty.","2000":"In 2000 Albania was a parliamentary republic still recovering from the 1997 collapse of pyramid investment schemes and the ensuing unrest. It had absorbed large numbers of ethnic Albanian refugees from neighboring Kosovo during the 1999 war. The Socialist Party led the government.","2010":"Albania in 2010 was a parliamentary republic with a center-right government led by Prime Minister Sali Berisha of the Democratic Party. The country was a NATO member, having joined the alliance in April 2009, and was pursuing European Union membership. Domestic politics were marked by a tense standoff with the opposition Socialist Party over disputed 2009 election results.","2026":"Albania is a parliamentary republic and an EU candidate country that opened accession negotiations in 2024, with Edi Rama serving as prime minister after his Socialist Party won re-election. It is a NATO member and continues its push toward European Union membership through 2026. Tirana is the capital."},
  "algeria": {"1900":"Algeria in 1900 was a French possession governed as an integral part of France, organized into departments and administered by a governor-general rather than as a typical colony. A large settler population of European colons held political and economic dominance over the Muslim majority, who had limited rights under the indigénat legal regime.","1920":"Algeria in 1920 was a French possession, administered as an integral part of France through départements rather than as a separate colony, with a substantial European settler population. Muslim Algerians remained largely without full political rights, and the territory was governed under French rule from Algiers.","1960":"In 1960 Algeria was still legally part of France, governed as French departments, while the Algerian War of Independence raged between French forces and the FLN. That year saw the Week of Barricades in Algiers by European settlers opposed to any negotiated independence, as Charles de Gaulle moved toward self-determination.","1994":"In 1994 Algeria was in the midst of a civil war between the military-backed government and Islamist insurgents, sparked by the army's 1992 cancellation of elections the Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. Liamine Zeroual became head of state in early 1994 as violence by groups including the Armed Islamic Group escalated.","2000":"In 2000 Algeria was a republic recovering from the violent civil war of the 1990s between the government and Islamist insurgents. Abdelaziz Bouteflika had become president in 1999 and promoted a Civil Concord amnesty law aimed at ending the conflict, though violence continued at a reduced level.","2010":"Algeria in 2010 was a republic governed by President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, who had won a third term in 2009. The country's economy was heavily dependent on oil and natural gas exports. A state of emergency, in place since 1992 following the civil war with Islamist groups, remained in effect through 2010.","2026":"Algeria is a presidential republic led by Abdelmadjid Tebboune, who won a second term in the September 2024 election. As a major oil and gas exporter, it remained an important energy supplier amid shifting European demand, while relations with neighboring Morocco stayed tense. Algiers is the capital."},
  "algeria (france)": {"1938":"Algeria was governed as an integral part of France, administered as French departments rather than a colony, with a large European settler population alongside the Muslim majority. The settlers held political privileges while most Muslims lacked full citizenship rights. It was directly tied to metropolitan France's administration."},
  "american samoa": {"1900":"The eastern Samoan islands were partitioned to the United States under the Tripartite Convention of 1899, which divided Samoa between the U.S. and Germany. In 1900 local chiefs ceded Tutuila and adjacent islands to the United States, which administered the territory through the U.S. Navy.","1920":"American Samoa was an unincorporated territory of the United States, administered by the U.S. Navy with a naval governor based at Pago Pago. In 1920 it remained under naval administration, and local discontent with this rule was building toward the Mau movement of the following years.","1938":"American Samoa was an unincorporated territory of the United States, administered by the U.S. Navy from the naval station at Pago Pago. Local affairs continued under traditional Samoan chiefly structures overseen by naval governors.","1960":"American Samoa in 1960 was an unincorporated territory of the United States, administered by the Department of the Interior. A constitution for the territory was being developed around this period, with its first constitution taking effect in the early 1960s.","1994":"In 1994 American Samoa was an unincorporated territory of the United States in the South Pacific, with a locally elected governor and legislature. Its residents were U.S. nationals.","2000":"In 2000 American Samoa was an unincorporated, unorganized territory of the United States in the South Pacific, with its capital at Pago Pago. Its residents were U.S. nationals, and it had a locally elected governor and legislature plus a non-voting delegate to the U.S. House of Representatives.","2010":"American Samoa in 2010 was an unincorporated, unorganized territory of the United States in the South Pacific. It was recovering from a major earthquake and tsunami that had struck in September 2009, killing dozens and causing extensive damage. Its economy relied heavily on tuna canning and U.S. government support.","2026":"American Samoa is an unincorporated territory of the United States in the South Pacific, whose people are U.S. nationals rather than full citizens by birth. It is governed by a locally elected governor and legislature, with Pago Pago as its center of administration."},
  "andorra": {"1938":"Andorra was a small co-principality in the Pyrenees under the joint suzerainty of the President of France and the Bishop of Urgell in Spain. During the late 1930s it was affected by the turmoil of the neighboring Spanish Civil War along its southern border.","1960":"Andorra in 1960 was a co-principality under the joint suzerainty of the President of France and the Spanish Bishop of Urgell. It remained a small, largely rural country without full sovereignty in the modern sense, with its traditional institutions intact.","1994":"In 1994 Andorra was a co-principality in the Pyrenees, having adopted its first written constitution in 1993 that made it a parliamentary democracy. The French president and the Bishop of Urgell remained nominal co-princes, and the country joined the United Nations in 1993.","2000":"In 2000 Andorra was a small landlocked parliamentary co-principality in the Pyrenees, with the President of France and the Bishop of Urgell as its two co-princes. It had adopted a constitution in 1993 and was a member of the United Nations.","2010":"Andorra in 2010 was a small landlocked parliamentary co-principality in the Pyrenees, headed jointly by the President of France and the Bishop of Urgell as co-princes. Its economy depended largely on tourism, retail, and banking. It was not a member of the European Union but used the euro as its currency.","2026":"Andorra is a small landlocked principality in the Pyrenees governed as a parliamentary co-principality, with the President of France and the Bishop of Urgell serving jointly as heads of state. Its economy relies on tourism, retail, and banking, and it uses the euro despite not being an EU member. Andorra la Vella is the capital."},
  "angola": {"1900":"Angola was a Portuguese colony in southwestern Africa, though in 1900 effective Portuguese control was largely confined to coastal areas and the territory's interior boundaries were still being established. Portugal pursued military campaigns to extend administration inland during this period.","1920":"Angola in 1920 was a Portuguese colony in southwestern Africa governed from Luanda. Portugal was working to consolidate effective control over the interior through military campaigns and a forced-labor colonial economy, having only relatively recently subdued much of the territory.","1960":"In 1960 Angola was an overseas province of Portugal, governed as part of the Portuguese colonial empire under the Estado Novo regime. Nationalist sentiment was rising, and armed struggle for independence broke out the following year in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Angola remained gripped by civil war between the MPLA government and Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels after fighting resumed following the 1992 elections. The Lusaka Protocol, a peace agreement, was signed in November 1994 in an attempt to end the conflict.","2000":"In 2000 Angola was a republic still embroiled in its long civil war between the ruling MPLA government under José Eduardo dos Santos and Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels. The conflict, funded partly by oil and diamonds, continued until Savimbi's death in 2002.","2010":"Angola in 2010 was a republic led by President José Eduardo dos Santos, who had held power since 1979. The country was rebuilding after its long civil war ended in 2002, fueled by substantial oil revenues that made it one of Africa's largest petroleum producers. A new constitution adopted in 2010 abolished direct presidential elections, strengthening dos Santos's hold on power.","2026":"Angola is a presidential republic led by João Lourenço of the long-ruling MPLA, which has held power since independence in 1975. Its economy depends heavily on oil exports, and the country has worked to diversify and attract investment. Luanda is the capital."},
  "angola (portugal)": {"1938":"Angola was a Portuguese overseas colony in southwestern Africa, governed under the authoritarian Estado Novo regime of António de Oliveira Salazar. Portuguese administration emphasized economic exploitation and forced labor systems across the territory."},
  "anguilla": {"1800":"In 1800, Anguilla was a small British colony in the Leeward Islands, first settled by English planters from St Kitts in 1650. In 1800, it was governed locally by a council of freeholders while nominal oversight came through Antigua, decades before the unpopular 1825 union that placed it under St Kitts. In 1800, its economy rested on struggling sugar, cotton and provision estates worked by enslaved Africans, hampered by thin soil, low rainfall and frequent drought. In 1800, enslaved people vastly outnumbered the free population, as reflected in the 1819 count of 360 Europeans, 320 free people of colour and 2,451 slaves. In 1800, the scattered settlements around The Valley formed the island's administrative and social centre, the plantation-era Wallblake House of 1787 standing among its earliest surviving structures.","1900":"Anguilla was a small British Caribbean possession, administered as part of the British Leeward Islands colony along with Saint Kitts. It remained a minor, sparsely populated British territory in 1900.","1920":"Anguilla in 1920 was a small British Caribbean possession, administered as part of the colony of St Kitts (Saint Christopher) and Nevis within the British Leeward Islands. It was a poor, sparsely populated island with an economy based on salt, fishing, and subsistence farming.","1938":"Anguilla was a British possession in the Caribbean, administered as part of the colony of Saint Kitts-Nevis-Anguilla within the British West Indies.","1960":"In 1960 Anguilla was a British colonial possession administered as part of the colony of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla in the West Indies. It remained under British rule, with its later separatist revolt against association with Saint Kitts coming toward the end of the decade.","1994":"In 1994 Anguilla was a British dependent territory in the Caribbean, internally self-governing with a governor appointed by the British Crown.","2000":"In 2000 Anguilla was a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, with internal self-government under a governor appointed by the United Kingdom. Its economy relied on tourism and offshore finance.","2010":"Anguilla in 2010 was a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, internally self-governing under a governor appointed by the United Kingdom. Its economy depended largely on tourism and offshore financial services, both affected by the global economic downturn.","2026":"Anguilla is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, internally self-governing with a locally elected government while the United Kingdom retains responsibility for defense and foreign affairs. Its economy is based on tourism and offshore finance, with The Valley as its capital."},
  "annam": {"1920":"Annam in 1920 was a protectorate of France in central Vietnam, part of French Indochina, where the Nguyễn emperor at Huế reigned under close French oversight with real power held by the colonial administration. The emperor at this time was Khải Định, who ruled as a figurehead under the French résident supérieur."},
  "antarctica": {"1960":"Antarctica in 1960 was an uninhabited continent governed by no single state, with several countries maintaining overlapping territorial claims and research stations. The Antarctic Treaty had been signed in December 1959 to reserve the continent for peaceful scientific use, though it entered into force in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Antarctica had no sovereign government and was administered under the Antarctic Treaty System, which reserved the continent for peaceful and scientific use. Various nations maintained research stations and overlapping territorial claims that the treaty held in abeyance.","2000":"In 2000 Antarctica had no government or permanent population and was governed internationally under the Antarctic Treaty System, which reserved the continent for peaceful and scientific use and held territorial claims in abeyance. Numerous countries operated research stations there.","2010":"Antarctica in 2010 was not a sovereign state but a continent governed under the Antarctic Treaty System, which set it aside for peaceful and scientific purposes and held territorial claims in abeyance. Numerous countries operated research stations there, and no permanent population existed beyond rotating scientific personnel.","2026":"Antarctica is not a sovereign state but a continent governed by the Antarctic Treaty System, which reserves it for peaceful and scientific use and suspends territorial claims. In 2026 it has no permanent population, hosting only rotating research station personnel from many nations."},
  "antigua and barb.": {"1960":"In 1960 Antigua and Barbuda was a British colony in the Leeward Islands of the West Indies. It remained under British administration, later becoming an associated state in 1967 before full independence in 1981.","1994":"In 1994 Antigua and Barbuda was an independent constitutional monarchy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. The Bird family's Antigua Labour Party dominated politics, with Lester Bird becoming prime minister in 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Antigua and Barbuda was an independent Commonwealth realm in the Caribbean with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, governed as a parliamentary democracy. Lester Bird of the Antigua Labour Party served as prime minister, and the economy depended heavily on tourism.","2010":"Antigua and Barbuda in 2010 was an independent constitutional monarchy and Commonwealth realm in the Caribbean, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Its government was led by Prime Minister Baldwin Spencer of the United Progressive Party. The tourism-dependent economy was strained by the global financial crisis and the collapse of Allen Stanford's financial empire, a major local employer.","2026":"Antigua and Barbuda is an independent Commonwealth realm in the Caribbean with King Charles III as head of state, represented by a governor-general, and Gaston Browne as prime minister. Its economy relies heavily on tourism. Saint John's is the capital."},
  "antigua and barbuda": {"1900":"Antigua and Barbuda were British colonial islands in the eastern Caribbean, administered within the Federal Colony of the Leeward Islands. Antigua served as the seat of the Leeward Islands government in 1900.","1920":"Antigua and Barbuda in 1920 were British colonial islands administered within the British Leeward Islands. The economy rested heavily on sugar production, and the islands were governed under Crown colony administration.","1938":"Antigua and Barbuda were British colonial possessions in the Leeward Islands of the Caribbean, administered as part of the British Leeward Islands. The economy remained centered on sugar production."},
  "argentina": {"1900":"Argentina in 1900 was a sovereign republic under a constitutional government, with Julio Argentino Roca serving his second presidential term. The country was experiencing rapid economic growth driven by agricultural exports and large-scale European immigration, particularly to Buenos Aires.","1920":"Argentina in 1920 was an independent republic governed under the presidency of Hipólito Yrigoyen of the Radical Civic Union, who had been elected in 1916. The period was marked by labor unrest, including the aftermath of the 1919 Semana Trágica, amid a generally prosperous export economy based on beef and grain.","1938":"Argentina was a republic that in 1938 saw Roberto Ortiz take office as president, having won an election widely regarded as fraudulent during the period known as the Infamous Decade. The country was a major agricultural exporter with close economic ties to Britain, and conservative governments dominated through electoral manipulation.","1960":"Argentina in 1960 was a republic governed by President Arturo Frondizi, who had taken office in 1958. His administration pursued developmentalist economic policies and foreign investment, while operating under the constraints of a proscribed Peronist movement and a watchful military.","1994":"In 1994 Argentina was a federal republic under President Carlos Menem, whose Peronist government pursued free-market reforms and a currency pegged to the U.S. dollar. A new constitution was adopted in 1994 permitting presidential re-election, and in July a bombing of the AMIA Jewish community center in Buenos Aires killed dozens.","2000":"In 2000 Argentina was a federal republic governed by President Fernando de la Rúa, who had taken office in December 1999. The country was deep in recession with high debt and unemployment, foreshadowing the severe economic and political crisis of 2001.","2010":"Argentina in 2010 was a federal republic led by President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner. That year the country celebrated its bicentennial of the May Revolution of 1810, and it became the first Latin American nation to legalize same-sex marriage nationwide. The former president and her husband Néstor Kirchner died suddenly in October 2010.","2026":"Argentina is a federal presidential republic led by libertarian president Javier Milei, who took office in December 2023 and pursued sweeping austerity, deregulation, and spending cuts to combat very high inflation. By 2026 inflation had fallen sharply from its peak while the economy remained under strain. Buenos Aires is the capital."},
  "armenia": {"1920":"Armenia in 1920 was the independent First Republic of Armenia, but it faced catastrophe during the year: defeat in the Turkish–Armenian War of late 1920 and Soviet pressure led to the collapse of the independent republic and its Sovietization in early December 1920. By the end of the year it was becoming a Soviet republic.","1938":"Armenia in 1938 was the Armenian Soviet Socialist Republic, a constituent republic of the Soviet Union. It was subject to Stalin's Great Purge, which struck its Communist Party and intelligentsia during this period.","1994":"In 1994 Armenia was an independent republic that had emerged from the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, led by President Levon Ter-Petrosyan. A Russian-brokered ceasefire in May 1994 halted the war with Azerbaijan over Nagorno-Karabakh, leaving Armenian forces in control of the enclave and surrounding territory.","2000":"In 2000 Armenia was an independent republic in the South Caucasus, led by President Robert Kocharyan. It remained in an unresolved conflict with Azerbaijan over Nagorno-Karabakh, and its economy was still recovering from the post-Soviet collapse and a blockade by Azerbaijan and Turkey.","2010":"Armenia in 2010 was a republic in the South Caucasus led by President Serzh Sargsyan. The unresolved Nagorno-Karabakh conflict with neighboring Azerbaijan kept its border with that country and with Turkey closed. A 2009 effort to normalize relations with Turkey through signed protocols stalled and was effectively suspended in 2010.","2026":"Armenia is a parliamentary republic led by Prime Minister Nikol Pashinyan, navigating the aftermath of Azerbaijan's September 2023 takeover of Nagorno-Karabakh, which ended the breakaway Armenian-populated enclave and displaced its population. In 2026 Armenia continued pursuing closer ties with the West and the European Union while distancing itself from Russia. Yerevan is the capital."},
  "aruba": {"1960":"In 1960 Aruba was part of the Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It did not yet have the separate status it gained in 1986, remaining administered from Curaçao within the federation.","1994":"In 1994 Aruba was an autonomous constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, having gained separate status from the Netherlands Antilles in 1986. A planned move toward full independence was halted, and Aruba remained part of the Kingdom.","2000":"In 2000 Aruba was an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, having gained separate status from the Netherlands Antilles in 1986. It had internal self-government, with the Dutch crown responsible for defense and foreign affairs, and a tourism-based economy.","2010":"Aruba in 2010 was a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, having held that autonomous status separately since 1986. Its economy was heavily based on tourism. In 2010 the dissolution of the Netherlands Antilles took effect, but Aruba's own status as a separate kingdom country was unchanged.","2026":"Aruba is a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, self-governing in internal affairs while the Kingdom handles defense and foreign policy. Its economy is heavily dependent on tourism, and it uses the Aruban florin. Oranjestad is the capital."},
  "asante": {"1900":"The Asante (Ashanti) kingdom in the interior of the Gold Coast was in the process of being conquered by Britain; following the 1896 deposition and exile of Asantehene Prempeh I, the British declared a protectorate. In 1900 the War of the Golden Stool broke out after a British demand for the Golden Stool provoked a major Asante uprising, after which Britain formally annexed Ashanti in 1901."},
  "ashmore and cartier is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Ashmore and Cartier Islands were uninhabited external territories of Australia in the Indian Ocean. They were administered by Australia and carried no permanent population.","1994":"In 1994 the Ashmore and Cartier Islands were an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the Indian Ocean, administered from Canberra.","2000":"In 2000 the Ashmore and Cartier Islands were an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the Indian Ocean, administered from Canberra. They had no permanent population and were managed as a nature reserve.","2010":"Ashmore and Cartier Islands in 2010 were an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the Indian Ocean, off the northwest coast. Administered as a nature reserve, they had no permanent population.","2026":"Ashmore and Cartier Islands is an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the Indian Ocean, administered by the Australian government and managed largely as a nature reserve. It has no permanent population in 2026."},
  "australia": {"1920":"Australia in 1920 was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire, the Commonwealth of Australia, with Billy Hughes serving as prime minister. Having contributed heavily to the Allied war effort, Australia gained League of Nations mandates over former German territories such as New Guinea and was dealing with postwar demobilization and economic adjustment.","1938":"Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire, with Joseph Lyons of the United Australia Party serving as prime minister. The country was emerging from the Depression and growing increasingly concerned about Japanese expansion in the Pacific.","1960":"Australia in 1960 was an independent federal dominion within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as monarch and Robert Menzies as prime minister leading a Liberal-Country coalition. The country maintained the White Australia immigration policy and close defense ties with Britain and the United States during the Cold War.","1994":"In 1994 Australia was a federal parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, governed by Prime Minister Paul Keating's Labor Party. Debate over becoming a republic was prominent during this period under Keating's government.","2000":"In 2000 Australia was a federal parliamentary constitutional monarchy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, governed by Prime Minister John Howard of the Liberal Party. A 1999 referendum to become a republic had failed, and Sydney hosted the Summer Olympic Games in September 2000.","2010":"Australia in 2010 was a federal parliamentary constitutional monarchy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. In June 2010 Julia Gillard replaced Kevin Rudd as Labor leader and became the country's first female prime minister, and the August federal election produced a hung parliament that she retained government through with the support of independents and the Greens. The economy had weathered the global financial crisis comparatively well, aided by demand for its mineral exports.","2026":"Australia is a federal parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Charles III as head of state and a governor-general as his representative. Anthony Albanese's Labor government, re-elected in the May 2025 federal election, holds power in Canberra. The country continues to navigate economic ties with China alongside security commitments including the AUKUS partnership with the United States and United Kingdom."},
  "austria": {"1920":"Austria in 1920 was the newly created Republic of Austria, a small landlocked state left after the dissolution of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, with its capital at Vienna. In 1920 it adopted a new federal constitution, while the country faced severe economic hardship and the Treaty of Saint-Germain barred union with Germany.","1960":"Austria in 1960 was a sovereign federal republic, having regained full independence with the 1955 State Treaty that ended four-power occupation. It was a permanently neutral state under a constitutional commitment to neutrality, governed by a grand coalition of the People's Party and the Social Democrats.","1994":"In 1994 Austria was a neutral federal parliamentary republic led by a coalition government, with Thomas Klestil as president and Franz Vranitzky of the Social Democrats as chancellor. In a June 1994 referendum Austrians voted roughly two-thirds in favor of joining the European Union, paving the way for its accession on 1 January 1995.","2000":"Austria was a federal parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union, which it had joined in 1995. In early 2000 a coalition government formed between the conservative Austrian People's Party and Jörg Haider's far-right Freedom Party, prompting the other 14 EU member states to impose diplomatic sanctions in protest. Thomas Klestil was the federal president and Wolfgang Schüssel became chancellor.","2010":"In 2010 Austria was a federal parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and the eurozone, with Vienna as its capital. The country was governed by a grand coalition of the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), with Werner Faymann as Chancellor and Heinz Fischer as the popularly re-elected Federal President. A neutral state, it was a prosperous, highly developed economy still managing the aftermath of the 2008 global financial crisis.","2026":"Austria is a federal parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union, using the euro and maintaining its constitutional neutrality. Following the September 2024 elections, a coalition government led by Chancellor Christian Stocker of the Austrian People's Party took office in early 2025 after talks involving the far-right Freedom Party, which had won the most votes, failed to produce a government."},
  "austria hungary": {"1900":"Austria-Hungary was a dual monarchy ruled by Emperor-King Franz Joseph I, uniting the Austrian and Hungarian halves under a common monarch, foreign policy, and military while each retained its own parliament and government. In 1900 it was a major European power and one of the continent's largest states, but was increasingly strained by nationalist tensions among its many ethnic groups."},
  "azerbaijan": {"1920":"Azerbaijan began 1920 as the independent Azerbaijan Democratic Republic but was invaded by the Soviet Red Army in April 1920, ending its independence. By the end of the year it had been established as the Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic under Bolshevik control, centered on Baku and its oil fields.","1994":"Azerbaijan in 1994 was an independent republic that had emerged from the Soviet Union in 1991, with Heydar Aliyev having taken power in 1993. It remained locked in the Nagorno-Karabakh war with Armenia and Armenian-backed forces until a Russian-brokered ceasefire (the Bishkek Protocol) took effect in May 1994, leaving much of the territory under Armenian control. In September 1994 the government signed the so-called Contract of the Century with Western oil companies to develop its Caspian oil fields.","2000":"Azerbaijan was a presidential republic in the South Caucasus, independent since the 1991 dissolution of the Soviet Union and led by President Heydar Aliyev. The conflict with Armenia over Nagorno-Karabakh remained frozen after the 1994 ceasefire, with Armenian forces controlling the enclave and surrounding districts. The country's economy was increasingly oriented around Caspian Sea oil development.","2010":"Azerbaijan in 2010 was an independent presidential republic in the South Caucasus, led by President Ilham Aliyev, who had succeeded his father Heydar Aliyev. Its economy was heavily driven by oil and gas exports, especially via the Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan pipeline. The conflict with Armenia over Nagorno-Karabakh remained frozen and unresolved, with the territory under Armenian control.","2026":"Azerbaijan is a presidential republic led by Ilham Aliyev, who has held power since 2003. After its September 2023 offensive that led to the dissolution of the breakaway Nagorno-Karabakh region and the exodus of its ethnic Armenian population, Azerbaijan now controls the full territory, and in 2026 it continued pursuing a peace settlement with Armenia. The country is a major oil and gas exporter on the Caspian Sea."},
  "bahamas": {"1800":"In 1800, the Bahamas were a British colony administered from Nassau on New Providence, having been confirmed as a British possession by the 1783 Peace of Paris. The colony had been transformed by the arrival of roughly two thousand American Loyalists and the people they enslaved between 1783 and about 1789, which nearly tripled the population and shifted its economy toward cotton and sea-island plantation agriculture. These plantations largely failed within a generation as thin island soils were exhausted and pests destroyed the cotton, leaving an enslaved African-descended majority alongside a smaller white settler class and a growing free black community. Lord Dunmore, the former royal governor of Virginia and New York, had served as governor from 1787 until 1796, overseeing fortification of Nassau and much land granting to the newcomers. The islands remained economically marginal within the British Empire, their scattered \"Out Islands\" thinly settled and their trade dependent on shipping, salt, wrecking, and the produce of struggling estates.","1938":"The Bahamas was a British colony in the Caribbean, governed by a British colonial administration with a local assembly dominated by a white merchant elite known as the Bay Street Boys.","1960":"In 1960 the Bahamas was a British colony in the Caribbean, governed under a constitution as a self-governing colony with a British-appointed governor. Political life was dominated by the white merchant elite known as the Bay Street Boys, while the recently formed Progressive Liberal Party agitated for majority rule on behalf of the Black majority. The islands' economy rested heavily on tourism and offshore finance.","1994":"The Bahamas in 1994 was an independent parliamentary democracy and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, represented by a governor-general. Hubert Ingraham of the Free National Movement served as prime minister, having ended decades of Progressive Liberal Party rule in 1992, and the economy depended heavily on tourism and offshore finance.","2000":"The Bahamas was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, represented by a governor-general. Hubert Ingraham of the Free National Movement was prime minister, and the economy depended heavily on tourism and offshore financial services.","2010":"The Bahamas in 2010 was an independent constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a Governor-General. Hubert Ingraham of the Free National Movement served as Prime Minister. The economy depended heavily on tourism and offshore financial services and was affected by the global recession.","2026":"The Bahamas is a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy in the Commonwealth, with Charles III as head of state. Prime Minister Philip Davis of the Progressive Liberal Party leads the government. Its economy depends heavily on tourism and offshore financial services."},
  "bahrain": {"1960":"In 1960 Bahrain was a British-protected sheikhdom in the Persian Gulf, ruled by the Al Khalifa family with its foreign affairs and defence controlled by Britain under longstanding treaties. Its economy was based on oil, which had been in production since the 1930s, along with pearling and trade. Britain maintained a political agent and significant influence over the state.","1994":"Bahrain in 1994 was an emirate ruled by the Al Khalifa family under Emir Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa, an absolute monarchy with no elected parliament. Late 1994 saw the outbreak of a sustained Shia-led uprising demanding the restoration of the suspended parliament and constitution, met with arrests and crackdowns.","2000":"Bahrain was a hereditary monarchy ruled by the Al Khalifa family; Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa had become emir in 1999 following the death of his father and began introducing political reforms. It was still a state (it declared itself a kingdom in 2002) with an oil-based economy and hosted the U.S. Navy's Fifth Fleet.","2010":"Bahrain in 2010 was a small Persian Gulf kingdom ruled by King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa, a constitutional monarchy in form but with power concentrated in the ruling Sunni family. Parliamentary elections were held in 2010 amid tensions with the Shia-majority population and a crackdown on opposition activists ahead of the vote. Its economy was based on oil, banking, and finance.","2026":"Bahrain is a constitutional monarchy ruled by the Al Khalifa dynasty, with King Hamad bin Isa Al Khalifa as head of state. It hosts the headquarters of the United States Navy's Fifth Fleet and is a member of the Gulf Cooperation Council. The country normalized relations with Israel under the 2020 Abraham Accords."},
  "baikonur": {"2026":"Baikonur refers to the Baikonur Cosmodrome and surrounding city in Kazakhstan, which Russia leases and administers under an agreement currently set to run through 2050. The world's oldest and one of the largest spaceports, it remains a primary launch site for Russian crewed and cargo missions to the International Space Station."},
  "bajo nuevo bank": {"1960":"Bajo Nuevo Bank is an uninhabited reef and bank in the western Caribbean Sea. In 1960 it was a disputed/claimed feature with no permanent population or administration. It carried a long-standing United States claim under the Guano Islands Act and was also claimed by Colombia.","1994":"Bajo Nuevo Bank is an uninhabited reef and bank in the western Caribbean Sea, claimed by Colombia and administered as part of its territory, with competing claims by other states. In 1994 it had no permanent population or government, consisting only of small cays and a lighthouse.","2000":"Bajo Nuevo Bank is an uninhabited, largely submerged reef and small cays in the western Caribbean Sea, administered by Colombia but also claimed by other states. In 2000 it had no permanent population or government and remained the subject of competing territorial claims.","2010":"Bajo Nuevo Bank is a small uninhabited reef in the western Caribbean Sea administered by Colombia in 2010, though also claimed by other states. It has no resident population and no government of its own. Its sovereignty was among the maritime disputes in the region.","2026":"Bajo Nuevo Bank is a small, largely uninhabited reef in the western Caribbean Sea administered by Colombia, though it is also claimed by several other states. A 2012 International Court of Justice ruling on the broader maritime dispute affirmed Colombian sovereignty over the bank while reshaping nearby maritime boundaries."},
  "bangladesh": {"1994":"Bangladesh in 1994 was a parliamentary republic with Khaleda Zia of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party as prime minister and Abdur Rahman Biswas as president. Late 1994 was marked by a deepening political crisis as the opposition Awami League and its allies resigned from parliament and launched mass agitation demanding that elections be held under a neutral caretaker government.","2000":"Bangladesh was a parliamentary republic in South Asia, with Sheikh Hasina of the Awami League serving as prime minister after winning the 1996 elections. The country faced widespread poverty and recurrent flooding, and politics were marked by intense rivalry between the Awami League and the Bangladesh Nationalist Party.","2010":"Bangladesh in 2010 was an independent parliamentary republic in South Asia, with Sheikh Hasina of the Awami League serving as Prime Minister following her party's victory in the 2008 elections. The country, one of the world's most densely populated, had a fast-growing economy anchored by the garment export industry. In 2010 its International Crimes Tribunal began proceedings over atrocities committed during the 1971 war of independence.","2026":"Bangladesh is a parliamentary republic that underwent major upheaval in August 2024 when a student-led uprising forced longtime Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina to flee the country. An interim government headed by Nobel laureate Muhammad Yunus took charge and oversaw a return to elected rule, with national elections held in February 2026 amid efforts at political reform."},
  "barbados": {"1920":"Barbados in 1920 was a British colony in the Caribbean with a long-established representative assembly. Its economy was dominated by sugar plantations, and it was governed under British colonial administration.","1938":"Barbados was a British colony in the Caribbean with a long-established colonial legislature. The island had experienced labor unrest and riots in 1937 amid widespread Depression-era hardship, which fed growing demands for political and social reform.","1960":"In 1960 Barbados was a British colony in the eastern Caribbean with internal self-government and a British-appointed governor. It was a member of the West Indies Federation, established in 1958, and Grantley Adams of Barbados served as the Federation's first prime minister. The economy was dominated by sugar production.","1994":"Barbados in 1994 was an independent parliamentary democracy and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. In the September 1994 general election the Barbados Labour Party under Owen Arthur won power, making him prime minister.","2000":"Barbados was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Owen Arthur of the Barbados Labour Party was prime minister, and the economy relied on tourism, sugar, and financial services.","2010":"Barbados in 2010 was an independent constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and a parliamentary democracy. David Thompson of the Democratic Labour Party was Prime Minister but died of cancer in October 2010, after which Freundel Stuart succeeded him. The economy relied chiefly on tourism and offshore finance.","2026":"Barbados is a parliamentary republic, having removed Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and become a republic in November 2021. Mia Mottley serves as prime minister, and Jeffrey Bostic became president in November 2025. Mottley has been a prominent international advocate for climate finance reform for vulnerable nations."},
  "barotse": {"1900":"Barotseland was the kingdom of the Lozi people in the upper Zambezi region, ruled by the Litunga Lewanika. By 1900 it had come under British influence through treaties with the British South Africa Company, making it a protected state administered as part of what became Northern Rhodesia while retaining its monarchy."},
  "basutoland": {"1900":"Basutoland was a British protectorate inhabited by the Basotho people, having come under direct British Crown control in 1884 after a period of Cape Colony administration. In 1900 it was governed by a British resident commissioner while the Basotho retained considerable internal authority under their paramount chief."},
  "belarus": {"1994":"Belarus in 1994 was an independent republic that had become sovereign with the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991. It adopted its first post-Soviet constitution in March 1994 creating a presidency, and in the July 1994 presidential election Alexander Lukashenko won, becoming the country's first president.","2000":"Belarus was a presidential republic led by Alexander Lukashenko, who had consolidated authoritarian power after a contested 1996 referendum expanding his authority. In 1999 Belarus and Russia signed a treaty creating a Union State, deepening their integration, while the government faced Western criticism over its human rights record.","2010":"Belarus in 2010 was an authoritarian presidential republic led by Alexander Lukashenko, often described as Europe's last dictatorship. He won a contested presidential election in December 2010, which was followed by mass opposition protests in Minsk and a violent crackdown with numerous arrests. The country maintained close ties with Russia.","2026":"Belarus is an authoritarian presidential republic led by Alexander Lukashenko, who secured another term in the January 2025 election widely dismissed as neither free nor fair. A close ally of Russia, Belarus has supported Moscow's war in Ukraine, including allowing its territory to be used, and remains under Western sanctions."},
  "belgian congo": {"1938":"The Belgian Congo was a vast colony in central Africa under Belgian rule, administered through a centralized colonial government with significant involvement of the Catholic Church and large mining companies such as Union Minière. The economy depended on the extraction of copper, diamonds, and other minerals."},
  "belgium": {"1900":"Belgium in 1900 was an independent constitutional monarchy ruled by King Leopold II, an industrialized nation with a parliamentary government. Leopold also personally held the Congo Free State in central Africa as his private possession, a regime that was drawing growing international criticism for its brutal exploitation.","1920":"In 1920 Belgium was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Albert I, recovering from the devastation of German occupation during the First World War. It had recently annexed the small German districts of Eupen and Malmedy and was awarded a League of Nations mandate over Ruanda-Urundi, taken from German East Africa. The country was rebuilding its war-ravaged industrial and agricultural regions and pressing claims for German reparations.","1938":"Belgium was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Leopold III, who had reasserted a policy of strict neutrality after 1936, formally ending its military alliance with France. Through 1938 the country sought to stay out of the escalating tensions in Europe, declining binding commitments while strengthening its own defenses against the threat of another German invasion.","1960":"In 1960 Belgium was a constitutional monarchy in Western Europe under King Baudouin, a member of NATO and the European Economic Community. On 30 June 1960 it granted independence to the Belgian Congo, an event followed almost immediately by the Congo Crisis. Domestically, late 1960 into early 1961 saw a major general strike against the government's austerity measures.","1994":"Belgium in 1994 was a federal constitutional monarchy; the 1993 constitutional reforms formally transformed it into a federal state of regions and communities, taking full effect in this period. King Albert II reigned, having succeeded his brother Baudouin in 1993, and Jean-Luc Dehaene served as prime minister.","2000":"Belgium was a federal constitutional monarchy under King Albert II and a founding member of the European Union, hosting EU institutions in Brussels. A coalition government led by Liberal prime minister Guy Verhofstadt had taken office in 1999, and the country adopted the euro for accounting purposes that year ahead of cash circulation in 2002.","2010":"Belgium in 2010 was a federal constitutional monarchy and founding EU member, with King Albert II as head of state. Following inconclusive June 2010 federal elections, the country entered a prolonged political deadlock between Flemish and Walloon parties, beginning a record-setting period without a fully formed government. The N-VA's strong showing intensified debates over Flemish autonomy.","2026":"Belgium is a federal parliamentary constitutional monarchy and a founding EU member, with Brussels hosting major EU and NATO institutions; King Philippe is head of state. Following the June 2024 elections and lengthy coalition talks, Bart De Wever of the Flemish nationalist N-VA became prime minister in early 2025, leading a multiparty federal coalition."},
  "belize": {"1900":"In 1900 the territory was the colony of British Honduras, ruled by Britain on the Caribbean coast of Central America. Its economy centered on the export of mahogany and other timber, and Guatemala continued to dispute British sovereignty over the territory.","1920":"In 1920 Belize was the colony of British Honduras, governed as a British Crown colony on the Caribbean coast of Central America. Its economy rested heavily on the export of mahogany and other timber. Guatemala continued to dispute British sovereignty over the territory.","1938":"In 1938 the territory was the crown colony of British Honduras, governed by Britain. Its economy depended heavily on forest products such as mahogany and chicle, and it had suffered severely from the 1931 hurricane and the Great Depression, conditions that fed labor unrest in the 1930s. Guatemala continued to assert a longstanding territorial claim to the colony.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was the colony of British Honduras, administered by Britain on the Caribbean coast of Central America. It had recently moved toward self-government, with the People's United Party under George Price as the dominant political force pressing for fuller autonomy and eventual independence. Guatemala maintained a long-standing territorial claim over the colony.","1994":"Belize in 1994 was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, with Manuel Esquivel of the United Democratic Party as prime minister. British military forces, long stationed there as a guarantee against Guatemala's territorial claim, were withdrawn in 1994, leaving Belize responsible for its own defense.","2000":"Belize was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Said Musa of the People's United Party was prime minister, and the country continued to face a long-standing territorial claim from neighbouring Guatemala.","2010":"Belize in 2010 was an independent constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and a parliamentary democracy. Dean Barrow of the United Democratic Party served as Prime Minister, the country's first black prime minister. Guatemala continued to maintain a territorial claim over Belize.","2026":"Belize is a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy in the Commonwealth, with Charles III as head of state. Prime Minister John Briceño of the People's United Party leads the government, having won re-election in the March 2025 general election. Belize maintains a long-standing territorial dispute with Guatemala that has been referred to the International Court of Justice."},
  "benin": {"1960":"In 1960 this territory, then known as Dahomey, gained independence from France on 1 August 1960 as the Republic of Dahomey. It had previously been part of French West Africa, and Hubert Maga became the country's first president. It would not adopt the name Benin until 1975.","1994":"Benin in 1994 was a multiparty presidential republic, having transitioned from Marxist one-party rule through its 1990 national conference, with Nicéphore Soglo as the elected president since 1991. The country was implementing economic reforms and absorbing the shock of the January 1994 devaluation of the CFA franc.","2000":"Benin was a multiparty presidential republic in West Africa, regarded as a relatively stable democracy following its transition from Marxist-Leninist rule in 1990. Mathieu Kérékou, who had returned to power through elections in 1996, was president.","2010":"Benin in 2010 was an independent presidential republic in West Africa, with Thomas Boni Yayi serving as President. It was considered one of Africa's more stable multiparty democracies. The economy depended heavily on agriculture, particularly cotton, and on regional trade through the port of Cotonou.","2026":"Benin is a presidential republic in West Africa where Patrice Talon served as president from 2016 until 2026, reaching his second and final constitutional term. In 2026 the country faced growing security threats from jihadist groups spilling over from the Sahel into its northern regions, and held a presidential election in April 2026 that chose a successor to Talon."},
  "bermuda": {"1960":"In 1960 Bermuda was a self-governing British colony in the North Atlantic with a British-appointed governor and an elected House of Assembly long dominated by a white merchant elite. Its economy depended heavily on tourism and on British and American military bases established during the Second World War. The franchise remained restricted by property qualifications at this time.","1994":"Bermuda in 1994 was a self-governing British overseas territory with a governor appointed by the United Kingdom and an elected government, then led by the United Bermuda Party. Its economy was based on tourism and international business and insurance.","2000":"Bermuda was a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic, with a governor representing the British Crown and an elected government. The Progressive Labour Party, which had won the 1998 election, was in power under Premier Jennifer Smith, and the economy was based on international business and tourism.","2010":"Bermuda in 2010 was a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic, with a Governor representing the British Crown and an elected Premier handling internal affairs. Ewart Brown of the Progressive Labour Party served as Premier. Its economy was among the wealthiest per capita in the world, built on international insurance, reinsurance, and tourism.","2026":"Bermuda is a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic, with a governor appointed by the British Crown and an elected premier leading internal government. Its economy is built on international insurance and reinsurance business and tourism."},
  "bhutan": {"1900":"In 1900 Bhutan was a Himalayan Buddhist state that was politically fragmented, with rival regional governors and the nominal dual system of the Druk Desi and the Zhabdrung's office in decline. Real power was concentrating in the hands of Ugyen Wangchuck, the governor of Tongsa, who would be enthroned as the first hereditary king in 1907.","1920":"In 1920 Bhutan was a hereditary monarchy under Ugyen Wangchuck, the first Druk Gyalpo, who had founded the dynasty in 1907. Under the 1910 Treaty of Punakha, Britain guided Bhutan's external affairs in exchange for not interfering in its internal administration. The kingdom remained largely isolated and self-governing internally.","1938":"Bhutan was a monarchy under King Jigme Wangchuck, with its foreign relations guided by Britain under the 1910 Treaty of Punakha, by which Britain handled external affairs in exchange for not interfering internally. It remained an isolated, largely closed Himalayan kingdom in 1938.","1960":"In 1960 Bhutan was an independent Himalayan kingdom ruled by King Jigme Dorji Wangchuck, whose foreign relations were guided by India under the 1949 treaty. The king had begun a programme of modernization, including the start of Bhutan's first five-year plan and the building of roads. China's takeover of Tibet heightened Bhutan's security concerns and drew it closer to India during this period.","1994":"Bhutan in 1994 was an absolute monarchy ruled by King Jigme Singye Wangchuck. The period was marked by tensions over the Lhotshampa, the ethnic Nepali population of southern Bhutan, tens of thousands of whom had fled or been expelled and were living in refugee camps in eastern Nepal.","2000":"Bhutan was a hereditary monarchy in the eastern Himalayas ruled by King Jigme Singye Wangchuck. It remained an absolute (though gradually reforming) kingdom with a largely Buddhist society, and faced an unresolved issue of ethnic Nepali refugees who had been expelled and were living in camps in Nepal.","2010":"Bhutan in 2010 was a Himalayan constitutional monarchy, having transitioned from absolute monarchy to a parliamentary democracy in 2008 under King Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck. Jigme Thinley served as the country's first democratically elected Prime Minister. The kingdom was known for its Gross National Happiness development philosophy and cautious opening to the outside world.","2026":"Bhutan is a landlocked constitutional monarchy in the eastern Himalayas, ruled by King Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck with an elected parliamentary government. In 2026 it remains one of the few countries that measures progress through Gross National Happiness, and it has been developing the ambitious Gelephu Mindfulness City special administrative region near its southern border to attract investment."},
  "bir tawil": {"2026":"Bir Tawil is a small landlocked area between Egypt and Sudan that remains unclaimed by either state, a consequence of the conflicting 1899 and 1902 boundary lines, since claiming it would mean forfeiting the larger Hala'ib Triangle. As of 2026 it stays one of the only terrestrial regions on Earth that no recognized government claims, despite occasional novelty claims by individuals."},
  "bolivia": {"1900":"Bolivia in 1900 was an independent republic that had lost its Pacific coastline to Chile in the War of the Pacific in the 1880s, leaving it landlocked. Its economy was driven by mining, with tin emerging as the leading export, and the Liberal Party had recently come to power following the 1899 Federal War, moving the seat of government to La Paz.","1920":"In 1920 Bolivia was a republic whose Liberal Party government was overthrown in a July coup that brought the Republican Party to power. The economy depended heavily on tin mining for export. Bolivia continued to feel the loss of its Pacific coastline to Chile in the earlier War of the Pacific.","1938":"Bolivia in 1938 was recovering from its defeat by Paraguay in the Chaco War, which had ended with a 1935 ceasefire; in July 1938 a peace treaty was signed in Buenos Aires that confirmed Paraguay's control over most of the disputed Chaco. The country was under the government of Germán Busch, an army officer who had taken power amid postwar political upheaval and rising military-socialist and nationalist sentiment. In 1938 a constituent assembly adopted a new, reform-oriented constitution.","1960":"In 1960 Bolivia was a republic governed by the Nationalist Revolutionary Movement (MNR), the party of the 1952 revolution, with Víctor Paz Estenssoro returning to the presidency in 1960. The country remained shaped by the revolution's reforms, including universal suffrage, agrarian reform, and the nationalization of the major tin mines under COMIBOL. It was heavily dependent on tin exports and received substantial United States aid.","1994":"Bolivia in 1994 was a presidential republic with Gonzalo Sánchez de Lozada as president, who had taken office in 1993. His government pursued major reforms including the capitalization (partial privatization) of state enterprises and the 1994 Law of Popular Participation that decentralized power to municipalities.","2000":"Bolivia was a presidential republic in South America, with Hugo Banzer, the former military dictator who had been democratically elected in 1997, serving as president. In 2000 the city of Cochabamba was the scene of the \"Water War,\" mass protests against the privatization of the municipal water supply that forced the government to reverse the contract.","2010":"Bolivia in 2010 was a presidential republic led by Evo Morales, the country's first indigenous president, who had been re-elected in 2009. A new constitution adopted in 2009 had renamed the country the Plurinational State of Bolivia and expanded indigenous rights and state control over natural resources, including nationalized gas. Morales pursued left-wing policies and aligned with other Latin American leftist governments.","2026":"Bolivia is a sovereign plurinational state in South America. In 2026 it underwent a major political shift after the August 2025 general election, which ended roughly two decades of dominance by the Movement for Socialism; centrist senator Rodrigo Paz won the runoff and took office, amid a severe economic crisis marked by fuel shortages and a scarcity of US dollars."},
  "bosnia and herz.": {"1994":"In 1994 Bosnia and Herzegovina was an internationally recognized independent state, but it was engulfed in the Bosnian War following its 1992 secession from Yugoslavia. Sarajevo remained under siege by Bosnian Serb forces, and the year saw the Washington Agreement create a Bosniak-Croat Federation, ending fighting between those two groups while war with the Serb side continued. NATO conducted its first combat actions in the conflict, including shooting down Serb aircraft.","2000":"In 2000 Bosnia and Herzegovina was an independent state still governed under the Dayton Accords that had ended the 1992-1995 war, comprising two entities, the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska, under a rotating tripartite presidency. International oversight continued through the Office of the High Representative and NATO-led peacekeeping forces, and the country remained deeply divided along ethnic lines while rebuilding from the war.","2010":"In 2010 Bosnia and Herzegovina was a sovereign state still governed under the 1995 Dayton framework, divided into two entities, the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska, with an international High Representative overseeing the peace settlement. General elections held in October 2010 returned a fragmented result, and the country remained politically deadlocked, with prolonged difficulty forming a state-level government afterward.","2026":"Bosnia and Herzegovina is a sovereign state in the western Balkans whose governance is still shaped by the 1995 Dayton Agreement, dividing it into the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina and Republika Srpska under a tripartite presidency and an international High Representative. In 2026 it remains an EU candidate but faces persistent political deadlock, including separatist tensions driven by Republika Srpska leadership."},
  "bosnia-herzegovina": {"1900":"In 1900 Bosnia-Herzegovina was nominally part of the Ottoman Empire but had been occupied and administered by Austria-Hungary since 1878 under the terms of the Congress of Berlin. The Habsburg administration governed the ethnically and religiously mixed territory directly, though it would not be formally annexed until 1908."},
  "botswana": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory was the Bechuanaland Protectorate, administered by Britain with its administrative seat located at Mafeking outside the protectorate's borders. Power was shared between the colonial administration and the chiefs of the Tswana peoples. The economy was based on cattle herding and migrant labor to South African mines.","1938":"In 1938 the territory was the Bechuanaland Protectorate, administered by Britain, with its administrative seat located at Mafeking outside the protectorate itself. It was a sparsely populated, largely pastoral territory whose tribal reserves retained considerable internal autonomy under their chiefs, while South Africa continued to press, unsuccessfully, for its incorporation.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was the Bechuanaland Protectorate, a British protectorate in southern Africa administered from Mafeking, which lay outside its borders in South Africa. It remained sparsely populated and economically underdeveloped, with cattle-raising as the mainstay. It would not become independent as Botswana until 1966.","1994":"Botswana in 1994 was a stable multiparty democracy that had been independent from Britain since 1966, with Quett Masire of the Botswana Democratic Party as president. Its economy, anchored by diamond mining, was among the fastest-growing in the world. General elections held in 1994 again returned the BDP to power, though the opposition made gains.","2000":"Botswana in 2000 was a stable multiparty democracy led by President Festus Mogae of the long-dominant Botswana Democratic Party. Its economy was among Africa's most prosperous, driven heavily by diamond mining, but the country faced one of the world's highest HIV/AIDS infection rates.","2010":"Botswana in 2010 was a stable multiparty democracy and one of Africa's longest-running, with the Botswana Democratic Party in power and Ian Khama serving as president. Its diamond-dependent economy, having been hit by the 2008-09 global downturn, was recovering as commodity demand returned.","2026":"Botswana is a landlocked parliamentary republic in southern Africa, long regarded as one of the continent's most stable democracies and heavily reliant on diamond mining. In 2026 it is governed by President Duma Boko of the Umbrella for Democratic Change, who won the October 2024 election that ended nearly six decades of rule by the Botswana Democratic Party."},
  "br. indian ocean ter.": {"1994":"In 1994 the British Indian Ocean Territory was a British overseas territory in the Indian Ocean, comprising the Chagos Archipelago. Its largest island, Diego Garcia, hosted a major United States military base under an Anglo-American agreement, and the territory had no permanent civilian population, the Chagossians having been removed in the late 1960s and early 1970s.","2000":"The British Indian Ocean Territory in 2000 was a British overseas territory in the Indian Ocean consisting of the Chagos Archipelago, with no permanent civilian population after the Chagossians had been removed in the late 1960s and early 1970s. Its largest island, Diego Garcia, hosted a major United States military base under an Anglo-American agreement.","2010":"The British Indian Ocean Territory in 2010 was a British Overseas Territory in the Indian Ocean comprising the Chagos Archipelago, with no permanent civilian population after the Chagossians were removed in the late 1960s and 1970s. Its largest island, Diego Garcia, hosted a major United States military base under UK-US agreement. In April 2010 the UK declared a marine protected area around the territory, a move later contested in legal proceedings.","2026":"The British Indian Ocean Territory is an overseas territory of the United Kingdom comprising the Chagos Archipelago, including the Diego Garcia military base used jointly with the United States. In 2026 it is at the center of a sovereignty transfer: the UK agreed in 2025 to cede sovereignty over the Chagos Islands to Mauritius while retaining a long-term lease on Diego Garcia."},
  "brazil": {"1920":"In 1920 Brazil was a federal republic in the period known as the Old Republic, dominated politically by the coffee-producing elites of São Paulo and Minas Gerais. Epitácio Pessoa served as president. The economy remained heavily dependent on coffee exports, and the country had been a member of the Allied side in the First World War.","1938":"Brazil in 1938 was ruled by Getúlio Vargas, who had established the authoritarian Estado Novo dictatorship in November 1937, dissolving Congress and political parties and centralizing power. In May 1938 the integralist (fascist-inspired) movement attempted a coup against Vargas, which was suppressed. The government pursued nationalist and state-led industrialization policies during this period.","1960":"In 1960 Brazil was a federal republic, and Juscelino Kubitschek was president, presiding over rapid industrialization and developmentalist policies summed up in his slogan of \"fifty years of progress in five.\" The new capital city of Brasília was inaugurated on 21 April 1960 to replace Rio de Janeiro. In the October 1960 election Jânio Quadros was chosen as the next president.","1994":"In 1994 Brazil was a federal presidential republic and the most populous country in South America, governed under its 1988 constitution. That year the Plano Real introduced the new currency, the real, successfully curbing the country's hyperinflation, and Fernando Henrique Cardoso, associated with the plan, won the presidential election. Brazil also won the FIFA World Cup in 1994.","2000":"Brazil in 2000 was a federal presidential republic led by President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, whose government had stabilized the economy with the Real Plan while the currency had been floated after the 1999 devaluation. The country marked the 500th anniversary of the Portuguese landing in 2000 and remained South America's largest nation by population and economy.","2010":"Brazil in 2010 was a federal presidential republic and Latin America's largest economy, completing the second term of President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva. The economy grew strongly that year, and in the October 2010 elections Dilma Rousseff was elected as Brazil's first woman president; Brazil had also recently been awarded the 2014 World Cup and 2016 Olympics.","2026":"Brazil is a federal presidential republic and the largest country in South America. In 2026 it is led by President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, who returned to office in 2023, and the country is heading toward a general election in October 2026; it hosted the COP30 climate summit in Belém in late 2025."},
  "british guiana": {"1800":"In 1800, the coastal Guiana territory comprised the three separate Dutch colonies of Essequibo, Demerara, and Berbice, held under British military occupation since 1796 during the wars of the French Revolution. Each colony kept its Dutch-derived administration and Court of Policy, with Essequibo and Demerara jointly governed and Berbice run separately, so no unified \"British Guiana\" yet existed. The administrative and commercial center was Stabroek at the mouth of the Demerara River, a town laid out on the Dutch grid plan that would be renamed Georgetown only in 1812. The economy rested on plantation agriculture worked by enslaved Africans, with Essequibo and Demerara together holding roughly 380 estates producing sugar, cotton, and coffee. Legal sovereignty remained Dutch and disputed, and the colonies would briefly revert to the Batavian Republic under the 1802 Peace of Amiens before permanent British reoccupation in 1803.","1900":"British Guiana in 1900 was a British colony on the northern coast of South America, the only British possession on the continent. Its plantation economy relied heavily on sugar produced with indentured laborers brought largely from India, and gold mining was also significant; a long-running boundary dispute with Venezuela had recently been settled by arbitration in 1899."},
  "british raj": {"1900":"In 1900 British India was directly governed by Britain under the Crown, with Lord Curzon serving as Viceroy and ultimate authority resting with the British government and Parliament. The territory encompassed both directly ruled provinces and numerous princely states under British paramountcy, and large parts of the subcontinent were suffering from a severe famine around 1899-1900.","1920":"In 1920 British India was under direct British Crown rule, with the Government of India Act 1919 introducing limited provincial self-government known as dyarchy. Indian nationalist agitation was intensifying, with Mohandas Gandhi launching the Non-Cooperation Movement and widespread anger persisting over the 1919 Amritsar massacre. The territory encompassed present-day India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Burma.","1938":"In 1938 British India was under British colonial rule, with a Viceroy governing alongside provincial autonomy introduced by the Government of India Act 1935 and elections held in 1937. The Indian National Congress controlled ministries in most provinces, and in 1938 Subhas Chandra Bose was elected its president. The independence movement was steadily growing in strength."},
  "british somaliland": {"1920":"In 1920 British Somaliland was a British protectorate in the Horn of Africa. That year British forces, using aerial bombardment, decisively defeated Mohammed Abdullah Hassan's Dervish movement, which had resisted colonial rule for two decades. The protectorate's economy was based largely on livestock herding.","1938":"British Somaliland was a British protectorate on the Horn of Africa in 1938, bordering Italian-controlled territory after Italy's conquest of Ethiopia and its creation of Italian East Africa. It was a thinly administered, largely pastoral territory."},
  "british virgin is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the British Virgin Islands was a British colony in the Caribbean. Its economy was small and based largely on agriculture and fishing, with growing economic ties to the neighbouring United States Virgin Islands. The territory had its own administrator and was moving toward greater internal self-government during this period.","1994":"In 1994 the British Virgin Islands were a British overseas territory in the Caribbean with internal self-government and a tourism- and offshore-finance-based economy. The territory used the US dollar as its currency.","2000":"The British Virgin Islands in 2000 was a self-governing British overseas territory in the Caribbean with a British-appointed governor and an elected local government. Its economy relied on tourism and a large offshore financial services sector based on company incorporation.","2010":"The British Virgin Islands in 2010 were a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean with internal self-government under a 2007 constitution and a governor appointed by the UK. Its economy rested heavily on tourism and on its status as an offshore financial center and company-incorporation jurisdiction.","2026":"The British Virgin Islands is a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, with a premier-led elected government and a UK-appointed governor. In 2026 it remains a major offshore financial center and continues governance reforms prompted by a 2022 commission of inquiry into corruption."},
  "brunei": {"1920":"In 1920 Brunei was a British protected sultanate on the northern coast of Borneo, administered through a British Resident under the system established in 1906. The sultan retained his throne but real administrative authority lay with the Resident. The discovery of major oil reserves was still a few years away.","1938":"In 1938 Brunei was a British protected state ruled by Sultan Ahmad Tajuddin under a British Resident, an arrangement in place since 1906 by which Britain controlled administration and external affairs. Oil had been discovered at Seria in 1929, and its development was becoming central to the small sultanate's economy.","1960":"In 1960 Brunei was a British protectorate on the north coast of Borneo, a sultanate whose foreign affairs and defence were controlled by Britain through a High Commissioner. Its economy was dominated by the oil fields at Seria, which had made it one of the wealthier territories in the region. Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien III ruled, and a new written constitution restoring internal self-government had just been promulgated in 1959.","1994":"In 1994 Brunei was an independent sovereign sultanate on the island of Borneo, fully independent from Britain since 1984 and ruled as an absolute monarchy by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah. Its economy was dominated by oil and natural gas exports, giving it a high per-capita income.","2000":"Brunei in 2000 was an oil- and gas-rich absolute monarchy on Borneo ruled by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, who held supreme executive authority. The small, wealthy state maintained high living standards funded by hydrocarbon exports and followed Malay Islamic Monarchy as its national ideology.","2010":"Brunei in 2010 was an absolute monarchy on the island of Borneo ruled by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, who served as head of state and government. Its wealth derived from substantial oil and natural gas reserves, giving the small population a high per-capita income, and the state followed an official ideology of Malay Islamic Monarchy.","2026":"Brunei is a small, oil- and gas-rich absolute monarchy on the island of Borneo, ruled by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah, who serves as head of state and government. In 2026 it continues to apply a Sharia-based penal code phased in from 2014 and relies heavily on hydrocarbon revenues while seeking economic diversification."},
  "buganda": {"1900":"In 1900 Buganda was a kingdom in present-day Uganda that came under formal British control through the Uganda Agreement of 1900 (the Buganda Agreement), negotiated by Sir Harry Johnston. The agreement defined Buganda's status within the British Uganda Protectorate, reorganized land tenure, and confirmed the kabaka's monarchy under British oversight, with the young Daudi Cwa as kabaka under a regency."},
  "bulgaria": {"1900":"In 1900 Bulgaria was an autonomous principality nominally under Ottoman suzerainty but effectively self-governing, ruled by Prince Ferdinand I of the House of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha. It would not declare full independence as a kingdom until 1908.","1938":"Bulgaria in 1938 was a kingdom under Tsar Boris III, who had consolidated a royal authoritarian regime after the 1934 coup, governing without a strong parliament. The country pursued revisionist aims regarding territory lost after the First World War and was drawing closer economically to Germany, while officially balancing its foreign relations.","1960":"In 1960 the People's Republic of Bulgaria was a one-party communist state and a close ally of the Soviet Union within the Warsaw Pact and Comecon. The Bulgarian Communist Party, led by Todor Zhivkov, controlled the government, pursuing collectivized agriculture and centrally planned industrialization. It was among the most loyal Soviet satellites in Eastern Europe.","1994":"In 1994 Bulgaria was a parliamentary republic transitioning from communism, having held its first free elections in 1990. The country was undergoing difficult economic reforms following the end of one-party rule, and December 1994 parliamentary elections returned the Bulgarian Socialist Party, successor to the Communist Party, to power.","2000":"Bulgaria in 2000 was a parliamentary republic governed by Prime Minister Ivan Kostov of the Union of Democratic Forces, with Petar Stoyanov as president. The country was pursuing market reforms and Euro-Atlantic integration, having opened formal accession negotiations with the European Union in 2000 and seeking NATO membership.","2010":"Bulgaria in 2010 was a member of the European Union, which it had joined in 2007, and of NATO, governed by the center-right GERB party under Prime Minister Boyko Borisov, who took office in 2009. The country was dealing with the effects of the global financial crisis and continued EU scrutiny over judicial reform and corruption.","2026":"Bulgaria is a sovereign parliamentary republic in southeastern Europe and a member of the European Union and NATO. On 1 January 2026 it adopted the euro as its currency, becoming the eurozone's newest member after years of political instability marked by repeated elections."},
  "bunyoro": {"1900":"In 1900 Bunyoro (Bunyoro-Kitara) was a kingdom in present-day western Uganda that had been subjugated by British forces, having resisted colonial expansion under its king Kabarega through the 1890s. Kabarega had been captured and exiled in 1899, and the kingdom was brought under the British Uganda Protectorate."},
  "burkina faso": {"1960":"The territory known today as Burkina Faso was in 1960 the Republic of Upper Volta, which gained full independence from France on 5 August 1960. Maurice Yaméogo became its first president, leading the country out of the French Community. It was a landlocked West African state whose name only changed to Burkina Faso in 1984.","1994":"In 1994 Burkina Faso was a West African republic led by Blaise Compaoré, who had taken power in a 1987 coup. In January 1994 the CFA franc was devalued by 50 percent, a shock shared across francophone Africa that raised import prices.","2000":"Burkina Faso in 2000 was a republic led by President Blaise Compaoré, who had held power since the 1987 coup. The period was marked by domestic tension following the 1998 murder of journalist Norbert Zongo, which had triggered significant protests and a political crisis.","2010":"Burkina Faso in 2010 was a republic in West Africa led by President Blaise Compaore, who had held power since 1987 and was re-elected in the November 2010 presidential election. It remained one of the world's poorer countries, with an economy heavily dependent on cotton and increasingly on gold.","2026":"Burkina Faso is a landlocked West African state governed in 2026 by a military junta led by Captain Ibrahim Traoré, who took power in a September 2022 coup. It faces a severe jihadist insurgency, has pivoted away from former colonial power France toward Russia, and in 2024 formed the Alliance of Sahel States with Mali and Niger before the three withdrew from ECOWAS."},
  "burundi": {"1900":"In 1900 the Kingdom of Burundi was a monarchy ruled by a mwami and was being incorporated into German East Africa, the colonial sphere assigned to Germany. German control was largely indirect, exercised through the existing monarchy and chiefs rather than direct administration.","1920":"In 1920 the territory formed part of Ruanda-Urundi, which had been taken from German East Africa during the war and assigned to Belgium as a League of Nations mandate. The kingdom of Urundi retained its monarchy, ruled by its mwami, under Belgian oversight. Belgium administered the territory through indirect rule.","1938":"In 1938 the territory was part of Ruanda-Urundi, administered by Belgium as a League of Nations mandate and governed in association with the Belgian Congo. Belgium ruled through the existing Tutsi monarchy and chiefs under a policy of indirect rule.","1960":"In 1960 Burundi was part of the Belgian-administered United Nations Trust Territory of Ruanda-Urundi, not yet independent. It remained a monarchy under its Tutsi mwami within the Belgian colonial framework, with political parties such as UPRONA emerging ahead of independence. Burundi would become a separate independent kingdom in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Burundi was a republic gripped by severe ethnic violence between Hutu and Tutsi following the October 1993 assassination of its first elected Hutu president, Melchior Ndadaye. In April 1994 President Cyprien Ntaryamira was killed alongside Rwanda's president when their plane was shot down over Kigali, deepening instability as the country teetered toward civil war.","2000":"Burundi in 2000 was a republic still gripped by a civil war between the Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu rebel groups that had raged since 1993. In August 2000 the Arusha Peace and Reconciliation Agreement was signed under the mediation of Nelson Mandela, though several rebel factions did not sign and fighting continued, with Pierre Buyoya serving as president.","2010":"Burundi in 2010 was a republic in the African Great Lakes region recovering from a long civil war, with President Pierre Nkurunziza re-elected in 2010 in polls that the main opposition boycotted, alleging fraud. The contested elections heightened political tension in the country.","2026":"Burundi is a landlocked republic in East Africa's Great Lakes region, governed in 2026 by President Évariste Ndayishimiye of the ruling CNDD-FDD party. It remains one of the world's poorest countries and held legislative elections in 2025; its government has voiced concern over instability in the neighboring eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo."},
  "cabo verde": {"1960":"In 1960 Cabo Verde (the Cape Verde Islands) was an overseas province of Portugal, governed as part of the Portuguese colonial empire off the West African coast. There was no independence movement in power; the islands were ruled directly from Lisbon under the Estado Novo regime. The PAIGC liberation movement, founded in 1956, sought independence for both Cape Verde and Portuguese Guinea, but independence did not come until 1975.","1994":"In 1994 Cabo Verde was an independent island republic off West Africa that had introduced multiparty democracy in 1991, with António Mascarenhas Monteiro as president and the Movement for Democracy in government. The country was known for its political stability and reliance on remittances and aid.","2000":"Cabo Verde in 2000 was a stable multiparty democratic republic on its Atlantic island archipelago off West Africa. The country held legislative and presidential elections in early 2001, and its economy depended heavily on services, remittances from its large diaspora, and foreign aid.","2010":"Cabo Verde in 2010 was a stable democratic island republic off the West African coast, regarded as one of Africa's better-governed states. Its economy relied largely on services, tourism, and remittances from a large diaspora.","2026":"Cabo Verde is a sovereign island republic in the Atlantic off West Africa, a stable multiparty democracy with an economy centered on tourism and services. In 2026 José Maria Neves serves as president, with the Movement for Democracy holding the government, and the country is widely cited as one of Africa's better-governed states."},
  "calabar": {"1900":"Calabar was a port and trading center on the lower Cross River in what is now southeastern Nigeria, long known for the palm-oil trade. By 1900 it had become a British colonial possession; it served as the administrative capital of the Niger Coast Protectorate, which in that year was reorganized into the Protectorate of Southern Nigeria."},
  "cambodia": {"1938":"In 1938 Cambodia was a French protectorate within French Indochina, ruled by King Sisowath Monivong under French oversight. France controlled administration and external affairs while the monarchy retained a largely ceremonial role.","1960":"In 1960 Cambodia was an independent kingdom that had won full independence from France in 1953. Prince Norodom Sihanouk dominated politics through his Sangkum movement; on the death of his father King Norodom Suramarit in 1960, Sihanouk became head of state while leaving the throne formally vacant. He pursued a policy of neutrality in the Cold War and the widening Indochina conflict.","1994":"In 1994 Cambodia was a constitutional monarchy with Norodom Sihanouk as king, following the 1991 Paris Peace Accords and the UN-organized 1993 elections that produced a coalition government. The Khmer Rouge, having boycotted the elections, continued an armed insurgency, and in 1994 the government formally outlawed the movement.","2000":"Cambodia in 2000 was a constitutional monarchy with King Norodom Sihanouk as head of state and Hun Sen as prime minister following the 1998 elections. The Khmer Rouge insurgency had effectively collapsed by the late 1990s after Pol Pot's death in 1998 and mass defections, and discussions were underway about a tribunal to try surviving Khmer Rouge leaders.","2010":"Cambodia in 2010 was a constitutional monarchy with King Norodom Sihamoni as head of state and Prime Minister Hun Sen, leader of the Cambodian People's Party, dominating the government. In 2010 the UN-backed Khmer Rouge tribunal delivered its first verdict, convicting the former prison chief Kaing Guek Eav, known as Duch.","2026":"Cambodia is a constitutional monarchy in Southeast Asia with King Norodom Sihamoni as head of state, governed by Prime Minister Hun Manet, who succeeded his father Hun Sen in 2023 while the elder Hun Sen retained influence as Senate president. The ruling Cambodian People's Party dominates politics following the dissolution of major opposition parties. In 2025 a deadly border dispute and brief armed clashes erupted with Thailand, straining relations between the two neighbors."},
  "cameroon": {"1960":"In 1960 French Cameroon became independent as the Republic of Cameroon on 1 January 1960, with Ahmadou Ahidjo as its first president. Independence was accompanied by an armed insurgency by the UPC nationalist movement, which the government fought with French military support. The British-administered Southern Cameroons remained separate at this point and would join in 1961 to form a federation.","1994":"In 1994 Cameroon was a republic led by President Paul Biya, who had been in power since 1982. The country was affected by the January 1994 50 percent devaluation of the CFA franc, and tensions with Nigeria over the Bakassi Peninsula escalated around this period.","2000":"Cameroon in 2000 was a republic led by President Paul Biya, who had held power since 1982. The country was a bilingual francophone-anglophone state, and around this time construction of the Chad-Cameroon oil pipeline was being arranged with World Bank involvement.","2010":"Cameroon in 2010 was a republic in Central Africa led by President Paul Biya, in power since 1982. The country marked fifty years of independence in 2010, and its economy drew on oil, agriculture, and timber.","2026":"Cameroon is a republic in Central Africa led by President Paul Biya, one of the world's longest-serving leaders, who has held power since 1982 and won a contested election in late 2025 to extend his rule into his nineties. The country continues to face the Anglophone separatist conflict in its English-speaking northwest and southwest regions, as well as Boko Haram attacks in the Far North."},
  "canada": {"1900":"In 1900 Canada was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire, with the Crown handling its foreign affairs, under Prime Minister Wilfrid Laurier. The country was experiencing rapid growth, with westward settlement of the prairies and large-scale immigration, and Canadians had begun contributing troops to Britain's effort in the Second Boer War.","1920":"In 1920 Canada was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire, having gained greater international standing through its First World War contribution and separate signature of the Treaty of Versailles. Arthur Meighen became prime minister that year, succeeding Robert Borden. Canada was an original member of the newly formed League of Nations.","1938":"Canada in 1938 was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire under Prime Minister William Lyon Mackenzie King, having gained full legislative autonomy through the Statute of Westminster in 1931. The country was still emerging from the Great Depression and watching the deepening crisis in Europe with caution.","1960":"In 1960 Canada was an independent parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. John Diefenbaker's Progressive Conservatives were in government, and in 1960 Parliament enacted the Canadian Bill of Rights and extended the federal franchise to status Indians without requiring them to give up treaty rights. The country remained closely tied to the United States and the Western alliance in NATO and NORAD.","1994":"In 1994 Canada was a federal parliamentary constitutional monarchy and a Commonwealth realm, with Jean Chrétien of the Liberal Party as prime minister following his 1993 election victory. On January 1, 1994, the North American Free Trade Agreement among Canada, the United States, and Mexico took effect. Quebec sovereignty was a major issue, with the Parti Québécois winning the provincial election that year.","2000":"Canada in 2000 was a federal parliamentary constitutional monarchy and Commonwealth realm led by Liberal Prime Minister Jean Chrétien, who won a third consecutive majority in the November 2000 federal election. The territory of Nunavut had been created in 1999, and the Clarity Act addressing the terms of any Quebec secession referendum was passed in 2000.","2010":"Canada in 2010 was a federal parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy, governed by a Conservative minority under Prime Minister Stephen Harper. In 2010 Canada hosted the Winter Olympics in Vancouver and the G8 and G20 summits in Ontario.","2026":"Canada is a federal parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy with King Charles III as head of state, governed by Prime Minister Mark Carney of the Liberal Party, who took office in 2025 after Justin Trudeau resigned and led the Liberals to an election win. Relations with the United States have been tense over tariffs and President Trump's repeated rhetoric about annexing Canada as a '51st state.'"},
  "cape colony": {"1800":"In 1800, the Cape of Good Hope was a British-occupied colony, seized from the Dutch East India Company in 1795 to secure the sea route to India during the French Revolutionary Wars. It was administered as a military possession, with Sir George Yonge serving as governor over a population of former Company officials, Boer farmers, slaves, and Khoikhoi under British authority. Cape Town remained the administrative and commercial hub, its garrison and harbour guarding the strategic passage around Africa. Frontier tensions persisted to the east, where colonists, the Xhosa, and the Khoikhoi contested land and cattle along the unstable eastern districts. The occupation proved temporary, for under the 1802 Treaty of Amiens Britain agreed to restore the Cape to the Batavian Republic, which took control in 1803.","1900":"The Cape Colony was a British self-governing colony at the southern tip of Africa, with its capital at Cape Town. In 1900 it was deeply involved in the Second Boer War against the Boer republics, having been invaded by Boer forces in 1899, with fighting and a Cape Afrikaner rebellion affecting parts of the colony."},
  "cayman is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Cayman Islands were a British dependency in the Caribbean. They had long been administered as a dependency of Jamaica, and remained so until Jamaica's independence in 1962, after which the Caymans chose to remain a British Crown colony. In 1960 the islands were a small, sparsely populated territory whose economy rested on seafaring, turtling, and remittances.","1994":"In 1994 the Cayman Islands were a British overseas territory in the Caribbean, a major offshore financial center and tourism destination. The territory used the Cayman Islands dollar and was governed with a British-appointed governor alongside local representatives.","2000":"The Cayman Islands in 2000 was a British overseas territory in the Caribbean with a British-appointed governor and an elected local government. It was a major international offshore financial center, hosting a large number of registered hedge funds and banks, with tourism as its other principal industry.","2010":"The Cayman Islands in 2010 were a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean with internal self-government and a UK-appointed governor. Their economy was built on tourism and on being one of the world's leading offshore financial centers, and the territory was working through fiscal strains following the global financial crisis.","2026":"The Cayman Islands are a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, with a governor appointed by the British Crown and an elected premier leading the local government. The territory is a major offshore financial center and tourism destination."},
  "central african rep.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Central African Republic gained full independence from France on 13 August 1960. David Dacko became its first president as the country left the French Community. The former colony of Ubangi-Shari was a landlocked state in the heart of Africa, retaining close economic and military ties to France.","1994":"In 1994 the Central African Republic was governed by President Ange-Félix Patassé, who had won the country's first multiparty elections in 1993, ending the long rule of André Kolingba. The country remained one of the world's poorest, dependent on subsistence agriculture and facing recurring difficulties paying civil servants and soldiers.","2000":"In 2000 the Central African Republic was a sovereign republic led by President Ange-Félix Patassé, who had won re-election in 1999. The country remained politically unstable in the wake of a series of army mutinies in 1996-1997, and economic conditions were dire with frequent unpaid civil-service and military salaries.","2010":"In 2010 the Central African Republic was a landlocked republic governed by President François Bozizé, who had taken power in a 2003 coup and won a disputed 2005 election. The country remained deeply unstable and impoverished, with rebel groups active in the north and a 2008 peace agreement that was only partly holding.","2026":"The Central African Republic is a republic in Central Africa led by President Faustin-Archange Touadéra, who secured a controversial third term after a 2023 constitutional referendum removed term limits. The government relies heavily on Russian Wagner Group (now Africa Corps) forces for security amid an ongoing civil conflict with armed rebel groups."},
  "central asian khanates": {"1800":"In 1800, the region was divided among rival Muslim states rather than unified under any single throne. In Bukhara the Manghit founder Shah Murad died and was succeeded by his son Emir Haydar, a pious ruler devoted to the Naqshbandi Sufi order who leaned heavily on scholars and religious judges. In Kokand, Alim Khan had recently taken power following the death of Narbuta Biy in 1799 and was beginning the ruthless expansion that would make him the first of his line to claim the title of khan. Khiva was governed by the Qungrat inaqs, who held real power on behalf of puppet khans and would openly assume the khanship under Iltuzar in 1804. The three Kazakh hordes ranged across the northern steppe under their own sultans and khans, nominally under Russian suzerainty but in practice autonomous, while the small Caucasus khanates maneuvered between Persian and advancing Russian influence.","1900":"In 1900 the Central Asian khanates of Khiva and Bukhara survived as nominally autonomous states but were Russian protectorates, having been subjugated by the Russian Empire in the 1860s and 1870s. The Khanate of Kokand had already been abolished and absorbed into Russian Turkestan in 1876."},
  "ceylon": {"1900":"Ceylon was a British Crown colony comprising the island now known as Sri Lanka, governed by a British governor based in Colombo. Its economy by 1900 rested heavily on plantation agriculture, especially tea, which had largely replaced the earlier coffee crop, worked in part by Tamil labor brought from southern India.","1920":"In 1920 Ceylon was a British Crown colony comprising the island now known as Sri Lanka. Its economy was dominated by plantation exports of tea, rubber and coconut. Constitutional reforms were expanding the legislative council, reflecting growing pressure for greater local representation.","1938":"In 1938 Ceylon was a British crown colony, governed under the 1931 Donoughmore Constitution, which had introduced an elected State Council with universal adult suffrage while ultimate authority remained with the British governor. Its economy rested heavily on tea, rubber, and coconut exports."},
  "chad": {"1960":"In 1960 Chad gained full independence from France on 11 August 1960, with François Tombalbaye as its first president. The former French Equatorial African territory was a vast, landlocked and ethnically divided state, with a Christian and animist south and a Muslim north. It retained close ties to France after independence.","1994":"Chad in 1994 was ruled by Idriss Déby, who had seized power in 1990 and headed a transitional government promising a move toward multiparty democracy. In 1994 the International Court of Justice ruled in Chad's favor in its long dispute with Libya over the Aozou Strip, and Libya withdrew its forces from the territory that year.","2000":"In 2000 Chad was a sovereign republic governed by President Idriss Déby, who had taken power in 1990. The country was preparing for the Chad-Cameroon Petroleum Development and Pipeline Project, with the World Bank approving financing in 2000 to develop the Doba oil fields, while a long-running rebellion continued in the north.","2010":"In 2010 Chad was a republic under President Idriss Déby, who had ruled since 1990. A January 2010 rapprochement with neighboring Sudan eased years of cross-border proxy conflict tied to the Darfur war, and the UN peacekeeping mission MINURCAT began winding down at Chad's request that year. Oil revenue from the Doba fields was central to the economy.","2026":"Chad is a republic in Central Africa led by President Mahamat Idriss Déby, who took power after his father's death in 2021 and won a 2024 election cementing the transition from a military junta to civilian rule. The country faces instability in the Sahel, Boko Haram threats around Lake Chad, and a large influx of refugees fleeing the war in neighboring Sudan."},
  "chile": {"1900":"Chile in 1900 was an independent republic governed under the 1833 constitution as modified after the 1891 civil war, operating in a parliamentary-style system in which Congress dominated the executive. Its economy was buoyed by nitrate exports from the northern provinces it had taken from Peru and Bolivia in the War of the Pacific (1879-1883).","1920":"In 1920 Chile was a republic that elected the reformist Arturo Alessandri to the presidency, reflecting demands from the middle and working classes for change. The economy depended heavily on nitrate exports, which were entering decline as synthetic substitutes emerged. Chile still held the formerly Bolivian and Peruvian territories won in the War of the Pacific.","1938":"In 1938 Chile was a republic that had just elected, in the October presidential election, Pedro Aguirre Cerda of the leftist Popular Front coalition, who took office in late December. The year was marked by the Seguro Obrero massacre in September, when police killed dozens of young members of the National Socialist Movement of Chile after a failed putsch tied to the Ibáñez candidacy. The economy was still recovering from the Great Depression, which had hit Chile's nitrate and copper exports especially hard.","1960":"In 1960 Chile was a republic with a long-established democratic tradition, governed by President Jorge Alessandri. In May 1960 it was struck by the most powerful earthquake ever recorded, the magnitude 9.5 Valdivia earthquake, which devastated the south and caused a Pacific-wide tsunami. The country had a market economy heavily dependent on copper exports.","1994":"Chile in 1994 was a democratic republic in which Eduardo Frei Ruiz-Tagle, of the center-left Concertación coalition, took office as president in March, succeeding Patricio Aylwin. The country continued its consolidation of democracy after the 1990 end of Augusto Pinochet's military rule, while Pinochet remained commander-in-chief of the army.","2000":"In 2000 Chile was a democratic republic; Socialist Ricardo Lagos was inaugurated as president in March 2000, the first Socialist to lead the country since Salvador Allende. The period was marked by the aftermath of former dictator Augusto Pinochet's 1998 detention in London and his return to Chile in 2000, where efforts to prosecute him for human-rights abuses were underway.","2010":"In 2010 Chile was a stable democratic republic that saw billionaire Sebastián Piñera inaugurated in March, the first elected right-of-center president since the return of democracy. On 27 February 2010 a magnitude 8.8 earthquake and tsunami struck central Chile, killing several hundred people, and in October the world watched the rescue of 33 miners trapped underground at the San José mine near Copiapó.","2026":"Chile is a republic in South America. President Gabriel Boric of the left led the government through 2025, and a presidential election held in late 2025 went to a runoff in December, after which a new president was set to take office in March 2026; the contest featured the rise of right-wing candidates amid concerns over crime and migration."},
  "china": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory of China was governed by the People's Republic of China under the Communist Party led by Mao Zedong, with the rival Republic of China confined to Taiwan. The PRC was in the grip of the Great Leap Forward, whose collectivization and policy failures combined with poor harvests to produce a catastrophic famine that killed tens of millions. In 1960 the Sino-Soviet split deepened sharply as the Soviet Union abruptly withdrew its advisers and aid.","1994":"In 1994 the People's Republic of China was a one-party state under the Communist Party, with Jiang Zemin as Party general secretary and president and Deng Xiaoping, though aged and in declining health, still the paramount influence behind the reform program. The economy was growing rapidly amid market-oriented reforms, and in 1994 China unified its dual exchange rates and devalued the yuan.","2000":"In 2000 the People's Republic of China was a one-party socialist state ruled by the Communist Party, with Jiang Zemin as President and General Secretary and Zhu Rongji as Premier. The country was undergoing rapid economic growth and market reform, and was negotiating its entry into the World Trade Organization, which it would formally join in 2001.","2010":"In 2010 the People's Republic of China was a one-party socialist state led by the Communist Party under Hu Jintao as president and Wen Jiabao as premier. That year China overtook Japan to become the world's second-largest economy, and it hosted Expo 2010 in Shanghai. Jailed dissident Liu Xiaobo was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 2010, drawing strong objection from Beijing.","2026":"China is governed as a one-party socialist state under the Chinese Communist Party, with Xi Jinping holding the posts of CCP general secretary, state president, and military commission chairman. In 2026 the country contends with slowing economic growth, a property-sector slump, demographic decline, and continued tensions with the United States over trade and with neighbors over Taiwan and the South China Sea."},
  "chinese warlords": {"1920":"In 1920 China was nominally a republic under the Beijing government but was fractured among regional militarists in the Warlord Era that followed Yuan Shikai's death in 1916. That year the Anhui clique of Duan Qirui was defeated by the allied Zhili and Fengtian cliques in the Zhili–Anhui War, shifting control of Beijing. Real power lay with rival warlord armies across the provinces rather than any single central authority.","1938":"By 1938 the era of fully autonomous warlord regimes had largely given way to nominal unification under the Nationalist government, but regional militarists still commanded their own armies and territories within the framework of the Second Sino-Japanese War, which had begun in July 1937. Figures and cliques such as the Guangxi clique, Yan Xishan in Shanxi, and Ma family commanders in the northwest retained considerable local power while fighting or maneuvering against the Japanese invasion. The war pushed many former rivals into the Second United Front alongside the Nationalists and Communists against Japan."},
  "clipperton i.": {"1960":"In 1960 Clipperton Island was an uninhabited French possession in the eastern Pacific Ocean. Sovereignty had been awarded to France in a 1931 arbitration by the King of Italy, settling a long dispute with Mexico. The low coral atoll had no permanent population and was administered as part of France's overseas holdings.","1994":"Clipperton Island in 1994 was an uninhabited French overseas possession in the eastern Pacific Ocean, administered by France. It had no permanent population and was visited only occasionally.","2000":"In 2000 Clipperton Island was an uninhabited French overseas possession in the eastern Pacific Ocean, administered as part of France's state private domain. It had no permanent population and was used chiefly in connection with fishing rights in its surrounding waters.","2010":"Clipperton Island in 2010 was an uninhabited French overseas possession in the eastern Pacific Ocean, administered directly by the French government. It had no permanent population and was used mainly in connection with fishing rights and its surrounding exclusive economic zone.","2026":"Clipperton Island is an uninhabited coral atoll in the eastern Pacific Ocean that belongs to France and is administered as part of the French overseas domain. It has no permanent population and is occasionally visited by the French Navy and scientific expeditions."},
  "cochin china": {"1920":"Cochinchina in 1920 was the southernmost region of French Indochina, governed directly as a French colony with Saigon as its center, unlike the protectorates of Annam and Tonkin. It was administered by a French governor and was the most economically integrated part of the colony, centered on rice exports from the Mekong Delta.","1938":"In 1938 Cochinchina was the southern, directly administered French colony of French Indochina, centered on Saigon and the Mekong Delta. Unlike the protectorates of Annam and Tonkin, it was governed as a colony under a French governor and was the most economically developed part of Indochina, a major exporter of rice and rubber. It remained firmly under French colonial control on the eve of the Second World War."},
  "colombia": {"1900":"Colombia was an independent republic that in 1900 was engulfed in the Thousand Days' War (1899-1902), a devastating civil war between the ruling Conservatives and the Liberals. The country still included the Isthmus of Panama, which would not separate until 1903.","1920":"Colombia in 1920 was an independent republic, in the period of Conservative Party hegemony that had governed since the 1880s. Its economy was expanding around coffee exports, and it was still recovering from the loss of Panama in 1903, for which the United States later paid compensation.","1938":"In 1938 Colombia was a republic governed by the Liberal Party; Eduardo Santos was elected president that year, succeeding Alfonso López Pumarejo and taking office in August. The country celebrated the 400th anniversary of the founding of Bogotá in 1938. Santos's administration moderated the pace of the social and economic reforms of López's preceding 'Revolución en Marcha.'","1960":"In 1960 Colombia was a sovereign republic governed under the National Front, a power-sharing pact between the Liberal and Conservative parties that alternated the presidency to end the partisan civil conflict known as La Violencia. Alberto Lleras Camargo, a Liberal, served as president, having taken office in 1958 as the first National Front leader.","1994":"Colombia in 1994 was a democratic republic; Ernesto Samper of the Liberal Party won the presidential election and took office in August, succeeding César Gaviria. The Medellín drug cartel had been broken after the 1993 death of Pablo Escobar, but Samper's campaign was soon engulfed by allegations that it had received funding from the Cali cartel.","2000":"In 2000 Colombia was a republic led by President Andrés Pastrana Arango. The country was engulfed in its long-running internal armed conflict with leftist guerrillas such as the FARC and ELN and right-wing paramilitaries, and in 2000 the United States approved Plan Colombia, a major aid package to combat drug trafficking and insurgency.","2010":"In 2010 Colombia was a democratic republic where Juan Manuel Santos was elected president and inaugurated in August, succeeding Álvaro Uribe. The state continued its long counter-insurgency against the FARC guerrillas, and in September 2010 a military operation killed senior FARC commander Mono Jojoy.","2026":"Colombia is a republic in South America led by President Gustavo Petro, its first leftist president, who took office in 2022 and continued his 'total peace' negotiations with armed groups while clashing with the United States. A presidential election is scheduled for 2026, as Petro is barred from immediate reelection by a single-term limit."},
  "comoros": {"1994":"The Comoros in 1994 was an independent federal republic in the Indian Ocean led by President Said Mohamed Djohar. The country remained politically unstable and impoverished, with continuing tensions that had earlier involved the mercenary Bob Denard.","2000":"In 2000 the Comoros was in political crisis following the 1997 secessionist declarations of the islands of Anjouan and Mohéli and a 1999 coup that brought Colonel Azali Assoumani to power. Efforts mediated by the Organisation of African Unity were underway to resolve the secession dispute and restore national unity.","2026":"The Comoros is an island republic in the Indian Ocean off East Africa, led by President Azali Assoumani, who won a disputed reelection in 2024. The country remains one of the world's poorest and continues to claim the French-administered island of Mayotte."},
  "congo": {"1900":"In 1900 the Congo was the Congo Free State, a vast territory in central Africa held as the personal possession of King Leopold II of Belgium rather than by the Belgian state. Its administration was notorious for forced labor and brutal exploitation of the population in the extraction of rubber and ivory.","1960":"The French colony of Middle Congo became the independent Republic of the Congo (Congo-Brazzaville) on 15 August 1960, with Fulbert Youlou as its first president. It emerged from French Equatorial Africa during the wave of African decolonization that year.","1994":"The Republic of the Congo in 1994, with its capital at Brazzaville, was a multiparty state under President Pascal Lissouba, who had been elected in 1992. The period was marked by serious tension and intermittent armed clashes between rival political militias in Brazzaville.","2000":"In 2000 the Republic of the Congo (Congo-Brazzaville) was led by President Denis Sassou Nguesso, who had returned to power after winning the 1997 civil war. The country was recovering from renewed conflict in 1998-1999, and a ceasefire process with militia groups was underway.","2010":"In 2010 the Republic of the Congo (Congo-Brazzaville) was governed by President Denis Sassou Nguesso, who had returned to power in 1997. The oil-exporting central African state celebrated fifty years of independence from France in 2010.","2026":"The Republic of the Congo (Congo-Brazzaville) is a republic in Central Africa led by President Denis Sassou Nguesso, who has dominated the country's politics for decades and remains in power. The oil-dependent economy faces heavy debt and economic difficulties; a presidential election is due in 2026."},
  "congo (france)": {"1938":"In 1938 French Congo (Moyen-Congo, with Brazzaville) was a territory of French Equatorial Africa, a federation of French colonies administered from Brazzaville. It remained under French colonial rule as part of the wider AEF grouping that also included Gabon, Ubangi-Shari, and Chad. The territory's economy was based on extraction and forced or coerced labor characteristic of the period."},
  "cook is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Cook Islands were a dependent territory administered by New Zealand. They had not yet attained the self-governing status in free association with New Zealand that came in 1965.","1994":"The Cook Islands in 1994 was a self-governing territory in free association with New Zealand, whose residents held New Zealand citizenship and which relied on New Zealand for defense and external affairs. It was led by a prime minister, with Geoffrey Henry heading the government.","2000":"In 2000 the Cook Islands was a self-governing state in free association with New Zealand, with New Zealand responsible for defence and external affairs and Cook Islanders holding New Zealand citizenship. It had its own parliamentary government and was recovering from a severe economic and financial crisis of the mid-1990s.","2010":"In 2010 the Cook Islands was a self-governing nation in free association with New Zealand, with Cook Islanders holding New Zealand citizenship and New Zealand responsible for defense and some foreign affairs. It had its own parliamentary government in Rarotonga, with the British monarch as head of state represented locally.","2026":"The Cook Islands is a self-governing state in free association with New Zealand in the South Pacific, with New Zealand responsible for defense and many Cook Islanders holding New Zealand citizenship. In 2025 the government signed cooperation agreements with China, which created friction with New Zealand over consultation."},
  "coral sea is.": {"1994":"The Coral Sea Islands in 1994 were an uninhabited external territory of Australia, consisting of small reefs and islands northeast of Queensland. They had no permanent population and were administered by Australia, with only a staffed weather station on Willis Island.","2000":"In 2000 the Coral Sea Islands were an external territory of Australia, comprising small uninhabited reefs and islets off the northeastern coast. They had no permanent civilian population, with a meteorological station staffed on Willis Island.","2010":"In 2010 the Coral Sea Islands were an uninhabited external territory of Australia, consisting of small reefs and islets east of Queensland. They had no permanent population apart from a manned weather station on Willis Island and were administered by the Australian federal government.","2026":"The Coral Sea Islands Territory is an external territory of Australia comprising small, mostly uninhabited reefs and islands off Australia's northeast coast. It has no permanent civilian population, hosting only a small weather station staff on Willis Island, and is administered by the Australian federal government."},
  "costa rica": {"1900":"Costa Rica was an independent Central American republic, which around 1900 was governed under a relatively stable constitutional order. Its economy depended heavily on coffee and increasingly on banana exports, the latter tied to foreign companies and the railway to the Caribbean coast.","1920":"Costa Rica in 1920 was an independent republic, having restored constitutional government after the overthrow of the Tinoco dictatorship in 1919. Its economy depended heavily on coffee and banana exports.","1938":"In 1938 Costa Rica was a republic under President León Cortés Castro, whose term ran from 1936 to 1940. His government was conservative and pursued public-works and infrastructure projects while the economy depended heavily on coffee and banana exports. The country remained politically stable relative to many of its neighbors.","1960":"In 1960 Costa Rica was a stable democratic republic, having abolished its army in 1948. Mario Echandi Jiménez served as president, and the country maintained its tradition of civilian constitutional government in Central America.","1994":"Costa Rica in 1994 was a stable democratic republic without a standing army; José María Figueres Olsen of the National Liberation Party won the presidency and took office in May, succeeding Rafael Ángel Calderón Fournier.","2000":"In 2000 Costa Rica was a stable democratic republic led by President Miguel Ángel Rodríguez of the Social Christian Unity Party. The country maintained its long tradition of having no standing army and a comparatively high level of social development for the region.","2010":"In 2010 Costa Rica was a stable democratic republic that inaugurated Laura Chinchilla in May as its first female president, succeeding Óscar Arias. The country, which has had no standing army since 1948, remained one of Central America's most stable democracies. A border dispute with Nicaragua over the Isla Calero/San Juan River area flared in late 2010.","2026":"Costa Rica is a stable presidential democracy in Central America with no standing army, a status it has maintained since 1948. In 2026 it held general elections, with Rodrigo Chaves Robles constitutionally barred from immediate re-election after his single term ending in 2026."},
  "cotonou": {"1900":"Cotonou was a coastal town on the Bight of Benin that France had acquired and used as a port and foothold in the region. By 1900 it lay within the French colony of Dahomey, part of French West Africa, serving as a principal port for the territory."},
  "croatia": {"1994":"Croatia in 1994 was an independent republic, recognized internationally since 1992, with Franjo Tuđman as president. Much of the country remained outside government control in the self-proclaimed Serb entity of Krajina, and in 1994 the Washington Agreement created a Bosniak-Croat federation in neighboring Bosnia, easing Croat-Bosniak fighting there.","2000":"In 2000 Croatia underwent a major political transition: long-time President Franjo Tuđman died in late 1999, and in early 2000 elections a center-left coalition took power and Stjepan Mesić was elected president. The new government moved to reduce presidential powers, cooperate with the international war-crimes tribunal, and pursue integration with the European Union and NATO.","2010":"In 2010 Croatia was a parliamentary republic and a candidate for European Union membership, actively negotiating its accession. Ivo Josipović was inaugurated as president in February 2010, and Jadranka Kosor served as prime minister. The country was already a NATO member, having joined in 2009.","2026":"Croatia is a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union and NATO, having adopted the euro and joined the Schengen Area at the start of 2023. In 2026 it remains governed under Prime Minister Andrej Plenkovic's HDZ-led government, with Zoran Milanovic as president."},
  "cuba": {"1920":"Cuba in 1920 was an independent republic but under heavy United States influence through the Platt Amendment, which permitted American intervention. The presidency of Mario García Menocal coincided with the collapse of the sugar boom known as the Dance of the Millions, when wartime sugar prices crashed and triggered a severe financial crisis.","1938":"In 1938 Cuba was a republic in which Fulgencio Batista, as army chief of staff, was the dominant power behind a series of presidents. That year the Communist Party of Cuba was legalized as Batista shifted toward a more populist, reformist alignment ahead of the constitutional convention process. The economy remained dependent on sugar and closely tied to the United States.","1960":"In 1960 Cuba was governed by the revolutionary regime that had taken power under Fidel Castro in January 1959, and the year saw a rapid radicalization and break with the United States. The government nationalized American-owned businesses and sugar mills and signed trade agreements with the Soviet Union, while Washington imposed economic sanctions, moving toward the embargo and the severing of relations.","1994":"Cuba in 1994 was a one-party socialist state led by Fidel Castro, enduring the severe economic crisis of the post-Soviet \"Special Period\" after the loss of Soviet subsidies. In August 1994 a wave of unrest in Havana and a mass exodus of rafters (the balseros) led to a migration accord with the United States.","2000":"In 2000 Cuba was a one-party socialist state led by Fidel Castro. The country was still coping with the economic hardship of the post-Soviet \"Special Period,\" and 2000 was dominated by the high-profile international custody dispute over the young Cuban boy Elián González, who was returned to Cuba that year.","2010":"In 2010 Cuba was a one-party socialist state led by Raúl Castro, who had formally succeeded his brother Fidel as president in 2008. That year the government announced major economic reforms, including plans to lay off large numbers of state workers and expand private-sector self-employment, and it released a number of political prisoners in an arrangement involving the Catholic Church and Spain.","2026":"Cuba is a one-party socialist state led by the Communist Party, with Miguel Diaz-Canel as president and first secretary. In 2026 the country continues to suffer a severe economic crisis marked by shortages of food, fuel, and medicine, frequent electrical blackouts, and large-scale emigration, all worsened by ongoing U.S. sanctions."},
  "curaçao": {"1960":"In 1960 Curaçao was part of the Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands. The island served as the capital and seat of government of the Netherlands Antilles.","1994":"In 1994 Curaçao was not a separate country but an island that formed part of the Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, with Willemstad as the Antilles' capital. A 1993 referendum on Curaçao had favored remaining within the Netherlands Antilles rather than seeking separate status.","2000":"In 2000 Curaçao was not a separate country but the largest island of the Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands; it would only become a separate constituent country in 2010. The island served as the seat of the Netherlands Antilles government in Willemstad.","2010":"On 10 October 2010 the Netherlands Antilles was dissolved, and Curaçao became a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, gaining autonomy in internal affairs while the Netherlands retained responsibility for defense and foreign policy. Before that date in 2010 it had been an island territory within the Netherlands Antilles.","2026":"Curacao is a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, self-governing in internal affairs while the Netherlands handles defense and foreign policy. In 2026 it remains an autonomous Caribbean island, its economy reliant on tourism and financial services, and it continues to host migrants from neighboring Venezuela."},
  "cyprus": {"1960":"Cyprus became an independent republic on 16 August 1960, ending British colonial rule under the terms of the Zürich and London Agreements, with Britain retaining sovereign base areas. Archbishop Makarios III became the first president, with a Turkish Cypriot vice president, under a power-sharing constitution guaranteed by Britain, Greece, and Turkey.","1994":"In 1994 the Republic of Cyprus was a divided island, with the internationally recognized Greek Cypriot government controlling the south and the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (recognized only by Turkey) holding the north behind the UN-patrolled Green Line. Glafcos Clerides served as president, and the island had been partitioned since the 1974 Turkish invasion. Reunification talks under UN auspices continued without resolution.","2000":"An independent republic that remained de facto partitioned in 2000, with the internationally recognized Greek Cypriot government controlling the south and the Turkish-occupied north (the unrecognized Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus) separated by a UN-patrolled buffer zone. Glafcos Clerides was president, and the Republic was pursuing European Union accession negotiations, which had opened in 1998.","2010":"Cyprus was an independent republic and European Union member state, having joined the EU in 2004 and adopted the euro in 2008. The island remained divided, with the internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus controlling the south and the Turkish-occupied north existing as the unrecognized Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus. Demetris Christofias, elected in 2008, served as president, and reunification talks continued without resolution.","2026":"Cyprus is a presidential republic and European Union member, though the EU's effective control extends only to the Greek Cypriot south, with the island still divided since the 1974 Turkish invasion. In 2026 Nikos Christodoulides serves as president, and efforts to restart reunification talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities continue."},
  "cyprus u.n. buffer zone": {"2026":"The Cyprus U.N. Buffer Zone, or Green Line, is a demilitarized strip dividing the island between the Republic of Cyprus and the Turkish-controlled north, patrolled by the United Nations Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP). In 2026 it remains in place as it has for decades, with the UN mandate periodically renewed by the Security Council."},
  "czechia": {"1994":"In 1994 the Czech Republic was a young sovereign state, having peacefully separated from Slovakia in the dissolution of Czechoslovakia on 1 January 1993. Václav Havel was president and Václav Klaus led a center-right government pursuing market reforms and privatization. The country was orienting itself toward Western institutions, seeking eventual membership in NATO and the European Union.","2000":"An independent parliamentary republic that had emerged from the 1993 dissolution of Czechoslovakia, with Vaclav Havel as president and a minority Social Democratic government under Milos Zeman governing through an opposition agreement with the Civic Democratic Party. The country had joined NATO in 1999 and was in active negotiations to join the European Union.","2010":"The Czech Republic was an independent parliamentary democracy in Central Europe and a member of the European Union, which it had joined in 2004, as well as NATO. In 2010 Václav Klaus was president, and parliamentary elections that year led to a center-right coalition government under Prime Minister Petr Nečas. The country had not adopted the euro, retaining the Czech koruna.","2026":"Czechia is a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union and NATO. In 2026, following October 2025 parliamentary elections won by Andrej Babis's ANO movement, Babis returned as prime minister, with Petr Pavel serving as president."},
  "czechoslovakia": {"1920":"Czechoslovakia in 1920 was a newly independent republic created in 1918 from the breakup of Austria-Hungary, with Tomáš Garrigue Masaryk as its first president. In February 1920 it adopted a democratic constitution, establishing one of the more stable parliamentary states of interwar central Europe.","1938":"In 1938 Czechoslovakia was a democratic republic under President Edvard Beneš that faced its gravest crisis as Nazi Germany pressed demands over the German-speaking Sudetenland. At the Munich Conference in September, Britain, France, Italy, and Germany agreed to force Czechoslovakia to cede the Sudetenland without Czechoslovak participation, and it also lost territory to Poland and Hungary. Beneš resigned and went into exile, leaving the weakened, truncated 'Second Republic' that would be dismembered in March 1939.","1960":"In 1960 Czechoslovakia was a communist state within the Soviet bloc, ruled by the Communist Party under Antonín Novotný. That year a new constitution renamed the country the Czechoslovak Socialist Republic, proclaiming the achievement of socialism."},
  "côte d'ivoire": {"1960":"Côte d'Ivoire (Ivory Coast) gained independence from France on 7 August 1960, with Félix Houphouët-Boigny as its first president. It emerged from French West Africa and maintained close political and economic ties with France.","1994":"In 1994 Côte d'Ivoire was a one-party-dominated republic adjusting to the death of its founding president Félix Houphouët-Boigny in December 1993, with Henri Konan Bédié having succeeded him. The CFA franc was devalued by 50 percent in January 1994, causing economic hardship across the franc zone. Bédié's government promoted the divisive concept of \"Ivoirité\" as political competition intensified.","2000":"A West African republic in political turmoil around 2000 following a December 1999 military coup led by General Robert Guei that ousted President Henri Konan Bedie. A disputed October 2000 election brought Laurent Gbagbo to power amid violence after Guei attempted to claim victory, and the exclusion of Alassane Ouattara from the race deepened ethnic and regional tensions.","2010":"Côte d'Ivoire was a republic in West Africa that held a long-delayed presidential election in late 2010. The disputed result, in which both incumbent Laurent Gbagbo and Alassane Ouattara claimed victory, triggered a major political crisis and the second Ivorian civil war. The country remained effectively split between a government-controlled south and a rebel-held north in the years leading up to the vote.","2026":"Cote d'Ivoire is a presidential republic in West Africa and one of the region's largest economies, the world's leading cocoa producer. In 2026 Alassane Ouattara remains president following the October 2025 election, in which he won a contested fourth term."},
  "dahomey": {"1900":"By 1900 Dahomey, the former West African kingdom, had been conquered by France in the wars of 1890-1894 and annexed as a French colony. It was incorporated into the federation of French West Africa, administered by French colonial officials after the deposition of its last independent king, Behanzin."},
  "dem. rep. congo": {"1960":"The Belgian Congo became the independent Democratic Republic of the Congo on 30 June 1960, with Joseph Kasa-Vubu as president and Patrice Lumumba as prime minister. Independence was immediately followed by the Congo Crisis: an army mutiny, the secession of Katanga under Moïse Tshombe, the arrival of UN forces, and Lumumba's dismissal and arrest amid a power struggle with Kasa-Vubu and Colonel Mobutu.","1994":"In 1994 this state was named Zaire and was ruled by the long-standing dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. It was overwhelmed by a massive influx of Rwandan refugees, including Hutu génocidaires fleeing into the eastern Kivu region after the Rwandan genocide and the RPF victory. The country's economy was in deep decay and Mobutu's authority was eroding amid demands for democratization.","2000":"A central African state ruled by President Laurent-Desire Kabila and engulfed in the Second Congo War, which had begun in 1998 and drew in multiple African nations. The country was effectively split, with Rwandan- and Ugandan-backed rebels holding the east, and the 1999 Lusaka Ceasefire Agreement largely unimplemented as fighting continued.","2010":"The Democratic Republic of the Congo was a large republic in Central Africa led by President Joseph Kabila. In 2010 the country marked fifty years of independence from Belgium, while continuing to face armed conflict in its eastern provinces involving numerous militias and a large United Nations peacekeeping presence. The mission was renamed MONUSCO in 2010.","2026":"The Democratic Republic of the Congo is a large central African presidential republic led by President Felix Tshisekedi. In 2026 its eastern provinces remain engulfed in conflict, with the M23 rebel group, backed by Rwanda, having seized the major cities of Goma and Bukavu in early 2025, prompting a U.S.-brokered peace effort."},
  "denmark": {"1900":"Denmark in 1900 was a constitutional monarchy under King Christian IX, governed under the 1849 constitution as later revised. Its politics were marked by a long struggle between the conservative governments appointed by the king and the Liberal-dominated lower house of parliament, a conflict resolved only with the parliamentary breakthrough of 1901; Denmark still held Iceland, the Faroes, Greenland, and the Danish West Indies.","1920":"Denmark in 1920 was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Christian X. That year, following plebiscites mandated by the Treaty of Versailles, the northern part of Schleswig was reunited with Denmark. The year also saw the Easter Crisis, a constitutional confrontation when the king dismissed the elected government.","1938":"In 1938 Denmark was a constitutional monarchy under King Christian X with a Social Democratic-led government headed by Prime Minister Thorvald Stauning. The country pursued a neutral foreign policy while warily watching Nazi Germany to its south; in 1939 it would sign a non-aggression pact with Germany. Domestically the Social Democrats continued their welfare-state and cooperative economic policies.","1960":"In 1960 Denmark was a constitutional monarchy under King Frederik IX and a parliamentary democracy. It was a member of NATO and joined the newly formed European Free Trade Association that year.","1994":"In 1994 Denmark was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Margrethe II, governed by a Social Democrat-led coalition under Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen. It was a member of the European Union, having ratified the Maastricht Treaty in 1993 after a second referendum, but retained opt-outs including from the single currency. A general election was held in September 1994.","2000":"A constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy under Queen Margrethe II, governed by a Social Democratic-led coalition with Poul Nyrup Rasmussen as prime minister. In a September 2000 referendum, Danish voters rejected adopting the euro, choosing to keep the krone.","2010":"Denmark was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy in Northern Europe under Queen Margrethe II, and a member of the European Union and NATO. In 2010 the government was a center-right coalition led by Prime Minister Lars Løkke Rasmussen of the Venstre party. Denmark retained its own currency, the krone, having opted out of the euro.","2026":"Denmark is a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy, a member of the European Union and NATO, with King Frederik X on the throne since 2024. In 2026 Mette Frederiksen continues as prime minister, and tensions persist over U.S. President Trump's stated ambitions to acquire the Danish autonomous territory of Greenland."},
  "dhekelia": {"2026":"Dhekelia is one of two British Sovereign Base Areas on Cyprus, remaining under United Kingdom sovereignty since Cypriot independence in 1960 and used as a military base. In 2026 it continues as British overseas territory administered alongside Akrotiri."},
  "djibouti": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory of present-day Djibouti was a French colony known as French Somaliland. It remained under French administration and had not yet moved toward independence.","1994":"In 1994 Djibouti was a republic led by President Hassan Gouled Aptidon, in power since independence from France in 1977. The country was emerging from a civil war that had begun in 1991 between the government and the Afar-based FRUD rebels; a peace agreement was reached with a faction of FRUD in December 1994. Djibouti retained close ties with France, which maintained a military base there.","2000":"A small Horn of Africa republic led by President Ismail Omar Guelleh, who had taken office in 1999 succeeding Hassan Gouled Aptidon. In 2000 the government pursued peace negotiations to end the conflict with the Afar FRUD rebel faction, and the country hosted strategic port and military facilities.","2010":"Djibouti was a small republic in the Horn of Africa led by President Ismaïl Omar Guelleh. In 2010 the constitution was amended to remove presidential term limits, allowing Guelleh to seek further terms. The country's strategic location near the Bab-el-Mandeb strait hosted foreign military bases, including French and American forces.","2026":"Djibouti is a small Horn of Africa republic strategically positioned at the entrance to the Red Sea, led by long-serving President Ismail Omar Guelleh. In 2026 it continues to host foreign military bases from the United States, France, China, Japan, and others, deriving significant revenue from port and basing fees."},
  "dominica": {"1800":"In 1800, Dominica was a British colony that France had ceded in the 1763 Treaty of Paris, though its population and planter class remained heavily Francophone. In 1800, the island was administered as a separate Crown colony governed from Roseau, with a British-appointed administration and a legislative assembly that represented only the white settler minority. In 1800, its economy rested on plantation agriculture, especially coffee and sugar, worked by an enslaved African majority who vastly outnumbered the European inhabitants. In 1800, enslaved Africans continued to be landed on the island as part of a heavy wave of arrivals in the years before Britain abolished the slave trade in 1807. In 1800, Dominica still faced the threat of French attack, and Roseau would be raided and largely burned by a French naval force in 1805.","1900":"Dominica was a British colony in the Lesser Antilles of the Caribbean, with a population largely descended from enslaved Africans and a mountainous, agricultural interior. Around 1900 it was administered as part of Britain's Leeward Islands federation.","1920":"Dominica in 1920 was a British colony in the Lesser Antilles, administered as part of the Leeward Islands. Its economy rested on small-scale agriculture including limes and cocoa.","1938":"In 1938 Dominica was a British colony in the Leeward Islands (administered within the British West Indies). It remained under colonial administration, with an economy based on agriculture such as limes and other tropical produce. The wider British Caribbean experienced significant labor unrest in the late 1930s.","1960":"In 1960 Dominica was a British colony in the Windward Islands and a member of the West Indies Federation, which had been established in 1958. It was governed under British colonial administration with a local legislature, and remained far from independence at this point.","2000":"A small independent parliamentary republic in the eastern Caribbean and a member of the Commonwealth. Following January 2000 elections, Roosevelt Douglas of the Dominica Labour Party became prime minister, but he died suddenly in October 2000 and was succeeded by Pierre Charles.","2010":"Dominica was an independent island nation in the eastern Caribbean and a parliamentary democracy within the Commonwealth. In 2009 Prime Minister Roosevelt Skerrit's Dominica Labour Party won re-election, and he remained in office through 2010. The country was a member of CARICOM and the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States.","2026":"Dominica is a parliamentary republic and Caribbean island nation, a member of the Commonwealth, with Roosevelt Skerrit serving as long-time prime minister. In 2026 it remains focused on rebuilding climate resilience after past hurricane damage and pursuing its goal of becoming a climate-resilient nation."},
  "dominican rep.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Dominican Republic was ruled by the dictatorship of Rafael Trujillo, who had dominated the country since 1930. That year his agents attempted to assassinate Venezuelan president Romulo Betancourt, prompting the Organization of American States to impose sanctions and break relations; the regime also faced growing internal opposition, and the Mirabal sisters were murdered by his secret police in November 1960.","1994":"In 1994 the Dominican Republic was a republic whose May 1994 presidential election returned the aging Joaquín Balaguer to office amid widespread allegations of fraud against his rival José Francisco Peña Gómez. The disputed result triggered a political crisis, resolved by a pact that shortened Balaguer's term to two years and barred his immediate re-election. The country shares the island of Hispaniola with Haiti.","2000":"A Caribbean republic occupying the eastern part of Hispaniola, holding presidential elections in May 2000 that brought Hipolito Mejia of the Dominican Revolutionary Party to office, succeeding Leonel Fernandez. The economy was among the fastest-growing in the region during this period.","2010":"The Dominican Republic was a presidential republic occupying the eastern portion of the island of Hispaniola, led by President Leonel Fernández. In 2010 the country adopted a new constitution, and it provided significant aid and support to neighboring Haiti following the devastating January 2010 earthquake. Its economy relied heavily on tourism, remittances, and services.","2026":"The Dominican Republic is a presidential representative democracy occupying the eastern two-thirds of Hispaniola, with Luis Abinader as president after winning re-election in 2024. In 2026 the country maintains one of the strongest economies in the Caribbean and continues to grapple with instability and migration pressures stemming from neighboring Haiti, including ongoing construction of a border wall."},
  "dominican republic": {"1900":"The Dominican Republic was an independent republic occupying the eastern part of the island of Hispaniola. By 1900 it was burdened by heavy foreign debt and chronic political instability, with the long dictatorship of Ulises Heureaux having ended in his assassination in 1899.","1920":"The Dominican Republic in 1920 was under United States military occupation, which had begun in 1916, with a U.S. military governor administering the country. American forces controlled the customs, finances, and administration during this period.","1938":"In 1938 the Dominican Republic was under the dictatorship of Rafael Trujillo, who that year arranged for a figurehead, Jacinto Peynado, to hold the presidency while he retained absolute control. The regime was still in the aftermath of the October 1937 Parsley Massacre, in which thousands of Haitians and Haitian-descended people near the border were killed on Trujillo's orders. Trujillo dominated the economy and political life through repression and personal enrichment."},
  "dominion of newfoundland": {"1920":"Newfoundland in 1920 was a self-governing dominion of the British Empire, separate from Canada. It depended heavily on the cod fishery and was burdened by debt incurred during the First World War, in which its regiment had suffered heavy losses.","1938":"In 1938 Newfoundland was no longer self-governing; having suspended responsible government in 1934 amid financial collapse, it was administered by a British-appointed Commission of Government. It remained a distinct dominion in name but was effectively ruled directly from London by the Commission. The Depression-era economy, heavily dependent on fishing, remained troubled."},
  "dutch east indies": {"1800":"In 1800, the former Company possessions had just passed into the hands of the Batavian Republic, with Pieter Gerardus van Overstraten serving as Governor-General at Batavia. He was both the last Company Governor-General and the first appointed under direct state rule, presiding over a colony still administered by the inherited Council of the Indies. Effective Dutch authority remained concentrated on Java and a network of coastal forts and enclaves rather than the wider archipelago. The colony was drawn into the wider Revolutionary and Napoleonic conflicts, its shipping and outposts vulnerable to British naval power following the collapse of the old Dutch Republic. Administration in this period was strained by war, corruption inherited from the Company, and the disruption of trade with a besieged homeland.","1920":"The Dutch East Indies in 1920 was a colony of the Netherlands encompassing the Indonesian archipelago, administered from Batavia under a Dutch governor-general. The colony was a major exporter of commodities such as sugar, rubber, oil, and tobacco, and nascent nationalist and Islamic movements like Sarekat Islam were growing.","1938":"In 1938 the Dutch East Indies was a colony of the Netherlands encompassing present-day Indonesia, governed from Batavia under a Dutch governor-general. It was a major producer of oil, rubber, tin, sugar, and other commodities. Indonesian nationalist movements were active but suppressed, with leaders such as Sukarno in detention or exile under Dutch authority."},
  "dutch guiana": {"1900":"Dutch Guiana, also known as Surinam, was a colony of the Netherlands on the northeastern coast of South America. By 1900 its plantation economy, after the abolition of slavery in 1863, relied substantially on indentured laborers brought from British India and the Dutch East Indies."},
  "east prussia": {"1920":"East Prussia in 1920 was a province of Germany that had been geographically separated from the rest of the country by the Polish Corridor established under the Treaty of Versailles. In July 1920 plebiscites in the Allenstein and Marienwerder areas resulted in large majorities to remain with Germany rather than join Poland."},
  "ecuador": {"1900":"Ecuador was an independent republic on South America's Pacific coast. In 1900 it was led by President Eloy Alfaro, who had taken power in the 1895 Liberal Revolution and was pursuing anticlerical and modernizing reforms, including beginning construction of the railway linking Guayaquil to Quito.","1920":"Ecuador in 1920 was an independent republic governed by the Liberal Party, which had held power since the revolution of 1895. Its economy was dominated by cacao exports, which were entering a crisis as disease and falling prices undercut the trade.","1938":"In 1938 Ecuador was politically unstable, governed for most of the year by the military strongman Alberto Enríquez Gallo, who had taken power in late 1937 and notably enacted a labor code before handing power toward a constituent process. The country experienced rapid changes of leadership characteristic of the era. Its economy depended on agricultural exports such as cacao.","1960":"In 1960 Ecuador was a sovereign republic, and Jose Maria Velasco Ibarra was elected to the presidency that year, beginning another of his several terms. The country faced economic difficulties and political instability typical of the period.","1994":"In 1994 Ecuador was a republic under President Sixto Durán Ballén, who pursued market-oriented economic reforms and privatization. His government faced a major indigenous uprising organized by CONAIE over land and agrarian policy in 1994. Tensions with Peru over the disputed border region persisted, escalating into war in early 1995.","2000":"A South American republic that experienced acute instability in January 2000, when a coup backed by indigenous protesters and junior military officers toppled President Jamil Mahuad amid a severe economic and banking crisis. Vice President Gustavo Noboa assumed the presidency, and the country moved to adopt the US dollar as its official currency, abandoning the sucre.","2010":"Ecuador was a presidential republic in South America led by President Rafael Correa. In September 2010 the country experienced a police revolt that Correa characterized as an attempted coup, during which he was briefly confined in a hospital before being freed by the military. The economy used the U.S. dollar, which Ecuador had adopted in 2000.","2026":"Ecuador is a presidential republic on South America's Pacific coast, with Daniel Noboa as president after winning re-election in the April 2025 runoff. The country remains gripped by a security crisis driven by drug-trafficking gangs, and Noboa has continued his militarized \"internal armed conflict\" crackdown declared in early 2024."},
  "egypt": {"1900":"In 1900 Egypt was nominally an autonomous province of the Ottoman Empire ruled by the Khedive Abbas II, but in practice it was under British occupation and control following the British takeover in 1882. British power was exercised through the Consul-General, Lord Cromer, who dominated Egyptian finances and administration.","1920":"Egypt in 1920 was a British protectorate, a status declared in 1914, though nominally ruled by Sultan Fuad. The country was in the midst of nationalist agitation following the 1919 revolution led by Saad Zaghlul and the Wafd; the Milner Commission visited in 1920 to investigate the unrest, paving the way toward the 1922 declaration of nominal independence.","1938":"In 1938 Egypt was a nominally independent kingdom under King Farouk I, who had acceded to the throne in 1936. Britain retained substantial influence under the 1936 Anglo-Egyptian Treaty, which permitted British troops to remain in the Suez Canal Zone, while domestic politics were dominated by the rivalry between the palace and the nationalist Wafd party.","1960":"In 1960 Egypt was governed by Gamal Abdel Nasser and was united with Syria as the United Arab Republic, a union formed in 1958. Construction of the Aswan High Dam began in 1960 with Soviet assistance, a centerpiece of Nasser's development and industrialization program.","1994":"In 1994 Egypt was a republic under President Hosni Mubarak, who had held power since 1981. The government was waging a violent campaign against an Islamist insurgency led by groups such as al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya, which targeted security forces, officials, and tourists, damaging the vital tourism industry. Cairo hosted the UN International Conference on Population and Development in September 1994.","2000":"An Arab republic led by President Hosni Mubarak, who had held power since 1981 and continued to dominate politics through the ruling National Democratic Party. Parliamentary elections were held in late 2000 under judicial supervision following a court ruling, and the government maintained its peace treaty with Israel while contending with Islamist opposition.","2010":"Egypt was a republic under the long-ruling President Hosni Mubarak, who had held power since 1981. In 2010 parliamentary elections in November and December were widely criticized as fraudulent and dominated by Mubarak's National Democratic Party. Discontent was building in the months before the January 2011 uprising that would eventually force Mubarak from office.","2026":"Egypt is a presidential republic led by Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, who began a third term in 2024. In 2026 the country faces persistent economic strain, high inflation and external debt following IMF-backed currency reforms, while remaining a key mediator in efforts around Gaza given its border with the territory."},
  "el salvador": {"1900":"El Salvador was an independent republic in Central America, the smallest and most densely populated state in the region. Its economy by 1900 was increasingly dominated by coffee exports, which had displaced earlier indigo cultivation.","1920":"In 1920 El Salvador was an independent republic in Central America, its economy overwhelmingly dependent on coffee exports controlled by a small landowning oligarchy. Jorge Meléndez served as president, part of the Meléndez-Quiñónez family dynasty that dominated Salvadoran politics in this era.","1938":"El Salvador in 1938 was ruled by the authoritarian president General Maximiliano Hernández Martínez, who had taken power in 1931 and consolidated a personal dictatorship. The country remained an agrarian, coffee-export economy still marked by the aftermath of the 1932 peasant uprising and its brutal suppression (La Matanza).","1960":"In 1960 El Salvador was a republic ruled by the regime of Colonel Jose Maria Lemus, who had become president in 1956. Amid economic discontent and political repression, Lemus was overthrown in a military coup in October 1960, replaced by a short-lived governing junta.","1994":"In 1994 El Salvador held its first elections following the 1992 Chapultepec Peace Accords that ended its long civil war, with the former FMLN guerrillas participating as a political party. Armando Calderón Sol of the right-wing ARENA party won the presidency in elections held in March and April 1994. The country was undergoing demobilization, reform of the security forces, and postwar reconstruction.","2000":"A Central American republic governed by President Francisco Flores of the right-wing ARENA party, roughly eight years after the 1992 peace accords that ended its civil war. The former guerrilla movement FMLN had become a major political party and made strong gains in the March 2000 legislative and municipal elections.","2010":"El Salvador was a presidential republic in Central America led by President Mauricio Funes, who took office in 2009 as the first president from the leftist FMLN party. The country used the U.S. dollar as its currency, having adopted it in 2001. It continued to grapple with high levels of gang-related violence.","2026":"El Salvador is a presidential republic governed by Nayib Bukele, who began a constitutionally contested second term in 2024. His government continues the \"state of exception\" gang crackdown that has mass-incarcerated suspected gang members, sharply lowering homicide rates while drawing human-rights criticism; under IMF pressure the country also abolished Bitcoin's status as legal tender in early 2025, limiting its use to voluntary private transactions."},
  "empire of japan": {"1920":"In 1920 the Empire of Japan was a constitutional monarchy under Emperor Taishō and a major world power, having emerged from World War I on the victorious Allied side and gained former German Pacific islands as League of Nations mandates. It held Korea as a colony, Taiwan, and a leasehold in southern Manchuria, and was a founding permanent member of the League of Nations Council, while a postwar economic downturn struck that year.","1938":"By 1938 the Empire of Japan was a constitutional monarchy under Emperor Hirohito, with the military exercising dominant influence over the government. It was deep in the Second Sino-Japanese War begun in 1937, having captured Nanjing in late 1937 and pushing further into China during 1938 with battles such as Taierzhuang and the capture of Wuhan and Canton."},
  "eq. guinea": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory of present-day Equatorial Guinea was a Spanish colonial possession, comprising Rio Muni on the mainland and the island of Fernando Po. In 1959 Spain had reorganized these as overseas provinces; the territory remained under Spanish rule and would not gain independence until 1968.","1994":"In 1994 Equatorial Guinea was ruled by President Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo, who had seized power in 1979. It was nominally a multiparty state but remained an authoritarian regime with a poor human rights record and a suppressed opposition. The economy was beginning to be reshaped by the discovery of substantial offshore oil reserves.","2000":"A small Central African state ruled by President Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo, who had held power since a 1979 coup, governing in an authoritarian manner. Around 2000 the country was beginning to experience a major economic transformation driven by rapidly expanding offshore oil production.","2010":"Equatorial Guinea was a small oil-rich republic in Central Africa ruled by President Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo, in power since 1979. The country held a presidential election in 2009 that Obiang won overwhelmingly amid criticism of its fairness, and his rule continued through 2010. Despite substantial petroleum wealth, much of the population remained in poverty.","2026":"Equatorial Guinea is an oil-rich Central African republic ruled by Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo, the world's longest-serving head of state, in power since 1979. The state remains a tightly controlled authoritarian regime with his son Teodorín as vice-president and presumed successor."},
  "equatorial guinea": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory now called Equatorial Guinea was Spanish Guinea, a colony of Spain comprising the island of Fernando Pó (Bioko) and the mainland enclave of Río Muni. It was administered as a Spanish overseas possession, with cocoa plantations on Fernando Pó central to its economy.","1938":"The territory comprising present-day Equatorial Guinea was in 1938 the Spanish colony of Spanish Guinea, including Río Muni on the mainland and the island of Fernando Po. It was administered by Spain and produced cocoa and timber under a colonial regime, with control affected by the ongoing Spanish Civil War in the metropole."},
  "eritrea": {"1920":"In 1920 Eritrea was a colony of the Kingdom of Italy, governed from Asmara as Italy's oldest African possession. It served as a base for Italian commercial and military interests on the Red Sea coast.","1960":"In 1960 Eritrea was federated with Ethiopia under an arrangement established by the United Nations in 1952, retaining its own assembly and limited autonomy. Ethiopian central authority was progressively eroding this autonomy, and the federation would be formally dissolved and Eritrea annexed in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Eritrea was a newly independent state, having achieved sovereignty in May 1993 after a referendum following its long war of independence from Ethiopia. It was governed by the People's Front for Democracy and Justice under President Isaias Afwerki, who led a single-party transitional government. The country was focused on postwar reconstruction and nation-building.","2000":"A Horn of Africa state led by President Isaias Afwerki, having gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. In 2000 it was concluding the devastating 1998-2000 border war with Ethiopia, with major Ethiopian offensives that year followed by the Algiers Agreement signed in December 2000 to end hostilities.","2010":"Eritrea was a one-party state in the Horn of Africa led by President Isaias Afwerki, who had ruled since independence from Ethiopia in 1993. No national elections had been held, and the country maintained mandatory, often indefinite, national service. In 2009 the United Nations imposed sanctions over Eritrea's alleged support for armed groups in Somalia.","2026":"Eritrea is a one-party authoritarian state in the Horn of Africa, ruled by President Isaias Afwerki since independence in 1993, with no elections held and no implemented constitution. In 2026 tensions with neighboring Ethiopia have risen sharply over Ethiopian aspirations for sea access, raising fears of renewed conflict."},
  "eritrea (italy)": {"1938":"In 1938 Eritrea was an Italian colony, and following Italy's 1936 conquest of Ethiopia it had been incorporated into Italian East Africa. It served as a base and staging area for Italian colonial administration and military forces in the Horn of Africa, with Asmara as its principal city."},
  "estonia": {"1920":"In 1920 Estonia was a newly independent republic, having declared independence in 1918 and successfully defended it in the Estonian War of Independence against Soviet Russia. The Treaty of Tartu signed in February 1920 saw Soviet Russia recognize Estonian independence and renounce claims to the territory.","1938":"Estonia in 1938 was an independent republic that had come under the authoritarian rule of Konstantin Päts following his 1934 coup. A new constitution took effect in 1938 establishing a presidency, and Päts became president; the country pursued a policy of neutrality while remaining wary of both the Soviet Union and Germany.","1994":"In 1994 Estonia was an independent republic, having restored its independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, and had adopted the kroon as its currency in 1992. The last Russian troops withdrew from Estonian territory in August 1994. The government pursued radical free-market reforms and sought integration with Western institutions, while tensions persisted over the status of its large Russian-speaking minority.","2000":"A Baltic parliamentary republic that had regained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, governed in 2000 by a center-right coalition with Mart Laar as prime minister and Lennart Meri as president. The country was pursuing EU and NATO membership and was known for rapid market reforms and growing information-technology development.","2010":"Estonia was an independent parliamentary republic on the Baltic Sea and a member of the European Union and NATO, both joined in 2004. In 2010 the government was led by Prime Minister Andrus Ansip, and the country was approved to adopt the euro, which it would do on 1 January 2011. Toomas Hendrik Ilves served as president.","2026":"Estonia is a parliamentary republic and member of the EU, NATO and the eurozone. In 2026 it remains a strong supporter of Ukraine and a frontline state wary of Russia, having significantly increased defense spending."},
  "eswatini": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory was Swaziland, a British protectorate in southern Africa ruled traditionally under King Sobhuza II alongside British colonial administration. It remained a dependency, and full independence was not achieved until 1968.","1994":"In 1994 the country, then internationally known as Swaziland, was an absolute monarchy ruled by King Mswati III, who had ascended the throne in 1986. Political parties remained banned under the 1973 royal decree, and the kingdom continued to be governed largely through the king and the traditional tinkhundla system. Its capitals were Mbabane (administrative) and Lobamba (royal/legislative).","2000":"In 2000 the country, then internationally known as Swaziland, was an absolute monarchy ruled by King Mswati III, with political parties banned and executive power held by the king and his appointed government. Pro-democracy groups and trade unions pressed for constitutional reform and an end to the long-standing state of emergency. (The country officially renamed itself eSwatini only in 2018.)","2010":"Known in 2010 as the Kingdom of Swaziland, it was a landlocked absolute monarchy in southern Africa ruled by King Mswati III, who held sweeping executive powers under the 2005 constitution. Political parties remained banned from contesting elections, and the country faced one of the world's highest HIV/AIDS prevalence rates along with significant economic and fiscal pressures. The renaming to eSwatini did not occur until 2018.","2026":"eSwatini, formerly Swaziland, is a landlocked absolute monarchy in Southern Africa ruled in 2026 by King Mswati III, who retains sweeping executive powers. The kingdom continues to face calls for democratic reform following the deadly pro-democracy protests of 2021, while remaining economically tied to neighboring South Africa."},
  "ethiopia": {"1900":"Ethiopia was an independent empire ruled by Emperor Menelik II. Having decisively defeated Italy at the Battle of Adwa in 1896, it had secured its sovereignty and was the major African state to resist European colonization; Menelik was expanding the empire's borders and developing his new capital at Addis Ababa.","1920":"In 1920 Ethiopia (Abyssinia) was an independent empire, one of the few African states to retain sovereignty, having defeated Italy at Adwa in 1896. Empress Zewditu reigned as nominal ruler while Ras Tafari Makonnen, the future Haile Selassie, served as regent and heir, holding effective power and steering the country toward modernization.","1960":"In 1960 Ethiopia was an empire ruled by Emperor Haile Selassie I, who had reigned since 1930. In December 1960, while the emperor was abroad, members of the Imperial Guard staged an attempted coup that was suppressed within days, exposing tensions over the slow pace of reform.","1994":"Ethiopia was governed by the Transitional Government led by Meles Zenawi's EPRDF, which had taken power in 1991 after the fall of the Marxist Derg regime under Mengistu Haile Mariam. In 1994 a Constituent Assembly was elected and drafted a new federal constitution that reorganized the country along ethnic lines. Eritrea had effectively separated in 1991 and formally became independent in 1993, leaving Ethiopia landlocked.","2000":"In 2000 Ethiopia was a federal republic whose government was dominated by the Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front under Prime Minister Meles Zenawi. The country was engaged in a costly border war with neighbouring Eritrea, which had separated in 1993; a major Ethiopian offensive in May 2000 was followed by the Algiers peace agreement signed in December 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Ethiopia was a federal republic led by Prime Minister Meles Zenawi of the EPRDF, which won a sweeping victory in the May 2010 parliamentary elections that opposition groups and observers criticized as unfair. The country was one of Africa's fastest-growing economies and continued large state-led projects, including planning and early work on the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam on the Blue Nile.","2026":"Ethiopia is a federal republic led by Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed. Although the 2022 Pretoria agreement ended the Tigray war, the country in 2026 faces continued internal conflict and instability in the Amhara and Oromia regions, alongside rising tension with Eritrea over Abiy's push for access to a Red Sea port."},
  "ethiopia (italy)": {"1938":"In 1938 Ethiopia had been conquered by Italy in 1936 and was administered as part of Italian East Africa, with the Italian king proclaimed emperor. Emperor Haile Selassie was in exile, and Italian control faced continued armed resistance from Ethiopian patriots in much of the countryside."},
  "faeroe is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Faroe Islands were a self-governing region of the Kingdom of Denmark, having gained home rule under the 1948 Home Rule Act. They managed many of their own affairs while remaining under Danish sovereignty.","1994":"The Faroe Islands were a self-governing autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, having held home rule since 1948. In the early 1990s the islands were in a severe economic and banking crisis following the collapse of fish stocks and overinvestment, requiring financial bailouts from Denmark.","2000":"In 2000 the Faroe Islands were a self-governing autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, handling most domestic affairs through their own Løgting parliament while Denmark retained responsibility for defence and foreign policy. Around this period there were active negotiations and debate over greater autonomy or full independence from Denmark.","2010":"In 2010 the Faroe Islands were a self-governing autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, with their own parliament (the Logting) and government handling most domestic affairs while Denmark retained responsibility for defence and foreign policy. The economy remained heavily dependent on fishing and fish farming.","2026":"The Faroe Islands are a self-governing autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, with their own parliament (the Løgting) handling most domestic affairs while Denmark manages defense and foreign policy. They are not part of the European Union."},
  "falkland is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Falkland Islands were a British colony in the South Atlantic, administered by a governor and a small settler population centered on Stanley. Argentina maintained its long-standing claim to the islands, but they remained firmly under British control.","1994":"The Falkland Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, administered by Britain following the 1982 war in which the United Kingdom repelled an Argentine invasion. Argentina continued to claim sovereignty over the islands, but they remained under British control with a permanent military garrison.","2000":"In 2000 the Falkland Islands were a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, administered by a governor appointed by the United Kingdom with an elected Legislative Council handling internal affairs. Their sovereignty remained disputed by Argentina, which claims them as the Malvinas, following the 1982 war.","2010":"In 2010 the Falkland Islands were a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, with the United Kingdom responsible for defence and foreign affairs. Tensions with Argentina, which claims the islands, rose that year as British companies began exploratory oil drilling in surrounding waters, drawing protests from Buenos Aires.","2026":"The Falkland Islands are a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, with internal self-government and the United Kingdom responsible for defense and foreign affairs. Argentina continues to claim the islands, but the UK maintains sovereignty backed by the islanders' overwhelming 2013 vote to remain British."},
  "fiji": {"1900":"Fiji was a British Crown Colony, having been ceded to Britain in 1874. Its economy in 1900 centered on sugar plantations worked largely by indentured laborers brought from British India.","1920":"In 1920 Fiji was a British Crown Colony in the South Pacific, administered from Suva. Its economy centered on sugar plantations worked largely by indentured Indian labourers, though the indenture system was being wound down in this period.","1938":"Fiji was a British Crown Colony in 1938, governed by a British colonial administration from Suva. Its economy centered on sugar production worked substantially by descendants of indentured Indian laborers alongside the indigenous Fijian population.","1960":"In 1960 Fiji was a British Crown colony in the South Pacific, governed by a colonial administration. Its economy centered on sugar production, and it remained well short of the path to independence, which it would reach in 1970.","1994":"Fiji was a republic, having become one in 1987 after two military coups led by Sitiveni Rabuka removed it from the Commonwealth. A new constitution adopted in 1990 entrenched political dominance for indigenous Fijians over the large Indo-Fijian population. Rabuka served as prime minister, having won elections in 1992.","2000":"In 2000 Fiji was a republic that suffered a major political crisis when, in May 2000, businessman George Speight led an armed coup that took Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and members of his government hostage in parliament. The crisis led to the abrogation of the 1997 constitution and the eventual installation of an interim administration.","2010":"In 2010 Fiji was under military-backed rule led by Commodore Frank Bainimarama, who had taken power in a 2006 coup; the country remained under a state of emergency and the 1997 constitution had been abrogated in 2009. Fiji was suspended from the Commonwealth and the Pacific Islands Forum over its failure to restore democratic elections.","2026":"Fiji is a parliamentary republic in the South Pacific, led since the December 2022 election by a coalition government under Prime Minister Sitiveni Rabuka. The country remains a regional hub and member of the Pacific Islands Forum."},
  "finland": {"1920":"In 1920 Finland was an independent republic, having declared independence from Russia in 1917 and adopted a republican constitution in 1919 with K. J. Ståhlberg as its first president. The Treaty of Tartu in October 1920 settled the border with Soviet Russia, with Finland gaining the Petsamo corridor to the Arctic Ocean.","1938":"Finland in 1938 was an independent parliamentary republic pursuing a policy of neutrality, with relations with the Soviet Union an ongoing concern. The Soviet Union began secret approaches to Finland in 1938 seeking security concessions, foreshadowing the tensions that would lead to the 1939 Winter War.","1960":"In 1960 Finland was an independent republic, with Urho Kekkonen serving as president. It pursued a policy of neutrality and careful relations with the neighboring Soviet Union under the 1948 Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation, and Mutual Assistance, while maintaining a Western-style democracy and market economy.","1994":"Finland was an independent republic that was emerging from a deep economic recession of the early 1990s triggered partly by the collapse of Soviet trade. In 1994 Finns elected Martti Ahtisaari president, and the country negotiated and held a referendum in which voters approved joining the European Union, which it entered on 1 January 1995.","2000":"In 2000 Finland was a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union, which it had joined in 1995, and it was among the countries adopting the euro for accounting purposes ahead of the 2002 cash changeover. In March 2000 Tarja Halonen took office as Finland's first female president, and a revised constitution came into force the same month.","2010":"In 2010 Finland was a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union and the eurozone, with Tarja Halonen as president and Mari Kiviniemi becoming prime minister in June after Matti Vanhanen resigned. The country had a high-income economy recovering from the global financial downturn.","2026":"Finland is a parliamentary republic and EU member that joined NATO in April 2023, ending its longstanding military non-alignment in response to Russia's invasion of Ukraine. President Alexander Stubb took office in 2024, and in 2026 the country maintains a fortified, largely closed border with Russia."},
  "fr. polynesia": {"1960":"In 1960 French Polynesia was an overseas territory of France in the South Pacific, having been designated a territoire d'outre-mer. It remained under French administration with some local representation.","1994":"French Polynesia was an overseas territory of France in the South Pacific with a degree of internal autonomy. France conducted nuclear testing in the region at Moruroa and Fangataufa atolls, though a testing moratorium was in place in 1994 before President Chirac resumed tests in 1995.","2000":"In 2000 French Polynesia was an overseas territory of France in the South Pacific, possessing internal autonomy with its own assembly while France retained control of defence, justice and foreign affairs. Its long-serving president Gaston Flosse led the local government during this period.","2010":"In 2010 French Polynesia was an overseas collectivity of France in the South Pacific with substantial internal autonomy, electing its own assembly and president while France handled defence and foreign affairs. Its politics in this period were marked by frequent instability and shifting governing coalitions.","2026":"French Polynesia is a semi-autonomous overseas collectivity of France in the South Pacific, with its own assembly and government handling many internal matters while France retains sovereignty. It uses the CFP franc and its residents are French and EU citizens."},
  "fr. s. antarctic lands": {"1960":"In 1960 the French Southern and Antarctic Lands were an overseas territory of France, created in 1955, comprising scattered sub-Antarctic islands and the Adelie Land claim in Antarctica. The territory was uninhabited apart from scientific and support personnel at research stations.","1994":"The French Southern and Antarctic Lands were an overseas territory of France comprising scattered sub-Antarctic islands and a claimed sector of Antarctica. The territory had no permanent population, only scientific and support personnel staffing research stations.","2000":"In 2000 the French Southern and Antarctic Lands were an overseas territory of France comprising scattered sub-Antarctic islands and Adélie Land in Antarctica, with no permanent civilian population and only scientific and support personnel present. The territory was administered by a French-appointed senior administrator.","2010":"In 2010 the French Southern and Antarctic Lands were an overseas territory of France comprising scattered sub-Antarctic islands and Adelie Land in Antarctica, with no permanent civilian population, hosting only scientific and support staff. It was administered by a senior official representing the French state.","2026":"The French Southern and Antarctic Lands are an overseas territory of France comprising scattered sub-Antarctic islands, the Adélie Land Antarctic claim, and scattered Indian Ocean islands, with no permanent civilian population. It is administered by a senior official and inhabited mainly by scientific and military personnel."},
  "france": {"1900":"France in 1900 was a republic, the Third Republic, with a parliamentary government. The country was hosting the Exposition Universelle and the Olympic Games in Paris that year, and its politics were still convulsed by the aftermath of the Dreyfus Affair; it also controlled a vast colonial empire across Africa and Indochina.","1920":"In 1920 France was a republic under the Third Republic, victorious but deeply scarred by World War I, with vast war casualties, devastated northern regions, and a heavy reconstruction burden. It held a large overseas colonial empire and pressed for enforcement of the Treaty of Versailles and German reparations, while Alexandre Millerand led the government and later became president that year.","1938":"France in 1938 was the Third Republic, a parliamentary democracy whose Popular Front coalition was collapsing, with Édouard Daladier becoming prime minister in April 1938. France signed the Munich Agreement in September 1938, conceding the Sudetenland to Nazi Germany in an attempt to avoid war.","1960":"In 1960 France was a republic under the Fifth Republic, established in 1958 with Charles de Gaulle as its first president. The country was deeply engaged in the Algerian War, and 1960 saw rising tension over Algeria's future, including the \"Week of the Barricades\" by settlers in Algiers in January. France also detonated its first atomic bomb in the Sahara in February 1960 and granted independence to most of its sub-Saharan African colonies that year.","1994":"France was a republic under the Fifth Republic, with Socialist President Francois Mitterrand in the final years of his presidency. Following the 1993 legislative elections won by the right, the country was in a period of cohabitation with conservative Prime Minister Edouard Balladur. The Channel Tunnel linking France and Britain opened in 1994.","2000":"In 2000 France was a semi-presidential republic under President Jacques Chirac, with a left-wing government led by Prime Minister Lionel Jospin in a period of cohabitation. A September 2000 referendum approved reducing the presidential term from seven to five years, and France remained a leading member of the European Union preparing for the euro.","2010":"In 2010 France was a semi-presidential republic and leading member of the European Union and eurozone, with Nicolas Sarkozy as president and Francois Fillon as prime minister. The year saw major social unrest, including large strikes and protests against a pension reform that raised the retirement age.","2026":"France is a semi-presidential republic and member of the EU, NATO, the eurozone and the UN Security Council, with Emmanuel Macron as president. In 2026 the country faces persistent political instability stemming from a hung National Assembly since the 2024 snap elections, with repeated changes of prime minister and difficulty passing budgets."},
  "french cameroons": {"1920":"In 1920 the French Cameroons was the larger portion of the former German colony of Kamerun, administered by France following its partition with Britain after World War I. It became a League of Nations mandate, with France formally receiving the mandate in 1922, governed as part of France's African holdings.","1938":"In 1938 the French Cameroons was the larger portion of the former German Kamerun administered by France as a League of Nations mandate. It was governed as part of France's colonial empire in Central Africa, producing cocoa and other tropical commodities."},
  "french equatorial africa": {"1920":"In 1920 French Equatorial Africa was a federation of French colonial territories in central Africa, comprising Gabon, Middle Congo, Ubangi-Shari, and Chad, administered from Brazzaville. It was a sparsely governed colonial possession exploited largely through concessionary companies.","1938":"French Equatorial Africa in 1938 was a federation of French colonies comprising Gabon, Middle Congo, Ubangi-Shari, and Chad, with its capital at Brazzaville. It was administered by France as part of its colonial empire under a governor-general."},
  "french guiana": {"1900":"French Guiana was a French colony on the northeastern coast of South America. By 1900 it was notorious as a French penal colony, including the offshore Devil's Island, to which convicts were transported from France.","1920":"In 1920 French Guiana was an overseas colony of France on the northeast coast of South America, governed from Cayenne. It was notorious as the site of France's penal colonies, including the Îles du Salut and the bagne at Cayenne, to which convicts were transported.","1938":"French Guiana in 1938 was a French colony on the northeastern coast of South America. It was notorious as the site of France's penal colonies, including the settlement at Cayenne and the offshore Devil's Island, to which prisoners were transported."},
  "french indo-china": {"1920":"French Indochina was a federation of French colonial territories in Southeast Asia, comprising the protectorates of Tonkin, Annam, Cambodia, and Laos together with the directly ruled colony of Cochinchina. In 1920 it was administered by a Governor-General under French sovereignty, with the Nguyen emperor in Annam reduced to a figurehead. The colonial economy centered on rice and rubber exports, and the period saw the early stirrings of Vietnamese nationalist and anti-colonial sentiment.","1938":"French Indochina was a federation of French colonial territories in Southeast Asia, comprising the protectorates of Tonkin, Annam, Cambodia and Laos and the directly ruled colony of Cochinchina. In 1938 it was governed by a French Governor-General and remained firmly under French control, though it was a source of rubber, rice and other exports for France."},
  "french indochina": {"1900":"French Indochina was a federation of French colonial possessions in Southeast Asia, comprising the colony of Cochinchina and the protectorates of Tonkin, Annam, and Cambodia, with Laos added in the 1890s. In 1900 it was governed under Paul Doumer, who reorganized its administration and finances and promoted infrastructure development."},
  "french somaliland": {"1920":"French Somaliland was a French colony on the Horn of Africa around the port of Djibouti, governed under French sovereignty. Its strategic value lay in Djibouti's harbor and the railway running inland toward Addis Ababa in Ethiopia, which made it an important trade outlet.","1938":"French Somaliland was a French colony on the Horn of Africa centered on the port of Djibouti, the terminus of the railway to Addis Ababa in Ethiopia. In 1938 it was administered by France and its strategic value had grown after Italy's conquest of Ethiopia, leaving the colony bordered by Italian East Africa."},
  "french west africa": {"1920":"French West Africa was a federation of French colonies governed from Dakar by a Governor-General under French sovereignty. In 1920 it grouped together territories including Senegal, French Sudan, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Dahomey, Mauritania, Niger, and Upper Volta. Colonial rule relied on forced labor and cash-crop production, and African troops from the federation had been heavily recruited for the First World War.","1938":"French West Africa was a large federation of French colonial territories administered from Dakar, grouping possessions such as Senegal, French Sudan, Guinea, Ivory Coast, Dahomey, Niger and Mauritania. In 1938 it remained under French rule, headed by a Governor-General overseeing the constituent colonies."},
  "gabon": {"1900":"Gabon was a French colonial territory in Equatorial Africa, administered as part of French Congo. Around 1900 it was being organized within France's central African holdings, with an economy based on the export of timber and other forest products.","1960":"Gabon was a French colony within French Equatorial Africa that gained full independence from France on 17 August 1960. Léon M'ba became its first leader, serving as prime minister and then president of the new republic.","1994":"Gabon was a republic led by President Omar Bongo, who had ruled since 1967. Following the introduction of multiparty politics in the early 1990s, Bongo had won a contested 1993 presidential election that triggered unrest and disputes into 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Gabon was a republic in central Africa led by President Omar Bongo, who had held power since 1967 and continued to dominate its politics. The oil-rich state remained closely tied to France.","2010":"In 2010 Gabon was a republic in Central Africa led by President Ali Bongo Ondimba, who had taken office in 2009 following the death of his father Omar Bongo, who had ruled for over four decades. The oil-rich country remained heavily dependent on petroleum exports.","2026":"In 2026 Gabon is a Central African republic governed by the administration that took power in the August 2023 coup which ended the Bongo family's decades-long rule. Brice Oligui Nguema, who led the takeover, was elected president in April 2025, formalizing his leadership after the transition. The oil-rich country continues to navigate a return to constitutional order under his government."},
  "gambia": {"1900":"The Gambia was a British colony and protectorate consisting of the territory along the Gambia River, surrounded by French-held Senegal. Its boundaries with the French had been settled in the late nineteenth century, and its economy depended heavily on groundnut (peanut) exports.","1960":"In 1960 the Gambia was still a British colony and protectorate in West Africa, not yet independent. Constitutional reforms were underway in this period leading toward greater self-government, but it would not become independent until 1965.","1994":"The Gambia, a small republic surrounded by Senegal, saw its long-serving president Dawda Jawara overthrown in July 1994 in a bloodless military coup. Lieutenant Yahya Jammeh took power at the head of a military council, ending decades of multiparty civilian rule.","2000":"In 2000 The Gambia was a republic led by President Yahya Jammeh, who had originally taken power in a 1994 coup and won the 1996 election. In April 2000 security forces opened fire on a student demonstration in which a number of people were killed.","2010":"In 2010 the Gambia was a republic in West Africa led by President Yahya Jammeh, who had held power since a 1994 coup and governed in an increasingly authoritarian manner. The small country, nearly surrounded by Senegal, relied on agriculture, tourism, and remittances.","2026":"In 2026 The Gambia is a small West African republic on the Atlantic coast, almost entirely surrounded by Senegal. It is led by President Adama Barrow, who has held office since 2017 after defeating longtime ruler Yahya Jammeh."},
  "gambia, the": {"1920":"The Gambia was a British colony and protectorate consisting of a narrow strip along the Gambia River, surrounded by French Senegal. In 1920 it was under British sovereignty, with an economy dominated by the export of groundnuts.","1938":"The Gambia was a British colony and protectorate consisting of a narrow strip of land along the Gambia River, surrounded by French Senegal. In 1938 it was under British colonial administration, with a Crown Colony around Bathurst and a protectorate over the interior."},
  "georgia": {"1920":"In 1920 Georgia was the independent Democratic Republic of Georgia, governed by a Menshevik social-democratic administration that had declared independence in 1918 after the collapse of the Russian Empire. Its independence was recognized by Soviet Russia in a May 1920 treaty, but the republic's existence was precarious and it would be invaded and absorbed by the Red Army in early 1921.","1994":"Georgia was an independent republic that had become independent with the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991. In 1994 it was led by Eduard Shevardnadze and remained deeply unstable, having recently lost effective control of the breakaway region of Abkhazia after fighting in 1992–1993, while South Ossetia was also separatist. Georgia joined the Commonwealth of Independent States in 1993–1994.","2000":"In 2000 Georgia was an independent republic, having gained independence with the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991, and was led by President Eduard Shevardnadze, who was re-elected in April 2000. The country faced unresolved separatist conflicts in Abkhazia and South Ossetia and significant economic difficulties.","2010":"In 2010 Georgia was a republic in the South Caucasus led by President Mikheil Saakashvili, still dealing with the aftermath of its 2008 war with Russia, after which Russia recognized the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia as independent. Georgia pursued closer ties with the West and aspirations toward NATO and EU membership.","2026":"In 2026 Georgia is a republic in the South Caucasus whose government is dominated by the Georgian Dream party, which faced large protests after the contested 2024 parliamentary elections and the suspension of EU accession talks. Mikheil Kavelashvili serves as president after a disputed electoral-college selection, while Russia continues to back the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia."},
  "germany": {"1900":"Germany in 1900 was the German Empire, a federation of states led by Prussia under Kaiser Wilhelm II, with Bernhard von Bülow becoming Chancellor that year. It was a leading industrial and military power, was expanding its navy under the 1900 Naval Law promoted by Tirpitz, and held colonies in Africa and the Pacific.","1920":"In 1920 Germany was the Weimar Republic, a parliamentary democracy that had replaced the monarchy after the 1918 revolution. It was burdened by the Treaty of Versailles, which imposed territorial losses, military restrictions, and reparations, and the year saw severe political instability including the Kapp Putsch in March, an attempted right-wing coup that was defeated by a general strike.","1938":"In 1938 Germany was the Nazi dictatorship under Adolf Hitler, who held total power through the Nazi Party. That year Germany annexed Austria in the Anschluss in March and, following the Munich Agreement in September, took the Sudetenland from Czechoslovakia; the Kristallnacht pogrom against Jews occurred in November.","1960":"In 1960 Germany was divided into the Federal Republic of Germany in the west, led by Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, and the German Democratic Republic in the east under the Socialist Unity Party and Walter Ulbricht. Berlin remained divided and a focus of Cold War tension; the Berlin Wall would not be built until August 1961. Large numbers of East Germans continued to flee to the West, largely via Berlin.","1994":"Germany was a reunified federal republic, four years after the 1990 reunification of West and East Germany. Chancellor Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats won the 1994 federal elections. The country was managing the costly economic integration of the former East and saw the final withdrawal of Russian and Allied troops from Berlin in 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Germany was a federal parliamentary republic led by Chancellor Gerhard Schröder of a Social Democrat–Green coalition, with Berlin as its capital following the move from Bonn. It was a leading member of the European Union preparing for the introduction of the euro.","2010":"In 2010 Germany was a federal parliamentary republic and the largest economy in the European Union, governed by a coalition of Angela Merkel's CDU/CSU and the FDP, with Merkel as chancellor and Christian Wulff elected president in mid-2010. Germany played a central role in responding to the eurozone debt crisis, including support for the Greek bailout.","2026":"In 2026 Germany is a federal parliamentary republic and the EU's largest economy, led by a CDU/CSU-SPD coalition government with Friedrich Merz as chancellor following the February 2025 federal election. The country continues to grapple with economic stagnation, debates over support for Ukraine, and the rise of the far-right AfD."},
  "ghana": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory of present-day Ghana was the British Gold Coast colony, under British sovereignty. Its economy was dominated by cocoa exports as well as gold mining, and educated Africans were beginning to organize politically, with the National Congress of British West Africa holding its inaugural conference at Accra in 1920.","1960":"Ghana had been independent from Britain since 1957 under Kwame Nkrumah. On 1 July 1960 it became a republic within the Commonwealth, with Nkrumah as its first president after a plebiscite and presidential election earlier that year.","1994":"Ghana was a republic led by Jerry Rawlings, who had originally taken power in a 1981 coup and then won the 1992 multiparty presidential election that returned the country to constitutional rule under the Fourth Republic. By 1994 Ghana was pursuing economic liberalization and structural adjustment programs.","2000":"In 2000 Ghana was a republic that held a landmark December presidential election in which John Agyekum Kufuor of the opposition New Patriotic Party defeated the ruling party's candidate, since outgoing President Jerry Rawlings was constitutionally barred from a further term. This produced the country's first peaceful, democratic transfer of power between elected governments.","2010":"In 2010 Ghana was a stable multiparty republic in West Africa led by President John Atta Mills of the NDC, who had won the closely contested 2008 election. The country began commercial offshore oil production from the Jubilee field in December 2010, adding to its established gold and cocoa exports.","2026":"In 2026 Ghana is a West African republic and a relatively stable democracy. John Mahama returned to the presidency after winning the December 2024 election, with the country working to recover from a severe debt and currency crisis."},
  "gibraltar": {"1960":"In 1960 Gibraltar was a British colony and strategic naval base at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula. It remained under British sovereignty, a status long contested by Spain.","1994":"Gibraltar was a British Overseas Territory at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, internally self-governing while Britain retained responsibility for defense and foreign affairs. Spain continued to claim sovereignty over the territory, and the land border remained a point of friction.","2000":"In 2000 Gibraltar was a self-governing British Overseas Territory on the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, with an elected House of Assembly and a UK-appointed governor, its sovereignty disputed by Spain. Peter Caruana served as Chief Minister during this period.","2010":"In 2010 Gibraltar was a self-governing British Overseas Territory at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, with the United Kingdom responsible for defence and foreign affairs and Spain continuing to assert a sovereignty claim. Its economy relied on financial services, tourism, shipping, and online gaming.","2026":"In 2026 Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, self-governing in domestic affairs while the UK handles defence and foreign relations. Its status remains contested by Spain, and following Brexit negotiations continued over its border arrangements with the EU."},
  "gilbert and elice islands": {"1938":"The Gilbert and Ellice Islands were a British colony in the central Pacific comprising two main groups of atolls and islands. In 1938 the colony was administered by Britain through a Resident Commissioner."},
  "gold coast": {"1938":"The Gold Coast was a British colony on the West African coast, corresponding to present-day Ghana, and was a major producer and exporter of cocoa. In 1938 it remained under British colonial rule administered by a Governor."},
  "greece": {"1900":"In 1900 Greece was an independent constitutional monarchy ruled by King George I, who had reigned since 1863. The country was still smaller than the modern state, with much of the Greek-populated Aegean and Macedonia still under Ottoman rule, and irredentist ambitions (the Megali Idea) dominated national politics. It had recently suffered a costly defeat in the Greco-Turkish War of 1897, which led to international financial control over Greek finances.","1920":"In 1920 Greece was a kingdom engaged in the Greco-Turkish war, occupying Smyrna and parts of Anatolia following Allied authorization, and at the Treaty of Sevres in 1920 it was awarded eastern Thrace and administration of the Smyrna region. The year saw dramatic political reversal: Prime Minister Eleftherios Venizelos lost the November 1920 elections, and a plebiscite restored the exiled King Constantine I to the throne.","1938":"In 1938 Greece was a kingdom under King George II, but real power lay with the dictatorship of Prime Minister Ioannis Metaxas, who had suspended parliament and established the authoritarian \"4th of August Regime\" in 1936. The regime suppressed political opposition and pursued nationalist and corporatist policies.","1960":"In 1960 Greece was a constitutional monarchy under King Paul, with Konstantinos Karamanlis serving as prime minister and his National Radical Union in power. The country was a member of NATO and recovering and developing economically in the postwar period. In 1960 Cyprus, with its large Greek population, gained independence, an issue of considerable concern to Greece.","1994":"In 1994 Greece was a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and NATO, governed by the Panhellenic Socialist Movement (PASOK) under Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, who had returned to power in late 1993. Relations with the newly independent Republic of Macedonia were tense, and in February 1994 Greece imposed a trade embargo on it over the dispute about its name and symbols.","2000":"In 2000 Greece was a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and NATO, governed by the PASOK party under Prime Minister Costas Simitis. The country was preparing to adopt the euro, which it joined in January 2001, and was working toward economic convergence with the rest of the EU.","2010":"In 2010 Greece was a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union and the eurozone, governed by the PASOK administration of Prime Minister George Papandreou. That year it was engulfed by a severe sovereign debt crisis and received a first international bailout from the EU and IMF in May 2010, accompanied by harsh austerity measures that triggered widespread strikes and protests.","2026":"In 2026 Greece is a member of the EU and the eurozone, governed by the centre-right New Democracy party under Prime Minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, who won re-election in 2023. The country has continued its economic recovery from the long debt crisis while managing migration pressures and tensions with Turkey."},
  "greenland": {"1900":"In 1900 Greenland was a colony of Denmark, governed under the Royal Greenland Trading Department, which held a monopoly over commerce with the island. The small Inuit and Danish settler population lived mainly along the southwestern coast, and the Danish administration kept the colony largely closed to outside trade and visitors.","1960":"In 1960 Greenland was an integral part of the Kingdom of Denmark, having been made a Danish county (amt) in 1953 rather than a colony. Denmark was pursuing a policy of modernization and \"Danization,\" and the island hosted the major American Thule Air Base under a Danish-US defense arrangement.","1994":"In 1994 Greenland was a self-governing territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, having had home rule since 1979, with its own parliament (Landsting) and government handling domestic affairs while Denmark retained control of foreign policy and defense. Despite Denmark's EU membership, Greenland remained outside the European Union, having withdrawn in 1985.","2000":"In 2000 Greenland was an autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, having exercised home rule since 1979 while Denmark retained control over foreign affairs and defense. Its population was small and concentrated on the coasts, with an economy heavily dependent on fishing.","2010":"In 2010 Greenland was a self-governing autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark, having gained expanded self-rule under the Self-Government Act that took effect in 2009. Its government was led by Premier Kuupik Kleist, with Denmark retaining responsibility for foreign affairs and defence.","2026":"In 2026 Greenland is an autonomous territory within the Kingdom of Denmark with extensive home rule, led by a government that took office after the March 2025 general election. The territory drew intense international attention from US President Donald Trump's renewed statements about acquiring it, which Greenlandic and Danish leaders rejected."},
  "grenada": {"1920":"In 1920 Grenada was a British colony in the West Indies under British sovereignty, with an economy based on the export of cocoa, nutmeg, and other spices.","1938":"Grenada was a British colony in the Windward Islands of the Caribbean. In 1938 it was under British colonial administration as part of the Windward Islands group.","1960":"In 1960 Grenada was a British colony in the West Indies. From 1958 it was part of the West Indies Federation; it would not become independent until 1974.","1994":"In 1994 Grenada was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a governor-general. It had recovered stability after the 1983 US-led invasion that ended the Marxist People's Revolutionary Government, with civilian constitutional government restored through elections.","2000":"In 2000 Grenada was an independent parliamentary democracy and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, represented by a governor-general. Keith Mitchell of the New National Party served as prime minister, and the economy relied on tourism and agriculture, including nutmeg.","2010":"In 2010 Grenada was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm in the Caribbean, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a governor-general. Tillman Thomas of the National Democratic Congress served as prime minister, having won the 2008 election.","2026":"In 2026 Grenada is an independent island nation in the southeastern Caribbean and a Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. It is a parliamentary democracy whose economy relies heavily on tourism and agriculture."},
  "griqualand west": {"1900":"By 1900 Griqualand West had been annexed to the British Cape Colony, into which it was formally incorporated in 1880. Centered on Kimberley, the region was the heart of the world's diamond industry, dominated by Cecil Rhodes's De Beers company. During the South African War, Kimberley was besieged by Boer forces from late 1899 until its relief in February 1900."},
  "guadeloupe": {"1900":"In 1900 Guadeloupe was a French colony in the Caribbean, its sugar-based plantation economy worked largely by descendants of enslaved Africans freed in 1848 along with indentured Indian laborers. It was administered by France and sent representatives to the French parliament.","1920":"In 1920 Guadeloupe was a French colony in the Caribbean under French sovereignty, with a plantation economy centered on sugar cane and rum.","1938":"Guadeloupe was a French colony in the Lesser Antilles of the Caribbean. In 1938 it was administered by France as an overseas possession."},
  "guam": {"1938":"Guam was an unincorporated territory of the United States in the Marianas, administered by the U.S. Navy under a naval governor. In 1938 it remained under American control, surrounded by the Japanese-mandated islands of the surrounding Pacific.","1960":"In 1960 Guam was an unincorporated territory of the United States in the western Pacific, administered under the Organic Act of 1950 which had granted its inhabitants US citizenship and civilian government. It hosted significant US naval and air military installations.","1994":"In 1994 Guam was an unincorporated organized territory of the United States in the western Pacific, whose residents were US citizens but could not vote in presidential elections and had a non-voting delegate in Congress. It hosted major US military installations, including Andersen Air Force Base and a large naval presence.","2000":"In 2000 Guam was an unincorporated organized territory of the United States in the western Pacific, whose residents were U.S. citizens but could not vote in presidential elections. The U.S. military maintained a major presence there, and the economy depended heavily on the bases and on tourism.","2010":"In 2010 Guam was an unincorporated organized territory of the United States in the western Pacific, whose residents are U.S. citizens but cannot vote in presidential elections. It hosted significant U.S. military installations, and plans were underway to relocate thousands of U.S. Marines there from Okinawa.","2026":"In 2026 Guam is an unincorporated organized territory of the United States in the western Pacific, whose residents are US citizens but cannot vote in presidential elections. It hosts major US military installations and remains strategically important amid US-China tensions in the Indo-Pacific."},
  "guatemala": {"1900":"In 1900 Guatemala was an independent republic under the dictatorship of Manuel Estrada Cabrera, who had taken power in 1898 and would rule until 1920. Its economy was dominated by coffee exports and increasingly by U.S. companies, including the nascent banana trade, with foreign capital exercising great influence.","1920":"In 1920 Guatemala was an independent republic, and that year saw the overthrow of the long-ruling dictator Manuel Estrada Cabrera, who had held power since 1898 and was declared insane and deposed by the national assembly in April 1920. The economy depended heavily on coffee and banana exports, with growing influence from the United Fruit Company.","1938":"In 1938 Guatemala was an independent republic ruled by the dictator Jorge Ubico, who had governed since 1931. His regime was authoritarian, closely tied to the United Fruit Company and U.S. interests, and maintained tight control over the country's largely agricultural, coffee-based economy.","1960":"In 1960 Guatemala was a republic under President Miguel Ydígoras Fuentes, who had taken office in 1958. In November 1960 a revolt by junior military officers was suppressed, an event later seen as a starting point of the long Guatemalan civil war. The country also allowed CIA training of Cuban exiles on its territory in this period.","1994":"In 1994 Guatemala was a republic still embroiled in its long-running civil war between the government/military and leftist URNG guerrillas, with peace negotiations underway under UN auspices that produced human-rights and other accords during the year. Ramiro de León Carpio served as president, having taken office in 1993 after the constitutional crisis triggered by Jorge Serrano's failed self-coup.","2000":"In 2000 Guatemala was a presidential republic, with Alfonso Portillo of the FRG taking office as president in January 2000. The country was in the post-conflict period following the 1996 peace accords that ended its decades-long civil war, grappling with poverty, inequality, and reconstruction.","2010":"In 2010 Guatemala was a presidential republic in Central America led by President Alvaro Colom of the National Unity of Hope party. The country continued to struggle with high levels of violent crime, drug-trafficking and gang activity, and in 2010 it was hit by Tropical Storm Agatha and the eruption of the Pacaya volcano.","2026":"In 2026 Guatemala is a Central American republic led by President Bernardo Arévalo, an anti-corruption reformer who took office in January 2024 after a contentious transition in which prosecutors attempted to block his inauguration. His government has faced continued resistance from entrenched political and judicial interests."},
  "guernsey": {"1960":"In 1960 Guernsey was a British Crown Dependency, a self-governing Bailiwick in the Channel Islands that was not part of the United Kingdom but for which the British Crown was responsible. It had its own legislature, the States of Guernsey.","1994":"In 1994 Guernsey was a British Crown Dependency, a self-governing Bailiwick possessing its own legislature (the States of Guernsey) and fiscal autonomy, with the United Kingdom responsible for its defense and foreign relations. It was not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union and functioned as an offshore financial center.","2000":"In 2000 Guernsey was a British Crown Dependency, a self-governing bailiwick that was not part of the United Kingdom, with the British monarch as head of state. It managed its own domestic affairs while the UK was responsible for defense and international representation, and its economy centered on finance and tourism.","2010":"In 2010 Guernsey was a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union, with the British monarch as head of state. It managed its own domestic affairs through the States of Guernsey while the UK was responsible for its defence and international relations.","2026":"In 2026 Guernsey is a British Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, self-governing in internal matters with the UK responsible for its defence and international relations. It is not part of the United Kingdom or the EU and maintains its own legislature, the States of Guernsey."},
  "guinea": {"1960":"Guinea had become independent from France in 1958 after voting \"no\" in the de Gaulle referendum, the only French African territory to reject continued association, prompting an abrupt French withdrawal. In 1960 it was a republic led by President Ahmed Sékou Touré, who pursued socialist policies and close ties with the Soviet bloc.","1994":"In 1994 Guinea was a republic led by President Lansana Conté, who had ruled since seizing power in a 1984 coup and had won the country's first multiparty presidential election in December 1993. The political environment remained dominated by Conté amid opposition complaints about the conduct of that election.","2000":"In 2000 Guinea was a presidential republic led by Lansana Conté, who had held power since 1984. Around this time the country was destabilized by cross-border attacks and an influx of refugees connected to the conflicts in neighboring Sierra Leone and Liberia.","2010":"In 2010 Guinea, a republic in West Africa, transitioned from military rule following the 2008 coup and the turbulent junta period under Moussa Dadis Camara. It held its first competitive presidential elections, with Alpha Conde declared the winner in a November runoff, marking a move toward civilian democratic government.","2026":"In 2026 Guinea is a West African republic under a military-led transitional government headed by Mamadi Doumbouya, who seized power in the September 2021 coup that ousted President Alpha Condé. The junta has extended its hold on power amid promises of an eventual return to civilian rule."},
  "guinea-bissau": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory of present-day Guinea-Bissau was Portuguese Guinea, a colony under Portuguese sovereignty. Portuguese control of the interior was still being consolidated through military campaigns against local populations in this period.","1938":"The territory of present-day Guinea-Bissau was Portuguese Guinea, a colony of Portugal in West Africa. In 1938 it was ruled by Portugal under the authoritarian Estado Novo regime of António de Oliveira Salazar.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was Portuguese Guinea, a colony of Portugal in West Africa. Amílcar Cabral's PAIGC had been founded in 1956 and was beginning to organize against Portuguese rule, but the armed independence war did not start until 1963.","1994":"In 1994 Guinea-Bissau held its first multiparty elections, in which President João Bernardo Vieira and his PAIGC party prevailed; Vieira had held power since a 1980 coup. The vote marked the country's transition from one-party rule toward multiparty democracy.","2000":"In 2000 Guinea-Bissau was recovering from a 1998–1999 civil war, and Kumba Ialá of the PRS won the presidency in elections held in late 1999 and early 2000. The country remained politically fragile and among the poorest in the world, with an economy dependent on cashew exports.","2010":"In 2010 Guinea-Bissau was a politically unstable republic in West Africa, governed under President Malam Bacai Sanha, who had been elected in 2009 after the assassination of President Joao Bernardo Vieira. The country remained plagued by military interference in politics and by its role as a transit point for cocaine trafficking."},
  "guyana": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory of present-day Guyana was British Guiana, a British colony on the northern coast of South America under British sovereignty. Its economy relied on sugar plantations and bauxite mining, with a labor force that included descendants of African slaves and indentured workers from India.","1938":"The territory of present-day Guyana was British Guiana, the only British colony on the South American mainland, with a plantation economy producing sugar and bauxite. In 1938 it remained under British colonial administration.","1960":"In 1960 it was the colony of British Guiana, still under British rule and not yet independent. Internal self-government had been expanding, and Cheddi Jagan's People's Progressive Party was a dominant political force amid tensions between the colony's Indo-Guyanese and Afro-Guyanese communities. Independence as Guyana would not come until 1966.","1994":"In 1994 Guyana was a cooperative republic governed by President Cheddi Jagan and his People's Progressive Party, who had won the 1992 election widely regarded as the country's first free and fair vote in decades, ending nearly three decades of PNC rule. The government was pursuing economic liberalization to recover from years of decline.","2000":"In 2000 Guyana was a cooperative republic and a Commonwealth member, with Bharrat Jagdeo of the PPP/C serving as president after taking office in 1999. The country remained marked by ethnic political tensions between Indo-Guyanese and Afro-Guyanese communities, with an economy based on bauxite, sugar, rice, and gold.","2010":"In 2010 Guyana was a republic on the northern coast of South America, with Bharrat Jagdeo of the People's Progressive Party serving as president. It remained one of the poorer countries in the region and was notable for its initiative to preserve its rainforest, including a deal with Norway to be paid for avoided deforestation.","2026":"Guyana is a sovereign republic on the northern coast of South America, governed under a presidential system with its capital at Georgetown. By 2026 it has become one of the world's fastest-growing economies, driven by a massive offshore oil boom in the Stabroek Block led by ExxonMobil, and it remains in a longstanding territorial dispute with Venezuela over the Essequibo region, which Venezuela escalated in 2023-2024."},
  "hail": {"1920":"In 1920 Hail was the seat of the Emirate of Jabal Shammar in north-central Arabia, ruled by the Rashidi dynasty (Al Rashid). The emirate was a rival of the expanding Saudi state under Ibn Saud, and it would be conquered and annexed by the Saudis in 1921.","1938":"Hail (Ḥāʾil) had been an independent emirate ruled by the Rashidi dynasty, but it was conquered by Ibn Saud's forces in 1921 and absorbed into his realm. By 1938 it was a province within the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, which had been unified and named in 1932, no longer an autonomous state."},
  "haiti": {"1900":"In 1900 Haiti was an independent republic, the first Black-led republic in the world, governed under a constitution but marked by political instability and frequent changes of leadership. Tirésias Simon Sam served as president, and the country struggled with heavy foreign debt and economic dependence.","1920":"In 1920 Haiti was an independent republic but under United States military occupation, which had begun in 1915 and would continue until 1934. The U.S. controlled Haitian finances and administration, and a constitution drafted under American influence had been imposed in 1918. Resistance to the occupation, including the Caco peasant insurgency, was active around this time.","1938":"In 1938 Haiti was an independent republic under President Sténio Vincent, having regained autonomy after the end of the United States occupation in 1934. The country was still recovering from the 1937 massacre of Haitians by Dominican forces under Rafael Trujillo along the border, an atrocity that strained relations with the neighboring Dominican Republic.","1960":"In 1960 Haiti was ruled by François \"Papa Doc\" Duvalier, who had taken the presidency in 1957 and was consolidating an increasingly authoritarian regime. He relied on the feared Tonton Macoutes militia to suppress opposition, and the country remained impoverished and politically repressive.","1994":"In 1994 Haiti was under the military regime that had ousted elected President Jean-Bertrand Aristide in 1991, but in September 1994 a US-led multinational force (Operation Uphold Democracy) intervened under UN authorization, the military leaders departed, and Aristide was restored to the presidency in October. The country had also been under international economic sanctions during the crisis.","2000":"In 2000 Haiti was a republic in deep political crisis, with contested legislative elections in May and a presidential election in November that returned Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power amid an opposition boycott and disputes over the results. The country remained the poorest in the Western Hemisphere and faced international criticism over the flawed elections.","2010":"In 2010 Haiti, a republic occupying the western part of Hispaniola, was devastated by a catastrophic magnitude 7.0 earthquake on January 12 that killed well over a hundred thousand people and destroyed much of Port-au-Prince. Rene Preval was president, and the disaster was followed later in the year by a deadly cholera outbreak and contested presidential elections.","2026":"Haiti is a sovereign republic in the Caribbean whose state has largely collapsed under the control of armed gangs, with much of the capital Port-au-Prince held by gang coalitions. By 2026 it has no elected president or functioning legislature, is administered by a transitional council, and is the focus of a Kenyan-led Multinational Security Support mission authorized by the UN to help its police regain control."},
  "heard i. and mcdonald is.": {"1960":"These uninhabited subantarctic islands in the southern Indian Ocean were an external territory of Australia in 1960, having been transferred from British to Australian administration in 1947. They had no permanent population and were significant chiefly for their barren volcanic terrain and surrounding wildlife.","1994":"In 1994 Heard Island and McDonald Islands were an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the subantarctic southern Indian Ocean, administered as a nature reserve with no permanent population. The islands were valued for their unspoiled subantarctic ecosystems and active volcanism.","2000":"In 2000 Heard Island and McDonald Islands were an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the southern Indian Ocean. They were administered as a nature reserve and held no permanent population.","2026":"Heard Island and McDonald Islands are an uninhabited external territory of Australia in the southern Indian Ocean, administered from Canberra. They have no permanent population and are protected as a marine reserve and UNESCO World Heritage site notable for active volcanism."},
  "hejaz": {"1920":"In 1920 the Kingdom of Hejaz along the western Arabian coast was an independent monarchy ruled by Hussein bin Ali, the Sharif of Mecca, who had led the Arab Revolt against the Ottomans during World War I. Its territory included the holy cities of Mecca and Medina. The kingdom was increasingly threatened by the rising power of Ibn Saud and the Najd to its east, which would conquer it by the mid-1920s.","1938":"The former independent Kingdom of the Hejaz, including Mecca and Medina, had been conquered by Ibn Saud in the mid-1920s and merged with Nejd. By 1938 it formed part of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, proclaimed under that unified name in 1932, and was no longer a separate state."},
  "honduras": {"1900":"In 1900 Honduras was an independent Central American republic, one of the poorest and least developed in the region, with a weak central government and recurrent political turmoil. Its economy depended on agriculture and mining, and U.S. and other foreign companies were beginning to develop banana plantations along the Caribbean coast.","1920":"In 1920 Honduras was an independent republic in Central America. Its economy was dominated by foreign-owned banana companies, especially U.S. firms operating on the northern coast, giving rise to its later characterization as a 'banana republic.' The period was marked by political instability and recurring revolts.","1938":"In 1938 Honduras was a republic governed by President Tiburcio Carías Andino, who had taken office in 1933 and consolidated an authoritarian regime. Its economy remained heavily dominated by U.S. banana companies, especially the United Fruit Company, which exercised great influence over the country.","1960":"In 1960 Honduras was a republic governed by President Ramón Villeda Morales of the Liberal Party, who had taken office in 1957 and pursued social and labor reforms. The country remained heavily dependent on banana exports and U.S. fruit-company interests, with the military a powerful institution that would overthrow Villeda in 1963.","1994":"In 1994 Honduras was a republic, with Carlos Roberto Reina of the Liberal Party inaugurated as president in January 1994 after winning the 1993 election. His government emphasized human-rights reforms and efforts to reduce the military's political influence, including moves toward ending conscription.","2000":"In 2000 Honduras was a presidential republic with Carlos Roberto Flores of the Liberal Party as president. The country was still recovering from the devastation caused by Hurricane Mitch in 1998, which had killed thousands and severely damaged infrastructure and agriculture.","2010":"In 2010 Honduras was a presidential republic in Central America led by President Porfirio Lobo, who took office in January following the 2009 coup that had ousted President Manuel Zelaya. The new government worked to restore the country's standing internationally after its suspension from the Organization of American States.","2026":"Honduras is a sovereign presidential republic in Central America with its capital at Tegucigalpa. As of 2026 it is led by President Xiomara Castro of the Libre party, the country's first woman president, and held general elections in late 2025 to choose her successor amid concerns over crime, migration, and relations with the United States and China."},
  "hong kong": {"1900":"In 1900 Hong Kong was a British crown colony, comprising Hong Kong Island and Kowloon ceded earlier plus the New Territories, which Britain had leased from China for 99 years in 1898. It was a major free port and commercial hub for trade with China under British colonial administration.","1920":"In 1920 Hong Kong was a British Crown Colony, comprising Hong Kong Island and Kowloon held in perpetuity and the New Territories held under a 99-year lease begun in 1898. It served as a major British trading and shipping port on the South China coast. The colony experienced significant labor unrest around this period, including a major mechanics' strike in 1920.","1938":"Hong Kong in 1938 was a British Crown Colony comprising Hong Kong Island, Kowloon, and the leased New Territories. With Japan's invasion of China underway after 1937, the colony absorbed large numbers of refugees and served as a key conduit for supplies to Nationalist China, while remaining outside the fighting at that time.","1960":"In 1960 Hong Kong was a British Crown Colony, comprising Hong Kong Island, Kowloon, and the New Territories leased from China. Its population was swelling with refugees who had fled mainland China after the 1949 Communist victory, and it was rapidly industrializing into a manufacturing and trade hub.","1994":"In 1994 Hong Kong was a British Crown colony in its final years of British rule, scheduled to be transferred to Chinese sovereignty in 1997 under the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration. Governor Chris Patten's democratic reforms to the Legislative Council were a major source of friction with Beijing during this period.","2000":"In 2000 Hong Kong was a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China, having been transferred from British to Chinese sovereignty in 1997 under the \"one country, two systems\" framework. Tung Chee-hwa served as chief executive, and the territory retained its own legal system, currency, and capitalist economy with a high degree of autonomy.","2010":"In 2010 Hong Kong was a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China, governed under the 'one country, two systems' framework with its own legal and economic system. Donald Tsang served as Chief Executive, and the year saw debate over political reform proposals for the electoral system.","2026":"Hong Kong is a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China governed under the \"one country, two systems\" framework. By 2026 its political autonomy has been sharply curtailed following the 2020 National Security Law and a further domestic security law (Article 23) enacted in 2024, with the opposition largely silenced and a \"patriots only\" electoral system in place."},
  "hungary": {"1920":"In 1920 Hungary became an independent kingdom in name, governed as a regency under Admiral Miklós Horthy, who took office in March 1920 after the collapse of the short-lived Hungarian Soviet Republic. In June 1920 Hungary signed the Treaty of Trianon, which stripped it of roughly two-thirds of its prewar territory and population to neighboring states. The losses caused lasting national grievance and revisionist sentiment.","1938":"In 1938 Hungary was a kingdom without a king, governed as a regency under Admiral Miklós Horthy, with Béla Imrédy becoming prime minister that year. Increasingly aligned with Nazi Germany, Hungary passed its first major anti-Jewish law in 1938 and, through the First Vienna Award in November, gained southern Slovakia and parts of Carpathian Ruthenia from dismembered Czechoslovakia.","1960":"In 1960 Hungary was a communist state in the Soviet bloc, led by János Kádár, who had been installed after Soviet forces crushed the 1956 revolution. By 1960 the post-revolution repression was easing somewhat as Kádár began the more accommodating policies that became known as \"goulash communism.\"","1994":"In 1994 Hungary was a parliamentary republic that had completed its transition from communism, and in May 1994 elections returned the Hungarian Socialist Party (the reformed former communists) under Gyula Horn to power, who formed a coalition with the liberal Alliance of Free Democrats. The country was pursuing market reforms and seeking integration with NATO and the European Union.","2000":"In 2000 Hungary was a parliamentary republic that had become a NATO member in 1999 and was negotiating accession to the European Union. The government was led by Prime Minister Viktor Orbán of Fidesz, who had taken office in 1998.","2010":"In 2010 Hungary was a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union. In the April 2010 elections Viktor Orban's Fidesz party won a two-thirds parliamentary supermajority, returning him to the premiership and beginning sweeping constitutional and institutional changes; the year also saw a major toxic red-mud spill near Ajka.","2026":"Hungary is a sovereign republic in Central Europe and a member of the European Union and NATO, with its capital at Budapest. As of 2026 it is governed by Prime Minister Viktor Orban's Fidesz party, and it faces a strong challenge from Peter Magyar's Tisza party ahead of parliamentary elections in 2026, while remaining in frequent disputes with the EU over rule-of-law and its stance on Ukraine."},
  "iceland": {"1900":"In 1900 Iceland was a dependency of Denmark, possessing its own legislative assembly (the Althing) with limited powers but lacking home rule, which it would not gain until 1904. Its small, predominantly rural population relied on fishing and farming, and a growing nationalist movement pressed for greater autonomy from Copenhagen.","1920":"In 1920 Iceland was a sovereign kingdom in personal union with Denmark, a status established by the Act of Union of 1918, sharing the Danish monarch while controlling its own internal affairs. Denmark continued to handle Iceland's foreign affairs and defense. The arrangement preserved a path toward full independence, which was later achieved in 1944.","1960":"In 1960 Iceland was an independent republic and a founding member of NATO, having become fully independent from Denmark in 1944. Its economy depended heavily on fishing, and disputes over fishing limits with Britain — the \"Cod Wars\" — were a major concern around this period.","1994":"In 1994 Iceland was an independent parliamentary republic, with Vigdis Finnbogadottir as president and a coalition government led by Prime Minister David Oddsson of the Independence Party. That year Iceland joined the European Economic Area, which took effect on 1 January 1994, expanding its access to the European single market while remaining outside the European Union.","2000":"In 2000 Iceland was an independent parliamentary republic, with the Althing as its legislature. It was enjoying strong economic prosperity and was a member of NATO and the European Economic Area, though not the EU. That year it marked the millennium of Leif Erikson's voyage to North America and the conversion of Iceland to Christianity around the year 1000.","2010":"In 2010 Iceland was a sovereign parliamentary republic still recovering from the collapse of its three major banks in the 2008 financial crisis, with a government led by Prime Minister Johanna Sigurdardottir. In April 2010 the eruption of the Eyjafjallajokull volcano sent an ash cloud across Europe, grounding much of the continent's air travel for days. The country was also embroiled in the Icesave dispute with Britain and the Netherlands over compensation for failed bank deposits.","2026":"Iceland is a sovereign parliamentary republic in the North Atlantic with its capital at Reykjavik. As of 2026 its head of state is President Halla Tomasdottir, elected in 2024, and a coalition government took office after a snap election in late 2024; the Reykjanes Peninsula near the town of Grindavik has experienced repeated volcanic eruptions since 2023-2024."},
  "imperial japan": {"1900":"In 1900 the Empire of Japan was a constitutional monarchy under the Meiji Constitution, with Emperor Meiji reigning and an elected Diet alongside a powerful oligarchy. Having industrialized and modernized rapidly, Japan had defeated China in the 1894–95 First Sino-Japanese War, gaining Taiwan, and in 1900 contributed troops to the Eight-Nation Alliance that suppressed the Boxer Rebellion in China."},
  "india": {"1900":"In 1900 India was under British rule as the British Raj, with Queen Victoria as Empress of India and Lord Curzon serving as Viceroy. It combined directly governed British provinces with hundreds of nominally autonomous princely states under British paramountcy, and the period was marked by severe famine, notably the Indian famine of 1899–1900.","1938":"In 1938 India was under British rule as the Indian Empire, governed under the Government of India Act 1935 which had introduced provincial autonomy, with the Indian National Congress holding power in most provinces after the 1937 elections. Subhas Chandra Bose was elected Congress president in 1938, while the independence movement led by figures such as Gandhi and Nehru continued to press against colonial authority.","1960":"In 1960 India was an independent sovereign republic led by Prime Minister Jawaharlal Nehru of the Congress Party. It pursued a policy of non-alignment in the Cold War and state-led economic planning, while tensions with China over the Himalayan border were rising in the years before the 1962 war.","1994":"In 1994 India was a federal parliamentary republic governed by a Congress minority government under Prime Minister P. V. Narasimha Rao, with the economic liberalization reforms launched in 1991 continuing to open up the economy. The period followed the 1992 demolition of the Babri Masjid and associated communal tensions, and the country faced ongoing insurgency in Jammu and Kashmir.","2000":"In 2000 India was a sovereign federal parliamentary republic, the world's most populous democracy, governed by a BJP-led NDA coalition under Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee. The country had conducted nuclear tests in 1998 and remained in tension with Pakistan after the 1999 Kargil conflict. In 2000 India's population officially passed one billion, and three new states (Chhattisgarh, Uttaranchal, and Jharkhand) were carved out late that year.","2010":"In 2010 India was a sovereign federal parliamentary republic, the world's largest democracy, governed by the Congress-led United Progressive Alliance under Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with Pratibha Patil as president. The economy was growing rapidly, and in October 2010 New Delhi hosted the Commonwealth Games, which drew attention for corruption allegations and organizational problems.","2026":"India is a sovereign federal parliamentary republic in South Asia and the world's most populous country, with its capital at New Delhi. As of 2026 it is governed by Prime Minister Narendra Modi, who began a third term in 2024 leading a BJP-headed NDA coalition, and it remains a major and rapidly growing economy."},
  "indian ocean ter.": {"2000":"This refers to British Indian Ocean Territory, a British overseas territory in the Chagos Archipelago, which in 2000 remained under UK sovereignty. The largest island, Diego Garcia, hosted a major joint US-UK military base. The Chagossians who had been expelled in the early 1970s continued to seek the right of return, and in November 2000 a British High Court ruling found their removal had been unlawful.","2010":"This refers to the Australian Indian Ocean Territories, namely Christmas Island and the Cocos (Keeling) Islands, which in 2010 were external territories of Australia administered under Australian law. Christmas Island held an immigration detention centre, and in December 2010 a boat carrying asylum seekers wrecked against its cliffs, killing dozens in a widely reported tragedy.","2026":"The Indian Ocean Territories are external territories of Australia comprising Christmas Island and the Cocos (Keeling) Islands, administered from Canberra. As of 2026 they have small populations and are governed under Australian law applied through the territories' administration."},
  "indonesia": {"1960":"In 1960 Indonesia was an independent republic under President Sukarno, who had introduced \"Guided Democracy\" after dissolving the elected constituent assembly in 1959. The country was a leading voice of non-alignment, and Sukarno balanced the army against the large Communist Party (PKI) amid economic difficulties and the unresolved dispute with the Dutch over West New Guinea.","1994":"In 1994 Indonesia was an authoritarian republic under President Suharto's New Order regime, which he had led since the 1960s. The country remained in occupation of East Timor, which it had annexed in 1976, and continued rapid economic growth as one of Southeast Asia's emerging economies.","2000":"In 2000 Indonesia was a republic undergoing democratic transition after the 1998 fall of Suharto, with Abdurrahman Wahid as president and Megawati Sukarnoputri as vice president. The country faced serious unrest, including separatist conflict in Aceh and sectarian violence in the Maluku islands. East Timor, which had voted for independence in 1999, was under UN administration and no longer governed by Indonesia.","2010":"In 2010 Indonesia was a sovereign presidential republic, the world's most populous Muslim-majority nation, led by President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, who had been re-elected in 2009. The year saw major natural disasters, including the eruption of Mount Merapi in central Java and a tsunami in the Mentawai Islands, both in late October 2010, which together killed hundreds.","2026":"Indonesia is a sovereign presidential republic and the world's largest archipelagic state, with its capital officially being relocated to Nusantara on Borneo. As of 2026 it is led by President Prabowo Subianto, who took office in October 2024 after winning the February 2024 election, succeeding Joko Widodo."},
  "iran": {"1920":"In 1920 Iran was a constitutional monarchy under the Qajar dynasty, with Ahmad Shah on the throne, but it was weak and heavily influenced by Britain and Russia. The proposed Anglo-Persian Agreement of 1919 sought to make Iran a virtual British protectorate but met strong opposition and was never ratified. Separatist movements such as the Soviet-backed Persian Socialist Soviet Republic in Gilan emerged in this period, shortly before Reza Khan's 1921 coup.","1938":"In 1938 Iran was a monarchy ruled by Reza Shah Pahlavi, who pursued aggressive modernization, secularization, and centralization of the state. The Trans-Iranian Railway, a major infrastructure project linking the Caspian to the Persian Gulf, was nearing completion during this period.","1960":"In 1960 Iran was a monarchy under Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, whose rule had been bolstered by the 1953 coup that ousted Prime Minister Mosaddegh. The country was closely aligned with the United States and the West, and oil revenues and growing royal authority shaped its politics ahead of the reforms later launched as the White Revolution.","1994":"In 1994 Iran was an Islamic republic with Ali Khamenei as Supreme Leader and Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani as president, who was pursuing post-war economic reconstruction and liberalization after the 1980s war with Iraq. The country remained internationally isolated, under U.S. sanctions and at odds with the West.","2000":"In 2000 Iran was the Islamic Republic of Iran, a theocratic system with Ayatollah Ali Khamenei as Supreme Leader and reformist Mohammad Khatami as elected president. Reformists won a strong majority in the February 2000 Majlis elections, but hardliners in the judiciary responded by closing many reformist newspapers. The period was marked by tension between the elected reformist government and unelected conservative institutions.","2010":"In 2010 Iran was the Islamic Republic of Iran under Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei, with Mahmoud Ahmadinejad as president following his disputed 2009 re-election that had sparked the Green Movement protests. The year was marked by intensifying international sanctions over its nuclear program and by the Stuxnet computer worm, which damaged centrifuges at its uranium enrichment facilities.","2026":"Iran is a sovereign Islamic republic in Western Asia with its capital at Tehran, governed under a system combining an elected president with a Supreme Leader, Ali Khamenei. As of 2026 its president is Masoud Pezeshkian, elected in 2024 after Ebrahim Raisi's death; the year followed a major June 2025 conflict in which Israel and the United States struck Iranian nuclear and military sites."},
  "iraq": {"1960":"In 1960 Iraq was a republic led by Prime Minister Abd al-Karim Qasim, who had come to power in the 1958 revolution that overthrew the Hashemite monarchy. Qasim pursued a non-aligned course, withdrew from the Western-backed Baghdad Pact, and his rivalry with Nasserists and Communists marked an unstable period; in 1960 he also legalized political parties and tensions with the Kurds and over oil policy were intensifying.","1994":"In 1994 Iraq was ruled by Saddam Hussein's Ba'athist regime, still subject to severe United Nations sanctions imposed after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait and defeat in the 1991 Gulf War. In October 1994 Iraq massed troops near the Kuwaiti border, prompting a U.S. military deployment, and that November Iraq formally recognized Kuwait's sovereignty and borders.","2000":"In 2000 Iraq was a republic under the authoritarian rule of President Saddam Hussein and the Ba'ath Party. The country remained under comprehensive UN sanctions imposed after the 1990 invasion of Kuwait, with humanitarian needs partly met through the Oil-for-Food Programme. Northern Iraq's Kurdish region operated with de facto autonomy, and US and UK aircraft patrolled no-fly zones over the north and south.","2010":"In 2010 Iraq was a sovereign federal parliamentary republic still under partial US military presence following the 2003 invasion and the toppling of Saddam Hussein. The March 2010 parliamentary elections produced no clear winner, leading to a prolonged government-formation deadlock that lasted months before Nouri al-Maliki was confirmed for a second term as prime minister late in the year, while sectarian violence continued.","2026":"Iraq is a sovereign federal parliamentary republic in Western Asia with its capital at Baghdad, including the autonomous Kurdistan Region in the north. As of 2026 it held parliamentary elections in November 2025, continues to balance relations between the United States and Iran, and works to manage Iran-aligned armed factions amid regional tensions."},
  "ireland": {"1938":"In 1938 the Irish state, governed by Éamon de Valera as Taoiseach, operated under the 1937 Constitution that renamed it Ireland (Éire) and asserted greater sovereignty from Britain. That year the Anglo-Irish Trade Agreement ended the economic war and returned the Treaty Ports to Irish control, while Douglas Hyde became the first President of Ireland.","1960":"In 1960 Ireland was an independent republic, having declared itself a republic in 1949 and left the Commonwealth. Seán Lemass had become Taoiseach in 1959, succeeding Éamon de Valera, and his government began promoting economic modernization and foreign investment to reverse stagnation and emigration; Ireland also joined the United Nations' peacekeeping efforts, sending troops to the Congo in 1960.","1994":"In 1994 Ireland was an independent parliamentary republic; a coalition government collapsed late in the year and a new Fine Gael-led 'Rainbow Coalition' under Taoiseach John Bruton took office in December. A pivotal event was the Provisional IRA's ceasefire announced on 31 August 1994, a major step in the Northern Ireland peace process.","2000":"In 2000 Ireland was an independent parliamentary republic, governed by a Fianna Fail-led coalition under Taoiseach Bertie Ahern. Its economy was booming during the Celtic Tiger era, with rapid growth and falling unemployment. Ireland was a member of the European Union and had adopted the euro as its currency from 1999, and the 1998 Good Friday Agreement had reshaped its constitutional claim to Northern Ireland.","2010":"In 2010 Ireland was a sovereign parliamentary republic and EU member led by Taoiseach Brian Cowen of Fianna Fail. Devastated by a banking and property collapse, the country accepted an EU-IMF bailout of roughly 85 billion euros in November 2010 amid severe austerity, an event that fatally undermined the governing coalition.","2026":"Ireland is a sovereign parliamentary republic occupying most of the island of Ireland, a member of the European Union, with its capital at Dublin. As of 2026 it is governed by a Fianna Fail-Fine Gael coalition formed after the November 2024 general election, with Micheal Martin as Taoiseach, and Catherine Connolly was elected president in October 2025."},
  "isle of man": {"1960":"In 1960 the Isle of Man was a self-governing British Crown Dependency with its own parliament, Tynwald, and was not part of the United Kingdom. The British Crown retained responsibility for defence and foreign affairs, while the island handled its own domestic legislation.","1994":"In 1994 the Isle of Man was a self-governing British Crown Dependency, not part of the United Kingdom, with its own parliament, the Tynwald, and the British monarch as head of state represented by a Lieutenant Governor. The United Kingdom remained responsible for its defence and external affairs.","2000":"In 2000 the Isle of Man was a self-governing British Crown Dependency, not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union, with the British monarch as Lord of Mann and represented by a Lieutenant Governor. It had its own ancient legislature, Tynwald, which legislated on domestic matters while the UK handled defence and foreign affairs. The island was a growing offshore financial centre.","2010":"In 2010 the Isle of Man was a self-governing British Crown Dependency, not part of the United Kingdom or the EU, with the British monarch as Lord of Mann and Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. It governed its own domestic affairs through the Tynwald, while the UK remained responsible for its defence and external relations.","2026":"The Isle of Man is a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Irish Sea, not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union, with the British monarch as Lord of Mann and the UK responsible for its defence and foreign affairs. As of 2026 it is governed by its own ancient parliament, Tynwald, and the UK Crown is represented by a Lieutenant Governor."},
  "israel": {"1960":"In 1960 Israel was an independent parliamentary republic, established in 1948, with David Ben-Gurion serving as prime minister. The state was absorbing large numbers of Jewish immigrants and remained in a state of unresolved conflict with its Arab neighbors after the 1948 war and the 1956 Suez crisis. In May 1960 Israeli agents captured the Nazi fugitive Adolf Eichmann in Argentina and brought him to Israel to stand trial.","1994":"In 1994 Israel was a parliamentary democracy under a Labor-led government with Yitzhak Rabin as prime minister, deepening the peace process begun with the 1993 Oslo Accords. That year the Gaza-Jericho Agreement established Palestinian self-rule in those areas, and on 26 October 1994 Israel signed a peace treaty with Jordan; Rabin shared the Nobel Peace Prize.","2000":"In 2000 Israel was a parliamentary democracy led by Prime Minister Ehud Barak of the Labor Party. In May 2000 Israel withdrew its forces from the security zone in southern Lebanon, and in July the Camp David summit with Yasser Arafat, brokered by US President Clinton, failed to reach a final peace agreement. In late September 2000 the Second Intifada erupted, beginning a prolonged period of violence.","2010":"In 2010 Israel was a sovereign parliamentary democracy led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who had returned to office in 2009, with Shimon Peres as president. In May 2010 Israeli commandos raided the Gaza-bound Mavi Marmara flotilla, killing nine Turkish activists and triggering a severe rupture in Israeli-Turkish relations, while US-brokered direct talks with the Palestinians briefly resumed and then stalled over settlement construction.","2026":"Israel in 2026 is a parliamentary democracy whose government was led by Benjamin Netanyahu at the head of a right-wing coalition. The country remained deeply affected by the war that began with the October 2023 Hamas attack, with continued military operations and regional tensions involving Gaza, Lebanon, and Iran."},
  "italian somaliland": {"1920":"In 1920 Italian Somaliland was a colony of Italy on the Indian Ocean coast of the Horn of Africa, administered from Mogadishu. Italian control of the interior was still incomplete, with the Sultanates of Hobyo and the Majeerteen retaining significant autonomy until the later 1920s. The colony was part of Italy's broader holdings in northeast Africa.","1938":"In 1938 Italian Somaliland was an Italian colony in the Horn of Africa. Following Italy's 1936 conquest of Ethiopia, it had been incorporated as a constituent part of Italian East Africa (Africa Orientale Italiana), administered together with Eritrea and the newly annexed Ethiopian territories."},
  "italy": {"1900":"In 1900 Italy was a constitutional monarchy, the Kingdom of Italy, unified since 1861 and ruled by the House of Savoy. King Umberto I was assassinated by the anarchist Gaetano Bresci at Monza in July 1900, and his son Victor Emmanuel III succeeded to the throne. The country was industrializing in the north while the south remained poor, and Italy had recently suffered a major colonial defeat at Adwa in Ethiopia in 1896.","1920":"In 1920 Italy was a constitutional monarchy under King Victor Emmanuel III, one of the victorious Allied powers of World War I but suffering deep postwar economic and social turmoil. The period known as the Biennio Rosso saw widespread strikes, factory occupations, and land seizures, while nationalist resentment over the peace settlement—the so-called 'mutilated victory'—was acute. Gabriele D'Annunzio's occupation of Fiume continued into late 1920, and Mussolini's Fascist movement was gaining ground.","1938":"In 1938 Italy was a kingdom under King Victor Emmanuel III but ruled by the Fascist dictatorship of Benito Mussolini. That year the regime enacted racial laws stripping Jews of many rights, and Italy was deepening its alignment with Nazi Germany while controlling its East African empire and Libya; Mussolini also took part in the Munich Conference in September 1938.","1960":"In 1960 Italy was a parliamentary republic governed by Christian Democrat-led coalitions, in the midst of a period of rapid industrialization and growth later called the economic miracle. Rome hosted the Summer Olympic Games in 1960. The year also saw political turmoil under the short-lived Tambroni government, which fell amid violent anti-fascist protests.","1994":"In 1994 Italy was a parliamentary republic undergoing major political upheaval following the Tangentopoli corruption scandals that had discredited the old parties. Elections in March 1994 brought media magnate Silvio Berlusconi to power as prime minister leading a center-right coalition, though his government collapsed by the end of the year.","2000":"In 2000 Italy was a parliamentary republic and a founding member of the European Union, having joined the euro. The center-left government saw Giuliano Amato become prime minister in April 2000, leading one of several short-lived coalition governments of the period. Italy hosted major Catholic Jubilee Year celebrations in Rome in 2000, drawing millions of pilgrims.","2010":"In 2010 Italy was a sovereign parliamentary republic and EU founding member, with Silvio Berlusconi as prime minister and Giorgio Napolitano as president. Berlusconi's center-right government was increasingly weakened by a split with his ally Gianfranco Fini and by personal scandals, while the country faced sluggish growth amid the wider European debt crisis.","2026":"Italy in 2026 is a parliamentary republic and member of the European Union and the eurozone, with Giorgia Meloni serving as prime minister at the head of a right-wing coalition that took office in 2022. Sergio Mattarella continued as president."},
  "ivory coast": {"1900":"By 1900 Ivory Coast was a French colony, formally established in 1893, on the West African coast. French control was still being extended inland against considerable African resistance, and the colony was administered as part of France's expanding West African empire."},
  "jamaica": {"1920":"In 1920 Jamaica was a British Crown Colony in the Caribbean, governed by a British-appointed governor. Its economy relied heavily on sugar and banana exports, and most of the population were descendants of enslaved Africans with limited political representation. Marcus Garvey's Pan-African movement had roots on the island during this era.","1938":"In 1938 Jamaica was a British colony in the Caribbean. The year saw major labor unrest and rioting over wages and conditions, which spurred the rise of trade unions and the founding of the People's National Party under Norman Manley, marking a turning point in Jamaican political and labor history.","1960":"In 1960 Jamaica was still a British colony and a member of the West Indies Federation, which had been formed in 1958. It had internal self-government, and full independence would not come until 1962. Norman Manley's People's National Party held power in the colonial legislature at this time.","1994":"In 1994 Jamaica was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, governed by Prime Minister P. J. Patterson of the People's National Party. The economy relied heavily on bauxite, tourism, and remittances, and the government continued market-oriented economic policies.","2000":"In 2000 Jamaica was an independent parliamentary democracy and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, represented by a Governor-General. The People's National Party government was led by Prime Minister P. J. Patterson. The country struggled with high crime and economic difficulties during this period.","2010":"In 2010 Jamaica was a sovereign parliamentary constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and Bruce Golding as prime minister. In May 2010 security forces launched a violent operation in the Tivoli Gardens area of Kingston to capture drug lord Christopher Coke for extradition to the United States, leaving dozens of people dead.","2026":"Jamaica in 2026 is a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with King Charles III as head of state represented by a governor-general. There has been ongoing public discussion about transitioning to a republic."},
  "japan": {"1960":"In 1960 Japan was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy under the 1947 constitution, allied with the United States. The year was dominated by the massive Anpo protests against the revision of the US-Japan Security Treaty, which led to the resignation of Prime Minister Nobusuke Kishi and the cancellation of a planned visit by President Eisenhower. Kishi was succeeded by Hayato Ikeda, who launched the Income Doubling Plan amid Japan's rapid postwar economic growth.","1994":"In 1994 Japan was a constitutional monarchy with Emperor Akihito on the throne, experiencing notable political instability that broke the long dominance of the Liberal Democratic Party. The year saw multiple changes of prime minister, culminating in June 1994 with Socialist Tomiichi Murayama leading an unusual coalition government, while the economy struggled in the aftermath of the asset-bubble collapse.","2000":"In 2000 Japan was a constitutional monarchy with Emperor Akihito as ceremonial head of state and a parliamentary government. Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi suffered a stroke and died in 2000, and Yoshiro Mori of the Liberal Democratic Party became prime minister. Japan was still grappling with the prolonged economic stagnation that followed its asset bubble, often called the Lost Decade, and hosted the G8 summit in Okinawa that year.","2010":"In 2010 Japan was a sovereign constitutional monarchy with Emperor Akihito as head of state, governed by the Democratic Party of Japan, which had taken power in 2009; Yukio Hatoyama resigned as prime minister in June 2010 and was succeeded by Naoto Kan. In September 2010 a collision near the disputed Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands sharply escalated tensions with China.","2026":"Japan in 2026 is a constitutional monarchy with Emperor Naruhito on the throne and a parliamentary government dominated for most of the postwar era by the Liberal Democratic Party. The country continued to grapple with an aging, shrinking population and regional security concerns involving China and North Korea."},
  "jersey": {"1960":"In 1960 Jersey was a British Crown Dependency, a self-governing bailiwick possessing its own legislature, the States of Jersey, and not part of the United Kingdom proper. It was not part of the colonial empire but a possession of the Crown with its own laws and institutions.","1994":"In 1994 Jersey was a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, not part of the United Kingdom, with its own legislature, the States of Jersey, and the British monarch as head of state represented by a Lieutenant Governor. The United Kingdom remained responsible for its defence and external relations.","2000":"In 2000 Jersey was a self-governing British Crown Dependency, the largest of the Channel Islands, not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union. The British monarch was head of state, represented by a Lieutenant Governor, while the States of Jersey legislated on domestic affairs and the UK handled defence and foreign relations. Jersey was a prominent international offshore financial centre.","2010":"In 2010 Jersey was a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, not part of the United Kingdom or the EU, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state in her capacity as Duke of Normandy. It managed its own internal affairs and finances, functioning as a significant offshore financial centre, while the UK handled its defence and international representation.","2026":"Jersey in 2026 is a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Channel Islands, not part of the United Kingdom or the European Union, with the UK responsible for its defence and foreign affairs. It has its own legislature, the States Assembly, and is a noted offshore financial centre."},
  "jordan": {"1938":"In 1938 the territory was the Emirate of Transjordan, ruled by Emir Abdullah of the Hashemite family under British Mandate authority, with Britain controlling its defense and foreign affairs. It was a distinct administrative entity separated from Mandatory Palestine, not yet a fully independent kingdom.","1960":"In 1960 the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan was an independent monarchy ruled by King Hussein, who had taken full powers in 1957. At this time Jordan controlled the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, which it had annexed in 1950. In August 1960 Prime Minister Hazza' al-Majali was assassinated in a bombing in Amman.","1994":"In 1994 Jordan was a constitutional monarchy ruled by King Hussein, who pursued political liberalization and peace with Israel. On 26 October 1994 Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel, becoming the second Arab state after Egypt to formally make peace, ending the official state of war between the two countries.","2000":"In 2000 Jordan was the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, a constitutional monarchy ruled by King Abdullah II, who had succeeded his father King Hussein after Hussein's death in 1999. Jordan maintained its 1994 peace treaty with Israel and pursued economic reform and liberalization. In 2000 Jordan acceded to the World Trade Organization and negotiated a free trade agreement with the United States.","2010":"In 2010 Jordan was a sovereign constitutional monarchy ruled by King Abdullah II, a close Western ally bordering Israel and the West Bank. Parliamentary elections were held in November 2010 under a revised electoral law after the king had dissolved the previous parliament, and the elections were boycotted by the Islamic Action Front.","2026":"Jordan in 2026 is a constitutional monarchy ruled by King Abdullah II, who holds substantial executive power alongside an appointed government and elected parliament. The kingdom continued to host large numbers of Palestinian and Syrian refugees and was affected by instability in the surrounding region."},
  "kanem-bornu": {"1900":"Around 1900 the historic Kanem-Bornu empire near Lake Chad had been overrun by the Sudanese warlord Rabih az-Zubayr, who had conquered Bornu in the 1890s. French forces defeated and killed Rabih at the Battle of Kousseri in 1900, after which the region was partitioned among French, British, and German colonial spheres."},
  "kazakhstan": {"1994":"An independent republic that had emerged from the dissolution of the Soviet Union in late 1991, led by President Nursultan Nazarbayev. In 1994 it remained the only post-Soviet state still holding nuclear weapons on its territory while negotiating their transfer to Russia, and that year it agreed to move its capital from Almaty to Akmola (later Astana).","2000":"An independent republic that had emerged from the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991, led by President Nursultan Nazarbayev. Around 2000 it was developing its vast oil and gas reserves in the Caspian region and had recently moved its capital from Almaty to Astana in 1997.","2010":"In 2010 Kazakhstan was an independent presidential republic led by Nursultan Nazarbayev, who had ruled since the Soviet era and the country's 1991 independence. That year Kazakhstan held the rotating chairmanship of the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe, the first former Soviet and Central Asian state to do so. Its economy was driven by large oil and gas reserves, and the capital was Astana.","2026":"Kazakhstan in 2026 is a presidential republic led by Kassym-Jomart Tokayev, who consolidated power following the 2022 unrest and the departure of long-ruling Nursultan Nazarbayev from political life. It is Central Asia's largest economy, rich in oil and minerals, and maintains close but balancing ties with Russia and China."},
  "kenya": {"1920":"In 1920 the colony was formally constituted as Kenya Colony, converted that year from the former British East Africa Protectorate into a Crown Colony (with a coastal strip remaining a protectorate nominally under the Sultan of Zanzibar). It was administered by Britain and characterized by white settler farming in the fertile highlands, where Africans faced land alienation and labor demands. African political grievances over land and taxation were growing in this period.","1938":"In 1938 Kenya was a British colony and protectorate in East Africa, administered from Nairobi. Its fertile highlands were reserved largely for white settler farming, while the African majority faced land restrictions and labor controls that fueled growing grievances, particularly among the Kikuyu.","1960":"In 1960 Kenya was a British colony, and the Mau Mau emergency declared in 1952 was formally ended in January 1960. The Lancaster House Conference held in London in early 1960 set Kenya on a path toward majority African rule and eventual independence. Kenyan political parties, including KANU, were forming during this year, though independence would not come until 1963.","1994":"A republic in East Africa governed by President Daniel arap Moi, who had won the country's first multiparty election in December 1992 after constitutional reforms ended one-party KANU rule. In 1994 the opposition remained fragmented and the government faced criticism over ethnic clashes and human rights, while veteran opposition figure Jaramogi Oginga Odinga died that January.","2000":"A sovereign republic in East Africa led by President Daniel arap Moi, whose long rule under the KANU party continued in 2000. The country faced economic difficulties, corruption concerns, and drought during this period, with multiparty elections having been reintroduced in the 1990s.","2010":"In 2010 Kenya was an independent republic in East Africa, with Mwai Kibaki as president governing in a power-sharing arrangement with Prime Minister Raila Odinga formed after the disputed 2007 election and ensuing violence. In August 2010 Kenyans approved a new constitution by referendum, introducing a devolved system of counties and a bill of rights. Nairobi was the capital.","2026":"Kenya in 2026 is a presidential republic with William Ruto as president, having won the 2022 election. The country faced significant public discontent, including major protests in 2024 over tax increases and the cost of living."},
  "kiribati": {"1960":"In 1960 the islands that now form Kiribati were administered by Britain as part of the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Colony. The territory was a British colony in the central Pacific and would not become the independent state of Kiribati until 1979.","1994":"An independent island republic in the central Pacific, having gained independence from Britain in 1979, with a president as head of state and government. In 1994 Teburoro Tito was elected president following a period of political change.","2000":"An independent island republic in the central Pacific, having gained independence from the United Kingdom in 1979. In 2000 it was a small nation spread across numerous atolls, increasingly concerned about the threat of rising sea levels.","2010":"In 2010 Kiribati was an independent republic in the central Pacific, spread across numerous atolls straddling the equator and the International Date Line. Anote Tong was president, and the low-lying nation was prominent in international discussions of climate change and sea-level rise. Its capital was on Tarawa.","2026":"Kiribati in 2026 is an independent island republic in the central Pacific, with the president serving as head of state and government. It is among the nations most threatened by sea-level rise and switched its diplomatic recognition from Taiwan to China in 2019."},
  "kong": {"1900":"The Kong Empire, a Dyula Muslim trading and military state in the region of present-day Côte d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso, had been destroyed by Samori Ture's forces in 1897-1898, who sacked the city of Kong. By 1900 the area had fallen under French colonial control following Samori's own capture in 1898."},
  "korea": {"1900":"In 1900 Korea was the Korean Empire, proclaimed in 1897 by Emperor Gojong, who had elevated himself from king to emperor in an assertion of independence. The country was nominally sovereign but was the object of intense rivalry between Russia and Japan, whose competition over Korea would soon lead to the Russo-Japanese War."},
  "kosovo": {"2026":"Kosovo in 2026 is a partially recognized republic that declared independence from Serbia in 2008; Serbia and several other states still do not recognize it. Tensions with Serbia and over the Serb-majority north have persisted, with EU-mediated normalization talks continuing."},
  "kuba": {"1900":"The Kuba Kingdom was a Central African state in the south-central Congo basin, ruled by a king from the Bushoong dynasty. Around 1900 it retained considerable autonomy under its own monarchy but lay within the territory claimed by the Congo Free State, King Leopold II's personally controlled colony."},
  "kuwait": {"1938":"In 1938 Kuwait was a sheikhdom under British protection, ruled by Sheikh Ahmad al-Jaber al-Sabah, with Britain handling its foreign relations. That same year commercial quantities of oil were discovered at the Burgan field, though large-scale exports would not begin until after the Second World War. The year also saw the short-lived Majlis movement, in which reform-minded merchants pressed for an elected council before the ruler suppressed it.","1960":"In 1960 Kuwait was still a British protectorate under a treaty dating to 1899, ruled by the Al Sabah family, with Sheikh Abdullah al-Salim al-Sabah as emir. Its economy was being transformed by large-scale oil exports. Full independence from Britain would come in 1961.","1994":"A sovereign emirate on the Persian Gulf ruled by the Al Sabah family, with Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah as emir, recovering and rebuilding after the 1990–1991 Iraqi invasion and the Gulf War that liberated it. In October 1994 Iraq again massed troops near the border, prompting a renewed US and coalition military deployment to deter another attack.","2000":"A sovereign emirate on the Persian Gulf ruled by the Al Sabah family, with Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmad al-Sabah as emir in 2000. Having been liberated from Iraqi occupation in the 1991 Gulf War, it had rebuilt its oil industry and remained a major oil exporter.","2010":"In 2010 Kuwait was an independent constitutional emirate on the Persian Gulf, ruled by Emir Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, with an elected National Assembly. Its economy was dominated by large petroleum reserves. The country experienced ongoing tensions between the appointed government and the parliament during this period.","2026":"Kuwait in 2026 is a constitutional emirate ruled by the Al Sabah family, with Sheikh Mishal Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah as emir following the death of his predecessor in 2023. In 2024 the emir dissolved parliament and suspended parts of the constitution, concentrating power in the ruling family amid political deadlock. It is a major oil exporter."},
  "kyrgyzstan": {"1994":"An independent Central Asian republic that became sovereign with the Soviet collapse in 1991, led by President Askar Akayev, who was regarded as relatively liberal among the region's leaders. In 1994 the country was pursuing market reforms while facing economic hardship and political tensions over the parliament and constitutional arrangements.","2000":"An independent Central Asian republic that became sovereign with the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991, led by President Askar Akayev in 2000. The country was relatively poor and mountainous, and faced incursions by militants in the south around this period.","2010":"In 2010 Kyrgyzstan underwent major political upheaval: in April protests overthrew President Kurmanbek Bakiyev, who fled the country, and an interim government led by Roza Otunbayeva took power. In June ethnic clashes between Kyrgyz and Uzbeks in the south, around Osh, killed hundreds and displaced many. A June referendum approved a new constitution shifting the country toward a parliamentary system.","2026":"Kyrgyzstan in 2026 is a presidential republic led by Sadyr Japarov, who came to power after the 2020 unrest and oversaw constitutional changes strengthening the presidency. It remains one of Central Asia's poorer states and maintains close ties with Russia."},
  "lagos": {"1900":"In 1900 Lagos was a British colony on the West African coast, having been annexed by Britain in 1861 and developed as a major port and trading center. In 1900 the surrounding region was reorganized as British colonial administration expanded, with the Colony of Lagos shortly afterward joined to the Protectorate of Southern Nigeria."},
  "laos": {"1938":"In 1938 Laos was a French protectorate forming part of French Indochina, with the kingdom of Luang Prabang preserved under French oversight and the rest administered directly by France. It was one of the least developed and most sparsely populated parts of the Indochinese Union.","1960":"In 1960 the Kingdom of Laos was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Sisavang Vatthana, but it was deeply unstable and caught up in Cold War rivalry. In August 1960 a coup led by Captain Kong Le seized Vientiane, deepening the civil war among neutralist, rightist, and communist Pathet Lao factions.","1994":"A one-party socialist state, the Lao People's Democratic Republic, governed by the Lao People's Revolutionary Party. In 1994 the country was gradually opening its economy under market-oriented reforms, and the Thai-Lao Friendship Bridge across the Mekong River opened that April, the first such bridge linking the two countries.","2000":"A one-party socialist republic governed by the Lao People's Revolutionary Party, having been established in 1975. In 2000 it remained one of the poorest countries in Southeast Asia, with a largely agrarian economy and close ties to Vietnam.","2010":"In 2010 Laos was a one-party socialist republic governed by the Lao People's Revolutionary Party. It remained a landlocked Southeast Asian state with a largely agricultural, developing economy, increasingly tied to investment from neighbors such as China, Vietnam, and Thailand and to hydropower projects on the Mekong. Vientiane was the capital.","2026":"Laos in 2026 is a one-party socialist republic governed by the Lao People's Revolutionary Party. The country faced serious economic strain, including high public debt much of it owed to China and significant currency depreciation and inflation."},
  "latvia": {"1920":"In 1920 Latvia was a newly independent republic, having declared independence in 1918 and secured it through the Latvian War of Independence against both German and Soviet Russian forces. In August 1920 Soviet Russia signed a peace treaty recognizing Latvian independence. A constituent assembly elected in 1920 began drafting the new state's institutions and land reforms.","1938":"In 1938 Latvia was an independent republic ruled authoritarianly by Kārlis Ulmanis, who had seized power in a 1934 coup and governed without parliament. The country remained nominally neutral, but its independence was increasingly threatened by the rising power of Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union.","1994":"An independent Baltic republic that had restored its sovereignty in 1991 after Soviet rule, with a parliamentary government. In 1994 the last Russian troops withdrew from Latvian territory at the end of August, and debates over citizenship laws affecting the large Russian-speaking minority were prominent.","2000":"An independent Baltic republic that restored its sovereignty in 1991 after Soviet rule. By 2000 it was pursuing integration with Western institutions, working toward membership in the European Union and NATO.","2010":"In 2010 Latvia was an independent parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and NATO, both joined in 2004. The country was enduring a severe economic downturn following the global financial crisis, having taken an international bailout, with sharp GDP contraction and austerity measures. Valdis Dombrovskis was prime minister and Riga was the capital.","2026":"Latvia in 2026 is a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union, the eurozone, and NATO. As a Baltic state bordering Russia, it has emphasized defense and security in response to Russia's war in Ukraine."},
  "lebanon": {"1960":"In 1960 Lebanon was an independent parliamentary republic operating under its confessional power-sharing system, with Fuad Chehab as president following the 1958 crisis. The country was in a period of relative stability and reform under Chehab after American forces had intervened in 1958 and then withdrawn.","1994":"A republic recovering from its long civil war, which had ended in 1990, governed under the Taif Agreement's power-sharing arrangements with substantial Syrian military and political influence. In 1994 the country was undergoing postwar reconstruction, with Rafic Hariri as prime minister overseeing rebuilding efforts.","2000":"A sovereign republic recovering from its long civil war that ended in 1990, with politics shaped by the Taif Agreement's power-sharing among religious communities. In 2000 Syrian troops maintained a strong presence, and Israel withdrew from its occupation zone in southern Lebanon in May of that year.","2010":"In 2010 Lebanon was an independent parliamentary republic with a confessional power-sharing system, under a national unity government led by Prime Minister Saad Hariri. Political tensions were high over the Special Tribunal for Lebanon investigating the 2005 assassination of Rafik Hariri, amid friction between the Western-aligned March 14 bloc and the Hezbollah-led March 8 bloc. Beirut was the capital.","2026":"Lebanon is a sovereign parliamentary republic on the eastern Mediterranean, governed under a confessional power-sharing system that allots top offices among religious communities. In 2026 the country is still recovering from a severe multi-year economic and banking collapse, with Hezbollah's political and military role and the aftermath of its 2024 conflict with Israel dominating national affairs after a prolonged presidential vacancy was resolved with the election of Joseph Aoun in early 2025."},
  "lesotho": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory was Basutoland, a British protectorate in southern Africa administered separately from the Union of South Africa and ruled indirectly through its paramount chief and traditional chiefs. Britain had kept it out of the Union of South Africa formed in 1910, preserving it as a distinct High Commission Territory. Its people, the Basotho, retained substantial internal customary governance under colonial oversight.","1938":"In 1938 the territory was Basutoland, a British High Commission protectorate in southern Africa ruled through its paramount chief and traditional authorities. It remained administratively separate from the neighboring Union of South Africa, which sought its incorporation.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was the British protectorate of Basutoland, not yet independent. A new constitution introduced in 1960 created an elected Basutoland National Council, an early step toward self-government. Full independence as the Kingdom of Lesotho would not come until 1966.","1994":"A constitutional monarchy entirely surrounded by South Africa, with King Letsie III on the throne and a government under Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle, who had won the 1993 elections that restored civilian rule. In August 1994 King Letsie III, with military backing, suspended the constitution and dismissed the government in a brief constitutional crisis, which was resolved through mediation by South Africa, Botswana, and Zimbabwe.","2000":"A sovereign kingdom entirely surrounded by South Africa, a constitutional monarchy with King Letsie III as head of state. The country had experienced political instability in the late 1990s, including a 1998 intervention by South African and Botswanan forces.","2010":"In 2010 Lesotho was an independent constitutional monarchy entirely surrounded by South Africa, with King Letsie III as head of state and Pakalitha Mosisili as prime minister. It remained a small, mountainous, developing country economically dependent on South Africa, with the Lesotho Highlands Water Project supplying water to its neighbor. Maseru was the capital.","2026":"Lesotho is a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy entirely landlocked within South Africa, with King Letsie III as head of state. In 2026 it remains a small, mountainous, lower-middle-income country reliant on water exports to South Africa, textile manufacturing, and remittances, with politics marked by frequent coalition governments."},
  "liberia": {"1900":"In 1900 Liberia was an independent republic on the West African coast, founded by freed American slaves and a sovereign state since 1847. It was governed by an Americo-Liberian elite, and its independence was increasingly pressured by the encroachment of neighboring British and French colonial territories.","1920":"In 1920 Liberia was an independent republic on the West African coast, governed by the Americo-Liberian elite descended from freed American slaves and dominated politically by the True Whig Party. The country was financially strained and heavily dependent on foreign loans, with the indigenous African majority largely excluded from political power. Its economy remained underdeveloped, predating the later Firestone rubber concession of the 1920s.","1938":"In 1938 Liberia was an independent republic on the West African coast, governed by the True Whig Party and the Americo-Liberian settler elite under President Edwin Barclay. Still recovering from the 1930s international scandal over forced labor practices, it remained economically dependent, with the Firestone rubber plantations a dominant presence in its economy.","1960":"In 1960 Liberia was an independent republic, one of Africa's few states never colonized by a European power, governed by the True Whig Party under President William Tubman. Tubman pursued his Open Door economic policy and a unification policy aimed at integrating the indigenous population with the Americo-Liberian elite.","1994":"A West African republic in the midst of a civil war that had begun in 1989, with much of the country divided among armed factions including Charles Taylor's NPFL while a fragile interim government held Monrovia. In 1994 the war continued despite peace agreements such as the Cotonou Accord, with ECOWAS's ECOMOG force deployed and repeated breakdowns in attempts to form a transitional government.","2000":"A West African republic led by President Charles Taylor, who had won the 1997 election following the country's civil war. In 2000 the nation remained unstable, and renewed armed conflict from rebel groups was emerging.","2010":"In 2010 Liberia was an independent republic on West Africa's coast, led by President Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, Africa's first elected female head of state. The country was recovering from prolonged civil war, with a United Nations peacekeeping mission still present and a focus on rebuilding institutions and infrastructure. Monrovia was the capital.","2026":"Liberia is a sovereign presidential republic on West Africa's Atlantic coast, founded by freed American slaves in the 19th century. In 2026 it is governed by President Joseph Boakai, who took office in early 2024 after defeating George Weah, and continues to grapple with poverty, corruption, and reconstruction following its earlier civil wars and Ebola epidemic."},
  "libya": {"1938":"In 1938 Libya was an Italian colony, consolidated after Italy's brutal reconquest of Cyrenaica that ended in 1932. Governor Italo Balbo promoted Italian agricultural colonization, and in 1938 large numbers of Italian settlers were brought in to establish farming communities.","1960":"In 1960 Libya was the independent United Kingdom of Libya, a federal monarchy under King Idris I, having gained independence in 1951. The country was still poor at this time, though major oil discoveries in the late 1950s were beginning to transform its prospects, with large-scale oil exports starting in 1961.","1994":"A state ruled by Muammar Gaddafi under his Jamahiriya system, subject to United Nations sanctions imposed in 1992 over its refusal to surrender suspects in the Lockerbie airliner bombing. In 1994 these air and arms embargoes remained in force, isolating the country internationally.","2000":"A state under the rule of Muammar Gaddafi, who had held power since 1969 under his system known as the Jamahiriya. In 2000 Libya remained subject to international pressure related to the Lockerbie bombing, though UN sanctions had been suspended in 1999 after two suspects were handed over for trial.","2010":"In 2010 Libya was ruled by Muammar Gaddafi, who had held power since a 1969 coup, under his idiosyncratic Jamahiriya system. The oil-rich North African state had in recent years normalized relations with Western governments after abandoning its weapons-of-mass-destruction programs. This was the year before the 2011 uprising that would topple Gaddafi.","2026":"Libya is a North African state that has remained politically fractured since the 2011 overthrow of Muammar Gaddafi, split between rival administrations. In 2026 power is divided between the internationally recognized Government of National Unity based in Tripoli in the west and authorities aligned with Khalifa Haftar's Libyan National Army in the east, with national elections repeatedly delayed."},
  "libya (it)": {"1920":"In 1920 the coastal regions of Tripolitania and Cyrenaica were Italian colonies, though Italy's control over the interior remained weak after its 1911 seizure of the territory from the Ottomans. In 1919 Italy had granted limited statute-based autonomy arrangements (the Legge Fondamentale) to Tripolitania, and Cyrenaica was under negotiations with the Senussi order led by Idris. Italian authority would not be fully reasserted until the later Fascist reconquest campaigns of the 1920s and 1930s."},
  "liechtenstein": {"1994":"A small independent principality between Switzerland and Austria, a constitutional monarchy under Prince Hans-Adam II in close economic union with Switzerland. In 1994 it joined the European Economic Area, having become a United Nations member in 1990.","2000":"A small sovereign constitutional monarchy in the Alps between Switzerland and Austria, with Prince Hans-Adam II as reigning prince. In 2000 it was a prosperous, low-tax financial center facing international scrutiny over its banking secrecy and money-laundering concerns.","2010":"In 2010 Liechtenstein was an independent constitutional monarchy and microstate between Switzerland and Austria, with Prince Hans-Adam II as sovereign and his son Hereditary Prince Alois acting as regent. It was a wealthy country with a strong financial-services and manufacturing economy, using the Swiss franc and in a customs union with Switzerland. Vaduz was the capital.","2026":"Liechtenstein is a tiny doubly landlocked constitutional monarchy between Switzerland and Austria, ruled by Prince Hans-Adam II with his son Hereditary Prince Alois serving as regent. In 2026 it remains a wealthy, low-tax financial and industrial microstate, closely tied to Switzerland through a customs and currency union and a member of the European Economic Area."},
  "lithuania": {"1920":"Lithuania had declared independence from Russia and Germany in 1918 and in 1920 was an independent republic, with the Soviet government recognizing its independence in the Treaty of Moscow that July. In October 1920 Polish forces under General Zeligowski seized Vilnius, which Lithuania claimed as its capital, leading to a lasting dispute and forcing the government to operate from Kaunas. The young state was still consolidating its institutions amid these conflicts with Poland and the recently repelled Bolshevik forces.","1938":"In 1938 Lithuania was an independent republic under the authoritarian rule of President Antanas Smetona and his Nationalist party. In March 1938 Poland issued an ultimatum forcing Lithuania to establish diplomatic relations and effectively renounce its claim to the Vilnius region, which Poland had held since 1920.","1994":"An independent Baltic republic that had restored its independence in 1990–1991 from the Soviet Union, with President Algirdas Brazauskas of the former communist Democratic Labour Party, elected in 1993. In 1994 the last Russian troops had already departed in 1993, and the country pursued integration with Western institutions.","2000":"An independent Baltic republic that restored its sovereignty in 1990–1991 after Soviet rule. By 2000 it was a parliamentary democracy pursuing membership in the European Union and NATO.","2010":"In 2010 Lithuania was an independent parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and NATO, both joined in 2004, with Dalia Grybauskaite as president. The country was contending with the aftermath of the global financial crisis, which had caused a deep recession and austerity measures. Vilnius was the capital.","2026":"Lithuania is a sovereign Baltic republic and a member of the European Union, NATO, and the eurozone. In 2026 it remains strongly focused on defense and security in response to Russia's war in Ukraine, increasing military spending and hosting allied forces, while maintaining tense relations with both Russia and Belarus on its borders."},
  "lozi": {"1900":"The Lozi kingdom (Barotseland) in the upper Zambezi floodplain was ruled around 1900 by Litunga Lewanika. Lewanika had signed treaties with the British South Africa Company in the 1890s, bringing Barotseland under British protection within what became Northern Rhodesia while the Lozi monarchy retained internal authority."},
  "luba": {"1900":"The Luba Empire was a Central African state in the savanna of the present-day Democratic Republic of the Congo. By around 1900 it had declined and fragmented amid 19th-century slave and ivory raiding, and its territory was being absorbed into the Congo Free State of King Leopold II."},
  "lunda": {"1900":"The Lunda Empire was a Central African state centered in the region of present-day Congo, Angola, and Zambia, headed by the ruler titled the Mwata Yamvo. By around 1900 the empire had broken up under 19th-century pressures and its lands were being partitioned among the Congo Free State, Portuguese Angola, and British territory."},
  "luxembourg": {"1900":"In 1900 Luxembourg was an independent grand duchy ruled by Grand Duke Adolphe of the House of Nassau-Weilburg, who had reigned since the personal union with the Netherlands ended in 1890. It was a small, neutral state whose economy was growing rapidly around its iron and steel industry.","1920":"Luxembourg in 1920 was an independent grand duchy under Grand Duchess Charlotte, who had acceded in 1919 after her sister Marie-Adelaide abdicated amid controversy over wartime conduct. A 1919 referendum had confirmed both the monarchy and an economic alignment with France, though France deferred to Belgium, and Luxembourg moved toward an economic union with Belgium. The country had emerged from German wartime occupation and was reorienting its political and economic ties westward.","1938":"In 1938 Luxembourg was an independent grand duchy under Grand Duchess Charlotte, maintaining a policy of neutrality. Bordering Nazi Germany, it grew increasingly anxious about its security as tensions rose in Europe.","1960":"In 1960 Luxembourg was an independent grand duchy under Grand Duchess Charlotte, a constitutional monarchy with a parliamentary government. A founding member of NATO and of the European Economic Community established in 1958, its prosperous economy rested heavily on its steel industry, and it formed an economic union with Belgium and the Netherlands (Benelux).","1994":"An independent grand duchy and constitutional monarchy under Grand Duke Jean, a founding member of the European Union, with Jacques Santer as prime minister. In 1994 Santer was selected to become President of the European Commission, and the country was a prosperous financial center within the EU.","2000":"A sovereign grand duchy and constitutional monarchy in Western Europe, with Grand Duke Henri acceding to the throne in 2000. A founding member of the European Union, it was a highly prosperous state and a major financial and banking center.","2010":"In 2010 Luxembourg was an independent constitutional monarchy and grand duchy, with Grand Duke Henri as head of state and Jean-Claude Juncker as prime minister. A founding member of the European Union, it was a wealthy state with a major financial-services sector and one of the world's highest GDPs per capita. Luxembourg City was the capital.","2026":"Luxembourg is a small, wealthy landlocked grand duchy in Western Europe and a founding member of the European Union, with Grand Duke Guillaume as head of state. In 2026 it remains a major international financial and banking center and host to several EU institutions, with one of the world's highest per-capita incomes."},
  "macao": {"1994":"In 1994 Macao was a Portuguese-administered territory on the southern coast of China, governed under the terms of the 1987 Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration that scheduled its return to Chinese sovereignty on 20 December 1999. It was run by a Portuguese-appointed governor, with a transitional administration preparing for the handover, and its economy relied heavily on tourism and gambling.","2000":"Macao was a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China, having been handed over from Portuguese administration on 20 December 1999 under the principle of \"one country, two systems.\" In 2000 it was led by its first Chief Executive, Edmund Ho, retaining its own legal system, currency, and a high degree of autonomy. Its economy centered on gaming and tourism.","2010":"In 2010 Macao was a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China, having returned from Portuguese administration in 1999, governed under the \"one country, two systems\" framework with Fernando Chui Sai On as Chief Executive. Its economy was dominated by gambling and tourism, with gaming revenue having overtaken Las Vegas, drawing huge numbers of mainland Chinese visitors.","2026":"Macao is a Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China on the Pearl River estuary, governed under a \"one country, two systems\" framework with its own legal and economic system. In 2026 it remains the world's largest gambling and casino tourism hub, economically dependent on mainland Chinese visitors, and is led by Chief Executive Sam Hou Fai, who took office in late 2024."},
  "madagascar": {"1900":"In 1900 Madagascar was a French colony, France having abolished the Merina monarchy and formally annexed the island in 1896 after military conquest. Queen Ranavalona III had been deposed and exiled, and General Joseph Gallieni governed as the colony's administrator, suppressing the menalamba rebellion and consolidating French control.","1960":"Madagascar became fully independent from France on 26 June 1960 as the Malagasy Republic, having been an autonomous republic within the French Community since 1958. Philibert Tsiranana led the new state as its first president, maintaining close ties with France.","1994":"In 1994 Madagascar was an island republic in the Indian Ocean led by President Albert Zafy, who had been elected in 1993 following the transition from Didier Ratsiraka's long rule under the new Third Republic constitution. The period was marked by economic difficulty and political friction between Zafy and the National Assembly.","2000":"Madagascar in 2000 was an independent republic governed under President Didier Ratsiraka, who had returned to power in 1997. The country remained one of the world's poorer nations, dependent on agriculture, and faced periodic cyclone damage.","2010":"In 2010 Madagascar was a republic mired in political crisis following the 2009 coup in which Andry Rajoelina ousted President Marc Ravalomanana and took power as head of a transitional authority. The unconstitutional change of government led to suspension from the African Union and SADC and the freezing of much foreign aid, and a constitutional referendum was held in November 2010."},
  "madagascar (france)": {"1920":"Madagascar was a French colony in 1920, having been annexed by France in 1896 after the monarchy was abolished. It was administered as part of the French colonial empire, with Antananarivo as its capital. Malagasy soldiers had served France during the First World War, and nationalist sentiment was beginning to stir, though the island remained firmly under French control.","1938":"In 1938 Madagascar was a French colony, administered as part of France's overseas empire. The economy centered on plantation agriculture and exports such as coffee, vanilla, and cloves under colonial control."},
  "malawi": {"1920":"The territory of present-day Malawi was the British protectorate of Nyasaland in 1920, administered by Britain since the 1890s. It was a colonial possession centered on the Shire Highlands and Lake Nyasa, with an economy based on European-owned estates growing crops such as tobacco. The 1915 Chilembwe uprising against colonial and estate conditions had been suppressed a few years earlier, and the protectorate remained under British administration.","1938":"In 1938 the territory was Nyasaland, a British protectorate in south-central Africa. Its economy relied heavily on labor migration, with many men leaving to work in mines and farms in Southern Rhodesia and South Africa, while a small settler community ran tea and tobacco estates.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was the British protectorate of Nyasaland, part of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland. African nationalist pressure was intensifying, with Hastings Banda's Malawi Congress Party (formed 1959) pressing for an end to the federation and self-government; it did not become independent Malawi until 1964.","1994":"In 1994 Malawi held its first multiparty elections in May, ending the decades-long one-party rule of Hastings Kamuzu Banda, with Bakili Muluzi of the United Democratic Front winning the presidency. This marked the country's transition to democracy after Banda's authoritarian regime.","2000":"Malawi was an independent multiparty republic led by President Bakili Muluzi of the United Democratic Front, who had won re-election in 1999. The country remained heavily dependent on agriculture, especially tobacco, and faced widespread poverty and a serious HIV/AIDS epidemic.","2010":"In 2010 Malawi was a republic led by President Bingu wa Mutharika, who had won re-election in 2009. The country, one of the world's poorest and heavily dependent on agriculture and donor aid, was pursuing a fertilizer subsidy program credited with improving maize harvests.","2026":"Malawi is a landlocked republic in southeastern Africa centered on Lake Malawi, governed as a presidential democracy. In 2026 it remains among the world's least developed and most agriculture-dependent economies; Peter Mutharika returned to the presidency after winning the 2025 general election, defeating incumbent Lazarus Chakwera."},
  "malaya": {"1900":"In 1900 the Malay Peninsula was under varying degrees of British control rather than a single unified state. The Federated Malay States (Perak, Selangor, Negeri Sembilan, and Pahang) had been formed in 1896 under a British Resident-General, while the Straits Settlements (Penang, Malacca, Singapore) were a British crown colony; other northern sultanates remained under nominal Siamese suzerainty."},
  "malaysia": {"1938":"There was no state called Malaysia in 1938; the region consisted of the British-controlled Straits Settlements, the Federated Malay States, and the Unfederated Malay States. These territories were major world producers of tin and rubber under British administration, with Malay sultans retaining nominal authority under British residents and advisers.","1960":"The state called Malaysia did not yet exist in 1960; the independent country was the Federation of Malaya, which had gained independence from Britain in 1957 under Prime Minister Tunku Abdul Rahman. Malaya in 1960 was nearing the end of the Malayan Emergency, the communist insurgency that was formally declared over that year, while Singapore, Sabah and Sarawak remained separate British territories until the wider Malaysia federation formed in 1963.","1994":"In 1994 Malaysia was a federal constitutional monarchy under Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, experiencing rapid, sustained economic growth as one of Southeast Asia's emerging industrial economies. The government pursued its Vision 2020 development goals during this period of strong expansion.","2000":"Malaysia in 2000 was a federal constitutional monarchy with Mahathir Mohamad as prime minister, recovering from the 1997-98 Asian financial crisis through capital controls. The period was marked by political tension following the 1998-99 dismissal, trial, and imprisonment of former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim.","2010":"In 2010 Malaysia was a federal constitutional monarchy with a rotating king, governed by the Barisan Nasional coalition under Prime Minister Najib Razak, who had taken office in 2009. His government promoted the \"1Malaysia\" slogan and a New Economic Model aimed at making the country a high-income economy.","2026":"Malaysia is a federal constitutional monarchy in Southeast Asia with a rotating kingship among its state rulers and a parliamentary system. In 2026 it is led by Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim's unity government while managing ethnic diversity, an export-oriented economy, and disputes in the South China Sea."},
  "maldives": {"1960":"In 1960 the Maldives was a sultanate under British protection, a status formalized by agreement that year granting Britain use of facilities including the Gan airbase in Addu Atoll. The country remained internally self-governing but did not gain full independence until 1965.","1994":"In 1994 the Maldives was an island republic in the Indian Ocean governed by President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom, who had held power since 1978. The economy depended heavily on tourism and fisheries.","2000":"The Maldives was an independent republic in the Indian Ocean led by President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom, who had held power since 1978. Its economy depended heavily on tourism and fishing, and the low-lying islands were increasingly concerned about sea-level rise.","2010":"In 2010 the Maldives was a republic led by President Mohamed Nasheed, who had won the country's first multiparty presidential election in 2008, ending Maumoon Abdul Gayoom's long rule. The low-lying island nation was internationally prominent for climate-change advocacy, having held a symbolic underwater cabinet meeting in 2009 to highlight the threat of rising seas.","2026":"The Maldives is a sovereign archipelagic republic of low-lying coral islands in the Indian Ocean, governed as a presidential republic. In 2026 it is led by President Mohamed Muizzu, elected in 2023 on a platform tilting toward China and away from India, and it remains acutely vulnerable to sea-level rise while depending heavily on luxury tourism."},
  "mali": {"1960":"In 1960 the area was part of the short-lived Mali Federation, a union of French Sudan and Senegal that became independent from France on 20 June 1960. The federation broke apart in August 1960 when Senegal seceded, and on 22 September 1960 the remaining French Sudan proclaimed itself the independent Republic of Mali under Modibo Keïta.","1994":"In 1994 Mali was a republic in West Africa under President Alpha Oumar Konaré, who had been elected in 1992 following the 1991 overthrow of Moussa Traoré and the country's transition to multiparty democracy. The year saw the sharp CFA franc devaluation of January 1994 affecting the economy, alongside ongoing tensions related to the Tuareg rebellion in the north.","2000":"Mali in 2000 was an independent multiparty democratic republic led by President Alpha Oumar Konaré, who had been elected in 1992 and re-elected in 1997. It remained one of the world's poorest countries, with an economy based on agriculture, livestock, and gold mining.","2010":"In 2010 Mali was a democratic republic led by President Amadou Toumani Touré, regarded at the time as one of West Africa's more stable democracies. Its vast northern desert regions faced growing insecurity from al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb activity and kidnappings.","2026":"Mali is a large landlocked republic in the Sahel region of West Africa, ruled since coups in 2020 and 2021 by a military junta led by Assimi Goita. In 2026 it faces a persistent jihadist insurgency, has expelled French and UN forces while partnering with Russia's Wagner/Africa Corps mercenaries, and has joined Burkina Faso and Niger in the Alliance of Sahel States after withdrawing from ECOWAS."},
  "malta": {"1900":"In 1900 Malta was a British crown colony and a key naval base in the central Mediterranean, home to an important Royal Navy dockyard. It was governed by a British governor, and this period saw ongoing tension over the use of English versus Italian in administration and the courts, known as the Language Question.","1960":"In 1960 Malta was a British Crown Colony and a major Royal Navy and NATO base in the Mediterranean. Its constitution had been suspended in 1958 amid disputes over its future, and the island was under direct colonial administration; it did not gain independence until 1964.","1994":"In 1994 Malta was an independent island republic in the Mediterranean, governed by a Nationalist Party administration under Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami, which was pursuing closer ties with Europe and an application for European Community/Union membership.","2000":"Malta was an independent republic in the Mediterranean, governed in 2000 by a Nationalist Party government under Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami, which was pursuing accession to the European Union. Malta had reactivated its EU membership application after the Nationalists returned to power in 1998.","2010":"In 2010 Malta was a republic and parliamentary democracy, a member of the European Union since 2004 and of the eurozone since adopting the euro in 2008, governed by a Nationalist Party administration under Prime Minister Lawrence Gonzi. The Mediterranean island faced significant irregular migration arriving by sea from North Africa.","2026":"Malta is a small island republic in the central Mediterranean and a member of the European Union and the eurozone. In 2026 it remains a densely populated, English- and Maltese-speaking state with an economy built on tourism, financial services, and its controversial citizenship-by-investment scheme."},
  "qing dynasty": {"1800":"In 1800, the Qing Empire was ruled by the Jiaqing Emperor, who had assumed full personal authority only the year before upon the death of his father, the retired Qianlong Emperor, in early 1799. Immediately after taking power Jiaqing had purged and executed the immensely corrupt favourite Heshen, whose graft had drained the treasury and rotted the military. The empire was mired in the White Lotus Rebellion, a massive religious and anti-tax uprising across the mountainous borderlands of Hubei, Sichuan, and Shaanxi that had begun in the mid-1790s and would not be suppressed until around 1804. Ruled from Peking and holding roughly China proper, Manchuria, Mongolia, Xinjiang, and Tibet, the Qing remained the most populous and one of the wealthiest states on earth, though the costly rebellion and endemic corruption exposed a dynasty past its zenith. These strains marked the beginning of a long decline that would deepen through the nineteenth century.","1900":"The Qing dynasty in 1900 ruled China under the de facto authority of the Empress Dowager Cixi, with the Guangxu Emperor sidelined after the failed 1898 reforms. The year 1900 was dominated by the Boxer Rebellion, an anti-foreign uprising that the Qing court initially supported; the siege of the Beijing legations provoked an Eight-Nation Alliance invasion that captured the capital and forced the court to flee."},
  "manchuria": {"1920":"In 1920 Manchuria was nominally part of the Republic of China but was effectively controlled by the warlord Zhang Zuolin, who dominated the Fengtian clique from his base in Mukden. The region was a focus of competing foreign interests, with Japan holding the Kwantung Leased Territory and the South Manchuria Railway zone, and Russian influence present along the Chinese Eastern Railway. Zhang governed the three northeastern provinces with considerable autonomy from the Beijing government."},
  "mandatory palestine (gb)": {"1920":"In 1920 Palestine came under British administration following the end of Ottoman rule, with the San Remo Conference in April 1920 assigning the mandate to Britain, though the League of Nations mandate was not formally confirmed until 1922. A British civilian administration under High Commissioner Herbert Samuel replaced military rule in July 1920. The Balfour Declaration's commitment to a Jewish national home was incorporated into British policy, and tensions between Arab and Jewish communities surfaced, including riots in Jerusalem in April 1920.","1938":"In 1938 Palestine was governed by Britain under a League of Nations mandate and was in the midst of the Arab Revolt, which intensified sharply that year into widespread armed rebellion against British rule and Jewish immigration. Britain responded with heavy military force, and in 1938 the Woodhead Commission examined and ultimately rejected as impractical the partition plan proposed by the Peel Commission the year before."},
  "marshall is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Marshall Islands were part of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, administered by the United States under a United Nations trusteeship. The U.S. used parts of the islands, notably Bikini and Enewetak atolls and the Kwajalein missile range, for military and nuclear-testing purposes; the islands did not become a sovereign state until decades later.","1994":"In 1994 the Marshall Islands was an independent republic in the central Pacific, in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association that had taken effect in 1986. It had become a United Nations member in 1991.","2000":"The Marshall Islands was an independent republic in the Pacific in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association. In 2000 it relied heavily on US financial assistance and continued to address the legacy of US nuclear testing at Bikini and Enewetak atolls.","2010":"In 2010 the Marshall Islands was an independent republic in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association, with the U.S. providing financial assistance and defense. The U.S. continued to operate the Reagan missile test site at Kwajalein Atoll, and the country remained concerned with the legacy of Cold War nuclear testing and the threat of sea-level rise.","2026":"The Marshall Islands is a sovereign island nation in the central Pacific, governed as a presidential republic and associated with the United States under a Compact of Free Association that provides U.S. defense responsibility and economic assistance. The country remains acutely vulnerable to sea-level rise and climate change, which threaten its low-lying atolls, and it continues to grapple with the lingering health and environmental legacy of U.S. nuclear testing at Bikini and Enewetak."},
  "martinique": {"1920":"Martinique in 1920 was a French colony in the Caribbean, administered as part of the French overseas empire long before its 1946 conversion into an overseas department. Its economy centered on sugar cane and rum production. The island remained firmly under French administration with Fort-de-France as its principal city.","1938":"In 1938 Martinique was a French colony in the Caribbean, administered as part of France's overseas territories. Its economy was dominated by sugarcane and rum production."},
  "mauritania": {"1960":"Mauritania became independent from France on 28 November 1960 as the Islamic Republic of Mauritania, having previously been a French colony and then an autonomous member of the French Community. Moktar Ould Daddah became its first president; newly independent Morocco contested its statehood and claimed the territory.","1994":"In 1994 Mauritania was a republic in northwest Africa led by President Maaouya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya, who had taken power in a 1984 coup and won the country's 1992 presidential election.","2000":"Mauritania in 2000 was a republic led by President Maaouya Ould Sid'Ahmed Taya, who had ruled since a 1984 coup. The country, straddling Arab and sub-Saharan Africa, faced issues including the legacy of slavery and ethnic tensions, and had controversially established diplomatic relations with Israel in 1999.","2010":"In 2010 Mauritania was an Islamic republic led by President Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz, who had come to power in a 2008 coup and then won a 2009 election. The country faced threats from al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and continued to grapple with the legacy of slavery and racial tensions between Arab-Berber and black African populations.","2026":"Mauritania is an Islamic republic in northwest Africa led by President Mohamed Ould Ghazouani, who was reelected in 2024. The country has positioned itself as a partner of Western and Gulf states on migration control and counterterrorism in the Sahel, and has pursued offshore gas development, notably the Greater Tortue Ahmeyim project shared with Senegal."},
  "mauritius": {"1960":"In 1960 Mauritius was a British Crown Colony in the Indian Ocean, with an economy dominated by sugar production. The colony was moving gradually toward greater self-government but remained under British rule, not becoming independent until 1968.","1994":"In 1994 Mauritius was an independent parliamentary republic in the Indian Ocean, having become a republic in 1992 while remaining within the Commonwealth. Anerood Jugnauth served as prime minister, and the country had a relatively diversified and growing economy based on sugar, textiles, and tourism.","2000":"Mauritius was a stable parliamentary democracy and one of Africa's more prosperous economies, based on sugar, textiles, tourism, and a growing financial sector. In a September 2000 general election, the alliance of Anerood Jugnauth and Paul Bérenger won, with Jugnauth becoming prime minister.","2010":"In 2010 Mauritius was a parliamentary republic with a stable multiparty democracy, and Navin Ramgoolam was re-elected prime minister in the May 2010 general election. The Indian Ocean island had one of Africa's strongest economies, diversified across tourism, textiles, sugar, and financial services.","2026":"Mauritius is a parliamentary republic in the Indian Ocean. Following the November 2024 elections, an opposition alliance led by Navin Ramgoolam took power, ousting Pravind Jugnauth's government. The country also reached agreements with the United Kingdom concerning the Chagos Archipelago, with the UK agreeing to cede sovereignty over the islands while retaining the Diego Garcia military base under a long-term lease."},
  "mbailundu": {"1900":"Bailundu (Mbailundu) was an Ovimbundu kingdom on the Benguela highlands of central Angola. By 1900 it was under increasing Portuguese colonial pressure; a major anti-Portuguese revolt, the Bailundo War, broke out in 1902, shortly after this date."},
  "mesopotamia (gb)": {"1920":"In 1920 Mesopotamia was under British military occupation following the defeat of the Ottomans, and the San Remo Conference that April assigned Britain the mandate for the territory. A major anti-British revolt broke out across the country in 1920, prompting Britain to move toward establishing an Arab government. These events led the following year to the creation of the Kingdom of Iraq under Faisal, but in 1920 the territory was still under direct British control amid widespread rebellion.","1938":"By 1938 the territory of former Mesopotamia was the independent Kingdom of Iraq, ruled by the young King Ghazi I, the British mandate having ended with Iraq's admission to the League of Nations in 1932. Although nominally sovereign, Britain retained considerable influence through the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty, including military air bases and oil concessions. The period saw recurring political instability, with army officers playing a growing role in government following Bakr Sidqi's 1936 coup."},
  "mexico": {"1900":"In 1900 Mexico was a republic under the long authoritarian rule of President Porfirio Díaz, a period known as the Porfiriato. The era brought railway expansion, foreign investment, and economic modernization, but also concentrated land ownership and political repression that would later help spark the 1910 Revolution.","1920":"In 1920 Mexico was a republic still in the late phase of its revolution; President Venustiano Carranza was overthrown and killed in May 1920 during the Agua Prieta rebellion led by Sonoran generals. Adolfo de la Huerta served as interim president before Alvaro Obregon was elected and took office in December 1920. The change of power marked a turning point toward greater stability after a decade of revolutionary violence.","1938":"In 1938 Mexico was a federal republic governed by President Lazaro Cardenas, whose administration pursued sweeping land redistribution and labor reform. That year Cardenas nationalized the foreign-owned oil industry, expropriating British and American companies and creating Pemex, a move that provoked a major diplomatic and commercial confrontation with those countries.","1960":"In 1960 Mexico was a federal republic governed by the long-dominant Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), with Adolfo López Mateos serving as president. The country was in a period of stable, state-led economic growth known as the Mexican Miracle, and in 1960 the government nationalized the electricity industry.","1994":"In 1994 Mexico was a federal republic that began the year with the launch of the North American Free Trade Agreement on 1 January and the simultaneous Zapatista uprising in Chiapas. The year also saw the assassination of presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio in March, the election of Ernesto Zedillo, and the December peso crisis that triggered severe economic turmoil.","2000":"Mexico in 2000 was a federal republic that experienced a historic political transition when Vicente Fox of the National Action Party won the July presidential election, ending more than seventy years of continuous rule by the Institutional Revolutionary Party. Fox took office in December 2000, marking the country's first peaceful transfer of presidential power to an opposition party.","2010":"In 2010 Mexico was a federal presidential republic led by President Felipe Calderón of the National Action Party, whose military-led offensive against drug cartels fueled escalating violence across the country. The nation marked the bicentennial of its 1810 independence and the centennial of the 1910 Revolution that year.","2026":"Mexico is a federal presidential republic led by President Claudia Sheinbaum of the Morena party, who took office in October 2024 as the country's first woman president. Her government has faced pressure from the United States under the second Trump administration over tariffs, migration, and drug-cartel violence, including U.S. designations of cartels as terrorist organizations."},
  "micronesia": {"1960":"In 1960 the islands now forming the Federated States of Micronesia were part of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, administered by the United States under United Nations trusteeship. They had no independent government, remaining under U.S. administration for decades before achieving sovereignty.","1994":"In 1994 the Federated States of Micronesia was an independent country in the western Pacific, in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association in effect since 1986, and a United Nations member since 1991.","2000":"The Federated States of Micronesia was an independent country in the western Pacific in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association. In 2000 it remained heavily dependent on US economic assistance and was negotiating renewal of the Compact's expiring funding provisions.","2010":"In 2010 the Federated States of Micronesia was an independent federation of four states in free association with the United States under the Compact of Free Association, relying heavily on U.S. financial assistance. The Pacific nation was active in advocacy over climate change and rising sea levels.","2026":"The Federated States of Micronesia is a sovereign Pacific nation comprising the states of Yap, Chuuk, Pohnpei, and Kosrae, governed as a federal republic in free association with the United States. Under its renewed Compact of Free Association, it continues to receive U.S. economic assistance in exchange for U.S. defense authority, and it remains a focus of strategic competition between the United States and China in the Pacific."},
  "moldova": {"1994":"In 1994 Moldova was an independent republic that had emerged from the Soviet Union in 1991, adopting a new constitution in July 1994. The breakaway Transnistria region on the east bank of the Dniester remained outside government control following the 1992 conflict, and Mircea Snegur served as president.","2000":"Moldova in 2000 was an independent former Soviet republic facing economic hardship and the unresolved separatist conflict in the Transnistria region, which remained outside government control. In 2000 parliament amended the constitution to make Moldova a parliamentary republic, with the president to be elected by the legislature.","2010":"In 2010 Moldova was a parliamentary republic experiencing prolonged political deadlock, governed by the pro-European Alliance for European Integration after the Communists lost their majority in 2009, but parliament was repeatedly unable to elect a president. The breakaway region of Transnistria remained outside government control, and a constitutional referendum and early elections were held late in the year.","2026":"Moldova is a parliamentary republic led by pro-European President Maia Sandu, who won reelection in 2024 alongside a narrowly approved referendum enshrining the goal of European Union membership. The country has pursued EU accession amid Russian pressure and the unresolved status of the breakaway Transnistria region, and faced an energy crisis after Russian gas transit through Ukraine ended at the start of 2025."},
  "monaco": {"2026":"Monaco is a sovereign city-state and constitutional monarchy on the Mediterranean coast, ruled by Prince Albert II of the House of Grimaldi. It remains a small, wealthy principality known for finance, tourism, and the Monaco Grand Prix, and in recent years has worked to address international scrutiny over financial transparency and money-laundering controls."},
  "mongolia": {"1920":"Outer Mongolia had declared autonomy from China after 1911 but in 1919 Chinese troops under Xu Shuzheng reoccupied the territory and abolished its autonomy. In late 1920 the White Russian forces of Baron Ungern-Sternberg invaded, advancing toward Urga, which they would capture in early 1921. The country was thus a contested arena among Chinese, White Russian, and emerging Mongolian revolutionary forces, with the Bogd Khan as a figurehead.","1938":"In 1938 the Mongolian People's Republic was a socialist state closely aligned with and heavily dependent on the Soviet Union, though recognized internationally by few states. The country was in the midst of severe Stalinist-style purges under Khorloogiin Choibalsan, in which tens of thousands of people, especially Buddhist lamas, were killed and monasteries destroyed. Soviet troops were stationed in the country amid tensions with Japanese forces in neighboring Manchukuo.","1960":"In 1960 Mongolia was the Mongolian People's Republic, a one-party communist state closely aligned with the Soviet Union and led by the Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party under Yumjaagiin Tsedenbal. It had been admitted to no UN seat yet, and a new constitution was adopted in 1960; its economy was based on collectivized livestock herding and Soviet aid.","1994":"In 1994 Mongolia was a democratic republic that had transitioned from communist one-party rule at the start of the 1990s, with the formerly communist Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party still dominant in government. The country was undergoing difficult market reforms after the loss of Soviet economic support.","2000":"Mongolia in 2000 was an independent parliamentary democracy that had transitioned from communism in 1990. In the July 2000 parliamentary elections the former communist Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party won a landslide victory, and Nambaryn Enkhbayar became prime minister as the country continued market reforms.","2010":"In 2010 Mongolia was a parliamentary democracy with President Tsakhiagiin Elbegdorj, who had taken office in 2009. The country was on the verge of a major mining boom, with development of the giant Oyu Tolgoi copper-gold deposit advancing after agreements signed in 2009.","2026":"Mongolia is a parliamentary democracy situated between Russia and China. Following the 2024 parliamentary elections, the Mongolian People's Party retained power but formed a coalition government, and in 2025 political turbulence led to a change of prime minister. The country continues to balance relations with its two large neighbors while seeking \"third neighbor\" partners and developing its mining sector."},
  "montenegro": {"1900":"In 1900 Montenegro was an independent principality in the Balkans, its sovereignty internationally recognized at the 1878 Congress of Berlin, and ruled by Prince Nikola I. It was a small, mountainous state with its capital at Cetinje, and Nikola elevated the realm to a kingdom in 1910.","1994":"In 1994 Montenegro was one of the two constituent republics of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, alongside Serbia, having joined in that federation proclaimed in 1992. Led by figures aligned with Slobodan Milošević, Montenegro was subject to the international sanctions imposed on rump Yugoslavia over the wars in Bosnia and Croatia.","2000":"In 2000 Montenegro was one of the two constituent republics of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, alongside Serbia. Under President Milo Đukanović, its government had grown increasingly estranged from Slobodan Milošević's regime in Belgrade and pursued greater autonomy, adopting the German mark as currency, though it remained legally part of the federation.","2010":"In 2010 Montenegro was a sovereign parliamentary republic, independent since its 2006 referendum split from the union with Serbia. It was an official EU candidate country, a status granted in December 2010, and had joined NATO's Membership Action Plan. The country used the euro despite not being in the eurozone.","2026":"Montenegro is a parliamentary republic in the Balkans and a NATO member that is among the frontrunners for European Union accession, aiming to conclude negotiations by around 2028. President Jakov Milatovic and a government led by Prime Minister Milojko Spajic have prioritized EU integration and economic reform."},
  "montserrat": {"1900":"In 1900 Montserrat was a British colony in the Leeward Islands of the Caribbean, administered as part of the British Leeward Islands federation. Its economy depended on agriculture, particularly limes and other crops, on a small island still recovering from the decline of the sugar plantation era.","1920":"Montserrat in 1920 was a British colony in the Leeward Islands of the Caribbean, administered as part of the British Leeward Islands federation. Its economy relied on agriculture, including cotton and limes. The small island remained under British colonial administration.","1938":"In 1938 Montserrat was a small British colony in the Leeward Islands of the Caribbean, administered as part of the Leeward Islands federal colony. Its economy rested on agriculture, including cotton and limes.","1960":"In 1960 Montserrat was a small British colony in the Caribbean and a member of the West Indies Federation formed in 1958. It remained under British administration as the federation moved toward its eventual dissolution in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Montserrat was a British Overseas Territory (then styled a British Dependent Territory) in the Caribbean, with a governor appointed by the United Kingdom and an elected local government. This was before the Soufrière Hills volcano began erupting in 1995, so the island's economy and capital Plymouth were still intact.","2000":"In 2000 Montserrat was a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean. The island remained devastated by the ongoing eruptions of the Soufrière Hills volcano, which had begun in 1995, rendering the capital Plymouth and much of the south uninhabitable and reducing the population to a few thousand living in the northern zone.","2010":"In 2010 Montserrat was a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, with a governor appointed by the UK Crown. Much of the island, including the former capital Plymouth, remained an uninhabitable exclusion zone following the eruptions of the Soufriere Hills volcano that began in 1995, with the population concentrated in the north around the de facto capital Brades.","2026":"Montserrat is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, internally self-governing with a premier and an elected assembly while the UK retains responsibility for defense and foreign affairs. Much of the island remains an exclusion zone because of the still-active Soufriere Hills volcano, whose eruptions since the 1990s buried the former capital Plymouth and forced a relocation of the population to the north."},
  "morocco": {"1900":"In 1900 Morocco was an independent sultanate ruled by the young Sultan Abd al-Aziz, who had come to the throne in 1894 with regent Ba Ahmed governing until 1900. The country faced mounting European pressure and financial difficulties, and its independence would steadily erode in the following years amid Franco-German rivalry over influence.","1920":"In 1920 most of Morocco was under a French protectorate established in 1912, with Marshal Lyautey as resident-general, while a northern zone formed a Spanish protectorate and Tangier had a special status. The sultan reigned nominally while real authority lay with French and Spanish authorities. Resistance continued in the mountainous interior, foreshadowing the Rif War that would erupt against Spain in 1921.","1960":"Morocco was an independent kingdom, having regained sovereignty from France and Spain in 1956 and ruled by King Mohammed V. In 1960 the king dismissed the government and took direct control of the cabinet, with his son Crown Prince Hassan as deputy premier. The young state was consolidating national institutions and integrating formerly separate French and Spanish zones.","1994":"In 1994 Morocco was a sovereign constitutional monarchy ruled by King Hassan II, who held wide executive power. The kingdom continued to administer most of the disputed Western Sahara, where a UN-brokered ceasefire with the Polisario Front had been in place since 1991.","2000":"In 2000 Morocco was a constitutional monarchy ruled by King Mohammed VI, who had ascended the throne in July 1999 following the death of his father Hassan II. The young king signaled a more liberal reform agenda, and Morocco continued to administer the disputed territory of Western Sahara.","2010":"In 2010 Morocco was a constitutional monarchy ruled by King Mohammed VI, who held substantial executive power. The country continued to administer most of the disputed Western Sahara territory amid an unresolved conflict with the Polisario Front. In late 2010 Moroccan forces dismantled the Gdeim Izik protest camp near Laayoune, an episode sometimes cited as a precursor to the Arab Spring.","2026":"Morocco is a constitutional monarchy under King Mohammed VI, with a government formed after the 2021 elections led by Aziz Akhannouch. The country has expanded international recognition of its claim over Western Sahara, including U.S. recognition, and is preparing to co-host the 2030 FIFA World Cup with Spain and Portugal while also hosting the 2025 Africa Cup of Nations."},
  "morocco (france)": {"1938":"In 1938 most of Morocco was a French protectorate established under the 1912 Treaty of Fez, with the sultan reigning under French oversight while the resident-general held real authority; a separate northern zone was under Spanish protection and Tangier was an international zone. French administration controlled the economy and military, and a nascent nationalist movement was beginning to press for reforms."},
  "mossi states": {"1900":"The Mossi states were a group of kingdoms, notably Ouagadougou and Yatenga, in the region of present-day Burkina Faso. By 1900 they had been conquered and absorbed into French West Africa, the kingdom of Ouagadougou having fallen to French forces in 1896–97, ending their independence."},
  "mozambique": {"1920":"Mozambique was a Portuguese colony, governed as Portuguese East Africa under the Portuguese Republic. Around 1920 much of the territory was still administered by chartered concession companies, notably the Mozambique Company and the Niassa Company, which held wide powers over land, labour, and revenue. A migrant-labour system sent large numbers of African workers to the mines of neighbouring South Africa and the Rhodesias.","1960":"In 1960 Mozambique was a Portuguese overseas province under colonial rule from Lisbon, governed as an integral part of Portugal under the Estado Novo regime of Antonio Salazar. There was no independent government, and nationalist organizing among Mozambicans was still nascent and suppressed. Forced labor and a settler-dominated economy characterized the territory.","1994":"In 1994 Mozambique was an independent republic recovering from a long civil war that had ended with the 1992 Rome General Peace Accords between the FRELIMO government and RENAMO. In October 1994 the country held its first multiparty general elections, won by FRELIMO with Joaquim Chissano elected president.","2000":"In 2000 Mozambique was a republic led by President Joaquim Chissano of the ruling FRELIMO party, having ended its long civil war in 1992. In early 2000 the country suffered catastrophic flooding, particularly along the Limpopo River, which displaced hundreds of thousands of people and drew a major international relief effort.","2010":"In 2010 Mozambique was a republic governed by the long-dominant FRELIMO party, with Armando Guebuza serving as president after his re-election in 2009. In September 2010 deadly riots broke out in Maputo and other cities over rising prices of bread, water, and electricity. The country remained one of the world's poorest but was experiencing relatively strong economic growth.","2026":"Mozambique is a presidential republic on the southeastern African coast. The disputed October 2024 election, won by Frelimo's Daniel Chapo, triggered widespread and deadly post-election protests led by supporters of opposition figure Venancio Mondlane. The country also continues to face an Islamist insurgency in the northern Cabo Delgado province, which has disrupted major liquefied natural gas projects."},
  "mozambique (portugal)": {"1938":"In 1938 Mozambique was a Portuguese colony in southeastern Africa, governed under the authoritarian Estado Novo regime of Antonio de Oliveira Salazar. Its economy was tied to plantation agriculture, migrant labor sent to South African and Rhodesian mines, and the railways and port of Lourenco Marques serving the interior."},
  "muscat and oman": {"1920":"Muscat and Oman was a sultanate ruled by Sultan Taimur bin Feisal, nominally independent but heavily under British influence through treaty relations. In 1920 the Treaty of Seeb was concluded, recognizing the autonomy of the interior tribes under the Imam while the Sultan retained authority over the coast around Muscat, ending years of conflict between coast and interior.","1938":"In 1938 Muscat and Oman was a sultanate on the southeastern Arabian Peninsula ruled by Sultan Said bin Taimur, who had acceded in 1932. Though nominally independent, it was under strong British influence and protection, and the interior remained largely under the autonomous authority of the Ibadi imamate rather than the sultan in Muscat."},
  "myanmar": {"1960":"Known then as Burma, the country was an independent parliamentary democracy that had gained independence from Britain in 1948. In 1960 elections returned U Nu to the premiership, following a period of caretaker government led by General Ne Win. The state faced ongoing ethnic insurgencies and pressures that would lead to Ne Win's 1962 coup.","1994":"In 1994 Myanmar (Burma) was ruled by the military junta known as the State Law and Order Restoration Council (SLORC), which had refused to honor the 1990 election results. Opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi remained under house arrest, where she had been held since 1989.","2000":"In 2000 Myanmar was ruled by a military junta, the State Peace and Development Council, led by Senior General Than Shwe. The opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi and her National League for Democracy remained suppressed, and she was placed under renewed house arrest in September 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Myanmar was ruled by a military junta, the State Peace and Development Council. In November 2010 it held its first general election in twenty years, widely criticized as rigged and won by the military-backed Union Solidarity and Development Party; days later opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi was released from house arrest.","2026":"Myanmar remains under a military junta, the State Administration Council led by Min Aung Hlaing, which seized power in the 2021 coup and has faced a widespread civil war against ethnic armed groups and pro-democracy resistance forces. By 2026 the junta had lost control of significant territory, and a devastating earthquake struck central Myanmar in March 2025; the regime has pushed to hold elections widely criticized as neither free nor fair."},
  "māori": {"1900":"By 1900 the Māori people had no independent sovereign state; the Māori tribes (iwi) of New Zealand were under British colonial rule, the islands having been annexed under the 1840 Treaty of Waitangi. Māori had lost much of their land through war and confiscation in earlier decades, though they retained four reserved seats in the colonial Parliament. A reformist movement led by figures such as the Young Māori Party was emerging to address Māori health, land, and welfare."},
  "n. cyprus": {"2026":"The Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus is a self-declared state occupying the northern third of the island of Cyprus, recognized only by Turkey and dependent on it militarily and economically. The rest of the international community regards the territory as part of the Republic of Cyprus under Turkish occupation, and reunification talks have remained deadlocked, with northern leadership favoring a two-state solution."},
  "n. mariana is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Northern Mariana Islands were part of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, administered by the United States under a United Nations trusteeship established in 1947. The islands had no independent government and were under U.S. naval and later civilian administration. They remained a strategic trust territory rather than a sovereign state.","1994":"In 1994 the Northern Mariana Islands were a Commonwealth in political union with the United States, with residents holding U.S. citizenship and a locally elected government. The islands were known for a garment industry that relied heavily on imported foreign labor.","2000":"In 2000 the Northern Mariana Islands were a Commonwealth in political union with the United States, with residents holding U.S. citizenship. The territory was known for a garment industry that relied heavily on imported foreign labor under local immigration controls, which drew scrutiny over labor conditions.","2010":"In 2010 the Northern Mariana Islands were a commonwealth in political union with the United States, whose residents are US citizens. By this time the US federal government had taken over control of the islands' immigration, phasing out the local system, and the once-large garment industry had largely collapsed.","2026":"The Northern Mariana Islands is a commonwealth in political union with the United States, whose residents are U.S. citizens. In 2026 it remains a self-governing territory with its own elected governor and legislature, while the federal government handles defense and foreign affairs, and its economy continues to struggle with the long decline of tourism and earlier industry."},
  "namibia": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory of South West Africa was administered by South Africa, which had governed it under a former League of Nations mandate and applied apartheid laws there. South Africa refused to place it under the UN trusteeship system, and its continued control was internationally contested. African nationalist movements, including SWAPO, were forming to oppose South African rule.","1994":"In 1994 Namibia was a sovereign republic that had gained independence from South African rule in 1990, governed by SWAPO under President Sam Nujoma. In 1994 South Africa formally returned the enclave port of Walvis Bay to Namibian control, and the country held its second general elections that year.","2000":"In 2000 Namibia was a republic led by President Sam Nujoma of the ruling SWAPO party, having gained independence from South Africa in 1990. Namibian forces were involved in the Second Congo War supporting the government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo.","2010":"In 2010 Namibia was a sovereign republic, independent from South African rule since 1990, governed by the dominant SWAPO party with Hifikepunye Pohamba as president. The country was a stable multiparty democracy with an economy based heavily on mining, particularly diamonds and uranium.","2026":"Namibia is a sovereign republic in southwestern Africa governed by SWAPO, which has dominated since independence in 1990. In 2026 Netumbo Nandi-Ndaitwah, elected in the November 2024 vote, serves as the country's first woman president, and the government is pursuing development of its offshore oil discoveries and large-scale green hydrogen projects."},
  "natal": {"1900":"In 1900 Natal was a self-governing British colony in southeastern Africa, with its capital at Pietermaritzburg and a substantial Indian indentured-labour population. During 1900 it was a base and battleground in the Second Boer War, including the relief of the besieged town of Ladysmith early that year."},
  "nauru": {"1960":"In 1960 Nauru was a United Nations trust territory administered by Australia on behalf of Australia, New Zealand, and the United Kingdom. Its economy centered on phosphate mining controlled by the British Phosphate Commissioners. It was not yet independent, achieving sovereignty only in 1968.","2000":"In 2000 Nauru was an independent island republic in the Pacific, one of the world's smallest states, whose economy had long depended on phosphate mining that was nearing exhaustion. The country faced severe financial difficulties and was criticized internationally as an offshore banking and money-laundering haven.","2010":"In 2010 Nauru was a small independent island republic in the Pacific. Its once-rich phosphate deposits were largely exhausted, leaving the country economically dependent on foreign aid; the year saw political instability with a prolonged parliamentary deadlock and repeated elections.","2026":"Nauru is a small sovereign island republic in the Pacific and one of the world's smallest states by population. In 2026 it remains independent with a parliamentary government, depends heavily on external revenue including phosphate, fishing licenses and arrangements with Australia, and switched its diplomatic recognition from Taiwan to the People's Republic of China in early 2024."},
  "ndebele": {"1900":"The Ndebele kingdom of Matabeleland had been destroyed by the British South Africa Company in the First Matabele War of 1893, and a major uprising in 1896–97 had been crushed. By 1900 the Ndebele people were under Company administration within Southern Rhodesia, no longer an independent state."},
  "nepal": {"1900":"Nepal in 1900 was an independent Hindu kingdom under the Shah dynasty, though real power lay with the hereditary Rana prime ministers, who had ruled as autocrats since 1846. The reigning prime minister was Deva Shumsher Jung Bahadur Rana, while the king served as a figurehead. Nepal maintained close ties with British India, supplying Gurkha soldiers, but was never colonized.","1920":"Nepal was an independent kingdom ruled in practice by the hereditary Rana prime ministers, with Chandra Shamsher Jung Bahadur Rana as the dominant figure and the Shah king reduced to a ceremonial role. It maintained close treaty ties with British India and had contributed large numbers of Gurkha troops to the British war effort, with a formal treaty recognizing Nepalese independence concluded in 1923.","1938":"In 1938 Nepal was a kingdom ruled in practice by the hereditary Rana prime ministers, who held real power while the Shah king was a figurehead; the Rana prime minister at the time was Juddha Shumsher. The country was independent but had a special treaty relationship with British India, and remained largely isolated and closed to outsiders.","1960":"Nepal was an independent kingdom under King Mahendra. In December 1960 the king carried out a royal coup, dismissing the elected government of Prime Minister B.P. Koirala, suspending the constitution, and banning political parties. This inaugurated the king's direct rule, later formalized as the partyless Panchayat system.","1994":"In 1994 Nepal was a constitutional monarchy under King Birendra, operating under the multiparty democratic constitution adopted in 1990. Mid-term elections in November 1994 produced a hung parliament, after which a minority government led by the Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist–Leninist) took office.","2000":"In 2000 Nepal was a constitutional monarchy under King Birendra, with an elected parliament dominated by the Nepali Congress. The country was in the midst of a Maoist insurgency that had begun in 1996 and was steadily intensifying across the countryside.","2010":"In 2010 Nepal was a federal republic, having abolished its monarchy in 2008. The country was in a difficult post-civil-war transition, with a Constituent Assembly struggling to draft a new constitution and recurring political deadlock, including a prolonged failure to elect a prime minister after the resignation of the Maoist-led government.","2026":"Nepal is a federal democratic republic in the Himalayas governed under its 2015 constitution. In 2026 the country experienced major upheaval after the September 2025 \"Gen Z\" protests, sparked partly by a social-media ban and anger over corruption, which forced Prime Minister K. P. Sharma Oli to resign and led to an interim government headed by former chief justice Sushila Karki."},
  "netherlands": {"1900":"The Netherlands in 1900 was an independent constitutional monarchy ruled by Queen Wilhelmina, who had come to the throne in 1890 and reached her majority in 1898. It was a neutral state in European affairs and held a substantial colonial empire, especially the Netherlands Indies. Its parliamentary government operated under the constitution as reformed in 1848.","1920":"The Netherlands was an independent constitutional monarchy under Queen Wilhelmina, having remained neutral throughout the First World War. Around 1920 it was governed under coalition cabinets and had recently introduced universal male suffrage and proportional representation, with women's suffrage extended in 1919. It retained a large colonial empire, chiefly the Dutch East Indies.","1938":"In 1938 the Netherlands was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Wilhelmina, maintaining a policy of strict neutrality as tensions rose in Europe. It still governed a large colonial empire, most notably the Dutch East Indies. The country was recovering slowly from the Great Depression.","1960":"The Netherlands was an independent constitutional monarchy in Western Europe under Queen Juliana, a member of NATO and the emerging European Economic Community. In 1960 it was governed by a center-right coalition and experiencing strong postwar economic growth. It still retained the western half of New Guinea as a colonial possession.","1994":"In 1994 the Netherlands was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy under Queen Beatrix, and a member of the European Union. Following the 1994 general election, a \"purple\" coalition led by Wim Kok of the Labour Party took office, the first Dutch government in decades to exclude the Christian Democrats.","2000":"In 2000 the Netherlands was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Beatrix, with a coalition government led by Prime Minister Wim Kok. A founding member of the European Union, it was a prosperous state notable in 2000 for legislation legalizing same-sex marriage, which took effect in 2001.","2010":"In 2010 the Netherlands was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy, with Queen Beatrix as head of state and an EU and eurozone member. A center-right minority government led by Mark Rutte took office in October 2010 with parliamentary support from Geert Wilders's Party for Freedom. In October 2010 the Netherlands Antilles was dissolved, with Curacao and Sint Maarten becoming constituent countries and Bonaire, Sint Eustatius, and Saba becoming special municipalities of the Netherlands.","2026":"The Netherlands is a sovereign constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy in Western Europe under King Willem-Alexander, and a founding member of the EU and NATO. In 2026 it is governed following the October 2025 general election, in which the centrist D66 party led by Rob Jetten made strong gains after the collapse of the coalition that had included Geert Wilders's PVV."},
  "netherlands antilles": {"1800":"In 1800, the Dutch Caribbean islands were possessions of the Batavian Republic rather than any unified \"Netherlands Antilles,\" which would not be created until 1954. In 1800, they were split between the Curaçao colony to the south — Curaçao, Bonaire, and Aruba, centered on Willemstad — and the Windward group of Sint Eustatius, Saba, and Sint Maarten to the north, each administered separately after the West India Company's dissolution in 1792. In 1800, French forces from Guadeloupe attacked Curaçao in July, and after the siege the Dutch governor surrendered the island to the British frigate HMS Nereide on 13 September. In 1800, this began a British occupation of Curaçao that was formalized in 1801 and lasted until the Peace of Amiens returned the island to the Batavian Republic in 1803. In 1800, the islands' economy rested on trade, shipping, and salt, with Curaçao long serving as a major entrepôt for smuggling and the trans-shipment of goods and enslaved people across the Caribbean.","1900":"In 1900 the islands later grouped as the Netherlands Antilles (Curaçao, Aruba, Bonaire, and the Leeward islands) were Dutch colonial possessions in the Caribbean, administered as the colony of Curaçao and Dependencies. The economy was modest, based on trade, salt, and shipping, before the oil-refining boom of later decades. They were governed under Dutch colonial authority.","1920":"The islands later grouped as the Netherlands Antilles were Dutch colonial possessions in the Caribbean, administered as the colony of Curaçao and dependencies. Around 1920 Curaçao's economy was being transformed by the construction and operation of a large oil refinery processing Venezuelan crude, which brought rapid industrial growth and immigration.","1938":"In 1938 the islands of the Dutch Caribbean formed the territory of Curacao, a Dutch overseas territory. Its economy was dominated by major oil refineries on Curacao and Aruba processing Venezuelan crude."},
  "netherlands indies": {"1900":"The Netherlands Indies in 1900 was the Dutch colonial territory in the Indonesian archipelago, governed from Batavia under a Governor-General. By this time the Dutch controlled Java and much of the archipelago, though the prolonged Aceh War in northern Sumatra continued. The colony was a major source of plantation exports such as sugar, coffee, and tobacco, and the so-called Ethical Policy emphasizing colonial welfare emerged in this period."},
  "new caledonia": {"1938":"In 1938 New Caledonia was a French overseas colony in the South Pacific, valued especially for its nickel mining. It was governed by French colonial administration.","1960":"In 1960 New Caledonia was a French overseas territory in the South Pacific, having held that status since 1946. It was governed under French administration with a territorial assembly and was a significant producer of nickel. It was not an independent state.","1994":"In 1994 New Caledonia was an overseas territory of France in the South Pacific, governed under the 1988 Matignon Accords that had ended violent unrest between Kanak independence supporters and loyalists. The accords provided for development measures and set a referendum on the territory's future status for later in the decade.","2000":"In 2000 New Caledonia was a special collectivity of France in the South Pacific. Following the 1998 Nouméa Accord, it was undergoing a gradual transfer of powers from France and a process aimed at a future referendum on self-determination, amid tensions between the indigenous Kanak population and European settlers.","2010":"In 2010 New Caledonia was a special collectivity (sui generis) of France in the South Pacific, operating under the 1998 Noumea Accord. That agreement provided for a gradual transfer of powers from France and set the stage for future referendums on independence, amid the territory's significant nickel mining economy and Kanak independence movement.","2026":"New Caledonia is a special-status overseas collectivity of France in the South Pacific. In 2026 its political future remains contested following the deadly 2024 unrest over voting-rights reforms, with France and local pro- and anti-independence factions negotiating a new institutional arrangement after a 2025 accord aimed at defining greater autonomy."},
  "new hebrides": {"1938":"In 1938 the New Hebrides was a Anglo-French condominium in the South Pacific, jointly administered by Britain and France under a unique dual-government arrangement. Its economy relied on copra and other plantation agriculture."},
  "new south wales (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 New South Wales was a self-governing British colony in Australia with its own responsible government and parliament, centered on Sydney. It was on the verge of federation, having voted to join the Commonwealth of Australia, which was constituted on 1 January 1901. Until then it remained a separate colony under the British Crown."},
  "new zealand": {"1920":"New Zealand was a self-governing Dominion within the British Empire, recognizing King George V as sovereign. Having suffered heavy casualties at Gallipoli and on the Western Front, it signed the Treaty of Versailles and joined the League of Nations, and in 1920 received a League mandate over Western Samoa, which it had occupied from Germany during the war.","1938":"In 1938 New Zealand was a self-governing Dominion within the British Empire under King George VI, with Michael Joseph Savage's first Labour government in power. That government enacted the Social Security Act of 1938, a landmark expansion of the welfare state including state-funded health care and pensions.","1960":"New Zealand was an independent parliamentary democracy and a realm within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. In the November 1960 general election the National Party under Keith Holyoake won power from the Labour government. The country maintained close defense ties with Britain, Australia, and the United States.","1994":"In 1994 New Zealand was an independent parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. The National Party government led by Prime Minister Jim Bolger was in office, in the period after the 1993 referendum that had approved switching to a mixed-member proportional electoral system.","2000":"In 2000 New Zealand was a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. The government was led by Prime Minister Helen Clark of the Labour Party, who had taken office in late 1999.","2010":"In 2010 New Zealand was a parliamentary democracy and constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth, with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and John Key of the National Party as prime minister. In September 2010 a magnitude 7.1 earthquake struck the Canterbury region near Christchurch, causing major damage but no direct deaths.","2026":"New Zealand is a sovereign parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. In 2026 it is governed by a center-right coalition led by National Party Prime Minister Christopher Luxon, formed after the 2023 election with the ACT and New Zealand First parties."},
  "ngwato": {"1900":"The Ngwato (Bamangwato) in 1900 were a Tswana kingdom whose territory lay within the British Bechuanaland Protectorate, established in 1885. Their ruler was Khama III, a Christian chief who had visited Britain in 1895 to help secure the protectorate's continuation under direct imperial rather than Cape Colony or company control. The Ngwato retained considerable internal autonomy under British overrule."},
  "nicaragua": {"1900":"Nicaragua in 1900 was an independent republic governed by the Liberal dictator José Santos Zelaya, who had taken power in 1893 and modernized and centralized the state. During his rule Nicaragua reincorporated the Mosquito Coast on the Caribbean in 1894. The country was also a prominent candidate site for a proposed interoceanic canal.","1920":"Nicaragua was a republic whose Conservative governments were sustained by United States influence, with a contingent of US Marines stationed in the country since 1912. American financial control over customs and banking under dollar diplomacy remained in place around 1920.","1960":"Nicaragua was an independent republic effectively controlled by the Somoza family dynasty. In 1960 Luis Somoza Debayle was president, having succeeded after the 1956 assassination of his father Anastasio Somoza Garcia. The family retained dominant power through the National Guard and aligned with the United States.","1994":"In 1994 Nicaragua was a republic governed by President Violeta Chamorro, who had won the 1990 election that ended Sandinista rule. Her government worked to consolidate peace after the Contra war and to manage tensions with the still-influential Sandinista movement.","2000":"In 2000 Nicaragua was a republic led by President Arnoldo Alemán of the Constitutionalist Liberal Party. The country was still recovering from the devastation of Hurricane Mitch in 1998, and Alemán's government later became notable for corruption allegations.","2010":"In 2010 Nicaragua was a republic led by President Daniel Ortega of the Sandinista National Liberation Front, who had returned to power in 2007. The country experienced a border dispute with Costa Rica that year over the San Juan River area around Isla Calero, which was referred to the International Court of Justice.","2026":"Nicaragua is a republic in Central America under the authoritarian rule of Daniel Ortega and his wife and co-president Rosario Murillo. In 2026 the government has consolidated power through a 2025 constitutional rewrite that formalized the co-presidency and extended state control, amid continued repression of opposition, civil society, and the Catholic Church and the stripping of citizenship from many critics."},
  "niger": {"1960":"Niger became an independent republic in August 1960, ending its status as a French colony within French West Africa. Its first president was Hamani Diori, leading the Nigerien Progressive Party. The new state remained closely tied to France economically and politically.","1994":"In 1994 Niger was a republic that had transitioned toward multiparty politics following its 1991 national conference, with Mahamane Ousmane serving as the country's first democratically elected president since 1993. The government faced a Tuareg rebellion in the north during this period, which was the subject of peace negotiations.","2000":"In 2000 Niger was a republic that had returned to civilian rule under President Mamadou Tandja, elected in late 1999 after a military coup earlier that year. It remained one of the world's poorest countries, with an economy heavily dependent on uranium mining and subsistence agriculture.","2010":"In 2010 Niger experienced a military coup in February that overthrew President Mamadou Tandja, who had controversially extended his rule; a junta led by Salou Djibo took power. The year also saw a severe food crisis affecting much of the population, and the country remained one of the poorest in the world despite significant uranium resources.","2026":"Niger is a landlocked Sahelian state ruled by a military junta that seized power in the July 2023 coup against President Mohamed Bazoum. In 2026 General Abdourahamane Tiani heads the government, the country has pulled away from France and the regional bloc ECOWAS, aligned with the juntas of Mali and Burkina Faso in the Alliance of Sahel States, and faces ongoing jihadist insurgency."},
  "nigeria": {"1920":"Nigeria was a British colony and protectorate, governed as the amalgamated Colony and Protectorate of Nigeria following the 1914 union of the northern and southern territories. It was administered largely through indirect rule, relying on existing local rulers, especially the emirs of the Muslim north.","1938":"In 1938 Nigeria was a British colony and protectorate, administered through a system of indirect rule that governed via traditional rulers, especially the emirs of the northern emirates. Lagos was the capital, and the territory's economy revolved around exports such as palm oil, groundnuts, cocoa, and tin.","1960":"Nigeria gained independence from Britain on 1 October 1960, becoming a federation within the Commonwealth with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Abubakar Tafawa Balewa served as prime minister, while Nnamdi Azikiwe became governor-general. The country was organized into regions reflecting major ethnic and political divisions.","1994":"In 1994 Nigeria was under military rule led by General Sani Abacha, who had seized power in a November 1993 coup. The year was marked by political crisis stemming from the annulled June 1993 presidential election; Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner, declared himself president in June 1994 and was arrested and detained for treason. Abacha's regime suppressed pro-democracy protests and a major oil-workers' strike during the year.","2000":"In 2000 Nigeria was a federal republic that had recently returned to civilian rule, with Olusegun Obasanjo having been inaugurated as elected president in May 1999 after years of military government. The year saw rising tensions as several northern states moved to adopt sharia law, triggering deadly sectarian violence, notably in Kaduna.","2010":"In 2010 Nigeria was a federal presidential republic and Africa's most populous country, a major oil producer in the Niger Delta. President Umaru Yar'Adua died in office in May 2010 and was succeeded by his vice president, Goodluck Jonathan. The country continued to grapple with militancy in the oil-rich Delta and rising sectarian violence around Jos.","2026":"Nigeria is a federal republic and Africa's most populous country, led by President Bola Tinubu of the APC, elected in 2023. In 2026 the government is pursuing economic reforms including the removal of fuel subsidies and currency liberalization, while contending with high inflation, insecurity in the north from insurgent and banditry groups, and persistent cost-of-living pressures."},
  "niue": {"1920":"Niue was a small Pacific island under New Zealand administration, having been annexed by New Zealand in 1901. Around 1920 it remained a dependency governed by a resident commissioner.","1938":"In 1938 Niue was a dependency of New Zealand, which administered the island following its annexation in 1901. The small Polynesian population lived under a resident commissioner appointed by New Zealand.","1960":"In 1960 Niue was a territory administered by New Zealand, having been under New Zealand control since 1901. It had no independent government and was governed as a dependency. Self-government in free association with New Zealand came only later, in 1974.","1994":"In 1994 Niue was a self-governing state in free association with New Zealand, a status it had held since 1974. New Zealand remained responsible for its defence and external affairs, and Niueans held New Zealand citizenship.","2000":"In 2000 Niue was a self-governing island state in free association with New Zealand, whose residents hold New Zealand citizenship and which relied heavily on New Zealand for budgetary support. Its small population continued to decline through emigration to New Zealand.","2010":"In 2010 Niue was a small self-governing island state in free association with New Zealand, whose citizens held New Zealand citizenship and which relied heavily on New Zealand for aid and defence. It had a tiny, declining population and was still recovering from the destruction caused by Cyclone Heta in 2004.","2026":"Niue is a small self-governing island state in free association with New Zealand, whose residents are New Zealand citizens. In 2026 it manages its own internal affairs while New Zealand provides defense, foreign-affairs assistance, and significant budget support, and it maintains a separate international identity in some bodies despite its tiny population."},
  "norfolk island": {"1960":"In 1960 Norfolk Island was an external territory of Australia in the South Pacific, administered under the Norfolk Island Act of 1957. Its small population included descendants of the Bounty mutineers who had been resettled from Pitcairn in 1856.","1994":"In 1994 Norfolk Island was an external territory of Australia with a degree of internal self-government under the Norfolk Island Act 1979, administered through a Legislative Assembly. Australia retained ultimate authority over the island.","2000":"In 2000 Norfolk Island was an external territory of Australia in the South Pacific, governed with a degree of internal self-government under its own Legislative Assembly. Its economy depended largely on tourism.","2010":"In 2010 Norfolk Island was an external territory of Australia in the South Pacific that retained a degree of self-government through its own Legislative Assembly. Facing serious financial difficulties, the territory was increasingly dependent on Australian financial support, foreshadowing the later loss of its self-government.","2026":"Norfolk Island is an external territory of Australia in the South Pacific. In 2026 it is administered under Australian governance arrangements that replaced its former self-government in 2015–2016, with local services delivered through a regional council model, while some residents continue to press for the restoration of greater autonomy."},
  "north korea": {"1960":"In 1960 North Korea, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, was a one-party communist state led by Kim Il-sung, rebuilding from the devastation of the Korean War which had ended in armistice in 1953. The country pursued rapid state-directed industrialization and remained closely aligned with both the Soviet Union and China, with the Korean peninsula divided at the demilitarized zone.","1994":"In 1994 North Korea experienced a pivotal transition when its founding leader Kim Il-sung died in July; his son Kim Jong-il succeeded him as de facto ruler. The year also saw the nuclear crisis with the United States ease through the Agreed Framework signed in October, under which North Korea agreed to freeze its plutonium program in exchange for energy assistance. The country was entering a period of severe economic decline.","2000":"In 2000 North Korea was a one-party communist state led by Kim Jong-il, who held power following the 1994 death of his father Kim Il-sung. The country was still recovering from a severe famine of the late 1990s, and in June 2000 Kim Jong-il hosted South Korean president Kim Dae-jung in Pyongyang for the first inter-Korean summit.","2010":"In 2010 North Korea was a one-party authoritarian state under Kim Jong-il, who was preparing his son Kim Jong-un for succession, formally elevated at a Workers' Party conference that year. Tensions on the Korean Peninsula were acute, with the sinking of the South Korean warship Cheonan in March and the shelling of Yeonpyeong Island in November.","2026":"North Korea is a one-party authoritarian state ruled by Kim Jong Un under the Kim dynasty. In 2026 it continues to expand its nuclear and missile programs, has deepened military cooperation with Russia including sending troops to support Russia's war in Ukraine, and remains heavily sanctioned and economically isolated while rejecting denuclearization."},
  "north macedonia": {"1994":"In 1994 the country, then known internationally as the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, was an independent state that had peacefully seceded from Yugoslavia in 1991, with Kiro Gligorov as president. It faced a dispute with Greece over its name and symbols, and in February 1994 Greece imposed an economic embargo on it. It had been admitted to the United Nations in 1993 under the provisional name.","2000":"In 2000 the country was a parliamentary republic known as the Republic of Macedonia, independent since the 1991 breakup of Yugoslavia, though its name remained disputed with Greece. Tensions between the Macedonian majority and the ethnic Albanian minority were rising, leading to armed conflict the following year.","2010":"In 2010 the country was the Republic of Macedonia, an independent parliamentary republic governed by Nikola Gruevski's VMRO-DPMNE-led government. It remained an EU and NATO aspirant blocked by a long-running naming dispute with Greece, and it had not yet adopted the name North Macedonia, which came with the 2018 Prespa Agreement.","2026":"North Macedonia is a sovereign parliamentary republic in the Balkans and a NATO member that joined in 2020. In 2026 it is governed by a VMRO-DPMNE-led coalition under Prime Minister Hristijan Mickoski, formed after the 2024 elections, while its EU accession remains stalled over disputes with Bulgaria concerning constitutional changes and identity issues."},
  "northern rhodesia": {"1938":"In 1938 Northern Rhodesia was a British protectorate administered by the Colonial Office, having passed from British South Africa Company rule in 1924. Its economy was dominated by the copper mines of the Copperbelt, which had expanded rapidly in the 1930s and drew large numbers of African migrant laborers."},
  "northern territory (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 the Northern Territory of Australia was administered by the colony of South Australia, which had controlled it since 1863. It was a sparsely populated region, and like the rest of the Australian colonies it was about to become part of the Commonwealth of Australia in 1901, remaining under South Australian administration until 1911."},
  "norway": {"1920":"Norway was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Haakon VII, having remained neutral during the First World War despite heavy losses to its large merchant fleet. In 1920 it joined the newly formed League of Nations, and the Spitsbergen Treaty signed that year recognized Norwegian sovereignty over the Svalbard archipelago.","1938":"In 1938 Norway was an independent constitutional monarchy under King Haakon VII, governed by a Labour Party administration led by Prime Minister Johan Nygaardsvold. The country maintained a policy of neutrality as tensions rose in Europe.","1960":"In 1960 Norway was a constitutional monarchy under King Olav V, governed by a Labour Party administration led by Prime Minister Einar Gerhardsen. A founding member of NATO, it was a stable parliamentary democracy with a growing welfare state and joined the European Free Trade Association, which was established in 1960.","1994":"In 1994 Norway was a constitutional monarchy under King Harald V with a parliamentary government. In a November 1994 referendum, Norwegian voters rejected membership in the European Union for the second time. The country also hosted the Winter Olympics in Lillehammer in February 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Norway was a constitutional monarchy under King Harald V and a parliamentary democracy, prosperous from North Sea oil and gas revenues. It remained outside the European Union, having rejected membership in a 1994 referendum.","2010":"In 2010 Norway was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy under King Harald V, governed by a red-green coalition led by Prime Minister Jens Stoltenberg. A wealthy non-EU country sustained by North Sea oil and gas and a large sovereign wealth fund, it was a member of NATO and the EEA.","2026":"In 2026 Norway is a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy under King Harald V, with Jonas Gahr Store of the Labour Party as prime minister following the 2025 election. It remains a non-EU but EEA member and a NATO founding member, deriving great wealth from North Sea oil and gas and the world's largest sovereign wealth fund."},
  "oman": {"1900":"Oman (Muscat and Oman) in 1900 was a sultanate ruled by Sultan Faisal bin Turki, independent in name but increasingly under British influence through treaties. Britain held strong commercial and political sway, and the interior tribes under religious leadership often resisted the Sultan's authority based at the coast in Muscat. The once-extensive Omani empire, including Zanzibar, had already been divided and diminished.","1960":"In 1960 the Sultanate of Muscat and Oman was an absolute monarchy ruled by Sultan Said bin Taimur, a deeply isolationist and reclusive sovereign with close ties to Britain. The country was emerging from the Jebel Akhdar War, in which British-backed forces had suppressed an interior rebellion by 1959.","1994":"In 1994 Oman was an absolute monarchy ruled by Sultan Qaboos bin Said, who had governed since 1970. The sultanate continued its development and modernization program funded by oil revenues while maintaining a generally non-confrontational foreign policy in the Gulf region.","2000":"In 2000 Oman was an absolute monarchy ruled by Sultan Qaboos bin Said, who had governed since 1970 and pursued gradual modernization. The sultanate, dependent on oil, maintained a generally moderate and stable foreign policy in the Gulf region.","2010":"In 2010 Oman was an absolute monarchy on the Arabian Peninsula ruled by Sultan Qaboos bin Said, who had governed since 1970. An oil-exporting state pursuing diversification and 'Omanisation' of its workforce, it maintained a generally non-confrontational foreign policy in the Gulf.","2026":"Oman in 2026 is an absolute monarchy ruled by Sultan Haitham bin Tariq Al Said, who succeeded Sultan Qaboos in 2020. It pursues a long-standing neutral foreign policy in the Gulf and is implementing the economic diversification program Oman Vision 2040 to reduce dependence on oil."},
  "orange free state": {"1900":"The Orange Free State in 1900 was a Boer republic in southern Africa that had entered the Second Boer War against Britain in alliance with the Transvaal in October 1899. During 1900 British forces under Lord Roberts invaded and occupied it, and in May 1900 Britain annexed it as the Orange River Colony, though Boer commandos continued guerrilla resistance. President Marthinus Theunis Steyn led the republic into the war."},
  "ottoman empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Ottoman Empire was ruled by Sultan Selim III, whose Nizam-i Cedid (\"New Order\") program sought to build a European-style professional army and reform the administration and treasury. Its territory stretched across southeastern Europe, Anatolia, the Levant, Iraq, the Hejaz, and much of North Africa, though central control over distant provinces and powerful local notables was weakening. The empire was entangled in the wider Napoleonic wars, with Bonaparte's army having invaded Ottoman Egypt in 1798 and Ottoman forces campaigning alongside Britain and Russia to expel the French. Provincial power was increasingly held by semi-autonomous governors and ayan such as the Mamluks in Egypt and pashas in the Balkans and Anatolia. Selim's reforms provoked fierce resistance from the Janissary corps and traditionalist factions, tensions that would culminate in his deposition in 1807.","1900":"The Ottoman Empire in 1900 was a multi-ethnic Islamic monarchy ruled by Sultan Abdülhamid II, who governed autocratically after suspending the constitution and parliament in 1878. It still controlled Anatolia, much of the Middle East, and parts of the Balkans, but was heavily indebted, financially supervised by European powers through the Public Debt Administration, and widely called the 'sick man of Europe.' The Hejaz Railway was begun in 1900 to link Damascus toward the holy cities."},
  "ottoman sultanate": {"1920":"The Ottoman Empire under Sultan Mehmed VI was a defeated power, its capital Constantinople under Allied occupation. In 1920 its government signed the punitive Treaty of Sèvres, which partitioned much of the empire, while a rival Turkish nationalist movement under Mustafa Kemal established a competing Grand National Assembly in Ankara and rejected the settlement."},
  "ovimbundu": {"1900":"The Ovimbundu were a Bantu-speaking people of the central highlands of Angola, organized into a number of kingdoms such as Bailundu and Bié rather than a single unified state. Around 1900 they were renowned long-distance caravan traders, but Portuguese colonial pressure was intensifying as Portugal worked to impose effective control over the interior of its Angola colony. Their autonomy was nearing its end, and the Bailundu Revolt against Portuguese rule and trading abuses broke out in 1902."},
  "oyo": {"1900":"The Oyo Empire, once a dominant Yoruba power in what is now southwestern Nigeria, had already collapsed as an independent state by 1900. Its capital had been destroyed in the 1830s amid civil wars and the rise of Ibadan and other successor states, and the Yoruba region was brought under British control in the late nineteenth century. By 1900 the area was incorporated into Britain's Lagos and Southern Nigeria administration."},
  "pakistan": {"1960":"In 1960 Pakistan was under military rule, having been governed by General Ayub Khan since his 1958 coup; he formally became president and consolidated power around this time. The country was split into geographically separate West and East wings, and the Indus Waters Treaty with India was signed that year.","1994":"In 1994 Pakistan was a parliamentary democracy with Benazir Bhutto serving as prime minister, having returned to power after the October 1993 elections, and Farooq Leghari as president. The country faced ongoing ethnic and sectarian violence, particularly in Karachi.","2000":"In 2000 Pakistan was under military rule, having been led by General Pervez Musharraf since his October 1999 coup that ousted Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. Musharraf governed as chief executive while the country faced international sanctions and tensions with India over Kashmir following the 1999 Kargil conflict.","2010":"In 2010 Pakistan was a federal parliamentary republic with Asif Ali Zardari as president and Yousaf Raza Gillani as prime minister, following the country's return to civilian rule in 2008. It faced a severe insurgency by the Pakistani Taliban and other militants, and in mid-2010 suffered catastrophic flooding that affected millions of people.","2026":"Pakistan in 2026 is a federal parliamentary republic with Shehbaz Sharif as prime minister and Asif Ali Zardari as president, following the contested February 2024 elections. The country continues to grapple with severe economic strain under an IMF program, political tension involving the imprisoned Imran Khan, and militant violence near its Afghan border."},
  "palau": {"1960":"In 1960 Palau was administered by the United States as part of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, a United Nations strategic trust established after World War II. It was not an independent state at this time.","1994":"In 1994 Palau became a fully independent sovereign state on 1 October, ending its status as the last remaining United Nations Trust Territory administered by the United States. It entered into a Compact of Free Association with the United States and joined the United Nations in December 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Palau was an independent republic in free association with the United States, having gained independence in 1994 under a Compact of Free Association that provided U.S. financial support and defense responsibility. Its economy relied on tourism and U.S. assistance.","2010":"In 2010 Palau was an independent island republic in the western Pacific in a Compact of Free Association with the United States, which provided defence and financial support. That year it gained attention for creating the world's first shark sanctuary in its waters.","2026":"Palau in 2026 is an independent island republic in the western Pacific in free association with the United States, with Surangel Whipps Jr. serving as president after winning re-election in 2024. It depends heavily on tourism and on U.S. financial support under the renewed Compact of Free Association."},
  "palestine": {"2026":"In 2026 the State of Palestine is a partially recognized state comprising the Israeli-occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip, with the Palestinian Authority under Mahmoud Abbas based in Ramallah. Gaza was devastated by the 2023-2025 war following Hamas's October 7 attack; a ceasefire reached in 2025 left the territory's governance and reconstruction deeply uncertain, and recognition of Palestinian statehood expanded among Western states during 2024-2025."},
  "panama": {"1920":"Panama was a republic whose strategic life centered on the United States-controlled Panama Canal, which had opened in 1914. By 1920 the US held sovereignty over the Canal Zone and exercised strong influence over Panamanian affairs under the 1903 treaty, and a dispute with Costa Rica over the Coto border region flared in 1921.","1960":"In 1960 Panama was a republic, with Roberto Chiari elected president that year, while tensions persisted with the United States over sovereignty in the Panama Canal Zone. Demands to fly the Panamanian flag in the Zone were a growing source of nationalist agitation.","1994":"In 1994 Panama held democratic elections in which Ernesto Pérez Balladares won the presidency, taking office in September. The country continued recovering from the 1989 U.S. invasion that had removed Manuel Noriega, and preparations continued for the eventual transfer of the Panama Canal under the Torrijos–Carter Treaties.","2000":"In 2000 Panama was a democratic republic led by President Mireya Moscoso, the country's first female president. The year was marked by Panama assuming full control of the Panama Canal on 31 December 1999, completing the U.S. handover and the departure of American forces.","2010":"In 2010 Panama was a presidential republic led by President Ricardo Martinelli, who had taken office in 2009. Its economy was among the fastest-growing in Latin America, anchored by the Panama Canal, whose major expansion project was underway.","2026":"Panama in 2026 is a presidential republic led by President Jose Raul Mulino, who took office in 2024. Its economy centers on the Panama Canal and a large services and banking sector, and in 2025 it faced pressure from the United States over the canal's operation and Chinese-linked port concessions."},
  "papua new guinea": {"1900":"In 1900 the territory was not a single state but was divided between two colonial powers: the southeastern portion, British New Guinea, was a British possession (administered with Australian involvement), while the northeastern portion, German New Guinea, was controlled by Germany. The western half of the island was part of the Dutch East Indies. British New Guinea was transferred to the new Commonwealth of Australia shortly after, becoming the Territory of Papua in 1906.","1920":"The eastern half of New Guinea in 1920 was divided into the Australian-administered Territory of Papua in the south and the former German New Guinea in the northeast, which Australia had occupied during the war. In 1920 the League of Nations granted Australia a mandate over the former German territory, administered separately as the Territory of New Guinea.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was administered by Australia as the combined Territory of Papua and New Guinea, with Papua an Australian possession and New Guinea a United Nations trust territory. It was not yet independent and remained under colonial administration.","1994":"In 1994 Papua New Guinea was an independent parliamentary democracy within the Commonwealth, with Sir Julius Chan becoming prime minister in August after Paias Wingti's removal. The government continued to grapple with the secessionist conflict on the island of Bougainville.","2000":"In 2000 Papua New Guinea was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, led by Prime Minister Mekere Morauta. The long secessionist conflict on Bougainville was winding down following a 1998 ceasefire and ongoing peace negotiations.","2010":"In 2010 Papua New Guinea was a parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, led by Prime Minister Michael Somare. The country anticipated major revenues from the large PNG LNG natural gas project, which reached its final investment decision around that time.","2026":"Papua New Guinea in 2026 is a parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state and James Marape as prime minister. The resource-rich nation continues to manage internal challenges including tribal violence, the future status of the autonomous region of Bougainville, and growing strategic competition between China and Western partners in the Pacific."},
  "paraguay": {"1800":"In 1800, Paraguay was the Intendancy of Paraguay, an interior province of the Spanish Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata governed from Buenos Aires. In 1800, it was administered by an Intendant Governor seated at Asunción, its sole city and capital, with the surrounding territory organized into the districts of Concepción, Curuguaty, Villarrica, and San Pedro de Ycuamandiyú. In 1800, the province remained a relatively isolated, cattle-raising and yerba-mate-producing frontier, its commerce taxed and channeled downriver through Buenos Aires. In 1800, the former Jesuit Guaraní missions—secularized after the Jesuit expulsion of 1767—had declined, and Spanish authority faced ongoing tension with indigenous peoples on its northern and Chaco frontiers. In 1800, Paraguay was still more than a decade from the 1811 revolution that would end Spanish rule and make it an independent republic.","1900":"In 1900 Paraguay was an independent republic in South America still recovering demographically and economically from the catastrophic War of the Triple Alliance of 1864–1870, which had killed a large share of its population. Its politics were dominated by rivalry between the Colorado and Liberal parties, with the Colorados in power at the turn of the century. The country remained largely agrarian and sparsely populated.","1920":"Paraguay was a republic dominated by the Liberal Party during this period, still recovering demographically and economically from the devastating War of the Triple Alliance of the previous century. Its politics around 1920 were marked by factional instability among the Liberals, and tensions with Bolivia over the Chaco region were mounting.","1938":"In 1938 Paraguay had just concluded the Chaco War against Bolivia, with a 1938 peace treaty awarding it most of the disputed Chaco region. The country was politically unstable in the war's aftermath, having seen the 1936 Febrerista revolution overthrow President Eusebio Ayala.","1960":"In 1960 Paraguay was a one-party authoritarian state under the dictatorship of General Alfredo Stroessner, who had taken power in 1954 and governed through the Colorado Party. His regime relied on repression of opponents and a long-standing state of siege.","1994":"In 1994 Paraguay was a democratic republic under President Juan Carlos Wasmosy, who had taken office in 1993 as the first civilian president after decades of authoritarian rule that ended with the 1989 fall of Alfredo Stroessner. The country was consolidating its young democratic institutions.","2000":"In 2000 Paraguay was a democratic republic led by President Luis Ángel González Macchi, who had taken office in 1999 after the assassination of vice president Luis María Argaña and the resulting political crisis. The country remained politically unstable, and a failed coup attempt occurred in May 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Paraguay was a presidential republic led by President Fernando Lugo, a former bishop whose 2008 election had ended decades of Colorado Party dominance. His government faced challenges from a hostile Congress and a small leftist insurgent group, the EPP, in the country's north.","2026":"Paraguay in 2026 is a presidential republic led by President Santiago Pena of the long-dominant Colorado Party, in office since 2023. It remains one of South America's few states maintaining formal diplomatic ties with Taiwan rather than China, and its economy relies on agriculture and hydroelectric power."},
  "persia": {"1900":"In 1900 Persia was an independent monarchy ruled by the Qajar dynasty, with Mozaffar ad-Din Shah on the throne following the assassination of Naser al-Din Shah in 1896. The state was financially weak and increasingly subject to British and Russian influence, and in 1900 the Shah took out a large loan from Russia to fund a European tour. Growing discontent over foreign concessions and royal extravagance would soon feed into the Constitutional Revolution of 1906."},
  "peru": {"1900":"In 1900 Peru was an independent republic that had entered a period of relative political stability and economic growth known as the Aristocratic Republic, dominated by the Civilista party. Eduardo López de Romaña served as president, and the economy was expanding through exports of sugar, cotton, copper, and rubber. The country was still marked by the lingering effects of its defeat by Chile in the War of the Pacific and the loss of territory.","1920":"Peru was an independent republic governed by President Augusto B. Leguía, who had taken power in 1919 and inaugurated his eleven-year authoritarian period known as the Oncenio. His government promoted foreign investment and public works while suppressing political opponents, and a new constitution was adopted in 1920.","1938":"In 1938 Peru was a republic under President Óscar R. Benavides, who governed authoritarianly after annulling the 1936 elections and extending his own term. The populist APRA party remained banned and persecuted during this period.","1960":"In 1960 Peru was a republic under the elected presidency of Manuel Prado Ugarteche, who governed in an arrangement supported by the previously banned APRA party. The country was a constitutional democracy during this period, though political life remained influenced by the military and oligarchic interests.","1994":"In 1994 Peru was governed by President Alberto Fujimori, who had carried out a self-coup in 1992 and overseen a new constitution adopted in 1993. The state continued its campaign against the Shining Path insurgency, whose leader Abimael Guzmán had been captured in 1992, and pursued economic stabilization reforms.","2000":"In 2000 Peru was a republic led by President Alberto Fujimori, who controversially won a third term in a disputed 2000 election. Late in the year a corruption scandal involving his intelligence chief Vladimiro Montesinos brought down his government, and Fujimori fled to Japan and resigned in November.","2010":"In 2010 Peru was a presidential republic under President Alan García, experiencing strong economic growth driven by mining and exports. The country was preparing for the 2011 general elections amid continued debate over the distribution of its commodity-driven prosperity.","2026":"Peru in 2026 is a presidential republic that experienced continued political instability; Dina Boluarte, who had governed since the 2022 ouster of Pedro Castillo, was removed in 2025 amid unrest, and the country headed toward general elections scheduled for April 2026. It continues to face high political turnover, corruption scandals, and crime concerns."},
  "philippines": {"1900":"In 1900 the Philippines was under contested control: Spain had ceded the islands to the United States by the 1898 Treaty of Paris, but Filipino revolutionaries who had declared the First Philippine Republic under Emilio Aguinaldo were fighting the Philippine–American War against U.S. forces. By 1900 the conflict had shifted to guerrilla warfare across the archipelago. The United States set up a civilian Philippine Commission under William Howard Taft that year to begin establishing colonial governance.","1920":"The Philippines was an unincorporated territory of the United States, administered under the Jones Act of 1916 which had created an elected Philippine Legislature and promised eventual independence. An American Governor-General held executive authority, while Filipino leaders such as Manuel Quezon and Sergio Osmeña pressed for self-government.","1938":"In 1938 the Philippines was a Commonwealth under United States sovereignty, established in 1935 as a transitional step toward full independence promised for 1946. Manuel L. Quezon served as its first president, exercising substantial domestic self-government while the United States retained authority over foreign affairs and defense.","1960":"In 1960 the Philippines was an independent republic, having gained independence from the United States in 1946, with Carlos P. Garcia serving as president. The country was a democracy aligned with the United States and pursued a 'Filipino First' economic nationalist policy under Garcia.","1994":"In 1994 the Philippines was a democratic republic under President Fidel V. Ramos, who pursued economic liberalization and reconciliation efforts. His administration worked on peace negotiations with communist and Muslim insurgents and promoted economic growth as part of its reform agenda.","2000":"In 2000 the Philippines was a democratic republic led by President Joseph Estrada, elected in 1998. By late 2000 Estrada faced mounting corruption allegations, and the House of Representatives impeached him in November, setting the stage for his removal in early 2001; the year also saw fighting against the Abu Sayyaf and MILF in Mindanao.","2010":"In 2010 the Philippines was a presidential republic that held elections in May, bringing Benigno 'Noynoy' Aquino III to the presidency in succession to Gloria Macapagal Arroyo. The country contended with poverty, corruption concerns, and the aftermath of the 2009 Maguindanao massacre, while a long-running insurgency in Mindanao continued.","2026":"The Philippines in 2026 is a presidential republic under President Ferdinand Marcos Jr., elected in 2022. It maintains a close security alliance with the United States while contending with escalating maritime confrontations with China in the South China Sea, alongside a sharp public rift between the Marcos and Duterte political camps."},
  "pitcairn is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Pitcairn Islands were a British colony in the South Pacific, inhabited by a small community descended from the HMS Bounty mutineers and their Tahitian companions. The remote settlement was administered through the British High Commissioner based in Fiji.","1994":"In 1994 the Pitcairn Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Pacific, administered through the British High Commissioner in New Zealand. The tiny population, descended largely from the HMS Bounty mutineers and their Tahitian companions, lived almost entirely on Pitcairn itself and governed local affairs through an Island Council.","2000":"In 2000 the Pitcairn Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Pacific, the only remaining British possession in the region. The tiny population, descended largely from HMS Bounty mutineers and Tahitians, lived almost entirely on Pitcairn itself and numbered only a few dozen. Administration was handled through the British High Commissioner in New Zealand.","2010":"In 2010 the Pitcairn Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Pacific, governed under a Governor (the British High Commissioner to New Zealand) with a locally elected Mayor and Island Council. The population was tiny, around 50 people, almost all descendants of HMS Bounty mutineers and their Tahitian companions living on Pitcairn itself.","2026":"In 2026 the Pitcairn Islands are a British Overseas Territory in the South Pacific, with King Charles III as head of state represented by a governor based in New Zealand. The settlement on Pitcairn has only a few dozen residents, mostly descendants of the HMS Bounty mutineers."},
  "poland": {"1920":"Poland was a newly re-established independent republic following its restoration at the end of the First World War, with Józef Piłsudski as Chief of State. In 1920 it was at war with Soviet Russia; the Red Army advanced to the outskirts of Warsaw before being repulsed in the Battle of Warsaw in August.","1938":"In 1938 Poland was an independent republic governed by the authoritarian Sanacja regime that had ruled since Józef Piłsudski's 1926 coup, with power held by figures such as Edward Rydz-Śmigły after Piłsudski's 1935 death. In October 1938, following the Munich Agreement, Poland annexed the contested Trans-Olza region from Czechoslovakia.","1960":"In 1960 Poland was the communist Polish People's Republic, a one-party state led by Władysław Gomułka as First Secretary of the Polish United Workers' Party and a member of the Warsaw Pact. Gomułka's earlier reformist 'thaw' of 1956 had given way to a more restrictive period, including renewed tensions with the Catholic Church.","1994":"In 1994 Poland was a parliamentary republic five years past the fall of communism, pursuing market reforms after the earlier 'shock therapy' liberalization. Lech Walesa was president, while a coalition led by the post-communist Democratic Left Alliance held the government following its 1993 election victory. Poland was actively seeking integration with Western institutions, aiming for eventual membership in NATO and the European Union.","2000":"In 2000 Poland was a parliamentary democracy and had been a NATO member since March 1999, having shed communist rule a decade earlier. It was pursuing accession to the European Union, which it would join in 2004, and its economy had been transformed by market reforms. Aleksander Kwasniewski was president and was re-elected in October 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Poland was a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union and NATO. The country was shaken in April 2010 when a plane crash near Smolensk, Russia, killed President Lech Kaczynski and many senior officials; Bronislaw Komorowski won the subsequent presidential election that summer.","2026":"Poland in 2026 is a parliamentary republic in the EU and NATO, with Donald Tusk leading a coalition government formed in late 2023 and Karol Nawrocki, a conservative ally of the Law and Justice party, serving as president after winning the 2025 election. This split has produced friction between the centrist government and the presidency, while Poland remains a key supporter of Ukraine and a major NATO frontline state."},
  "portugal": {"1900":"In 1900 Portugal was a constitutional monarchy under King Carlos I, ruling a large overseas empire that included Angola, Mozambique, and other colonies. The country faced serious financial difficulties, having partially defaulted on its debt in 1892, along with political instability and growing republican agitation. This unrest would eventually culminate in the assassination of Carlos I in 1908 and the fall of the monarchy in 1910.","1920":"Portugal was a republic under the unstable First Republic, marked by frequent changes of government and political turbulence following the 1910 overthrow of the monarchy. The country had fought on the Allied side in the First World War and continued to hold a colonial empire including Angola and Mozambique.","1938":"In 1938 Portugal was governed by the authoritarian Estado Novo regime under António de Oliveira Salazar, who held power as prime minister. The corporatist single-party state maintained close ties with Spain's Nationalists during the Spanish Civil War while officially professing neutrality.","1960":"In 1960 Portugal was an authoritarian corporatist state under the Estado Novo regime of António de Oliveira Salazar, who had ruled since the 1930s. It clung to its overseas empire in Africa and Asia, and on the eve of major colonial conflicts; that empire would soon be challenged, with India seizing Goa in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Portugal was a parliamentary republic and a member of the European Union, governed by Anibal Cavaco Silva's center-right Social Democratic Party, with Mario Soares as president. It still administered Macau, due to revert to Chinese sovereignty in 1999. Lisbon held the title of European Capital of Culture in 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Portugal was a parliamentary democracy and a member of the European Union and NATO, with a Socialist government led by Prime Minister Antonio Guterres. It held the rotating presidency of the Council of the European Union in the first half of 2000. It had also handed over its last overseas territory, Macau, to China in December 1999.","2010":"In 2010 Portugal was a parliamentary republic in the European Union and a member of the eurozone. It was hit hard by the European sovereign-debt crisis, with rising bond yields and austerity measures under the Socialist government of Prime Minister Jose Socrates, foreshadowing its 2011 bailout.","2026":"Portugal in 2026 is a parliamentary republic in the EU and NATO, with Luis Montenegro of the center-right AD coalition as prime minister following the May 2025 snap election. Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa serves as president, with a presidential election due in early 2026."},
  "portuguese east africa": {"1800":"In 1800, Portuguese Mozambique was a loose collection of coastal trading settlements and Zambezi-valley prazo estates rather than a unified colony, governed as a captaincy-general that had been detached from Portuguese India in 1752. Its administrative seat was Mozambique Island, where the Governor-General resided and the coastal fortress commanded the ivory, gold, and slave trades. Real Portuguese authority reached little beyond the ports of Sofala, Quelimane, Inhambane, and the inland outposts of Sena and Tete, with the interior dominated by the prazeiros and their Chikunda slave armies. The colony's Indian Ocean commerce had declined under competition from Omani and Mazrui Arabs to the north, even as the Atlantic-bound slave trade to Brazil expanded. Effective control over the vast interior remained minimal, and the settlements functioned largely as autonomous commercial enclaves tied to Goa, Lisbon, and the wider Indian Ocean world.","1900":"Portuguese East Africa, the colony corresponding to modern Mozambique, was a Portuguese possession in 1900. Portugal's control of the interior was still incomplete, and large parts of the territory were administered by chartered concession companies such as the Mozambique Company and the Niassa Company. Portugal was engaged in military campaigns to subjugate African polities and consolidate its authority over the region."},
  "portuguese guinea": {"1800":"In 1800, the Portuguese presence in Guinea consisted of a handful of coastal enclaves, chiefly the fortified towns of Bissau and Cacheu, administered from afar as a dependency of Portuguese Cape Verde whose seat lay at Santiago. Bissau, refounded and given a rebuilt stone fort, the Fortaleza de São José da Amura, by the Grão-Pará and Maranhão Company in 1775, had become the main garrison and slave-trading center. Cacheu, one of the oldest European settlements in the region, remained a second fortified post further north on its river. Real Portuguese control did not extend past the range of these forts, and the surrounding Papel, Balanta, and other peoples remained independent, with attacks on and killings of Portuguese agents recurrent. The settlements existed largely to tax and ship enslaved Africans across the Atlantic, above all to Brazil, and their prosperity rose and fell with that trade.","1900":"Portuguese Guinea, the territory of present-day Guinea-Bissau, was a Portuguese colony in West Africa in 1900. Portuguese control was confined largely to coastal trading posts, and the colonial administration was waging prolonged military campaigns to subdue inland peoples such as the Bijagós and Balanta. Effective Portuguese control over the whole territory would not be achieved until the early twentieth century."},
  "puerto rico": {"1920":"Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States, governed under the Jones-Shafroth Act of 1917, which had granted U.S. citizenship to Puerto Ricans. A governor appointed by the U.S. president headed the administration, alongside a locally elected legislature.","1938":"In 1938 Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States, whose inhabitants had held U.S. citizenship since 1917. The island suffered severe poverty during the Depression, and 1938 saw the founding of the Popular Democratic Party by Luis Muñoz Marín.","1960":"In 1960 Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States, organized since 1952 as the Commonwealth (Estado Libre Asociado) of Puerto Rico under its own constitution. Luis Muñoz Marín of the Popular Democratic Party served as the elected governor, and the island was in the midst of the industrialization drive known as Operation Bootstrap. Puerto Ricans were U.S. citizens but could not vote in presidential elections and had no voting representation in Congress.","1994":"In 1994 Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States organized as a Commonwealth (Estado Libre Asociado), whose residents were US citizens but did not vote in presidential elections. Pedro Rossello of the pro-statehood New Progressive Party served as governor. Debate over the island's political status, statehood versus continued commonwealth versus independence, remained a central issue.","2000":"In 2000 Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States with commonwealth status, its residents US citizens but without a vote in presidential elections. Sila Maria Calderon was elected governor in November 2000, becoming the territory's first woman governor. The status question and protests over US Navy bombing exercises on Vieques were prominent issues.","2010":"In 2010 Puerto Rico was an unincorporated territory of the United States with commonwealth status, its residents being U.S. citizens but without a vote in Congress or for president. The island was governed by Governor Luis Fortuno and faced serious fiscal and economic difficulties.","2026":"Puerto Rico in 2026 is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States, whose residents are U.S. citizens but cannot vote in presidential elections and lack voting representation in Congress. Governor Jenniffer Gonzalez-Colon, a statehood advocate, took office in 2025, while the island continues recovering from past hurricanes, debt restructuring, and an unresolved political-status debate."},
  "qatar": {"1900":"In 1900 Qatar was a peninsula on the Persian Gulf under the leadership of the Al Thani family, headed by Sheikh Jassim bin Mohammed Al Thani, and was nominally under Ottoman suzerainty with an Ottoman garrison at Doha. Its economy depended heavily on pearling and trade. Qatar's status as a distinct entity under Al Thani rule had been shaped by the 1893 confrontation with Ottoman forces at Al Wajbah.","1920":"Qatar was a sheikhdom on the Persian Gulf under the rule of the Al Thani family, bound to Britain by treaty as part of the British protective system over the Gulf states. Its economy depended on pearling and trade, and it lay within Britain's sphere of influence rather than under direct administration.","1938":"In 1938 Qatar was a sheikhdom under a British protectorate arrangement, with its foreign relations controlled by Britain through treaties signed in 1916. Ruled by Sheikh Abdullah bin Jassim Al Thani, the impoverished peninsula's pearling economy had collapsed, and an oil concession had been granted though commercial production had not yet begun.","1960":"In 1960 Qatar was a sheikhdom on the Persian Gulf under British protection through treaties dating to the 19th century, with Britain controlling its foreign affairs and defence. Sheikh Ali bin Abdullah Al Thani had ruled but abdicated in 1960 in favour of his son Ahmad bin Ali Al Thani. The economy depended on oil, which had been exported since 1949 and had displaced the earlier pearling trade.","1994":"In 1994 Qatar was an absolute monarchy on the Arabian Peninsula ruled by Emir Khalifa bin Hamad Al Thani, with its economy based on oil and natural gas, including the vast North Field gas reserves. His son Hamad bin Khalifa, who would seize power in 1995, was crown prince and increasingly influential.","2000":"In 2000 Qatar was an absolute monarchy on the Persian Gulf ruled by Emir Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, who had taken power from his father in a 1995 coup. Its economy rested on oil and rapidly expanding natural gas exports, and it hosted the Al Jazeera satellite news network launched in 1996. The country was pursuing modernization and a more independent foreign policy.","2010":"In 2010 Qatar was an absolute monarchy ruled by Emir Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, an oil- and gas-rich Gulf state with one of the world's highest per-capita incomes. In December 2010 it was selected to host the 2022 FIFA World Cup.","2026":"Qatar in 2026 is an absolute monarchy on the Arabian Peninsula ruled by Emir Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani. A small but extremely wealthy state funded by vast natural gas reserves, it has played a prominent diplomatic role as a mediator, notably in negotiations related to Gaza ceasefire talks between Israel and Hamas."},
  "queensland (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 Queensland was a self-governing British colony in northeastern Australia. It voted in referendums to join the federation of the Australian colonies, and on 1 January 1901 it became a state of the new Commonwealth of Australia. Its economy rested heavily on pastoralism, mining, and sugar plantations that controversially used indentured Pacific Islander labour."},
  "rapa nui": {"1900":"Rapa Nui, also known as Easter Island, had been annexed by Chile in 1888 and was therefore a Chilean possession in 1900. The island and most of its land were leased for sheep ranching, run for years by the Williamson-Balfour Company, and the small surviving Rapanui population was largely confined to the village of Hanga Roa. The indigenous community had been devastated by earlier Peruvian slave raids and introduced diseases.","1920":"Rapa Nui, or Easter Island, was a possession of Chile, which had annexed it in 1888. The island was largely leased to a sheep-ranching company, and the indigenous population was confined to the area around Hanga Roa.","1938":"In 1938 Rapa Nui (Easter Island) was a possession of Chile, which had annexed it in 1888. Much of the island was leased as a sheep ranch to a commercial company, and the Rapa Nui people were largely confined to the settlement of Hanga Roa."},
  "rattanakosin kingdom": {"1800":"In 1800, the Rattanakosin Kingdom of Siam was ruled by its founder, King Phutthayotfa Chulalok (Rama I), from the newly built capital at Bangkok, established in 1782 after the fall of Thonburi. In 1800, the kingdom had recently repelled the massive Burmese invasion of the Nine Armies' War of 1785–1786 and continued to skirmish with Bodawpaya's Konbaung Burma along the western frontier. In 1800, Siam exercised suzerainty over the three Lao kingdoms of Luang Prabang, Vientiane, and Champasak, and had installed the young King Ang Eng as a vassal ruler in Cambodia in 1794. In 1800, its influence extended over the Lanna principalities around Chiang Mai and over tributary Malay sultanates on the northern peninsula, forming a broad mandala of loosely held dependencies. In 1800, Rama I was consolidating the reunified state by reviving Ayutthaya-era administrative institutions and restoring the Theravada Buddhist sangha and the Thai literary tradition devastated by the earlier sack of Ayutthaya.","1900":"The Rattanakosin Kingdom was the Thai (Siamese) state ruled from Bangkok by the Chakri dynasty, and in 1900 it was an independent monarchy under King Chulalongkorn (Rama V). Chulalongkorn was pursuing wide-ranging modernizing reforms of administration, finance, and the military while skillfully ceding peripheral territories to Britain and France to preserve Siam's independence. Siam remained the only Southeast Asian state not colonized by a European power.","1920":"This refers to Siam under the Chakri dynasty, an independent absolute monarchy ruled in 1920 by King Vajiravudh (Rama VI). Siam had joined the Allies in the First World War and would become a founding member of the League of Nations."},
  "rio de oro": {"1920":"Río de Oro was the southern portion of Spanish Sahara, a colonial possession of Spain on the Atlantic coast of northwest Africa. Spanish presence was concentrated at coastal posts such as Villa Cisneros, with little effective control over the interior.","1938":"In 1938 Río de Oro was the southern part of the Spanish colony of Spanish Sahara, administered by Spain. It was a sparsely populated desert territory along the Atlantic coast, controlled from coastal posts while much of the interior remained beyond effective Spanish authority."},
  "romania": {"1900":"Romania was an independent kingdom, recognized as fully sovereign since the 1878 Treaty of Berlin and elevated to a kingdom in 1881 under King Carol I of the Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen dynasty. Around 1900 it was a constitutional monarchy with a parliamentary system dominated by the Liberal and Conservative parties, its economy heavily agrarian and based on grain exports, and it had secretly aligned with the Triple Alliance powers. The large peasant population remained impoverished, tensions that would erupt in the 1907 peasant revolt.","1920":"Romania was an independent kingdom under King Ferdinand I, greatly enlarged after the First World War by the union of Transylvania, Bessarabia, Bukovina, and other territories, forming Greater Romania. The Treaty of Trianon in 1920 confirmed its acquisition of Transylvania from Hungary.","1938":"In 1938 Romania was a kingdom under King Carol II, who in February 1938 abolished the parliamentary constitution and established a royal dictatorship, suppressing political parties including the fascist Iron Guard. It was an enlarged 'Greater Romania' that included Transylvania, Bessarabia, and Bukovina, and was increasingly pressured by Nazi Germany economically and diplomatically.","1960":"In 1960 Romania was a communist one-party state, the Romanian People's Republic, aligned with the Soviet bloc and a member of the Warsaw Pact and Comecon. Gheorghe Gheorghiu-Dej led the Romanian Workers' Party as the dominant figure of the regime. The country was pursuing rapid industrialization and the collectivization of agriculture, which was nearing completion in this period.","1994":"In 1994 Romania was a republic in the post-communist era following the 1989 overthrow of Nicolae Ceausescu, with Ion Iliescu as president and a government led by the post-communist Party of Social Democracy. The country was undergoing a slow and difficult transition to a market economy amid high inflation. Romania was seeking closer ties with the West and had joined NATO's Partnership for Peace program.","2000":"In 2000 Romania was a republic still undergoing post-communist transition, with an economy weakened by slow reform. In the late-2000 elections Ion Iliescu returned to the presidency and the extreme-nationalist candidate Corneliu Vadim Tudor reached the runoff. Romania was seeking integration with NATO and the European Union.","2010":"In 2010 Romania was a semi-presidential republic and a member of the European Union and NATO. Under President Traian Basescu the government imposed harsh austerity measures, including public-sector pay cuts and a VAT increase, in response to the economic crisis and an IMF agreement.","2026":"Romania in 2026 is a semi-presidential republic and member of the European Union and NATO. Nicușor Dan, elected in May 2025, serves as president following a turbulent election cycle in which an earlier 2024 presidential vote was annulled over irregularities."},
  "russia": {"1994":"In 1994 Russia was a federal republic under President Boris Yeltsin, operating under the new constitution adopted in December 1993 after his violent confrontation with parliament. The country was undergoing turbulent post-Soviet economic reforms, privatization, and high inflation. In December 1994 Russia launched a military intervention in the breakaway republic of Chechnya, beginning the First Chechen War.","2000":"In 2000 Russia was a federal republic; Vladimir Putin, who had become acting president when Boris Yeltsin resigned on 31 December 1999, won the presidential election in March 2000. The Second Chechen War was being waged, and in August 2000 the submarine Kursk sank with all hands. Putin moved to consolidate central authority over the regions and the oligarchs.","2010":"In 2010 the Russian Federation was a semi-presidential republic with Dmitry Medvedev as president and Vladimir Putin as prime minister in their power-sharing arrangement. That summer the country suffered severe wildfires and a heatwave, and it signed the New START nuclear arms reduction treaty with the United States.","2026":"Russia in 2026 is a federal state under the authoritarian rule of President Vladimir Putin and remains engaged in its full-scale war against Ukraine, ongoing since the February 2022 invasion. It faces extensive Western sanctions and has deepened ties with China, Iran, and North Korea."},
  "russian empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Russian Empire was ruled by Tsar Paul I, who had succeeded his mother Catherine the Great in 1796 and pursued erratic domestic and foreign policies that alienated the nobility. Russia had joined the Second Coalition against Revolutionary France in 1798, sending armies under Alexander Suvorov into Italy and Switzerland, but by 1800 Paul had broken with Britain and Austria and was moving toward rapprochement with Napoleon. Governed as an autocracy from Saint Petersburg, the empire rested on a vast serf population bound to noble estates and the state, with roughly nine-tenths of its people living in the countryside. Its borders reached from the Baltic and the recently partitioned Polish lands in the west across Siberia to the Pacific and the Russian colonies in Alaska. Paul's growing tyranny and his reversal of Catherine's policies led to a palace conspiracy that would kill him in March 1801, bringing his son Alexander I to the throne.","1900":"The Russian Empire was a vast autocracy ruled by Tsar Nicholas II of the Romanov dynasty, who held near-absolute power without a parliament or constitution. Around 1900 it was undergoing rapid industrialization, particularly with railway construction including the Trans-Siberian Railway, while expanding its influence in Manchuria and the Far East. Social unrest, peasant discontent, and revolutionary movements were growing, foreshadowing the upheavals of 1905."},
  "rwanda": {"1900":"Around 1900 Rwanda was a kingdom ruled by a Tutsi monarchy (the mwami), with Yuhi V Musinga reigning, and was nominally part of German East Africa following its assignment to Germany's sphere. German colonial presence was still minimal at this time, with the first European mission and administrative posts only just being established, so the kingdom retained substantial internal autonomy under indirect rule.","1960":"In 1960 Rwanda was part of the Belgian-administered United Nations trust territory of Ruanda-Urundi, not yet independent. The period was marked by the Rwandan Revolution that began in 1959, in which the Hutu majority rose against the Tutsi monarchy and aristocracy, leading to violence and the flight of many Tutsi. Communal elections in 1960 brought Hutu-dominated parties such as PARMEHUTU to power, foreshadowing the abolition of the monarchy and independence in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Rwanda experienced genocide: after President Juvenal Habyarimana's plane was shot down on 6 April, Hutu extremists carried out the mass slaughter of Tutsi and moderate Hutu, killing roughly 800,000 people in about a hundred days. The Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front, advancing militarily, captured Kigali and ended the genocide by July, after which a new government was formed and roughly two million Hutu refugees fled into neighboring countries.","2000":"In 2000 Rwanda was recovering from the 1994 genocide under a government dominated by the Rwandan Patriotic Front. Paul Kagame, previously vice-president and defence minister, became president in April 2000 after Pasteur Bizimungu resigned. Rwandan forces were militarily involved in the ongoing conflict in the neighbouring Democratic Republic of the Congo.","2010":"In 2010 Rwanda was a republic led by President Paul Kagame, who won re-election that August with an overwhelming majority amid criticism of restrictions on the opposition and press. The country continued its post-genocide reconstruction and was noted for rapid economic growth and stability.","2026":"Rwanda in 2026 is a republic led by President Paul Kagame, who was reelected in 2024. The country has faced international criticism over its support for the M23 rebel group amid renewed conflict in the eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo."},
  "rwanda (belgium)": {"1920":"Rwanda had been part of German East Africa but was occupied by Belgian forces during the First World War, and in 1919 it was assigned to Belgium. By 1920 it was administered by Belgium pending the formalization of a League of Nations mandate over Ruanda-Urundi, with Belgium ruling through the existing Tutsi monarchy.","1938":"In 1938 Ruanda was part of Ruanda-Urundi, a territory administered by Belgium under a League of Nations mandate following its transfer from German control after the First World War. Belgium ruled indirectly through the existing Tutsi monarchy and chiefly structures."},
  "s. geo. and the is.": {"1960":"In 1960 South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands were British territory, then administered as dependencies of the Falkland Islands. South Georgia hosted active whaling stations, such as Grytviken, operated chiefly by Norwegian and British interests, though the whaling industry was in decline. The islands had no permanent civilian population beyond whaling and a small official presence.","1994":"In 1994 South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, with no permanent civilian population. The territory had been administered separately from the Falkland Islands since 1985 and was used mainly for scientific research and a small official and military presence.","2000":"In 2000 South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic with no permanent civilian population. The territory was administered from the Falkland Islands and hosted only a small presence of officials, scientists, and a research station. Argentina continued to claim the islands.","2010":"In 2010 South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, with no permanent civilian population. The territory was administered from the Falkland Islands and hosted government officials, scientists, and the British Antarctic Survey, with sovereignty also claimed by Argentina.","2026":"South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands in 2026 is a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic with no permanent civilian population, administered alongside the Falkland Islands. It is uninhabited apart from research and government station staff and is claimed by Argentina."},
  "s. sudan": {"2026":"South Sudan in 2026 is the world's youngest sovereign state, independent from Sudan since 2011, and remains fragile after its civil war. It continues to struggle with political instability and tensions within its power-sharing arrangement between President Salva Kiir and Riek Machar."},
  "saint barthelemy": {"1900":"In 1900 Saint Barthelemy was a French possession, having been sold back to France by Sweden in 1878 after a long period of Swedish rule. It was a small, economically marginal Caribbean island administered as a dependency of Guadeloupe.","1920":"Saint Barthélemy was a French colonial possession in the Caribbean, administered as a dependency of Guadeloupe. France had reacquired the island from Sweden in 1878.","1938":"In 1938 Saint-Barthélemy was a French possession in the Caribbean, administered as a dependency of Guadeloupe. It was a small, sparsely populated island."},
  "saint helena": {"1960":"In 1960 Saint Helena was a British colony in the South Atlantic, administering the dependencies of Ascension and Tristan da Cunha. The island had a small population descended largely from settlers, formerly enslaved people, and others, with a limited economy. It was best known historically as the place of Napoleon's exile and death.","1994":"In 1994 Saint Helena was a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, with the dependencies of Ascension and Tristan da Cunha. Remote and reachable only by sea, it had no airport and was administered by a British-appointed governor.","2000":"In 2000 Saint Helena was a British Overseas Territory in the South Atlantic, including the dependencies of Ascension and Tristan da Cunha. The remote island had no airport and was reached only by the supply ship RMS St Helena. Islanders' full British citizenship had been a long-running grievance, restored by legislation in 2002.","2010":"In 2010 Saint Helena was part of the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, a remote South Atlantic island accessible only by ship. Around this time the UK confirmed plans to build an airport on the island to improve access.","2026":"Saint Helena in 2026 is part of the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, located in the South Atlantic. It is a remote, sparsely populated island known historically as Napoleon's place of exile."},
  "saint kitts and nevis": {"1900":"In 1900 Saint Kitts and Nevis were British colonies in the Leeward Islands, part of the British West Indies and administered within the Federal Colony of the Leeward Islands. Their economy rested chiefly on sugar production, which was in decline amid falling sugar prices and competition from European beet sugar.","1920":"Saint Kitts and Nevis were British colonial islands in the Leeward Islands of the Caribbean, part of the British colonial structure in the West Indies. Their economy rested chiefly on sugar production.","1938":"In 1938 Saint Kitts and Nevis was a British colony in the West Indies, its economy based on sugar. It was administered as part of the British Leeward Islands."},
  "saint lucia": {"1920":"Saint Lucia was a British colony in the Windward Islands of the eastern Caribbean. Its economy was based on agriculture, particularly sugar, and the island also served as a coaling station for shipping.","1938":"In 1938 Saint Lucia was a British colony in the West Indies, administered within the Windward Islands. Its economy depended heavily on sugar and other agricultural exports.","1960":"In 1960 Saint Lucia was a British colony in the Windward Islands of the eastern Caribbean and a member of the West Indies Federation, which had been formed in 1958. Its economy rested heavily on agriculture, especially bananas. The island would not become an associated state with internal self-government until 1967 and independent until 1979.","1994":"In 1994 Saint Lucia was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm in the eastern Caribbean, recognizing Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a governor-general. Its economy depended heavily on banana exports, which were sensitive to changes in preferential European market access. John Compton of the United Workers Party served as prime minister.","2000":"In 2000 Saint Lucia was an independent parliamentary democracy in the Caribbean and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. The Saint Lucia Labour Party government led by Prime Minister Kenny Anthony was in office. The economy depended heavily on banana exports and a growing tourism sector.","2010":"In 2010 Saint Lucia was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state, represented by a Governor-General. The Caribbean island nation's economy depended heavily on tourism and bananas, and it was struck by Hurricane Tomas in late 2010.","2026":"Saint Lucia in 2026 is an independent island nation in the eastern Caribbean and a Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. It is a parliamentary democracy with an economy heavily reliant on tourism."},
  "saint martin": {"1800":"In 1800, Saint Martin was a small Caribbean island that had been partitioned between France and the Dutch since the 1648 Treaty of Concordia, with the French holding the northern portion and the Dutch the southern. After the Dutch Republic collapsed into the French-client Batavian Republic in 1795, French forces took control of the whole island, so both the French north and the nominally Dutch south stood under French occupation. The island's economy rested on salt harvesting from its ponds and on sugar, cotton, and tobacco estates worked by a large enslaved African majority. Marigot served as the principal town of the French side and Philipsburg, founded in 1763 around the salt-pond fort on Great Bay, as the chief town of the Dutch side. British forces would seize the entire island in March 1801, so 1800 fell in a brief final interval of French wartime control before that occupation.","1900":"In 1900 the island of Saint Martin was divided between France and the Netherlands, an arrangement dating to the 1648 partition. The northern French portion was administered as a dependency of Guadeloupe, while the southern Dutch portion belonged to the colony of Curaçao; both were small and economically modest.","1920":"In 1920 the island of Saint Martin was divided between two European colonial powers, with the northern part belonging to France as a dependency of Guadeloupe and the southern part belonging to the Netherlands as part of the Netherlands Antilles. It was a small Caribbean possession with a population engaged in salt production and subsistence activity, governed remotely from the larger colonial administrations.","1938":"In 1938 the island of Saint Martin was divided between France and the Netherlands, with the northern French part administered as a dependency of Guadeloupe and the southern Dutch part (Sint Maarten) belonging to the Netherlands Antilles colony."},
  "saint vincent and the grenadines": {"1920":"In 1920 Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was a British colony in the Windward Islands of the eastern Caribbean. Its economy rested on plantation agriculture, and it was administered as part of the British Windward Islands colonial grouping. Sugar, arrowroot, and cotton were among its exports.","1938":"In 1938 Saint Vincent was a British colony in the West Indies, administered as part of the Windward Islands. Its economy was based on agriculture."},
  "saipan": {"1938":"In 1938 Saipan was administered by Japan as part of the South Seas Mandate, a League of Nations mandate over former German islands in the Pacific. It had become a center of Japanese sugar cultivation with a substantial settler population."},
  "samoa": {"1900":"In 1900 the Samoan islands had just been partitioned under the 1899 Tripartite Convention, which ended years of rivalry among Germany, Britain, and the United States. Germany took the western islands (Upolu and Savai'i) as German Samoa, formally established in 1900, while the United States took the eastern islands (American Samoa), and Britain withdrew its claims in exchange for concessions elsewhere.","1920":"In 1920 Western Samoa was administered by New Zealand, which had seized the islands from Germany in 1914; a League of Nations mandate over the territory was formally conferred in 1920. The eastern islands (American Samoa) remained under United States naval administration. The territory was recovering from the catastrophic 1918 influenza epidemic, which had killed roughly a fifth of the Western Samoan population under the New Zealand administration.","1938":"In 1938 the Samoan islands were divided: Western Samoa was administered by New Zealand under a League of Nations mandate, while American Samoa in the east was a United States territory governed by the U.S. Navy. In Western Samoa the Mau independence movement remained a significant feature of political life.","1960":"In 1960 the territory known as Western Samoa was a United Nations trust territory administered by New Zealand, moving toward independence. A constitution was adopted in 1960 and a UN-supervised plebiscite in 1961 confirmed the wish for independence, which took effect on 1 January 1962. The eastern islands of American Samoa remained a separate U.S. territory.","1994":"In 1994 the country, then officially named Western Samoa, was an independent parliamentary democracy in the South Pacific and a member of the Commonwealth, with Malietoa Tanumafili II as head of state. Tofilau Eti Alesana of the Human Rights Protection Party was prime minister, and the introduction of a value-added goods and services tax had provoked significant public protest.","2000":"In 2000 Samoa was an independent parliamentary democracy in the South Pacific, then still officially named Western Samoa though commonly called Samoa. Malietoa Tanumafili II served as head of state and Tuilaepa Sailele Malielegaoi was prime minister. Its economy relied on agriculture, fishing, remittances, and aid.","2010":"In 2010 Samoa was an independent parliamentary democracy in the South Pacific, led by Prime Minister Tuilaepa Sailele Malielegaoi. The country was still recovering from the deadly September 2009 tsunami, having switched to driving on the left in 2009."},
  "san marino": {"2026":"San Marino in 2026 is a small landlocked republic enclaved within Italy, one of the world's oldest republics. It is governed by two Captains Regent serving as joint heads of state and is not a member of the European Union, though it uses the euro."},
  "saudi arabia": {"1938":"In 1938 Saudi Arabia was a kingdom under King Abdulaziz (Ibn Saud), who had unified the realm and proclaimed the Kingdom in 1932. In March 1938 commercial quantities of oil were discovered at Dammam, marking the beginning of the country's oil era.","1960":"In 1960 Saudi Arabia was an absolute monarchy ruled by the House of Saud, with King Saud bin Abdulaziz on the throne amid a power struggle with his brother Crown Prince Faisal. The kingdom's wealth came from oil produced by the Aramco concession, and in 1960 it was a founding member of OPEC, established in Baghdad that September. The state was governed under Islamic law with no formal constitution or elected legislature.","1994":"In 1994 Saudi Arabia was an absolute monarchy ruled by King Fahd of the Al Saud dynasty, who held the title Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques. The oil-rich kingdom remained a close ally of the United States in the aftermath of the 1991 Gulf War. The government continued to face challenges from Islamist opposition critical of the royal family and of the post-war Western military presence.","2000":"In 2000 Saudi Arabia was an absolute monarchy ruled by the House of Saud, with King Fahd as monarch though Crown Prince Abdullah handled day-to-day governance after Fahd's 1995 stroke. The world's leading oil exporter, it was the custodian of Islam's holiest sites at Mecca and Medina. The state applied a strict Wahhabi interpretation of Islamic law.","2010":"In 2010 Saudi Arabia was an absolute monarchy ruled by King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz Al Saud, the world's largest oil exporter and custodian of Islam's holiest sites at Mecca and Medina. The kingdom maintained a conservative society governed under a strict interpretation of Islamic law.","2026":"Saudi Arabia in 2026 is an absolute monarchy ruled by King Salman, with Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman serving as the de facto leader and prime minister. The kingdom is pursuing its Vision 2030 economic diversification program, including megaprojects like NEOM, to reduce dependence on oil."},
  "scarborough reef": {"1994":"In 1994 Scarborough Shoal was an uninhabited reef and lagoon in the South China Sea, claimed by both the Philippines and China and lying within waters subject to overlapping territorial disputes. It had no permanent population or established government presence.","2000":"In 2000 Scarborough Shoal was an uninhabited reef and lagoon in the South China Sea, claimed by both China and the Philippines and also by Taiwan. It was not under permanent occupation but was a recurring point of dispute, particularly over fishing. China would seize effective control of it in 2012.","2010":"In 2010 Scarborough Shoal was a disputed, largely submerged reef and atoll in the South China Sea, claimed by both China and the Philippines (and also by Taiwan). It had no permanent inhabitants, and tensions over it had not yet escalated into the major 2012 standoff.","2026":"Scarborough Shoal in 2026 is a disputed reef and atoll in the South China Sea claimed by both China and the Philippines. It remains effectively controlled by China, which maintains a coast guard presence there, and is a flashpoint in regional maritime tensions."},
  "second samori empire": {"1900":"By 1900 the empire founded by Samori Ture had collapsed, as Samori was captured by French forces in 1898 and his Wassoulou state was dissolved and absorbed into French West Africa. The territory was therefore under French colonial control rather than existing as an independent state."},
  "senegal": {"1800":"In 1800, \"Senegal\" existed only as a pair of small French trading posts on the coast — the island town of Saint-Louis at the mouth of the Senegal River and the island of Gorée off the future Dakar — while the interior was ruled by independent African kingdoms such as Waalo, Cayor, and Futa Toro. In 1800, both posts were still in French hands, contrary to the notion that they were already under British occupation; Britain would not seize Gorée until April 1801 nor Saint-Louis until July 1809. In 1800, Saint-Louis served as the administrative seat, home to a French garrison and a mixed community of métis traders and the influential Afro-French signares. In 1800, the local economy remained bound up in the Atlantic slave trade alongside gum arabic exported through the river trade, though the trade would soon come under pressure from abolition. In 1800, France's presence was confined to these fortified enclaves and a few river factories, exercising no territorial control over the Senegalese mainland.","1900":"In 1900 Senegal was a French colony and a central part of French West Africa, with Saint-Louis serving as a key administrative center and Dakar a growing port. The Four Communes (Saint-Louis, Gorée, Rufisque, and Dakar) held a special status whose African inhabitants enjoyed certain French civic rights, while the interior was administered as a subject territory under expanding French control.","1960":"In 1960 Senegal gained independence from France. It first became independent in April 1960 as part of the Mali Federation together with French Sudan, but that federation broke up in August 1960, and Senegal proclaimed itself a separate independent republic. Léopold Sédar Senghor became its first president.","1994":"In 1994 Senegal was an independent multiparty republic led by President Abdou Diouf of the Socialist Party. In January 1994 the CFA franc was devalued by 50 percent, triggering sharp price rises and protests, and the government faced an ongoing low-intensity separatist insurgency in the southern Casamance region.","2000":"Senegal was an independent republic in West Africa. In March 2000 Abdoulaye Wade won the presidential election, defeating the long-ruling Socialist Party's Abdou Diouf and ending four decades of Socialist Party dominance in a peaceful, widely praised transfer of power. The country was a stable multiparty democracy, though a low-level separatist conflict continued in the southern Casamance region.","2010":"In 2010 Senegal was a sovereign republic in West Africa led by President Abdoulaye Wade of the Senegalese Democratic Party, who had been in office since 2000. The year was marked by controversy over the costly Monument of the African Renaissance unveiled in Dakar during the 50th anniversary of independence from France. Tensions were also rising over Wade's apparent intention to seek a third term and to position his son Karim for power.","2026":"Senegal in 2026 is a presidential republic in West Africa led by President Bassirou Diomaye Faye, who was elected in March 2024. His government, with Prime Minister Ousmane Sonko, has pursued reform and greater national sovereignty over resources."},
  "serbia": {"1900":"In 1900 Serbia was an independent kingdom, recognized as sovereign since the 1878 Treaty of Berlin and made a kingdom in 1882, ruled by King Alexander I of the Obrenovic dynasty. It was a small, predominantly agrarian Balkan state with unstable politics and economic dependence on Austria-Hungary; Alexander's unpopular reign would end in his assassination in the 1903 coup that restored the Karadordevic dynasty.","1994":"In 1994 Serbia, under President Slobodan Milosevic, was the dominant republic of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (with Montenegro), which had been formed in 1992 and was under international sanctions. It backed Serb forces in the wars in Bosnia and Croatia, though in 1994 Belgrade publicly distanced itself from the Bosnian Serbs after they rejected the international peace plan.","2000":"In 2000 Serbia was the dominant republic within the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, alongside Montenegro, under Slobodan Milosevic. In late September 2000 federal elections, mass protests culminated in the October 5 overthrow of Milosevic and the recognition of Vojislav Kostunica as Yugoslav president. This followed the 1999 NATO bombing campaign over Kosovo, which was placed under UN administration in 1999.","2010":"In 2010 Serbia was a sovereign parliamentary republic, with Boris Tadic as president and the country pursuing European Union integration. It continued to reject the 2008 unilateral declaration of independence by Kosovo, and in July 2010 the International Court of Justice issued an advisory opinion that Kosovo's declaration did not violate international law. Serbia applied for EU candidacy and worked to balance Western ties with relations with Russia.","2026":"Serbia in 2026 is a republic in the Balkans and a candidate for European Union membership, with Aleksandar Vučić as president. The country has been roiled by sustained mass protests since late 2024, sparked by the deadly collapse of a railway station canopy in Novi Sad."},
  "serranilla bank": {"1994":"Serranilla Bank is an uninhabited reef and group of cays in the western Caribbean, administered by Colombia but also claimed by the United States (and historically by others). It has no permanent population and no government of its own; in 1994 its sovereignty remained disputed.","2000":"Serranilla Bank is a largely submerged reef and small cays in the western Caribbean Sea, administered by Colombia. It is uninhabited apart from a small Colombian naval/military presence and has been the subject of competing territorial claims, including by the United States and Nicaragua.","2010":"Serranilla Bank is a small, largely submerged reef and cay in the western Caribbean Sea administered by Colombia, with a partly maintained Colombian naval/lighthouse presence. Its sovereignty was disputed, claimed also by the United States under the Guano Islands Act and historically by Nicaragua. In 2010 it remained uninhabited apart from any small Colombian detachment, with no permanent civilian population.","2026":"Serranilla Bank is a small, largely uninhabited reef and bank in the western Caribbean administered by Colombia as part of the San Andrés, Providencia and Santa Catalina archipelago department. Its sovereignty has historically been contested, but a 2012 International Court of Justice ruling between Nicaragua and Colombia left the surrounding maritime delimitation a continuing source of friction, with Colombia maintaining a small military presence on nearby features. The bank itself remains essentially unpopulated in 2026."},
  "seychelles": {"1960":"In 1960 the Seychelles were a British colony, a group of islands in the western Indian Ocean. The economy depended on plantation crops such as coconuts and cinnamon, and the colony had limited self-government at this time. It would not gain independence until 1976.","1994":"In 1994 Seychelles was an independent island republic led by President France-Albert Rene, who had reintroduced multiparty politics in the early 1990s after years of one-party rule. Its economy depended heavily on tourism and fishing.","2000":"Seychelles was an independent island republic in the Indian Ocean. In 2000 it was governed by President France-Albert Rene, who had led the country since 1977; his party won the 1998 elections and Rene was re-elected. The economy depended heavily on tourism and tuna fishing.","2010":"In 2010 Seychelles was a sovereign island republic in the Indian Ocean led by President James Michel of the People's Party. The country was recovering from a severe debt crisis, having defaulted in 2008 and undertaken an IMF-backed reform program with currency liberalization. Tourism and fishing remained the economic mainstays, while the country was increasingly affected by Somali piracy in surrounding waters."},
  "shona": {"1900":"By 1900 the Shona peoples of the territory between the Zambezi and Limpopo rivers had been brought under the control of the British South Africa Company within Southern Rhodesia. Their major uprising against company rule, the Chimurenga of 1896-97 (alongside the Ndebele), had been suppressed, and they were subject to colonial administration, taxation, and land alienation."},
  "siachen glacier": {"2026":"The Siachen Glacier in the eastern Karakoram remains a militarized zone disputed between India and Pakistan, with Indian forces holding most of the glacier and the Saltoro Ridge since Operation Meghdoot in 1984. A 2003 ceasefire along the Line of Control has largely held, but no demilitarization agreement has been reached, and both armies continue to maintain high-altitude posts in 2026."},
  "siam": {"1938":"In 1938 Siam was a constitutional monarchy following the 1932 revolution that ended absolute rule, with the young King Ananda Mahidol on the throne. In December 1938 Field Marshal Plaek Phibunsongkhram became prime minister, ushering in a nationalist, military-dominated government."},
  "sierra leone": {"1900":"In 1900 Sierra Leone was a British colony, with the coastal Freetown area a Crown Colony and the recently declared interior a Protectorate established in 1896. The imposition of a hut tax in the protectorate had provoked the Hut Tax War of 1898, led by figures such as Bai Bureh, which the British had suppressed by 1899.","1920":"In 1920 Sierra Leone was a British colony and protectorate in West Africa, with Freetown as its capital and chief port. The coastal Colony was governed directly while the interior was administered as a protectorate through indirect rule and local chiefs.","1938":"In 1938 Sierra Leone was a British colony and protectorate in West Africa, with a Crown Colony centered on Freetown and a protectorate over the interior. Its economy was based on agricultural exports and growing mineral production including diamonds and iron ore.","1960":"In 1960 Sierra Leone was a British colony and protectorate in West Africa, on the verge of independence. Constitutional talks in London in 1960 set the path to independence, which was achieved on 27 April 1961, with Milton Margai becoming prime minister. The capital, Freetown, had historic roots as a settlement for freed and liberated Africans.","1994":"In 1994 Sierra Leone was gripped by a civil war that had begun in 1991, with the rebel Revolutionary United Front fighting the government and controlling parts of the country. The state was under a military junta, the National Provisional Ruling Council led by Valentine Strasser, which had seized power in 1992.","2000":"In 2000 Sierra Leone was engulfed in its long civil war, with President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah's government fighting the Revolutionary United Front (RUF). The 1999 Lome Peace Accord collapsed as the RUF seized UN peacekeepers as hostages in May 2000, prompting a British military intervention that helped stabilize Freetown and bolster the UNAMSIL mission.","2010":"In 2010 Sierra Leone was a sovereign republic in West Africa led by President Ernest Bai Koroma, who had taken office in 2007. The country was rebuilding after its 1991-2002 civil war, and the UN peacebuilding mission UNIPSIL supported governance and recovery. That year the UN Security Council lifted the last remaining arms and travel sanctions on the country."},
  "singapore": {"1960":"In 1960 Singapore was a self-governing state, having achieved internal self-government in 1959 with Lee Kuan Yew of the People's Action Party as its first Prime Minister. Britain still retained control of external defence and foreign affairs, and the colony had not yet joined Malaysia or become independent.","1994":"In 1994 Singapore was an independent city-state and parliamentary republic, governed by the long-dominant People's Action Party under Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong, with Lee Kuan Yew as Senior Minister. It was a prosperous, highly developed economy; the 1994 caning of American teenager Michael Fay drew international attention.","2000":"Singapore was an independent city-state and republic in Southeast Asia. In 2000 Goh Chok Tong served as prime minister, with the People's Action Party in firm control of government, and S. R. Nathan was president. It was a wealthy, highly developed economy recovering strongly from the 1997-98 Asian financial crisis.","2010":"In 2010 Singapore was a sovereign city-state and parliamentary republic governed by the long-dominant People's Action Party, with Lee Hsien Loong as prime minister. The economy rebounded strongly from the global financial crisis, posting one of the world's highest growth rates that year. Two integrated resort casinos, Marina Bay Sands and Resorts World Sentosa, opened in 2010.","2026":"Singapore is a sovereign city-state and parliamentary republic in Southeast Asia, governed by the People's Action Party, which won the May 2025 general election under Prime Minister Lawrence Wong, who had succeeded Lee Hsien Loong in 2024. It remains a major global financial, shipping, and high-technology hub with one of the world's highest per-capita incomes. Tharman Shanmugaratnam serves as president in 2026."},
  "sint maarten": {"1960":"In 1960 the southern part of the island of Saint Martin was part of the Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands established in 1954. It was not a separate constituent country at this time.","2010":"Sint Maarten became a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands on 10 October 2010, when the Netherlands Antilles was dissolved. It occupies the southern part of the island of Saint Martin, sharing it with the French collectivity to the north. The new autonomous status gave it self-government in internal affairs while the Kingdom retained responsibility for defense and foreign policy.","2026":"Sint Maarten is a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, occupying the southern half of the Caribbean island of Saint Martin, with the French collectivity of Saint-Martin to the north. It has internal autonomy with the Dutch monarch as head of state, while continuing recovery and reconstruction efforts stemming from the devastation of Hurricane Irma in 2017. Philipsburg remains its capital in 2026."},
  "slovakia": {"1994":"In 1994 Slovakia was an independent parliamentary republic, having become sovereign on 1 January 1993 with the peaceful dissolution of Czechoslovakia. Politics were turbulent: Vladimir Meciar's government was ousted by a no-confidence vote in March 1994, a caretaker government followed, and Meciar's HZDS won the autumn elections.","2000":"Slovakia was an independent republic in Central Europe, formed by the 1993 split of Czechoslovakia. In 2000 it was governed by a coalition under Prime Minister Mikulas Dzurinda, with Rudolf Schuster as president, pursuing reforms aimed at EU and NATO membership after the more isolationist Meciar era. In 2000 Slovakia joined the OECD and pursued EU accession negotiations.","2010":"In 2010 Slovakia was a sovereign parliamentary republic, a member of the European Union, NATO, and the eurozone, having adopted the euro in 2009. June 2010 elections ended Robert Fico's first government, bringing a center-right coalition under Iveta Radicova, the country's first female prime minister. Her government became prominent in debates over eurozone bailouts, initially resisting Greek aid.","2026":"Slovakia is a sovereign parliamentary republic in Central Europe and a member of the European Union, NATO, and the eurozone. Robert Fico returned as prime minister after the 2023 election leading a coalition that took a more skeptical line on military aid to Ukraine, and Peter Pellegrini became president in 2024; Fico survived an assassination attempt in May 2024. The country remains politically polarized in 2026."},
  "slovenia": {"1994":"In 1994 Slovenia was an independent parliamentary republic, having seceded from Yugoslavia in 1991 after a brief ten-day war. It was the most prosperous of the former Yugoslav states, pursuing market reforms and integration with Western Europe under Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek.","2000":"Slovenia was an independent republic in Central Europe that had gained independence from Yugoslavia in 1991. In 2000 Milan Kucan was president, and the year saw political turnover, with Janez Drnovsek returning as prime minister after the autumn elections. The country was a stable democracy actively pursuing EU and NATO membership.","2010":"In 2010 Slovenia was a sovereign parliamentary republic, a member of the European Union, NATO, and the eurozone, governed by a center-left coalition under Prime Minister Borut Pahor. In June 2010 voters approved a referendum on an arbitration agreement with Croatia to resolve their long-standing border dispute, particularly over the Bay of Piran. The economy was contending with the aftermath of the global financial downturn.","2026":"Slovenia is a sovereign parliamentary republic in Central Europe and a member of the European Union, NATO, and the eurozone. Robert Golob's Freedom Movement has led the government since 2022, while Nataša Pirc Musar serves as president, and Slovenia held a non-permanent seat on the UN Security Council for 2024-2025. It remains a high-income economy in 2026."},
  "sokoto caliphate": {"1900":"In 1900 the Sokoto Caliphate was still an independent Islamic state in what is now northern Nigeria, a large confederation of emirates under the Sultan of Sokoto. It faced mounting pressure from the British, who proclaimed the Protectorate of Northern Nigeria under Frederick Lugard in 1900; the caliphate would be conquered over the following few years, culminating in its defeat in 1903."},
  "solomon is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Solomon Islands were the British Solomon Islands Protectorate, administered by the United Kingdom. Independence would not come until 1978.","1994":"In 1994 the Solomon Islands was an independent parliamentary democracy and Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Its economy relied on logging, fishing, and agriculture.","2000":"The Solomon Islands was an independent parliamentary state in the Pacific and a Commonwealth realm. In June 2000 a coup by the Malaita Eagle Force removed Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufaalu amid ethnic conflict between Malaitan and Guadalcanal militants. The Townsville Peace Agreement was signed in October 2000 in an effort to end the violence.","2010":"In 2010 Solomon Islands was a sovereign parliamentary monarchy in the South Pacific with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. The Australian-led Regional Assistance Mission to Solomon Islands (RAMSI) remained deployed to maintain stability after earlier ethnic conflict. August 2010 elections led to Danny Philip becoming prime minister.","2026":"Solomon Islands is a sovereign parliamentary state in the southwestern Pacific and a Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. After the April 2024 election, Jeremiah Manele became prime minister, continuing the closer alignment with China that began under predecessor Manasseh Sogavare, including the controversial 2022 security pact. The country remains a focus of geopolitical competition between China and Western powers in 2026."},
  "somalia": {"1960":"Somalia became independent in 1960 through the union of the former Italian-administered UN Trust Territory of Somaliland and the former British Somaliland, which had gained independence days earlier in June. The new Somali Republic was formed on 1 July 1960, with Aden Abdullah Osman Daar as its first President.","1994":"In 1994 Somalia had no functioning central government and was divided among rival clan-based factions following the 1991 collapse of Siad Barre's regime. The US-led UNITAF had given way to the UN's UNOSOM II mission; US forces withdrew in March 1994 after the previous year's Mogadishu clashes, and fighting between warlords such as Aidid and Ali Mahdi continued.","2000":"In 2000 Somalia had had no effective central government since the 1991 collapse of Siad Barre's regime, with the country fragmented among clan factions and warlords. In August 2000 a national reconciliation conference in Arta, Djibouti, established the Transitional National Government and selected Abdiqasim Salad Hassan as president, though it controlled little territory. The self-declared republic of Somaliland in the northwest remained de facto independent.","2010":"In 2010 Somalia was a fragmented state whose internationally recognized Transitional Federal Government, led by President Sharif Sheikh Ahmed, controlled only parts of Mogadishu with the protection of the African Union mission AMISOM. The militant Islamist group al-Shabaab held much of southern and central Somalia and waged insurgency against the government. The self-declared regions of Somaliland and Puntland operated autonomously, and Somali piracy off the coast was at a peak.","2026":"Somalia is a federal republic in the Horn of Africa whose central government in Mogadishu, led by President Hassan Sheikh Mohamud, continues to fight the al-Shabaab insurgency with support from an African Union mission. The transition from ATMIS to a new AU support mission unfolded amid debates over funding and troop levels, while tensions with Ethiopia flared over Ethiopia's 2024 port deal with Somaliland before a Turkey-brokered détente. The federal state's authority over regions like Puntland and Jubaland remains contested in 2026."},
  "somaliland": {"2026":"Somaliland is a self-declared independent republic in the northwest of the former Somali state, with its capital at Hargeisa, that has functioned with its own government, currency, and elections since 1991 but lacks international recognition. Abdirahman Mohamed Abdullahi (Irro) won the November 2024 presidential election, and Somaliland signed a memorandum with Ethiopia in early 2024 over sea access that drew strong objections from Somalia. It continues to seek recognition while operating as a de facto state in 2026."},
  "south africa": {"1960":"In 1960 South Africa was a self-governing dominion still under the apartheid system enforced by the National Party government. That year saw the Sharpeville massacre in March, in which police killed dozens of anti-pass-law protesters, and a referendum among white voters approved becoming a republic, which took effect in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 South Africa held its first non-racial democratic elections in April, ending apartheid, and Nelson Mandela became president at the head of a Government of National Unity. The African National Congress won the elections, and the country began its transition under an interim constitution.","2000":"South Africa was a democratic republic six years after the end of apartheid. In 2000 Thabo Mbeki was president, having succeeded Nelson Mandela in 1999, with the African National Congress governing. The country faced major challenges including high unemployment, crime, and a severe HIV/AIDS epidemic amid controversy over Mbeki's questioning of the link between HIV and AIDS; local government elections were held in December 2000.","2010":"In 2010 South Africa was a sovereign constitutional republic governed by the African National Congress under President Jacob Zuma, who had taken office in 2009. The country hosted the FIFA World Cup in June and July 2010, the first held on the African continent. It remained the continent's largest economy and was invited that year to join the BRIC grouping of emerging economies.","2026":"South Africa is a sovereign parliamentary republic at the southern tip of Africa. After the May 2024 election, the African National Congress lost its outright majority for the first time since 1994 and formed a Government of National Unity with the Democratic Alliance and other parties, with Cyril Ramaphosa continuing as president. South Africa holds the G20 presidency for 2025 and remains a member of BRICS in 2026."},
  "south australia (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 South Australia was a self-governing British colony on the eve of Australian federation, which took effect on 1 January 1901. It was notable for having granted women the vote in 1894, among the first in the world, and its economy rested on wheat farming, pastoralism, and mining."},
  "south korea": {"1960":"In 1960 South Korea (the Republic of Korea) saw the April Revolution, a popular uprising that forced President Syngman Rhee to resign after the rigged March election. This was followed by the establishment of the short-lived Second Republic under a parliamentary system.","1994":"In 1994 South Korea was a democratic republic led by President Kim Young-sam, the first civilian president in decades, who pursued anti-corruption and reform measures. Tensions with North Korea were high over Pyongyang's nuclear program, easing somewhat with the October 1994 Agreed Framework; North Korean leader Kim Il-sung's death in July 1994 added to regional uncertainty.","2000":"South Korea (the Republic of Korea) was an independent democratic republic led by President Kim Dae-jung. In June 2000 Kim held a historic inter-Korean summit in Pyongyang with North Korea's Kim Jong-il under his \"Sunshine Policy\" of engagement, for which he was awarded the 2000 Nobel Peace Prize. The economy had largely recovered from the 1997 Asian financial crisis.","2010":"In 2010 South Korea was a sovereign presidential republic led by President Lee Myung-bak of the conservative Grand National Party. Inter-Korean tensions sharply escalated: the warship Cheonan sank in March, blamed on a North Korean torpedo, and North Korea shelled Yeonpyeong Island in November. South Korea also hosted the G20 summit in Seoul that November, the first held in Asia.","2026":"South Korea is a sovereign presidential republic on the Korean Peninsula. After President Yoon Suk Yeol's short-lived December 2024 martial law declaration led to his impeachment and removal, Lee Jae-myung of the Democratic Party won the June 2025 presidential election. It remains a major economy and a US ally facing continued tensions with North Korea in 2026."},
  "south russia": {"1920":"In 1920 \"South Russia\" denoted the White (anti-Bolshevik) forces and territory under General Anton Denikin and later General Pyotr Wrangel during the Russian Civil War. Denikin's Armed Forces of South Russia, after their 1919 advance toward Moscow, were driven back and collapsed in early 1920; Wrangel reorganized the remnant in Crimea, which the Red Army overran in November 1920, ending the White hold and forcing a mass evacuation."},
  "southern patagonian ice field": {"2026":"The Southern Patagonian Ice Field is a large expanse of glacial ice in the southern Andes shared between Argentina and Chile, one of the largest freshwater reserves outside the polar regions. A roughly 50-kilometre stretch of the border near Mount Fitz Roy and the Southern Patagonian Ice Field remains undelimited between the two countries, a legacy of their boundary agreements. The ice field continues to lose mass through glacial retreat attributed to climate change in 2026."},
  "southern rhodesia": {"1938":"In 1938 Southern Rhodesia was a self-governing British colony in southern Africa, having held internal self-government since 1923, with a settler-dominated government and economy based on mining and agriculture. Political power and land were concentrated in the white minority under racially segregationist policies."},
  "spain": {"1900":"In 1900 Spain was a constitutional monarchy under the boy-king Alfonso XIII, whose mother Maria Christina served as regent. The country was reeling from its defeat in the Spanish-American War of 1898, which had stripped it of Cuba, Puerto Rico, the Philippines, and Guam, a national trauma known as the Disaster of '98 that spurred soul-searching among the Generation of '98 intellectuals.","1920":"In 1920 Spain was a constitutional monarchy under King Alfonso XIII, having remained neutral in the First World War. The period was marked by political instability, labor unrest, and violent conflict between unions and employers, especially in Barcelona. Spain was also engaged in colonial campaigns in its Moroccan protectorate.","1938":"Spain in 1938 was in the midst of its civil war, with the Nationalist forces under General Francisco Franco controlling much of the country and the Republican government holding Madrid, Barcelona, and the eastern regions. The Battle of the Ebro, the war's largest and bloodiest engagement, was fought from July to November 1938 and ended in a costly Republican defeat. Franco received military support from Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy, while the Republic was increasingly isolated as the international Non-Intervention policy held.","1960":"In 1960 Spain was an authoritarian dictatorship under Francisco Franco, who had ruled since the end of the Spanish Civil War in 1939. The country was beginning to emerge from economic isolation following the 1959 Stabilization Plan that liberalized the economy.","1994":"In 1994 Spain was a parliamentary monarchy under King Juan Carlos I, with a Socialist (PSOE) government led by Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez. The government was weakened by economic recession, high unemployment, and mounting corruption scandals, and the country was a member of the European Union and NATO.","2000":"Spain was a parliamentary constitutional monarchy under King Juan Carlos I and a member of the European Union and NATO. In March 2000 the conservative People's Party under Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar won an absolute majority. Spain had adopted the euro as its accounting currency at this period and continued to face Basque separatist violence from the group ETA.","2010":"In 2010 Spain was a sovereign parliamentary monarchy with King Juan Carlos I as head of state and a Socialist government under Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero. The country was deep in economic crisis amid the European sovereign debt turmoil, with very high unemployment, a collapsed housing bubble, and austerity measures introduced in May. Spain also won the FIFA World Cup in July 2010, its first ever world title.","2026":"Spain is a parliamentary constitutional monarchy under King Felipe VI, with a coalition government led by Socialist prime minister Pedro Sánchez. It remains a member of the European Union, the eurozone, and NATO, and continues to grapple with Catalan independence politics and a fragmented parliament that makes governing difficult."},
  "spanish sahara": {"1920":"In 1920 the coastal territory of the Western Sahara was a Spanish colonial possession, claimed by Spain since the late 19th century. Spanish control was limited largely to coastal posts such as Villa Cisneros, with the vast desert interior inhabited by largely autonomous Sahrawi nomadic groups.","1938":"Spanish Sahara was a Spanish colony on the northwest coast of Africa, comprising the territories of Río de Oro and Saguia el-Hamra. In 1938 it remained under Spanish administration despite the civil war raging in metropolitan Spain, governed as part of Spain's African possessions."},
  "spratly is.": {"1994":"The Spratly Islands were a group of disputed reefs, atolls, and islets in the South China Sea claimed in whole or part by China, Taiwan, Vietnam, the Philippines, Malaysia, and Brunei, with several claimants maintaining military outposts. In 1994 they had no sovereign government of their own and remained a flashpoint, with tensions running high amid overlapping claims and concerns over potential oil and gas resources.","2000":"In 2000 the Spratly Islands were a cluster of disputed reefs and islets in the South China Sea claimed in whole or part by China, Taiwan, Vietnam, the Philippines, Malaysia, and Brunei, with several claimants maintaining military outposts on individual features. No single sovereign controlled the archipelago, and tensions over occupation and fishing and oil rights persisted, shortly before the 2002 ASEAN-China Declaration on the Conduct of Parties.","2010":"In 2010 the Spratly Islands were a group of disputed reefs, atolls, and islets in the South China Sea claimed in whole or part by China, Taiwan, Vietnam, the Philippines, Malaysia, and Brunei, with several of the claimants occupying garrisons or outposts on individual features. No single sovereign controlled the archipelago, and competing claims over the islands and surrounding waters were a persistent source of regional tension.","2026":"The Spratly Islands are a disputed archipelago in the South China Sea claimed in whole or part by China, Vietnam, the Philippines, Taiwan, Malaysia, and Brunei, with no single recognized sovereign. In 2026 they remain a flashpoint, with China maintaining militarized artificial islands and tensions persisting with the Philippines and others over reefs and fishing waters."},
  "sri lanka": {"1960":"In 1960 the island, then known as Ceylon, was an independent dominion within the Commonwealth, having gained independence in 1948. Sirimavo Bandaranaike became Prime Minister in 1960, the world's first woman to hold that office, leading the Sri Lanka Freedom Party.","1994":"In 1994 Sri Lanka was a presidential republic gripped by its long civil war between government forces and the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam in the north and east. Parliamentary elections in August 1994 brought the People's Alliance to power, and in November Chandrika Kumaratunga was elected president, ending nearly two decades of United National Party rule and raising hopes for peace talks with the LTTE.","2000":"In 2000 Sri Lanka was a sovereign democratic republic with Chandrika Kumaratunga as president, in the midst of its long civil war against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE). Fighting was intense that year, including the LTTE's capture of the Elephant Pass military base, while the government pursued the conflict in the north and east.","2010":"Sri Lanka in 2010 was a unitary republic that had ended its decades-long civil war in May 2009 with the military defeat of the Tamil Tigers (LTTE). Mahinda Rajapaksa, riding the war victory, won re-election as president in January 2010, and the country was beginning post-war reconstruction amid international scrutiny over the conflict's final stages.","2026":"Sri Lanka is a republic that continued recovering from its 2022 economic crisis and sovereign default, operating under an IMF programme. Anura Kumara Dissanayake of the leftist NPP/JVP, elected president in September 2024, leads the government after his coalition also won a parliamentary majority."},
  "st-barthélemy": {"1960":"In 1960 Saint-Barthélemy was part of the French overseas department of Guadeloupe, and thus an integral part of France. It did not become a separate overseas collectivity until 2007.","1994":"In 1994 Saint-Barthélemy was not a separate territory but a commune within the French overseas department of Guadeloupe, and thus an integral part of France and the European Union. It was a small Caribbean island whose economy rested on upscale tourism.","2000":"In 2000 Saint-Barthélemy was not yet a separate French collectivity but a commune within the French overseas department of Guadeloupe, and thus part of France and the European Union. It would only become a distinct overseas collectivity in 2007.","2010":"Saint-Barthélemy was an overseas collectivity of France in 2010, in the Caribbean, having separated from Guadeloupe to become a distinct collectivity in 2007. As a French territory it was part of the French Republic, with its residents holding French citizenship.","2026":"Saint-Barthélemy is a French overseas collectivity in the Caribbean, an autonomous territory of France whose residents are French and EU citizens. It is governed locally by a territorial council and remains a high-end tourism economy."},
  "st-martin": {"1960":"In 1960 the northern part of Saint Martin was part of the French overseas department of Guadeloupe and therefore an integral part of France. It did not become a separate overseas collectivity until 2007.","1994":"In 1994 the northern part of the island of Saint-Martin was a French commune within the overseas department of Guadeloupe, making it part of France and the European Union, while the southern part (Sint Maarten) belonged to the Netherlands Antilles. It was a Caribbean tourism destination shared between the two jurisdictions.","2000":"In 2000 the northern part of the island of Saint-Martin was a French commune within the overseas department of Guadeloupe, part of France and the European Union, while the southern part (Sint Maarten) belonged to the Netherlands Antilles. The French side did not become a separate overseas collectivity until 2007.","2010":"Saint-Martin (the northern part of the island of St. Martin) was a French overseas collectivity in 2010, having split from Guadeloupe in 2007 to become its own collectivity. The southern part of the island, Sint Maarten, was Dutch; in October 2010 Sint Maarten became a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands when the Netherlands Antilles was dissolved.","2026":"Saint-Martin is the French overseas collectivity occupying the northern part of the island of Saint Martin, which it shares with the Dutch territory of Sint Maarten. It is part of France, with French and EU citizenship, and continues rebuilding and tourism-based recovery in the years after Hurricane Irma's 2017 devastation."},
  "st. kitts and nevis": {"1960":"In 1960 Saint Kitts and Nevis was a British colony, part of the federal colony of Saint Christopher-Nevis-Anguilla and a member of the West Indies Federation formed in 1958. Full independence was not achieved until 1983.","1994":"In 1994 Saint Kitts and Nevis was an independent two-island federation in the Caribbean, a constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Its sugar-based economy was shifting toward tourism, and tensions persisted over Nevisian dissatisfaction within the federation.","2000":"In 2000 the Federation of Saint Kitts and Nevis was an independent two-island state within the Commonwealth, a constitutional monarchy with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state and Denzil Douglas as prime minister. A 1998 referendum on Nevis's secession had narrowly failed to reach the required majority, leaving the federation intact.","2010":"Saint Kitts and Nevis was an independent federal two-island state in the Caribbean in 2010, a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a governor-general. Denzil Douglas of the Labour Party served as prime minister, and the federation included a degree of autonomy for Nevis.","2026":"Saint Kitts and Nevis is an independent two-island federation in the Caribbean and a Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. Its economy relies on tourism and a citizenship-by-investment programme."},
  "st. pierre and miquelon": {"1960":"In 1960 Saint Pierre and Miquelon was a French overseas territory in the North Atlantic off the coast of Newfoundland. It remained under French administration as it had been for centuries.","1994":"In 1994 Saint Pierre and Miquelon was a French territorial collectivity, a small group of islands off Newfoundland that remained part of France. Its fishing-dependent economy had been hard hit by a 1992 international arbitration that limited its maritime zone and by the collapse of North Atlantic cod stocks.","2000":"In 2000 Saint-Pierre and Miquelon was a French overseas territorial collectivity off the coast of Newfoundland, part of France though outside the European Union's customs territory. Its economy remained depressed following the collapse of the cod fishery and the 1992 maritime boundary ruling that limited its fishing zone.","2010":"Saint-Pierre and Miquelon was a French overseas collectivity in 2010, a small archipelago off the coast of Newfoundland, Canada. It remained part of the French Republic with its inhabitants as French citizens.","2026":"Saint-Pierre and Miquelon is a French self-governing overseas collectivity, an archipelago off the coast of Newfoundland and France's last territory in North America. Its residents are French and EU citizens, and the small economy depends on fishing and public spending."},
  "st. vin. and gren.": {"1960":"In 1960 Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was a British colony in the Windward Islands and a member of the West Indies Federation formed in 1958. It did not gain full independence until 1979.","1994":"In 1994 Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was an independent Caribbean state, a constitutional monarchy within the Commonwealth with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Its economy depended heavily on banana exports, which were sensitive to changes in preferential European market access.","2000":"In 2000 Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was an independent Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Sir James Mitchell stepped down as prime minister that year and was succeeded by Arnhim Eustace of the New Democratic Party, amid political tension that led to early elections in 2001.","2010":"Saint Vincent and the Grenadines was an independent Caribbean state in 2010, a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. Ralph Gonsalves of the Unity Labour Party was prime minister and won re-election in the December 2010 general election.","2026":"Saint Vincent and the Grenadines is an independent Caribbean state and Commonwealth realm with King Charles III as head of state. Its economy depends on tourism and agriculture, and it continued recovery from the 2021 La Soufrière volcanic eruption."},
  "sudan": {"1920":"In 1920 Sudan was governed as the Anglo-Egyptian Sudan, a condominium nominally shared between Britain and Egypt but in practice administered by British officials. Khartoum was the capital, and the administration was developing cotton agriculture, with the Gezira irrigation scheme under preparation in this period.","1938":"Sudan in 1938 was governed as the Anglo-Egyptian Sudan, a condominium nominally ruled jointly by Britain and Egypt but in practice administered by Britain. A governor-general appointed with British dominance oversaw the territory from Khartoum.","1960":"Sudan had become independent from Anglo-Egyptian condominium rule on 1 January 1956. By 1960 the country was under military rule following the November 1958 coup led by General Ibrahim Abboud, who governed through a Supreme Council of the Armed Forces. The first Sudanese civil war between the Arab-Muslim north and the southern provinces was already underway.","1994":"In 1994 Sudan was governed by the military-Islamist regime of Omar al-Bashir, who had seized power in a 1989 coup, with Hassan al-Turabi's National Islamic Front a dominant influence and sharia law in force. The country remained mired in its long civil war between the Khartoum government and the southern rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army.","2000":"In 2000 Sudan was a republic under President Omar al-Bashir, whose Islamist government remained at war with the southern rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army in a long-running civil war. The country had begun exporting oil in 1999, and a power struggle saw al-Bashir sideline Islamist leader Hassan al-Turabi that year.","2010":"In 2010 Sudan was a republic governed by President Omar al-Bashir, who won the country's first multiparty elections in over two decades in April 2010, though the polls were marred by opposition boycotts and irregularities. Under the 2005 Comprehensive Peace Agreement that had ended the north-south civil war, the south retained autonomy and was preparing for a January 2011 independence referendum, while the Darfur conflict continued and al-Bashir was under an International Criminal Court arrest warrant.","2026":"Sudan is engulfed in a devastating civil war that erupted in April 2023 between the Sudanese Armed Forces under Abdel Fattah al-Burhan and the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces led by Hemedti. By 2026 the conflict has caused one of the world's largest displacement and hunger crises, with the country effectively partitioned between the rival forces."},
  "sultinate of zanzibar": {"1900":"By 1900 the Sultanate of Zanzibar was a British protectorate, established formally in 1890, with the sultan reigning under British oversight. Its mainland coastal strip had largely passed to British and German control, and the long-distance ivory and clove trades centered on the islands continued under this diminished sovereignty."},
  "suriname": {"1920":"In 1920 Suriname was a colony of the Netherlands on the northeastern coast of South America, known as Dutch Guiana. Its plantation economy relied heavily on indentured laborers brought from British India and the Dutch East Indies after the abolition of slavery, and bauxite mining was emerging as an important industry.","1938":"Suriname in 1938 was a colony of the Netherlands, known as Dutch Guiana, on the northern coast of South America. Its economy rested on plantation agriculture and the growing bauxite mining industry, with the territory administered by a Dutch-appointed governor.","1960":"In 1960 Suriname was an autonomous constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, having attained internal self-government under the 1954 Charter for the Kingdom. The Netherlands retained responsibility for defense and foreign affairs, and Suriname would not become fully independent until 1975.","1994":"In 1994 Suriname was a republic that had returned to elected civilian government, with Ronald Venetiaan as president following 1991 elections after years of military dominance under Dési Bouterse. The country was recovering from the Surinamese Interior War, an insurgency that had largely wound down with peace accords in the early 1990s.","2000":"In 2000 Suriname was an independent republic; elections that year brought Ronald Venetiaan back to the presidency, replacing Jules Wijdenbosch amid economic difficulties and high inflation. It remained a multiparty democracy on the northern coast of South America.","2010":"Suriname was an independent republic on the northeastern coast of South America in 2010. In the May 2010 elections, Désiré Bouterse — a former military ruler — was elected president by the National Assembly, returning him to power decades after his earlier coup-era rule.","2026":"Suriname is a republic on the northern coast of South America. It holds the prospect of significant offshore oil wealth following major discoveries, with development of these fields advancing in the mid-2020s."},
  "swaziland": {"1920":"In 1920 Swaziland was a British protectorate (a High Commission Territory) in southern Africa, ruled internally by its own monarchy while under overall British authority. The Swazi kingship was held during the long regency for the young king Sobhuza II, and the territory's economy and land were heavily affected by earlier European concessions.","1938":"Swaziland in 1938 was a British High Commission Territory in southern Africa, administered separately from the Union of South Africa under a British resident commissioner. The Swazi monarchy continued to exist under indirect colonial rule."},
  "sweden": {"1920":"In 1920 Sweden was a constitutional monarchy under King Gustaf V, having remained neutral during the First World War. The country joined the League of Nations in 1920, and the year saw Hjalmar Branting form a Social Democratic government. Universal and equal suffrage reforms, including votes for women, were being enacted in this period.","1938":"Sweden in 1938 was a constitutional monarchy under King Gustaf V, governed by a Social Democratic administration led by Prime Minister Per Albin Hansson. The country maintained its long-standing policy of neutrality as tensions rose across Europe, and the Saltsjöbaden Agreement of 1938 between unions and employers helped cement its model of labor peace.","1960":"In 1960 Sweden was a constitutional monarchy under King Gustaf VI Adolf, governed by a Social Democratic government led by Prime Minister Tage Erlander. The country maintained its policy of neutrality and non-alignment outside NATO, and in 1960 it became a founding member of the European Free Trade Association.","1994":"In 1994 Sweden was a parliamentary constitutional monarchy with King Carl XVI Gustaf as head of state. In the September 1994 election the Social Democrats returned to power under Ingvar Carlsson, and in a November referendum Swedish voters approved joining the European Union, which it did at the start of 1995.","2000":"In 2000 Sweden was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy with King Carl XVI Gustaf as head of state and Göran Persson as Social Democratic prime minister. A member of the European Union since 1995, it had not adopted the euro, and the Öresund Bridge linking Sweden to Denmark opened that year.","2010":"Sweden in 2010 was a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary democracy and a member of the European Union, with King Carl XVI Gustaf as head of state. In the September 2010 general election, the center-right Alliance led by Prime Minister Fredrik Reinfeldt won re-election, and the far-right Sweden Democrats entered the Riksdag for the first time.","2026":"Sweden is a parliamentary constitutional monarchy under King Carl XVI Gustaf, governed by a center-right coalition led by prime minister Ulf Kristersson with support from the Sweden Democrats. It became a full member of NATO in March 2024, ending its long tradition of military non-alignment, and remains in the EU but outside the eurozone."},
  "sweden–norway": {"1900":"In 1900 Sweden and Norway were joined in a personal union under King Oscar II, sharing a common monarch and foreign policy while each retained its own parliament and internal government. Tensions over Norwegian demands for a separate consular service were mounting, friction that would culminate in the union's peaceful dissolution in 1905."},
  "switzerland": {"1900":"Switzerland in 1900 was a federal republic governed under its 1874 constitution, a neutral state with a collective executive in the Federal Council. It maintained its long-standing policy of armed neutrality and direct democracy, with referendums a regular feature of national politics.","1920":"In 1920 Switzerland was a federal republic that had maintained its neutrality through the First World War. It joined the League of Nations in 1920 after a national referendum approved membership, and Geneva became the seat of the League's headquarters. The country had experienced significant social tension, including the 1918 general strike, in the preceding years.","1960":"In 1960 Switzerland was a federal republic with its long-standing policy of armed neutrality, governed by the collegial Federal Council under the magic-formula multiparty arrangement. It remained outside both NATO and the United Nations, and in 1960 it was a founding member of the European Free Trade Association. Women did not yet have the right to vote in federal elections.","1994":"In 1994 Switzerland was a federal republic with a system of direct democracy and its long-standing policy of neutrality, governed by a collegial Federal Council. It remained outside the European Union after voters had rejected joining the European Economic Area in a December 1992 referendum.","2000":"In 2000 Switzerland was a federal republic and direct democracy outside the European Union, governed by its multiparty Federal Council. That year Swiss voters approved a package of bilateral agreements with the EU in a referendum, deepening cooperation while preserving formal independence.","2010":"Switzerland was a federal republic and direct democracy in central Europe in 2010, made up of 26 cantons and not a member of the EU. It maintained its long-standing neutrality, and executive power rested in the collegial seven-member Federal Council with a rotating annual presidency.","2026":"Switzerland is a federal republic and direct democracy governed by a seven-member Federal Council, maintaining its long-standing policy of neutrality. It is not a member of the EU but is deeply integrated through bilateral agreements, and it remains a major global financial center."},
  "syria": {"1960":"In 1960 Syria was not an independent state but a part of the United Arab Republic, the union with Egypt formed in February 1958 under President Gamal Abdel Nasser, in which it constituted the Northern Region. Centralized rule from Cairo and Nasserist policies generated growing discontent among Syrian officers and politicians, which would lead to Syria's secession from the union in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Syria was a one-party authoritarian state ruled by President Hafez al-Assad and his Baath Party, with the al-Assad regime firmly in control. Syria was engaged in U.S.-brokered peace negotiations with Israel centered on the return of the Golan Heights, and in early 1994 Assad's son and heir-apparent Basil al-Assad died in a car crash.","2000":"In 2000 Syria was a republic under Ba'ath Party rule; long-time president Hafez al-Assad died in June, and his son Bashar al-Assad succeeded him after a constitutional amendment and a confirming referendum. Bashar's early tenure briefly raised hopes of reform in the period known as the Damascus Spring.","2010":"In 2010 Syria was a republic under the authoritarian rule of President Bashar al-Assad and the Baath Party, which had governed since 1963. The country was relatively stable that year, before the popular uprising that began in 2011; it remained internationally isolated by the United States over issues including its role in Lebanon and ties to Iran.","2026":"Syria's long-ruling Assad regime collapsed in December 2024 when opposition forces led by Hayat Tahrir al-Sham swept into Damascus and Bashar al-Assad fled to Russia. By 2026 a transitional government headed by Ahmed al-Sharaa is attempting to rebuild and unify the country amid sectarian tensions, sporadic violence, and the legacy of more than a decade of civil war."},
  "syria (france)": {"1920":"In 1920 Syria was the object of competing claims: an Arab Kingdom of Syria under Faisal was proclaimed in Damascus in March 1920, but the San Remo conference assigned the territory to France as a League of Nations mandate. In July 1920 French forces defeated Faisal's army at the Battle of Maysalun and occupied Damascus, ending the short-lived Arab kingdom and establishing French mandatory control.","1938":"Syria in 1938 was under French rule as a League of Nations mandate, administered by France since the post-World War I partition of the Ottoman Empire. A Franco-Syrian treaty promising eventual independence had been negotiated in 1936 but was never ratified by the French parliament, leaving the mandate in place. In 1938–39 France ceded the Sanjak of Alexandretta to Turkey, where it became the Hatay State, angering Syrian nationalists."},
  "são tomé and principe": {"1960":"In 1960 São Tomé and Príncipe was a Portuguese overseas province (colony) in the Gulf of Guinea, administered as part of Portugal's empire under the Estado Novo regime of António de Oliveira Salazar. Its economy was based on plantation agriculture, especially cocoa, worked largely by contract laborers brought from other Portuguese African territories.","1994":"In 1994 São Tomé and Príncipe was a small island republic in the Gulf of Guinea that had become a multiparty democracy after constitutional reforms in 1990. Its cocoa-dependent economy was weak, and Príncipe gained autonomous status within the country in 1995.","2000":"In 2000 São Tomé and Príncipe was a small island republic in the Gulf of Guinea, a multiparty democracy with Miguel Trovoada as president. The country anticipated potential offshore oil wealth and was negotiating a joint development zone with Nigeria.","2010":"São Tomé and Príncipe was an independent island republic in the Gulf of Guinea off the west coast of Africa in 2010. Fradique de Menezes was president, and the country held parliamentary elections in August 2010; its economy was small and based largely on cocoa, with prospects of offshore oil.","2026":"São Tomé and Príncipe is a small island republic in the Gulf of Guinea off the coast of Central Africa. It is a multiparty democracy with an economy based on agriculture, especially cocoa, and tourism, and holds hopes for potential offshore oil revenues."},
  "taiwan": {"1960":"In 1960 Taiwan was the seat of the Republic of China government under President Chiang Kai-shek and the ruling Kuomintang, which had relocated there after losing the mainland to the Communists in 1949 and which still claimed to be the legitimate government of all China. The island remained under martial law and one-party rule, held the China seat at the United Nations, and was closely allied with the United States. Tensions with the People's Republic across the Taiwan Strait persisted following the 1958 crisis over Quemoy and Matsu.","1994":"In 1994 Taiwan, officially the Republic of China, was governed from Taipei by the Kuomintang under President Lee Teng-hui amid an ongoing process of democratization. That year brought further reforms, including legislation paving the way for the first direct popular election of the president, held in 1996, even as the ROC continued to assert it was the legitimate government of China.","2000":"In 2000 Taiwan, officially the Republic of China, was a democratic state governing Taiwan and surrounding islands. That year's presidential election brought Chen Shui-bian of the Democratic Progressive Party to power, ending the Kuomintang's decades of rule, amid continued tension with the People's Republic of China over the island's status.","2010":"In 2010 Taiwan (the Republic of China) was a democratic state governing Taiwan and several smaller islands, with Ma Ying-jeou of the Kuomintang as president. Ma pursued warmer relations with mainland China, and in June 2010 Taiwan and the People's Republic of China signed the Economic Cooperation Framework Agreement (ECFA) to liberalize cross-strait trade, even as Beijing continued to claim Taiwan as part of its territory.","2026":"In 2026 Taiwan (the Republic of China) is a self-governing democracy that the People's Republic of China claims as its territory, a status that remains the central flashpoint in cross-strait and US-China relations. Lai Ching-te of the Democratic Progressive Party serves as president, having taken office in May 2024, while the opposition Kuomintang and Taiwan People's Party hold sway in the legislature, producing frequent political gridlock. The island faces sustained Chinese military pressure including near-daily air and naval incursions."},
  "tajikistan": {"1994":"In 1994 Tajikistan was a newly independent former Soviet republic in Central Asia, in the midst of a devastating civil war that had erupted in 1992 between the government and an opposition coalition of Islamist and democratic forces. Emomali Rahmon led the government, and Russian border troops and CIS peacekeepers were deployed to stabilize the country. A new constitution was adopted by referendum in November 1994, and Rahmon was elected president that same month.","2000":"In 2000 Tajikistan was an independent former Soviet republic in Central Asia, led by President Emomali Rahmon (then styled Rahmonov), who had held power since 1992. The country was emerging from its 1992-1997 civil war, with a 1997 peace accord between the government and the United Tajik Opposition still being implemented amid lingering instability.","2010":"In 2010 Tajikistan was an independent former Soviet republic in Central Asia, led by President Emomali Rahmon, who had held power since the 1990s. The year saw renewed security trouble, including a deadly ambush of government troops in the Rasht Valley and a prison break in Dushanbe, reflecting lingering instability from the country's 1990s civil war.","2026":"Tajikistan in 2026 is a Central Asian republic ruled by President Emomali Rahmon, who has held power since 1992 and governs as an authoritarian leader with his family entrenched in key positions. His son Rustam Emomali, head of the upper house of parliament and mayor of Dushanbe, is widely regarded as the heir apparent. The country remains one of the poorest in the region, heavily dependent on remittances from labor migrants in Russia."},
  "tanzania": {"1960":"The state of Tanzania did not yet exist in 1960. The mainland was the United Nations trust territory of Tanganyika, administered by Britain and moving toward self-government in 1960 under Julius Nyerere's TANU before its independence in 1961, while Zanzibar remained a separate British protectorate; the two would unite to form Tanzania only in 1964.","1994":"In 1994 Tanzania was an independent republic in East Africa, a union of mainland Tanganyika and the islands of Zanzibar, with Ali Hassan Mwinyi as president. The country was moving toward multiparty politics after decades of single-party rule under Chama Cha Mapinduzi. Tanzania also received large numbers of refugees fleeing the Rwandan genocide and regional conflict in 1994.","2000":"In 2000 Tanzania was an independent East African republic, a union of mainland Tanganyika and the islands of Zanzibar. Multiparty general elections held in October 2000 returned the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi party to power, with Benjamin Mkapa elected to a second term as president, while the disputed Zanzibar elections triggered violence and opposition protests.","2010":"In 2010 Tanzania was an independent East African republic, a union of mainland Tanganyika and the semi-autonomous archipelago of Zanzibar. It held general elections in October 2010 in which President Jakaya Kikwete of the long-dominant CCM party was reelected to a second term.","2026":"Tanzania in 2026 is a republic on the East African coast governed by the long-dominant Chama Cha Mapinduzi party. Samia Suluhu Hassan, who became the country's first female president in 2021, won a full term in the October 2025 election; that contest was marred by the exclusion of the main opposition party CHADEMA and by deadly post-election unrest and a crackdown. The country includes the semi-autonomous archipelago of Zanzibar."},
  "tanzania, united republic of": {"1920":"In 1920 the mainland territory later forming part of Tanzania was Tanganyika, the former German East Africa, which Britain had occupied during the First World War and held under a League of Nations mandate confirmed in 1920. The offshore Sultanate of Zanzibar was a separate British protectorate. The two would not unite into Tanzania until 1964.","1938":"The territory of modern mainland Tanzania in 1938 was Tanganyika, a British-administered League of Nations mandate that had been taken from Germany after World War I. The islands of Zanzibar were a separate British protectorate under a sultan. The unified state of Tanzania did not yet exist."},
  "thailand": {"1960":"In 1960 Thailand was a constitutional monarchy under King Bhumibol Adulyadej, with effective power held by the military government of Field Marshal Sarit Thanarat, who had seized power in coups in 1957 and 1958. Sarit ruled by decree under martial law, pursued anti-communist and development-oriented policies, and aligned Thailand closely with the United States.","1994":"In 1994 Thailand was a constitutional monarchy under King Bhumibol Adulyadej, with a civilian government led by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, who had taken office after the 1992 pro-democracy demonstrations and the fall of military rule. The country was experiencing rapid, export-driven economic growth during its boom years before the 1997 financial crisis.","2000":"In 2000 Thailand was a constitutional monarchy under King Bhumibol Adulyadej, recovering from the 1997 Asian financial crisis that had begun with the collapse of the Thai baht. Chuan Leekpai's Democrat-led government was in office, and the country held its first elections for an appointed-then-elected Senate under the 1997 constitution.","2010":"In 2010 Thailand was a constitutional monarchy under King Bhumibol Adulyadej with Abhisit Vejjajiva of the Democrat Party as prime minister. The year was marked by mass anti-government protests by the Red Shirts in Bangkok that culminated in a violent military crackdown in May 2010 leaving scores dead.","2026":"Thailand in 2026 is a constitutional monarchy under King Maha Vajiralongkorn with a turbulent civilian government. Prime Minister Paetongtarn Shinawatra was removed by the Constitutional Court in 2025 over a leaked phone call, and the premiership passed amid coalition instability, with Anutin Charnvirakul among those forming a government. A border conflict with Cambodia flared into deadly clashes in 2025."},
  "tibet": {"1920":"Tibet in 1920 was a de facto independent state under the 13th Dalai Lama, who had returned from exile in 1913 and declared Tibet's independence after the fall of the Qing dynasty. Lhasa governed its own affairs free of effective Chinese control, though its independence was never internationally recognized, and the Dalai Lama was pursuing modernizing military and administrative reforms during this period.","1938":"Tibet in 1938 functioned as a de facto independent state under a Buddhist theocratic government in Lhasa, though China continued to claim sovereignty over it. The 14th Dalai Lama had been identified in 1937 but was still a young child, so authority was exercised by a regent. The country remained largely isolated from the outside world."},
  "timor-leste": {"2026":"Timor-Leste (East Timor) in 2026 is a Southeast Asian democratic republic that gained full independence in 2002. Veteran independence figure Xanana Gusmão serves as prime minister, while José Ramos-Horta is president. A major development is the country's accession to ASEAN, having been formally admitted as the bloc's eleventh member in 2025."},
  "togo": {"1938":"Togo in 1938 was divided into two League of Nations mandates carved from the former German colony of Togoland: British Togoland, administered with the neighbouring Gold Coast, and French Togoland, administered by France. Neither was an independent state.","1960":"Togo gained independence from French trusteeship on 27 April 1960, becoming the Republic of Togo. Its first head of government and then president was Sylvanus Olympio, who led the country into independence and would be elected president in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Togo was a republic in West Africa under President Gnassingbé Eyadéma, who had ruled since 1967, amid a difficult and contested transition toward multiparty democracy. Legislative elections held in early 1994 were marked by disputes and opposition tensions following years of political crisis.","2000":"In 2000 Togo was a West African republic ruled by President Gnassingbé Eyadéma, who had held power since a 1967 coup and was the longest-serving head of state in Africa. His rule continued amid international criticism over disputed elections and human-rights concerns.","2010":"In 2010 Togo was an independent West African republic governed by President Faure Gnassingbé, who won a presidential election in March 2010, extending the rule of the Gnassingbé family that had held power since 1967.","2026":"Togo in 2026 is a West African republic long dominated by the Gnassingbé family, which has ruled since 1967. Faure Gnassingbé, in power since 2005, consolidated his position through a 2024 constitutional change that shifted Togo to a parliamentary system; he assumed the newly powerful role of President of the Council of Ministers in 2025, a move critics call a means to extend his rule indefinitely."},
  "tonga": {"1920":"Tonga in 1920 was a Polynesian kingdom under a British protectorate established by treaty in 1900, retaining its own monarchy while Britain handled its foreign affairs. Queen Salote Tupou III, who had acceded in 1918, was the reigning sovereign.","1938":"Tonga in 1938 was a Polynesian kingdom under a British protectorate, with Queen Salote Tupou III reigning over its internal affairs while Britain controlled its external relations. The protectorate arrangement, established by treaty in 1900, left the monarchy in place.","1960":"In 1960 Tonga was a kingdom under Queen Salote Tupou III but remained a British-protected state under a treaty of protection, with Britain handling its foreign affairs through a British Agent and Consul. It retained its own monarchy and substantial internal autonomy, and did not become fully independent until 1970.","1994":"In 1994 Tonga was an independent constitutional monarchy in the South Pacific under King Tāufaʻāhau Tupou IV, with a political system dominated by the king and hereditary nobles. A pro-democracy movement seeking greater commoner representation was active during this period.","2000":"In 2000 Tonga was an independent Polynesian constitutional monarchy in the South Pacific, ruled by King Taufaʻahau Tupou IV. The political system remained dominated by the monarch and nobility, with only a minority of parliamentary seats elected by commoners.","2010":"In 2010 Tonga was an independent Polynesian kingdom in the South Pacific. It undertook a major democratic reform that year, holding its first general election under a new constitutional arrangement in November 2010 that reduced the monarch's powers and gave commoners a majority of seats in the legislature.","2026":"Tonga in 2026 is a Polynesian constitutional monarchy in the South Pacific under King Tupou VI. The kingdom continues to recover from the devastating 2022 Hunga Tonga-Hunga Haʻapai volcanic eruption and tsunami. Its politics feature an elected parliament alongside seats reserved for nobles."},
  "transvaal": {"1900":"The Transvaal, or South African Republic, was a Boer republic led by President Paul Kruger, and in 1900 it was at war with the British Empire in the Second Boer War that had begun in October 1899. British forces captured Pretoria in June 1900 and Britain annexed the republic that year, though Boer commandos continued a guerrilla campaign until 1902."},
  "trinidad": {"1920":"Trinidad in 1920 was a British colony, administered together with Tobago as the single colony of Trinidad and Tobago since 1889 under a Crown Colony government. Its economy centered on sugar, cacao, and a growing petroleum industry.","1938":"Trinidad in 1938 was a British colony in the Caribbean, administered jointly with Tobago as Trinidad and Tobago. The colony had been shaken by major labor unrest and oilfield strikes in 1937, and in 1938 the Moyne Commission was investigating social and economic conditions across the British West Indies."},
  "trinidad and tobago": {"1960":"In 1960 Trinidad and Tobago was a British colony that had achieved internal self-government, with Eric Williams of the People's National Movement as Chief Minister (later Premier). It was at this time a member of the West Indies Federation, and would attain full independence in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Trinidad and Tobago was an independent republic in the Caribbean within the Commonwealth, with Patrick Manning of the People's National Movement as prime minister. Its economy remained heavily based on oil and natural gas.","2000":"In 2000 Trinidad and Tobago was an independent Caribbean republic. Basdeo Panday of the United National Congress was prime minister, and a closely contested general election was held in December 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Trinidad and Tobago was an independent twin-island republic in the southern Caribbean and a Commonwealth member. In a snap general election in May 2010 the People's Partnership coalition won, making Kamla Persad-Bissessar the country's first female prime minister.","2026":"Trinidad and Tobago in 2026 is a twin-island republic in the southern Caribbean and a parliamentary democracy. Following the 2025 general election, Kamla Persad-Bissessar of the United National Congress returned as prime minister. Its economy is heavily based on oil and natural gas."},
  "trucial oman": {"1900":"Trucial Oman, the sheikhdoms along the southern Persian Gulf coast, was a collection of Arab emirates bound to Britain by a series of maritime truces and protective treaties. By 1900, following the Exclusive Agreement of 1892, the sheikhs had ceded control of their foreign relations to Britain, placing the coast within the British sphere of influence.","1920":"The Trucial States along the southeastern Persian Gulf coast were a group of sheikhdoms in special treaty relations with Britain, which controlled their external affairs and defense while leaving internal rule to the local rulers. In 1920 these emirates remained poor, pearl-diving and trading societies under British maritime protection.","1938":"Trucial Oman in 1938 referred to the Trucial States, a group of sheikhdoms along the southeastern Persian Gulf coast bound to Britain by a series of truces and protection treaties. Britain controlled their external relations and defence while local sheikhs governed internally; these states later formed the United Arab Emirates."},
  "tunisia": {"1900":"In 1900 Tunisia was a French protectorate, established by the 1881 Treaty of Bardo and the 1883 Convention of La Marsa, while remaining nominally ruled by the Bey of Tunis from the Husainid dynasty. A French resident-general held effective authority over the country's administration and foreign affairs.","1920":"Tunisia in 1920 was a French protectorate, nominally ruled by the Husainid Bey but effectively governed by a French Resident-General. The period saw the rise of nationalist agitation, with the Destour party emerging in 1920 to demand a constitution and greater Tunisian participation in government.","1938":"Tunisia was a French protectorate, governed under the nominal sovereignty of the Bey of Tunis (Ahmad II until 1942) but effectively controlled by a French Resident-General. In 1938 nationalist agitation by the Neo Destour party led by Habib Bourguiba intensified, and demonstrations in Tunis in April were suppressed by French authorities, who declared a state of emergency and arrested Bourguiba and other leaders.","1960":"Tunisia had become independent from France in 1956 and was proclaimed a republic in 1957 under President Habib Bourguiba, leader of the Neo-Destour party. By 1960 Bourguiba headed a one-party state pursuing modernizing and secularizing reforms, while a French military presence remained at the naval base of Bizerte, a point of tension that would erupt in 1961.","1994":"In 1994 Tunisia was a republic in North Africa under President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, who had taken power in 1987; he was reelected in 1994 elections in which his ruling party dominated. The government maintained tight control over political life and suppressed Islamist opposition.","2000":"In 2000 Tunisia was a North African republic under President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, who had ruled since taking power from Habib Bourguiba in 1987. The state was authoritarian and dominated by Ben Ali's ruling party, and the former president Bourguiba died in 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Tunisia was a republic ruled by President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, in power since 1987. In December 2010 the self-immolation of street vendor Mohamed Bouazizi sparked nationwide protests that became the Tunisian Revolution and the start of the Arab Spring.","2026":"Tunisia in 2026 is a North African republic under President Kais Saied, who won re-election in 2024 after years of consolidating power following his 2021 suspension of parliament. His tenure has been marked by rule largely by decree, the prosecution and imprisonment of opposition figures and critics, and the erosion of the democratic institutions established after the 2011 revolution. The country continues to grapple with economic difficulties and migration pressures."},
  "turkey": {"1938":"Turkey was a republic led by President Mustafa Kemal Atatürk, who died on 10 November 1938 and was succeeded by İsmet İnönü. The country pursued secularizing, modernizing reforms and a policy of neutrality; in 1938 it was negotiating with France over the Sanjak of Alexandretta (Hatay), which became an autonomous state that year before later joining Turkey.","1960":"In 1960 Turkey was a republic that underwent a military coup on 27 May 1960, when officers under the National Unity Committee, headed by General Cemal Gürsel, overthrew the government of Prime Minister Adnan Menderes and the Democrat Party. Menderes and other officials were arrested and later tried, and Turkey remained a member of NATO aligned with the West in the Cold War.","1994":"In 1994 Turkey was a republic with Süleyman Demirel as president and Tansu Çiller as prime minister, the country's first woman to hold that office. The year was marked by a severe economic and currency crisis in the spring and by the continuing armed conflict with the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) in the southeast.","2000":"In 2000 Turkey was a secular parliamentary republic, with Bülent Ecevit leading a coalition government and Ahmet Necdet Sezer elected president in May 2000. The country was an EU candidate after the December 1999 Helsinki summit and was still recovering from the devastating August 1999 İzmit earthquake, while a major banking and financial crisis erupted late in 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Turkey was a republic governed by the AK Party under Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, with Abdullah Gül as president. In September 2010 a national referendum approved a package of constitutional amendments, and the year also saw the Mavi Marmara flotilla incident that severely strained relations with Israel.","2026":"Turkey in 2026 is a republic straddling Europe and Asia, governed under a strong presidential system by Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who has led the country since 2003. His government continues to face economic strain from high inflation, and the 2025 arrest of Istanbul mayor Ekrem İmamoğlu, a leading opposition figure, sparked major protests. Turkey is a NATO member playing an active role in regional conflicts."},
  "turkish cypriot-administered area": {"1994":"In 1994 the northern part of Cyprus was administered by the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, proclaimed in 1983 and recognized only by Turkey, with Rauf Denktaş as its leader. It was effectively dependent on Turkish military presence and support, while the island remained divided after the 1974 Turkish intervention.","2000":"In 2000 the northern part of Cyprus was administered by the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, recognized only by Turkey and backed by Turkish troops. Rauf Denktaş was its leader, and the island remained divided pending UN-brokered talks toward a settlement.","2010":"In 2010 the northern part of Cyprus was administered by the self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, recognized only by Turkey. Derviş Eroğlu was elected its leader in April 2010, while UN-brokered reunification talks with the Greek Cypriot south continued without resolution."},
  "turkmenistan": {"1994":"In 1994 Turkmenistan was a newly independent former Soviet republic in Central Asia ruled by President Saparmurat Niyazov, who had built a highly personalized authoritarian regime and cult of personality. The country pursued a policy of neutrality and relied heavily on its large natural gas reserves.","2000":"In 2000 Turkmenistan was an independent former Soviet republic in Central Asia ruled by President Saparmurat Niyazov, who styled himself Türkmenbaşy and built an extensive personality cult. In late 1999 parliament had declared him president for life, and the state was highly authoritarian and isolated, relying heavily on natural gas exports.","2010":"In 2010 Turkmenistan was an independent, highly authoritarian former Soviet republic in Central Asia, rich in natural gas, led by President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow, who had succeeded Saparmurat Niyazov in 2006.","2026":"Turkmenistan in 2026 is a Central Asian republic and one of the world's most closed and authoritarian states, holding vast natural gas reserves. Power rests with the Berdimuhamedow family: Serdar Berdimuhamedow serves as president while his father Gurbanguly retains broad influence as head of the upper house of parliament and 'National Leader.' The country maintains a policy of official neutrality."},
  "turks and caicos is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Turks and Caicos Islands were a British colony in the Caribbean. They were administratively linked to Jamaica, then still a British colony moving toward independence.","1994":"In 1994 the Turks and Caicos Islands were a self-governing British dependent territory in the Caribbean, with a governor appointed by the United Kingdom and a locally elected government. Tourism and offshore finance were central to the economy.","2000":"In 2000 the Turks and Caicos Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, governed under a British-appointed governor with a locally elected legislature and chief minister. They were not an independent state.","2010":"In 2010 the Turks and Caicos Islands were a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean. Following a corruption inquiry, the UK had suspended the territory's self-government in 2009 and it remained under direct British administration through a governor in 2010.","2026":"The Turks and Caicos Islands in 2026 are a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, internally self-governing with a premier and an elected House of Assembly while the United Kingdom retains responsibility for defense and external affairs through an appointed governor. The economy is dominated by tourism and offshore financial services."},
  "turks and caicos islands": {"1800":"In 1800, the Turks and Caicos Islands were a small British-controlled Caribbean group administered as a dependency of the Bahamas following their formal annexation the previous year in 1799. Their economy rested chiefly on salt raking, worked largely by Bermudians on Grand Turk and the surrounding salt cays, supplemented by the recently established but fragile Loyalist cotton plantations on the Caicos. Political authority was exercised from Nassau rather than locally, and the islands possessed no separate legislature or governor of their own. Cockburn Town on Grand Turk served as the principal settlement and seat of local affairs, a role it had held since 1766. Lingering friction persisted between the independent-minded salt rakers and the Bahamian government over licensing and taxation of the lucrative salt exports.","1938":"The Turks and Caicos Islands were a British colony, administered as a dependency of Jamaica."},
  "tuvalu": {"1960":"In 1960 the islands later known as Tuvalu formed part of the British-administered Gilbert and Ellice Islands Colony, the Ellice Islands group. They were not a separate sovereign state and would not become independent until 1978.","1994":"In 1994 Tuvalu was an independent nation of low-lying Pacific atolls and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state represented by a governor-general. It was one of the world's smallest and least populous independent states.","2000":"In 2000 Tuvalu was an independent Polynesian state in the Pacific and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. It became a full member of the United Nations in September 2000, and around this period it earned significant revenue from leasing its \".tv\" internet domain.","2010":"In 2010 Tuvalu was an independent Polynesian island nation in the Pacific and a Commonwealth realm with Queen Elizabeth II as head of state. One of the world's smallest and lowest-lying countries, it was prominent in 2010 as a vocal advocate on the threat of sea-level rise from climate change.","2026":"Tuvalu in 2026 is a small Polynesian island nation in the Pacific and a Commonwealth realm, highly vulnerable to sea-level rise that threatens its low-lying atolls. It maintains diplomatic relations with Taiwan rather than China. A notable development is its Falepili Union treaty with Australia, which provides a climate migration pathway for Tuvaluans and security cooperation."},
  "u.s. minor outlying is.": {"1960":"In 1960 these scattered Pacific and Caribbean islands and atolls were unincorporated territories of the United States. Most were uninhabited or held only small military or government installations.","1994":"In 1994 the United States Minor Outlying Islands were a group of small, mostly uninhabited insular areas in the Pacific and Caribbean under United States sovereignty, including islands such as Midway, Wake, Johnston, and Baker. They had no permanent civilian population and were administered for military, scientific, or wildlife-refuge purposes.","2000":"In 2000 the United States Minor Outlying Islands were a group of small, mostly uninhabited insular areas of the United States in the Pacific and Caribbean, including islands such as Midway, Wake, Howland, Baker, and Johnston Atoll. They were unincorporated U.S. territories with no permanent civilian population and no independent government.","2010":"In 2010 the United States Minor Outlying Islands were a group of small, mostly uninhabited insular areas of the United States scattered across the Pacific and Caribbean, including Wake Island, Midway, Baker, Howland, Jarvis, Johnston and Palmyra atolls, and Navassa Island. They had no permanent civilian population and were administered by various U.S. federal agencies.","2026":"The United States Minor Outlying Islands in 2026 are a statistical grouping of unincorporated, mostly uninhabited US island territories in the Pacific and Caribbean, including Wake Island, Midway Atoll, Howland, Baker, Jarvis, Johnston Atoll, Kingman Reef, Palmyra Atoll, and Navassa Island. They have no permanent civilian population and are administered by the US federal government, with several managed as national wildlife refuges or used for military purposes."},
  "u.s. virgin is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the U.S. Virgin Islands were an unincorporated territory of the United States, purchased from Denmark in 1917. The territory was administered under the Revised Organic Act of 1954, with an appointed governor and an elected legislature.","1994":"In 1994 the United States Virgin Islands were an unincorporated U.S. territory in the Caribbean whose residents were U.S. citizens, with a locally elected governor and legislature. The territory's economy depended heavily on tourism and oil refining.","2000":"In 2000 the U.S. Virgin Islands were an unincorporated territory of the United States in the Caribbean, with residents holding U.S. citizenship but no vote in presidential elections. The territory was governed by a locally elected governor and legislature, with Charles Turnbull serving as governor.","2010":"In 2010 the United States Virgin Islands were an unincorporated, organized U.S. territory in the Caribbean whose residents are U.S. citizens. Its economy depended heavily on tourism and on the large Hovensa oil refinery on St. Croix, and John de Jongh served as the elected territorial governor.","2026":"In 2026 the U.S. Virgin Islands is an unincorporated and organized territory of the United States in the Caribbean, comprising St. Croix, St. Thomas, St. John and surrounding islands. Its residents are U.S. citizens but cannot vote in presidential elections and have only a non-voting delegate in Congress, and the territory is governed by a locally elected governor and legislature."},
  "uganda": {"1920":"Uganda in 1920 was a British protectorate in East Africa, administered through indirect rule that preserved the Kingdom of Buganda and other traditional kingdoms under British oversight. Its economy was increasingly built on cotton grown by African smallholders for export.","1938":"Uganda was a British protectorate in East Africa, administered through a system of indirect rule that retained the Kingdom of Buganda and other traditional kingdoms under British oversight. Its economy depended heavily on cotton and coffee cash crops grown by African farmers.","1960":"In 1960 Uganda was a British protectorate in East Africa, still under colonial administration and moving toward self-government. It would hold pre-independence elections and gain independence in 1962.","1994":"In 1994 Uganda was a sovereign republic led by President Yoweri Museveni, whose National Resistance Movement governed under a 'no-party' or 'movement' political system. A Constituent Assembly was elected in 1994 to debate and draft a new constitution, and Uganda hosted large numbers of refugees as the genocide unfolded in neighboring Rwanda.","2000":"In 2000, Uganda was a republic led by President Yoweri Museveni, who had held power since 1986 under a \"no-party\" Movement system that restricted multiparty politics. A referendum held in 2000 endorsed continuation of the Movement system over a return to multiparty competition. Uganda was also involved militarily in the ongoing conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.","2010":"In 2010 Uganda was a republic led by President Yoweri Museveni, who had held power since 1986 and was preparing for the 2011 elections. In July 2010 the country suffered twin bombings in Kampala during the FIFA World Cup final broadcast, claimed by the Somali militant group al-Shabaab in retaliation for Uganda's troop contribution to the African Union mission in Somalia.","2026":"In 2026 Uganda is a republic in East Africa led by President Yoweri Museveni, who has held power since 1986 and won another term in the January 2026 general election amid opposition complaints of repression. The opposition was again led by Bobi Wine (Robert Kyagulanyi) of the National Unity Platform."},
  "ukraine": {"1920":"Ukraine in 1920 was a contested and fragmented land fought over during the Russian Civil War and the Polish-Soviet War. By the end of the year Bolshevik forces had largely defeated rival Ukrainian governments and established Soviet control, leading to the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic, while western Ukrainian regions came under Polish control.","1994":"In 1994 Ukraine was an independent state, having become so with the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991. Leonid Kuchma won the presidency in 1994, defeating incumbent Leonid Kravchuk, and in December 1994 Ukraine signed the Budapest Memorandum, agreeing to give up the nuclear weapons left on its territory in exchange for security assurances.","2000":"In 2000, Ukraine was an independent republic, having gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, with Leonid Kuchma as president. The country was grappling with economic difficulties and corruption, and late 2000 saw the eruption of the Gongadze scandal after the disappearance and murder of journalist Georgiy Gongadze. In December 2000 the Chernobyl nuclear plant was permanently shut down.","2010":"In 2010 Ukraine was an independent republic where Viktor Yanukovych won the presidential election, defeating Yulia Tymoshenko and succeeding Viktor Yushchenko. That year his government signed the Kharkiv Pact with Russia, extending the lease on the Russian Black Sea Fleet's base in Sevastopol in exchange for discounted natural gas.","2026":"In 2026 Ukraine remains a sovereign republic at war with Russia, which launched its full-scale invasion in February 2022 and continues to occupy parts of the east and south, including Crimea. Led by President Volodymyr Zelenskyy, the country depends heavily on Western military and financial support while seeking a negotiated end to the conflict."},
  "union of south africa": {"1920":"The Union of South Africa in 1920 was a self-governing dominion of the British Empire, formed in 1910 from the Cape, Natal, Transvaal, and Orange Free State colonies, with Jan Smuts as prime minister. It had recently received a League of Nations mandate over the former German South West Africa, which it administered as effectively part of its own territory.","1938":"The Union of South Africa was a self-governing British dominion under Prime Minister J.B.M. Hertzog, leading the United Party formed by his 1934 fusion with Jan Smuts. In 1938 the centenary of the Great Trek was commemorated with a symbolic ox-wagon trek, which stirred Afrikaner nationalism, while segregationist policies governed the African majority."},
  "united arab emirates": {"1960":"In 1960 there was no United Arab Emirates; the territory consisted of the Trucial States, a group of sheikhdoms on the Persian Gulf under British protection. They would federate to form the UAE only in 1971.","1994":"In 1994 the United Arab Emirates was a federation of seven emirates on the Arabian Peninsula, with Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan of Abu Dhabi serving as president. It was a wealthy, oil-exporting state and a member of the Gulf Cooperation Council.","2000":"In 2000, the United Arab Emirates was a federation of seven emirates led by President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the ruler of Abu Dhabi, who had presided over the union since its 1971 founding. The country was a wealthy oil exporter and OPEC member with rapidly developing cities, especially Dubai and Abu Dhabi.","2010":"In 2010 the United Arab Emirates was a federation of seven emirates led by President Khalifa bin Zayed Al Nahyan of Abu Dhabi, with Dubai as its commercial hub. In January 2010 the Burj Khalifa, the world's tallest building, opened in Dubai, having been renamed in honor of the Abu Dhabi ruler after Dubai required financial support following its 2009 debt crisis.","2026":"In 2026 the United Arab Emirates is a federation of seven emirates on the Arabian Peninsula, with Abu Dhabi as capital and Dubai its largest commercial city. It is ruled by President Mohamed bin Zayed Al Nahyan, and its wealthy, oil- and trade-based economy continues to diversify into finance, tourism, logistics and technology."},
  "united kingdom": {"1938":"The United Kingdom was a constitutional monarchy under King George VI with Neville Chamberlain as Prime Minister. In 1938 Chamberlain pursued appeasement of Nazi Germany, signing the Munich Agreement in September that ceded the Sudetenland of Czechoslovakia and which he proclaimed had secured \"peace for our time.\"","1960":"In 1960 the United Kingdom was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Elizabeth II with Harold Macmillan as Conservative prime minister. It was decolonizing rapidly; in February 1960 Macmillan delivered his \"Wind of Change\" speech in South Africa acknowledging African nationalism, and conscription (National Service) was being phased out.","1994":"In 1994 the United Kingdom was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Elizabeth II, governed by the Conservative Party under Prime Minister John Major. That year the Channel Tunnel linking Britain and France opened, and the Provisional IRA declared a ceasefire in Northern Ireland in August 1994.","2000":"In 2000, the United Kingdom was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Elizabeth II with a Labour government led by Prime Minister Tony Blair, who had won a landslide in 1997. Devolved institutions in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland had recently been established, with the Northern Ireland Assembly operating under the 1998 Good Friday Agreement. London marked the millennium with projects such as the Millennium Dome and the London Eye.","2010":"In 2010 the United Kingdom was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Elizabeth II. The May 2010 general election produced a hung parliament, leading to a coalition government between the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats with David Cameron as Prime Minister and Nick Clegg as Deputy Prime Minister, which began implementing austerity measures in response to the financial crisis.","2026":"In 2026 the United Kingdom is a constitutional monarchy under King Charles III, governed by a Labour government led by Prime Minister Keir Starmer, who took office after Labour's landslide victory in the July 2024 general election. The country continues to navigate the economic and political aftermath of Brexit."},
  "united kingdom of great britain and ireland": {"1900":"In 1900 the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland was a constitutional monarchy under Queen Victoria, at the head of the world's largest empire. The country was engaged in the Second Boer War in South Africa, and the Conservative government under Lord Salisbury won the 1900 'Khaki Election' fought largely on the war.","1920":"In 1920 the United Kingdom still formally encompassed all of Ireland, but the Irish War of Independence was underway between the Irish Republican Army and British forces. The Government of Ireland Act 1920 was passed that year to partition Ireland into Northern and Southern home-rule entities, and Britain was governed by David Lloyd George's coalition while administering a vast empire enlarged by new League of Nations mandates."},
  "united states": {"1920":"The United States in 1920 was a republic under President Woodrow Wilson, though the Senate had rejected the Treaty of Versailles and membership in the League of Nations. That year saw the ratification of the Nineteenth Amendment granting women the vote, the start of nationwide Prohibition, the postwar Red Scare, and the election of Warren G. Harding.","1938":"The United States was a federal republic under President Franklin D. Roosevelt, still recovering from the Great Depression amid a sharp 1937–38 recession. In 1938 Congress passed the Fair Labor Standards Act, establishing a federal minimum wage and maximum hours, while the country maintained official neutrality toward the rising tensions in Europe and Asia."},
  "united states of america": {"1800":"In 1800, the United States was a young federal republic of sixteen states led by Federalist president John Adams, whose single term was drawing to a close. The seat of government moved that year from Philadelphia to the newly built federal city of Washington in the District of Columbia, where Congress first convened in November and Adams took up residence in the still-unfinished President's House. In the bitterly contested presidential election of 1800, Adams was defeated by the Democratic-Republican ticket, but because electors did not yet vote separately for president and vice president, Jefferson and his running mate Aaron Burr finished in an electoral tie. The House of Representatives resolved the deadlock in Jefferson's favor on the thirty-sixth ballot in February 1801, and the nation's settled lands reached westward to the Mississippi River with vast territory beyond still held by Native nations, Spain, and France. The 1800 census counted a population of about 5.3 million, including roughly 893,000 enslaved people concentrated in the Southern states.","1900":"In 1900 the United States was a federal republic with William McKinley as president, having just defeated Spain in the 1898 Spanish-American War. The country had emerged as a rising power, annexing Hawaii in 1898 and acquiring Puerto Rico, Guam, and the Philippines, where it was fighting the Philippine-American War. It was experiencing rapid industrialization, immigration, and westward settlement.","1960":"In 1960 the United States was a federal republic led by President Dwight D. Eisenhower in his final year in office, with the Cold War and space race shaping its policy. The 1960 presidential election, featuring the first televised debates, was won by John F. Kennedy over Richard Nixon that November.","1994":"In 1994 the United States was a federal republic with Bill Clinton as president. The November 1994 midterm elections produced a Republican takeover of both houses of Congress (the 'Republican Revolution'), and the North American Free Trade Agreement took effect on January 1, 1994.","2000":"In 2000, the United States was a federal republic in the final year of Bill Clinton's presidency, enjoying a strong economy amid the dot-com boom. The November 2000 presidential election between George W. Bush and Al Gore was extremely close and disputed, hinging on a Florida recount resolved by the Supreme Court's December decision in Bush v. Gore, which secured the presidency for Bush.","2010":"In 2010 the United States was a federal republic with Barack Obama as president and Democrats controlling Congress for most of the year. In March 2010 Obama signed the Affordable Care Act into law; the year also saw the Deepwater Horizon oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico and Republican gains in the November midterm elections that handed them control of the House.","2026":"In 2026 the United States is a federal constitutional republic with Donald Trump serving as president after his inauguration in January 2025 for a second, non-consecutive term, with JD Vance as vice president. The year also marks the 250th anniversary of the Declaration of Independence."},
  "united states virgin islands": {"1900":"In 1900 these Caribbean islands were the Danish West Indies, a colony of Denmark, not yet under United States rule. The economy had long depended on sugar plantations but was in serious decline by this period, and Denmark periodically considered selling the islands.","1920":"The Virgin Islands had been purchased by the United States from Denmark in 1917 and in 1920 were an unincorporated U.S. territory administered by the U.S. Navy. Their economy was depressed, resting on a declining sugar industry.","1938":"The Virgin Islands were a United States territory, purchased from Denmark in 1917, administered under the Department of the Interior since 1931. Their economy centered on sugar and related products."},
  "uruguay": {"1900":"In 1900 Uruguay was an independent republic governed under the constitution of 1830, with politics dominated by rivalry between the Colorado and Blanco (National) parties. The Colorados held power, and the country remained tense following decades of civil conflict; José Batlle y Ordóñez would be elected president in 1903.","1920":"Uruguay in 1920 was an independent republic that had undergone extensive social and democratic reforms associated with the influence of José Batlle y Ordóñez. Its prosperity rested on exports of beef and wool, and it operated under a constitution adopted in 1918 that introduced a plural executive.","1938":"Uruguay was a republic in South America. Its president in 1938 was Alfredo Baldomir, who took office in that year's term, following the authoritarian period associated with Gabriel Terra.","1960":"In 1960 Uruguay was a republic in South America governed by a collegial executive, the National Council of Government, rather than a single president, under a system in place since the 1952 constitution. The dominant Colorado and National (Blanco) parties contested power, with the Blancos winning the 1958 elections.","1994":"In 1994 Uruguay was a democratic republic in South America. In the November 1994 elections Julio María Sanguinetti of the Colorado Party was elected to return to the presidency, in a closely contested three-way race.","2000":"In 2000, Uruguay was a democratic republic; Jorge Batlle of the Colorado Party took office as president in March 2000. The country was a stable democracy that would soon be affected by the regional economic downturn stemming from Argentina's crisis.","2010":"In 2010 Uruguay was a democratic republic where José Mujica of the left-wing Broad Front coalition took office as president in March, succeeding fellow Broad Front leader Tabaré Vázquez. The country maintained a stable economy and remained in a long-running dispute with Argentina over a pulp mill on the shared Uruguay River, which the International Court of Justice ruled on in 2010.","2026":"In 2026 Uruguay is a stable democratic republic in South America, with Yamandú Orsi of the left-wing Broad Front having taken office as president in March 2025 after winning the 2024 election. It remains one of the region's most stable and socially liberal countries."},
  "usnb guantanamo bay": {"1960":"In 1960 the U.S. Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay was a United States military installation on Cuban territory, held under a lease dating to the early 1900s. Following the 1959 Cuban Revolution, relations between the new Cuban government under Fidel Castro and the United States were deteriorating sharply, and tension over the base grew.","1994":"In 1994 Guantanamo Bay was a United States Navy base on the southeastern coast of Cuba, held under a perpetual lease dating to 1903 and operated against the objections of the Cuban government. That year the base became a major site for housing tens of thousands of Cuban and Haitian migrants intercepted at sea, after the Clinton administration's policy shifts and the Cuban rafter crisis of August 1994 sent thousands fleeing the island.","2000":"In 2000, the United States Naval Station at Guantanamo Bay was a U.S. military base on the southeastern coast of Cuba, held under a perpetual lease dating from the early 20th century. Cuba's communist government under Fidel Castro disputed the U.S. presence and refused to cash the annual lease payments. At this time, before the post-2001 detention facility, it functioned as a naval base.","2010":"In 2010 the United States Naval Base at Guantanamo Bay was a U.S. military installation on the southeastern coast of Cuba, held under a lease dating to the early 20th century that Cuba did not recognize as legitimate. It housed the controversial detention camp holding terrorism suspects; President Barack Obama had pledged in 2009 to close the detention facility, but it remained open in 2010 amid congressional opposition.","2026":"In 2026 Guantanamo Bay is a United States naval base on the southeastern coast of Cuba, occupied by the U.S. under a long-standing lease that Cuba disputes and considers illegitimate. The base houses the military detention facility that, despite repeated pledges to close it, still held a small number of detainees in the mid-2020s."},
  "ussr": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory of the future Soviet Union was controlled by the Bolshevik government centered on the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic, with the Soviet Union itself not yet formally established until 1922. The Russian Civil War was being decided in the Bolsheviks' favor, while the Polish-Soviet War raged through much of the year.","1938":"The Union of Soviet Socialist Republics was a one-party communist state under the dictatorship of Joseph Stalin. In 1938 the Great Purge continued, with the third Moscow show trial in March condemning Nikolai Bukharin and others, while Soviet and Japanese forces clashed at Lake Khasan near the Manchurian frontier in July and August.","1960":"In 1960 the Soviet Union was a one-party communist state led by Nikita Khrushchev as First Secretary of the Communist Party. It was a Cold War superpower locked in rivalry with the United States; in May 1960 a U.S. U-2 spy plane was shot down over Soviet territory, wrecking the planned Paris summit, and the Sino-Soviet split was deepening that year."},
  "uzbekistan": {"1994":"In 1994 Uzbekistan was an independent Central Asian republic that had emerged from the Soviet Union in 1991, governed authoritatively by President Islam Karimov. Its economy remained heavily reliant on cotton production.","2000":"In 2000, Uzbekistan was an independent republic ruled by President Islam Karimov, who had governed since the Soviet era and was re-elected in a tightly controlled January 2000 vote. The authoritarian government faced an armed Islamist insurgency by the Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan, which launched incursions in the region during 2000.","2010":"In 2010 Uzbekistan was an authoritarian republic in Central Asia ruled by President Islam Karimov, who had governed since the Soviet era. That year ethnic violence erupted in neighboring Kyrgyzstan, sending many ethnic Uzbek refugees toward the Uzbek border.","2026":"In 2026 Uzbekistan is a doubly landlocked republic in Central Asia led by President Shavkat Mirziyoyev, who has pursued gradual economic and social liberalization since succeeding Islam Karimov in 2016. Tashkent is the capital and the country remains the most populous in Central Asia."},
  "vanuatu": {"1960":"In 1960 the islands later called Vanuatu formed the New Hebrides, an Anglo-French condominium jointly administered by Britain and France. It was not independent and would become Vanuatu only in 1980.","1994":"In 1994 Vanuatu was an independent island republic in the South Pacific, having gained independence from joint British-French rule in 1980. It was a member of the Commonwealth with a parliamentary system.","2000":"In 2000, Vanuatu was an independent parliamentary republic in the South Pacific, having gained independence from joint British-French (condominium) rule in 1980. Its politics in this period were marked by instability and frequent changes of coalition government.","2010":"In 2010 Vanuatu was an independent parliamentary republic in the South Pacific, a Melanesian archipelago that had gained independence from joint British-French rule in 1980. Its politics in this period were marked by frequent changes of government through shifting parliamentary coalitions.","2026":"In 2026 Vanuatu is an island republic in the South Pacific, a parliamentary democracy known for frequent changes of government through shifting coalitions in its parliament. It remains highly vulnerable to cyclones, earthquakes and rising seas, and Port Vila is recovering from a major earthquake that struck in December 2024."},
  "vatican": {"2026":"In 2026 Vatican City is an independent city-state within Rome and the seat of the Catholic Church, led by Pope Leo XIV, who was elected in May 2025 following the death of Pope Francis. It is the world's smallest sovereign state and an absolute elective monarchy headed by the pope."},
  "venezuela": {"1900":"In 1900 Venezuela was an independent republic under the dictatorship of Cipriano Castro, who had seized power in 1899 through the Liberal Restoration revolution. The country was heavily indebted to European creditors, tensions that would lead to the 1902–1903 naval blockade by Britain, Germany, and Italy.","1920":"In 1920 Venezuela was an independent republic ruled by the dictator Juan Vicente Gómez, who had held power since 1908 and governed through repression and a tightly controlled congress. The country's economy was still largely agricultural, centered on coffee and cacao, though the first commercial oil discoveries were beginning to draw foreign companies that would soon transform its finances.","1938":"Venezuela was a republic under President Eleazar López Contreras, who had taken power after the death of long-ruling dictator Juan Vicente Gómez in 1935 and oversaw a gradual political liberalization. Its economy was dominated by oil exports, which by the late 1930s made it one of the world's leading petroleum producers.","1960":"In 1960 Venezuela was a republic that had recently returned to democracy after the 1958 overthrow of dictator Marcos Pérez Jiménez, with Rómulo Betancourt of Acción Democrática serving as elected president. The oil-rich country was a founding member of OPEC, established in 1960.","1994":"In 1994 Venezuela was a republic, with Rafael Caldera having taken office as president in February 1994. The country was gripped by a severe banking crisis that year, beginning with the collapse of Banco Latino, which forced large-scale government interventions.","2000":"In 2000, Venezuela was a republic led by President Hugo Chávez, who had first taken office in 1999. Under a new constitution adopted in 1999 that renamed the country the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, Chávez won a fresh six-year term in the July 2000 \"mega-elections.\"","2010":"In 2010 Venezuela was a republic under President Hugo Chávez, who pursued his socialist Bolivarian Revolution and faced economic difficulties including high inflation and electricity shortages. In the September 2010 National Assembly elections the opposition made significant gains, ending the ruling party's two-thirds supermajority.","2026":"In 2026 Venezuela is a republic where Nicolás Maduro continues to claim the presidency after the disputed 2024 election, which the opposition and many foreign governments say was won by Edmundo González. The country remains mired in economic crisis, mass emigration and political confrontation, including heightened tensions with the United States."},
  "victoria (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 Victoria was a self-governing British colony in southeastern Australia, with Melbourne as its capital. It was on the verge of joining the Commonwealth of Australia, which was federated on 1 January 1901, after which Victoria became a state."},
  "vietnam": {"1960":"In 1960 Vietnam was divided at the 17th parallel into the communist-led Democratic Republic of Vietnam in the north under Ho Chi Minh and the U.S.-backed Republic of Vietnam in the south under Ngo Dinh Diem. In December 1960 the National Liberation Front (Viet Cong) was formally established in the south, escalating the insurgency that grew into the Vietnam War.","1994":"In 1994 Vietnam was a one-party socialist republic governed by the Communist Party, pursuing the Đổi Mới economic reforms that opened the economy. In February 1994 the United States lifted its decades-long trade embargo against Vietnam, a major step toward normalizing relations.","2000":"In 2000, Vietnam was a one-party socialist republic governed by the Communist Party of Vietnam, pursuing market-oriented \"Doi Moi\" economic reforms. In November 2000, U.S. President Bill Clinton made a historic visit to Vietnam, the first by a sitting U.S. president since the end of the Vietnam War, reflecting normalized relations and a new bilateral trade agreement signed that year.","2010":"In 2010 Vietnam was a one-party socialist republic governed by the Communist Party of Vietnam, with Nguyen Tan Dung as prime minister. The country marked the 1,000th anniversary of Hanoi in October 2010 and continued its rapid economic growth under the market-oriented Doi Moi reforms.","2026":"In 2026 Vietnam is a one-party socialist republic governed by the Communist Party of Vietnam, with Hanoi as its capital. It maintains a fast-growing, export-oriented market economy and balances close ties with both China and the United States."},
  "w. sahara": {"1960":"In 1960 the territory was Spanish Sahara, a colonial possession of Spain on the northwest African coast, governed as a Spanish province. Its sparsely populated desert interior was inhabited largely by nomadic Sahrawi peoples, and Spain retained control as decolonization spread across much of Africa.","1994":"In 1994 Western Sahara was a disputed territory, largely controlled by Morocco, which had built defensive berms across it, while the Polisario Front and its Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic claimed sovereignty. A 1991 UN-brokered ceasefire held, and the UN mission MINURSO was attempting to organize a referendum on the territory's status, with voter identification underway in 1994.","2000":"In 2000, Western Sahara was a disputed, largely non-self-governing territory, most of which was controlled and administered by Morocco, while the Polisario Front claimed it as the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic. A UN ceasefire from 1991 held, and the UN mission MINURSO continued efforts toward a referendum on self-determination that remained stalled over voter eligibility.","2010":"In 2010 Western Sahara was a disputed, largely non-self-governing territory; most of it was controlled by Morocco, which claimed it, while the Polisario Front sought independence as the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic. In November 2010 Moroccan forces dismantled the Gdeim Izik protest camp near Laayoune, an event that triggered violent clashes.","2026":"In 2026 Western Sahara is a disputed, largely non-self-governing territory in northwest Africa, most of which is controlled and administered by Morocco while the Polisario Front claims it as the Sahrawi Arab Democratic Republic. Its final status remains unresolved under the United Nations, though a growing number of countries have backed Morocco's autonomy plan."},
  "walbis bay": {"1938":"Walvis Bay was an exclave on the South West African coast that formed part of the Cape Province of the Union of South Africa, and was thus under South African administration. It served as the main deep-water port of the surrounding South West Africa territory, which South Africa governed under a League of Nations mandate."},
  "wallis and futuna is.": {"1960":"In 1960 the Wallis and Futuna islands were a French protectorate in the South Pacific. The islands were administered through their traditional Polynesian kingdoms under French oversight, and it was not until 1961 that they formally became a French overseas territory by referendum.","1994":"In 1994 Wallis and Futuna was a French overseas territory in the South Pacific, administered by France while retaining its traditional Polynesian kingdoms. Its inhabitants were French citizens.","2000":"In 2000, Wallis and Futuna was a French overseas territory in the South Pacific, administered by France and retaining its traditional Polynesian kingdoms. Its inhabitants were French citizens, and the territory included customary monarchs alongside the French administration.","2010":"In 2010 Wallis and Futuna was a French overseas collectivity in the South Pacific, comprising three traditional Polynesian kingdoms whose customary monarchs coexisted with French administration. It remained sparsely populated and economically dependent on France and remittances.","2026":"Wallis and Futuna is an overseas collectivity of France in the South Pacific, retaining its distinctive status with three traditional kingdoms (Uvea, Sigave, and Alo) coexisting alongside the French administration. In 2026 it remains one of France's smallest and most remote territories, with a small population, heavy dependence on subsidies from Paris, and ongoing concerns about emigration to New Caledonia and mainland France."},
  "wallis and futuna islands": {"1900":"In 1900 the islands of Wallis (Uvea) and Futuna in the South Pacific were under French protectorate, with Wallis having accepted a French protectorate in 1887 and Futuna in 1888. Local Polynesian kingdoms continued to govern internally under French oversight, and Catholic missionaries had a strong presence.","1920":"In 1920 the Wallis and Futuna Islands were a French protectorate in the South Pacific, with the local Polynesian kingdoms of Uvea, Sigave, and Alo retaining their traditional monarchs under French oversight. The islands were administered in connection with French colonial authority in the Pacific and remained a small, isolated missionized society dominated by the Catholic Church."},
  "western australia (uk)": {"1900":"In 1900 Western Australia was a self-governing British colony with Perth as its capital, having gained responsible government in 1890. Driven by the gold rushes at Coolgardie and Kalgoorlie, it was the last of the Australian colonies to vote to join the Commonwealth of Australia, becoming a state at federation on 1 January 1901."},
  "white russia": {"1920":"In 1920 the Belarusian lands were a contested borderland during the Polish-Soviet War, with territory changing hands between Polish forces and the Red Army. A Soviet Belarusian republic was proclaimed in this period, but much of the region's fate remained unsettled until the 1921 Treaty of Riga partitioned Belarus between Poland and Soviet Russia."},
  "xinjiang": {"1920":"In 1920 Xinjiang was a province of the Republic of China, governed in considerable isolation by the warlord Yang Zengxin, who had ruled since 1912 and maintained autonomy from the central government in Beijing. He kept the region stable through careful balancing of its Han, Uyghur, and other Muslim populations while staying largely insulated from China's broader warlord conflicts.","1938":"Xinjiang was nominally a province of the Republic of China but in 1938 was effectively controlled by the warlord Sheng Shicai, who ruled with heavy Soviet backing and economic and military influence. Sheng aligned his administration closely with the USSR and carried out purges of suspected opponents during this period."},
  "yemen": {"1920":"In 1920 northern Yemen was effectively independent under Imam Yahya Muhammad Hamid ad-Din of the Zaydi imamate, following the collapse of Ottoman authority at the end of the First World War. The southern port of Aden and its hinterland remained under British control as a protectorate, leaving Yemen divided between the highland imamate and the British-dominated south.","1938":"The Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen, an independent kingdom in the northern highlands, was ruled by Imam Yahya Muhammad Hamid ed-Din, who governed as an autocratic Zaydi imam and king. Having secured recognition of its independence and a settled border with Saudi Arabia after the 1934 Saudi-Yemeni war and the resulting Treaty of Taif, Yemen in 1938 remained deliberately isolationist and largely closed to foreign influence.","1960":"In 1960 North Yemen was the Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen, an independent imamate ruled by Imam Ahmad bin Yahya. The country was a conservative, isolated monarchy, and the south around Aden remained under British control as a separate colony and protectorate.","1994":"In 1994 Yemen was a republic that had unified North and South Yemen in 1990, with Ali Abdullah Saleh as president. A civil war broke out in 1994 when southern leaders attempted to secede; northern forces defeated the secession by July 1994, preserving unity.","2000":"In 2000, Yemen was a republic led by President Ali Abdullah Saleh, formed from the 1990 unification of North and South Yemen. In October 2000, the U.S. Navy destroyer USS Cole was attacked by al-Qaeda suicide bombers while refueling in the port of Aden, killing 17 American sailors.","2010":"In 2010 Yemen was a republic led by President Ali Abdullah Saleh, who had ruled the unified country since 1990 and North Yemen before that. The state faced multiple internal challenges, including the Houthi rebellion in the north, a secessionist movement in the south, and the growing presence of al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula.","2026":"Yemen in 2026 remains fractured and impoverished after more than a decade of civil war, with the Houthi (Ansar Allah) movement controlling the capital Sanaa and much of the north while the internationally recognized government and the Presidential Leadership Council, backed by Saudi Arabia, hold the south and Aden. A fragile lull in major Saudi-Houthi fighting persists, but the Houthis remained active in regional conflict, including attacks on Red Sea shipping, and the country continues to face one of the world's worst humanitarian crises."},
  "yemen (uk)": {"1938":"Southern Yemen was under British control, centered on Aden, which had been detached from British India and made the Crown Colony of Aden in 1937; the surrounding hinterland was governed indirectly through treaties with local rulers as the Aden Protectorate. Aden's value to Britain lay in its strategic port and coaling/refueling station on the route through the Red Sea to the Suez Canal and India."},
  "yugoslavia": {"1920":"In 1920 the country was the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes, a newly formed state proclaimed in December 1918 uniting Serbia and Montenegro with former South Slav lands of Austria-Hungary under the Serbian Karađorđević dynasty and King Peter I. The young kingdom faced disputes over its borders, including tension with Italy over the Adriatic, and internal strain over centralization between Serb and Croat political factions.","1938":"The Kingdom of Yugoslavia was a monarchy in which the boy king Peter II reigned under a regency headed by Prince Paul, following the 1934 assassination of King Alexander I. In 1938 the government of Prime Minister Milan Stojadinovic pursued closer economic and political ties with Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy while the unresolved Serb-Croat national question continued to strain the centralized state.","1960":"In 1960 Yugoslavia was the Socialist Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia, a one-party communist federation led by Josip Broz Tito. Having broken with the Soviet Union in 1948, it pursued an independent socialist path and was a leading force in the emerging Non-Aligned Movement."},
  "zaire (belgium)": {"1920":"In 1920 this territory was the Belgian Congo, a colony of Belgium administered directly by the Belgian state since it took over from King Leopold II's Congo Free State in 1908. Colonial rule centered on resource extraction, including copper from Katanga and rubber, with a system of forced labor and missionary activity across the vast Central African territory."},
  "zambia": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory was Northern Rhodesia, administered by the British South Africa Company under a royal charter rather than directly by the British Crown. The region's economy was based on labor migration and early mineral interests, and its copper-mining boom still lay ahead in the later 1920s.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was Northern Rhodesia, a British protectorate administered as part of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland. Its copper mining was economically central, and African nationalist movements were pressing for self-rule, though independence as Zambia did not come until 1964.","1994":"In 1994 Zambia was a sovereign republic governed by President Frederick Chiluba and his Movement for Multiparty Democracy, which had swept the 1991 elections that ended Kenneth Kaunda's long one-party rule under UNIP. The government was pursuing economic liberalization and privatization of the copper-dominated economy amid serious economic hardship. The capital was Lusaka.","2000":"In 2000 Zambia was a sovereign republic led by President Frederick Chiluba of the Movement for Multiparty Democracy, in his second term after the contested 1996 election. The country remained heavily dependent on copper mining amid low prices, and the privatisation of the state-owned Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines was finalised around this time. Chiluba's reported attempt to seek a constitutionally barred third term would generate major political controversy in 2001.","2010":"Zambia was a landlocked sovereign republic in southern Africa, governed in 2010 by President Rupiah Banda of the Movement for Multi-Party Democracy, who had won the 2008 election after the death of President Levy Mwanawasa. Its economy remained heavily dependent on copper mining, and rising global copper prices were aiding recovery from the 2008-09 downturn. The country was preparing for the general elections that would be held in 2011.","2026":"Zambia is a landlocked republic in Southern Africa governed in 2026 by President Hakainde Hichilema, who won the 2021 election, with general elections due in 2026. The country has worked to restructure its external debt after defaulting in 2020 and continues to rely heavily on copper mining, while contending with the effects of severe drought on its hydropower-dependent electricity supply."},
  "zimbabwe": {"1920":"In 1920 the territory was Southern Rhodesia, administered by the British South Africa Company, with a growing population of white settlers concentrated in farming and mining. Settler pressure for self-government was rising, leading toward the 1922 referendum in which the white electorate chose responsible government over union with South Africa.","1960":"In 1960 the territory was Southern Rhodesia, a self-governing British colony with a white-minority government, then part of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland. Political power rested with the white settler minority while African nationalist organizations campaigned for majority rule.","1994":"In 1994 Zimbabwe was a sovereign republic led by President Robert Mugabe and his ruling ZANU-PF party, which dominated politics following independence from white-minority Rhodesia in 1980. The country faced ongoing debates over land reform and the slow redistribution of land still largely held by white commercial farmers. The capital was Harare.","2000":"In 2000 Zimbabwe was a republic under President Robert Mugabe and the ruling ZANU-PF. That year a government-backed 'fast-track' land reform programme began, with war veterans and others occupying white-owned commercial farms, accompanied by political violence. A February referendum rejected a proposed new constitution, and in the June parliamentary elections the newly formed opposition Movement for Democratic Change won a substantial share of seats.","2010":"Zimbabwe in 2010 was a republic operating under a power-sharing Government of National Unity, formed in 2009 after the disputed 2008 elections, with Robert Mugabe as President and Morgan Tsvangirai of the MDC as Prime Minister. The country was recovering from a catastrophic period of hyperinflation that had peaked in 2008, having abandoned the Zimbabwean dollar in 2009 in favor of foreign currencies such as the US dollar and South African rand. Tensions persisted between ZANU-PF and the MDC over the implementation of the unity agreement.","2026":"Zimbabwe is a republic in Southern Africa led in 2026 by President Emmerson Mnangagwa of ZANU-PF, who was re-elected in the disputed 2023 election. The country continues to struggle with high inflation and currency instability, having introduced the gold-backed ZiG currency in 2024, amid persistent economic hardship and debate over extending his time in office beyond 2028."},
  "zululand": {"1900":"In 1900 Zululand was a British colony in southeastern Africa, the former Zulu Kingdom having been annexed by Britain after the 1879 Anglo-Zulu War and formally made a British colony in 1887. In December 1897 it was annexed to the British colony of Natal, so by 1900 it was administered as a district of Natal."},
  "åland": {"1960":"In 1960 the Åland Islands were an autonomous, demilitarized, Swedish-speaking region of Finland in the Baltic Sea. Their self-governing status derived from the 1921 League of Nations settlement, and the islands remained part of Finland with guaranteed cultural and linguistic autonomy.","1994":"In 1994 the Åland Islands were an autonomous, demilitarized, Swedish-speaking region of Finland, governed under a longstanding autonomy statute with their own parliament and government. In a separate 1994 referendum Ålanders voted in favor of European Union membership ahead of Finland's accession, and Åland negotiated special protocol arrangements preserving its autonomy and land-ownership rules. Its capital was Mariehamn.","2000":"In 2000 Åland was an autonomous, demilitarised and Swedish-speaking province of Finland, governed under its own parliament (Lagting) and a self-government act while remaining part of the Finnish state. Its autonomy and neutral, demilitarised status derived from the 1921 League of Nations settlement and subsequent Finnish self-government legislation.","2010":"Åland in 2010 was an autonomous, demilitarized, and Swedish-speaking region of Finland, located in the Baltic Sea archipelago between Finland and Sweden. Its autonomy was guaranteed under Finnish law and international agreements, giving it its own parliament (the Lagting) with legislative powers over many domestic matters. It was part of the European Union through Finland but held special exemptions, notably remaining outside the EU's VAT area.","2026":"Åland is an autonomous, demilitarized, and Swedish-speaking archipelago province of Finland in the Baltic Sea, governed by its own parliament (Lagting) under a special autonomy guaranteed by Finnish law and international agreement. In 2026 its security situation draws particular attention because of its strategic Baltic location following Finland's 2023 accession to NATO, even as the islands retain their long-standing demilitarized status."},
  "british canada": {"1800":"In 1800, Lower Canada and Upper Canada were governed under the framework of the Constitutional Act 1791, each with its own elected assembly and appointed councils. The governor general and administration of British North America sat at Quebec City, while York (present-day Toronto) had served as the capital of Upper Canada since the seat moved there from Newark in 1796. Lower Canada was overwhelmingly French-speaking and Catholic, whereas Upper Canada was a smaller, rapidly growing settler society of Loyalists and later American and British immigrants. Robert Shore Milnes served as lieutenant-governor administering Lower Canada, while Peter Hunter was lieutenant-governor of Upper Canada. Tensions between the elected assemblies and the appointed executive were already emerging, foreshadowing the constitutional conflicts of the following decades."},
  "bambara empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Bambara Empire of Ségou stood at the height of its power under the faama Mansong (Monzon) Diarra, who had ruled since 1790. Its capital, Ségou, was a prosperous city of roughly 30,000 people straddling both banks of the Niger, whose bustling canoes and cultivated surroundings had impressed the Scottish explorer Mungo Park on his 1796–1797 visit. Mansong was waging successful campaigns to extend Ségou's dominance over neighbouring polities, reportedly founding hundreds of new settlements and welcoming immigrants of varied origins. The state's strength continued to rest on the tonjon warrior caste and on wealth drawn from trade and the capture of slaves, with cowrie shells serving as currency. The empire faced no existential threat at this date, and the Fula jihad and internal decline that would erode it lay years in the future."},
  "awadh": {"1800":"In 1800, Awadh was ruled by Nawab Saadat Ali Khan II, who had been placed on the throne in January 1798 by the British East India Company after they deposed his nephew Wazir Ali Khan. His authority rested heavily on Company backing, and he pursued fiscal retrenchment, curbing the extravagant court spending inherited from his predecessors while promoting trade and building projects in and around Lucknow. The state remained one of the wealthiest in India, yet it was already burdened by large annual subsidies owed to the British for the upkeep of a subsidiary garrison. Negotiations were under way that would culminate in the Treaty of Lucknow of November 1801, by which Awadh surrendered about half its territory, including the Doab, Rohilkhand, and Allahabad, to the Company. Thus in 1800 Awadh stood as a rich but shrinking client state, its capital at Lucknow flourishing culturally even as its political independence steadily eroded."},
  "batavian republic": {"1800":"In 1800, the Batavian Republic was governed under the unitary 1798 constitution, with executive authority vested in the five-man Uitvoerend Bewind seated at The Hague and departments run by national agents such as Isaac Gogel at Finance. It remained a client of France, bound by the 1795 Treaty of The Hague to maintain a French garrison, cede territory, and pay a heavy indemnity, and it was drawn into France's war against Britain. The previous year's Anglo-Russian invasion of North Holland had been repelled by Franco-Batavian forces at Bergen and Castricum, and its aftermath included the loss of much of the Dutch fleet at Vlieter. The state was financially strained, its Asian and Atlantic commerce crippled by the British blockade and the mounting crisis of the Dutch East India Company. Napoleon's rise after the coup of 18 Brumaire in France was reshaping relations, foreshadowing the constitutional overhaul that would create the Batavian Commonwealth the following year."},
  "bahawalpur": {"1800":"In 1800, Bahawalpur was governed by Nawab Muhammad Bahawal Khan II, the third Abbasi ruler, who had reigned since 1772. The state was still formally a tributary of the fading Durrani Empire, and one of the nawab's sons had earlier been held as a hostage by Timur Shah Durrani. Bahawal Khan II was actively strengthening the realm, constructing irrigation canals and adding frontier forts such as Marot, Anupgarh, Walhar, and Wingrot. He was also expanding eastward across the Sutlej, incorporating tracts around Mailsi, Dunyapur, and Pakpattan. Within a few years the disintegration of Durrani authority would let him consolidate Bahawalpur as an effectively autonomous state, though he died in 1809."},
  "anhalt principalities": {"1800":"In 1800, the Anhalt territory consisted of three independent Ascanian principalities — Anhalt-Dessau, Anhalt-Bernburg, and Anhalt-Köthen — each an Estate of the Holy Roman Empire, the Zerbst line having recently died out and been absorbed. Anhalt-Dessau, the leading and most prosperous branch, was ruled by Leopold III Friedrich Franz (\"Prince Franz\"), a celebrated enlightened reformer who transformed Dessau into a model Garden Kingdom of parks, schools, and improved agriculture. Anhalt-Bernburg was under Prince Alexius Frederick Christian, and Anhalt-Köthen under Prince August Christian Friedrich, both continuing the dynasty's tradition of small but well-ordered courts. All three shared close family ties, a common Ascanian heritage, and a settled Protestant character, and none had yet been touched by the coming Napoleonic reorganization. Within a few years the collapse of the Holy Roman Empire would sweep them into the Confederation of the Rhine and raise each prince to the rank of duke."},
  "bornu empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Bornu Empire was ruled by Mai Ahmad Alimi of the Sayfawa dynasty from its fortified capital at Ngazargamu west of Lake Chad. In 1800, the state was a diminished but still-functioning Muslim empire, its authority reaching westward toward the Hausa lands even as its former reach had contracted. In 1800, Bornu was already strained by decades of decline, environmental stress, and the loss of its old commercial primacy on the trans-Saharan routes. In 1800, the rising militancy of the Fulani reform movement to the west posed a growing threat that would erupt into open jihad within a few years. In 1800, the empire retained its Sayfawa monarchy and Islamic character but stood on the eve of the crisis that would cost it Ngazargamu in 1808 and hollow out the dynasty."},
  "british ceylon": {"1800":"In 1800, British Ceylon consisted only of the former Dutch maritime provinces along the coast, with the interior Kingdom of Kandy remaining an independent native state. The colony was administered under the dual East India Company and Crown system established in 1798, with Frederick North governing from Colombo. North was pursuing early civil reforms, reorganising revenue collection and curbing the abuses that had sparked the 1797 rising against Company rule. The strategic value of the harbour at Trincomalee during the wars with France had convinced Britain to make its hold permanent rather than temporary. Full crown-colony status and the confirmation of British title by the Treaty of Amiens still lay two years ahead."},
  "british west indies": {"1800":"In 1800, the British West Indies were among the most valuable possessions of the British Empire, their economies driven by sugar, coffee, and enslaved African labour. Jamaica was by far the largest and richest colony, governed from Spanish Town, where the governor, assembly, and courts sat. Britain was at war with Revolutionary France and Spain, and had recently occupied Trinidad in 1797, though it was not yet formally British. Planter assemblies dominated island politics, while a rising abolitionist movement in Britain increasingly challenged the slave system that underpinned the colonies' wealth. The enslaved population vastly outnumbered the white minority, and fear of revolt had intensified after the ongoing revolution in neighbouring French Saint-Domingue."},
  "cisalpine republic": {"1800":"In 1800, the Cisalpine Republic was re-established by Napoleon on 4 June, two days after his entry into Milan and ten days before his decisive victory over Austria at the Battle of Marengo on 14 June. In 1800, the Austro-Russian occupation that had crushed the republic in 1799 collapsed as allied forces withdrew and French control over Lombardy and Emilia was reasserted. In 1800, Napoleon reconstituted its administration through an extraordinary Commission of Government of nine members and a legislative Consulta established on 17 June. In 1800, executive power was later concentrated in a restricted Committee of Government of three members, Giovan Battista Sommariva, Sigismondo Ruga, and Francesco Visconti, with Milan again its capital. In 1800, it functioned as a firmly dependent French client state, its restored institutions setting the stage for its transformation into the Italian Republic under Napoleon's presidency in early 1802."},
  "denmark–norway": {"1800":"In 1800, Denmark–Norway was nominally ruled by the incapacitated King Christian VII while Crown Prince Frederick exercised effective royal authority as regent from Copenhagen. That year the monarchy joined Russia, Sweden and Prussia in the Second League of Armed Neutrality, asserting the right of neutral shipping to trade freely during the French Revolutionary Wars. Britain regarded the League as a hostile pro-French alignment, setting the stage for direct conflict with the Royal Navy. The state remained an absolutist composite realm binding Denmark, Norway, Schleswig-Holstein and its Atlantic and tropical colonies under the Oldenburg crown. Within months this diplomatic stance would lead to the British attack on the Danish fleet at the First Battle of Copenhagen in April 1801."},
  "bundelkhand": {"1800":"In 1800, Bundelkhand was not a single state but a fragmented patchwork of Bundela Rajput chiefs and Maratha-held territory in central India. In 1800, the Maratha administration of the region rested with Ali Bahadur, Nawab of Banda and the Peshwa's subahdar, who had extended his authority over large parts of Bundelkhand. In 1800, numerous Bundela principalities — including Orchha, Datia, Panna, Ajaigarh, Bijawar, Charkhari and Chhatarpur — persisted as tributary or semi-autonomous chieftaincies amid this Maratha overlordship. In 1800, Ali Bahadur was campaigning to complete his control of the region and was besieging the great fortress of Kalinjar, before which he would die in August 1802. In 1800, British power had not yet entered Bundelkhand, but the Maratha cession under the 1802 Treaty of Bassein and the subsequent Anglo-Maratha wars would soon bring the region under East India Company control."},
  "barotseland": {"1800":"In 1800, Barotseland was a strong, expanding kingdom on the upper Zambezi under the tenth Litunga, Mulambwa Santulu, widely remembered as its greatest ruler. In 1800, royal authority rested on control of the annual flood, cattle and cultivation, exercised through a hierarchy of indunas and the kuta council rather than the king alone. In 1800, Mulambwa was consolidating power and issuing the legal reforms that earned him the epithet \"creator of laws,\" while enforcing a firm hostility to slave-raiding that kept slave traders out of his territory. In 1800, the kingdom was absorbing incoming groups, most notably Mbunda migrants fleeing conflict and the slave trade to the west, who were welcomed as allies and settlers. In 1800, no European power had yet reached the floodplain, and the succession dispute and Kololo conquest that would later shatter the kingdom still lay decades in the future."},
  "cyrenaica": {"1800":"In 1800, Cyrenaica was the eastern territory of the Karamanli-ruled Regency of Tripoli, administered from Tripoli rather than as a self-governing province. Its principal town and port was Benghazi, a small and impoverished coastal settlement whose silted harbor limited its commercial importance. The vast interior steppe and desert were the domain of largely autonomous Bedouin tribes, over whom Ottoman-Karamanli authority remained nominal and loosely enforced. The reigning pasha, Yusuf Karamanli, had held power since 1795 and would over the following years compel the region's tribes to acknowledge his overlordship. The Sanusi order that would later dominate Cyrenaican political and religious life had not yet been founded, so the region in 1800 remained a peripheral, thinly governed frontier of the Tripoli regency."},
  "carnatic": {"1800":"In 1800, the Carnatic was ruled by Nawab Umdat ul-Umara, who had succeeded his father Muhammad Ali Khan Wallajah in 1795 and held court at Chepauk Palace in Madras. The Nawabate was by then only nominally independent, its finances crippled by enormous debts to the East India Company and its private creditors. Fresh from destroying Tipu Sultan of Mysore in 1799, the Company accused Umdat ul-Umara of having secretly aided Tipu and demanded that he surrender the administration of his territories as indemnity. Umdat ul-Umara resisted these pressures throughout 1800, but the Company was already moving to absorb the state's revenues and reduce the Nawab to a figurehead. His death in July 1801 opened the way for the Carnatic Treaty of that year, which formally transferred civil government to the British."},
  "duchy of brunswick-wolfenbüttel": {"1800":"In 1800, the principality was ruled by Duke Charles William Ferdinand, a cultured \"enlightened despot\" and renowned soldier married to a sister of Britain's George III. Its capital and court were at Brunswick, where the ruling family resided in the ducal palace. The state remained a sovereign member of the Holy Roman Empire, maintaining close dynastic and military links to Prussia. It stood at peace after the earlier campaigns of the French Revolutionary Wars, in which the duke had commanded allied armies. Within a few years this stability would collapse, as the duke's death and Napoleon's conquest ended the principality's independent existence."},
  "duchy of holstein": {"1800":"In 1800, the Duchy of Holstein was a Holy Roman Empire fief governed by King Christian VII of Denmark as its duke, with the crown prince and future Frederick VI acting as effective regent. It had been a unified single state since the 1773 reunification, its administration and highest court seated at the capital, Glückstadt, while Kiel remained an important town and university seat. The duchy formed the southern, German-speaking half of the Danish composite monarchy, sharing its ruler and much of its administration with the Duchy of Schleswig to the north. Denmark's policy of armed neutrality during the Napoleonic-era wars shaped Holstein's affairs, and the Second League of Armed Neutrality that year drew Danish territories toward confrontation with Britain. Its status as an Imperial fief would end only a few years later, in 1806, when the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire left the duchy sovereign under the Danish king."},
  "duchy of massa and carrara": {"1800":"In 1800, Massa and Carrara was not a functioning sovereign duchy but occupied territory contested between France and the Second Coalition. Its rightful ruler, Maria Beatrice d'Este, had been dispossessed in 1796 and lived in exile, chiefly at the Austrian imperial court in Vienna. A Provisional Regency set up under Austro-Russian occupation on 28 July 1799 administered the towns through the first half of the year while awaiting a possible restoration. Napoleon's victory at the Battle of Marengo on 13 June reversed the Coalition's gains, and on 20 July 1800 the Regency was dissolved. The territory was thereupon reincorporated into the French-sponsored Cisalpine Republic, remaining part of the Napoleonic system until 1815."},
  "duchy of mecklenburg-strelitz": {"1800":"In 1800, Mecklenburg-Strelitz was a small north German duchy of the Holy Roman Empire ruled by Duke Charles II, who had succeeded his childless brother Adolf Friedrich IV in 1794. Its court and administration were seated at Neustrelitz, the planned Baroque residence town rebuilt in the 1730s. The duke pursued domestic reforms, encouraging new agricultural methods, founding a police force, and introducing compulsory schooling. Dynastic ties bound the ruling house to Britain, since the duke's sister Charlotte was the reigning queen consort of George III. The duchy stood on the eve of the Napoleonic turmoil that would soon force it, like its neighbours, to navigate between France, Prussia, and the collapsing Empire."},
  "duchy of mecklenburg-schwerin": {"1800":"In 1800, the Duchy of Mecklenburg-Schwerin was ruled by Duke Friedrich Franz I, who had reigned since 1785. In 1800, the duke governed from Ludwigslust, which had served as the ducal residence and administrative seat since 1765, while Schwerin remained the traditional and nominal capital. In 1800, the duchy was a sovereign member state of the Holy Roman Empire, its politics still shaped by the powerful noble Estates and the persistence of serfdom in the countryside. In 1800, it stood at peace on the eve of the Napoleonic upheavals that would bring French occupation to the region within a few years. In 1800, the duchy's leading Baltic port was the Hanseatic city of Rostock, while the neighbouring town of Wismar was still administered by Sweden and only passed to Mecklenburg under a pledge treaty in 1803."},
  "duchy of württemberg": {"1800":"In 1800, Württemberg was still a duchy of the Holy Roman Empire ruled by Duke Frederick, who had succeeded his father Frederick II Eugene in December 1797. That year French armies of the Revolutionary Wars occupied the duchy, and the duke and duchess fled to Vienna as the fighting swept across southwestern Germany. The war left Württemberg exposed and pressured, foreshadowing the territorial bargains Frederick would soon strike, including ceding the enclave of Montbéliard to France in 1801. Stuttgart remained the capital and seat of the ducal court and the powerful territorial estates. Within three years the duchy would be transformed by the Reichsdeputationshauptschluss into an enlarged Electorate, ending its centuries-long existence as a duchy."},
  "duchy of parma": {"1800":"In 1800, the Duchy of Parma was still ruled in name by the Bourbon Duke Ferdinand I, but its independence was largely a fiction under continuous French military presence. The French victory at Marengo that June tightened Napoleon's grip on the Po plain and left the neutral duchy subjected to constant troop movements and requisitions. Diplomatic bargaining between France and Spain was already underway to trade Parma to France in exchange for Tuscany for Ferdinand's heir. Parma remained the ducal capital and the seat of Ferdinand's pious, old-regime court, which had long patronized the arts and administration. Within months these negotiations would be formalized by the treaties of Lunéville and Aranjuez, sealing the duchy's absorption into the French orbit."},
  "duchy of oldenburg": {"1800":"In 1800, the Duchy of Oldenburg was a small north German state of the Holy Roman Empire under the House of Holstein-Gottorp. Its nominal ruler was Duke William, but because of his mental incapacity the government was directed by his cousin and regent, Peter Frederick Louis, who had held that role since 1785. Peter Frederick Louis also then reigned as the Lutheran Prince-Bishop of Lübeck, a neighboring territory whose secularization and union with Oldenburg would follow in 1803. The duchy maintained a policy of neutrality and orderly administration amid the upheavals of the Revolutionary and Napoleonic wars sweeping the German lands. Its capital and princely seat was the city of Oldenburg, and the dynasty retained close kinship ties to both the Danish and Russian imperial houses."},
  "durrani empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Durrani Empire was ruled by Zaman Shah Durrani, grandson of the founder, who had held the throne since 1793 from his capital at Kabul. In 1800, his authority was crumbling as his brother Mahmud Shah rebelled repeatedly from Herat and powerful Barakzai chiefs conspired against him after he executed their leader, Painda Khan. In 1800, Zaman Shah's ambitions to campaign into the Punjab and reassert power in India were repeatedly frustrated by unrest at home and by the mounting Qajar Persian threat under Fath-Ali Shah in the west. In 1800, the empire still nominally spanned much of present-day Afghanistan, Pakistan, and adjacent regions, but real control was fracturing amid competing factions and provincial governors. In 1800, the polity stood on the brink of collapse, and within a year Zaman Shah would be overthrown, captured, and blinded, plunging the realm into deeper civil strife."},
  "electorate of bavaria": {"1800":"In 1800, Bavaria was ruled by the new elector Maximilian IV Joseph, who had inherited the united Wittelsbach lands only the year before and governed from Munich. His powerful chief minister, Count Maximilian von Montgelas, dominated policy and pushed the state toward administrative modernization and a French-leaning foreign orientation. Despite these sympathies, weak finances and a scattered, disorganized army left Bavaria dependent on Austria, and its troops shared in the Austrian defeat at Hohenlinden on 3 December 1800, after which Moreau's French forces again occupied Munich. Montgelas concluded that Bavaria's interests lay with the French Republic, steering the reluctant elector toward a separate peace and alliance with France. Meanwhile Montgelas advanced early reforms, fostering agriculture and commerce, equalizing taxes, drafting a new criminal code, and suppressing religious houses to fund education."},
  "emirate of diriyah": {"1800":"In 1800, the Emirate of Diriyah was a rising Wahhabi power ruled by Emir Abdulaziz bin Muhammad, who had already brought most of Najd and the eastern coastal regions of Qatif and al-Hasa under Saudi control. The state functioned as a theocratic alliance between the House of Saud and the descendants of Muhammad ibn Abd al-Wahhab, enforcing a strict interpretation of Islam across the territories it absorbed. Its capital Diriyah had grown into a thriving political, religious, and cultural center, drawing scholars, tribute, and trade from across the peninsula. Saudi raiding forces, often led by the emir's energetic son Saud bin Abdulaziz, pressed against the frontiers of the Hejaz and southern Iraq, setting the stage for the sack of Karbala in 1802 and the capture of Mecca in 1803. The emirate's aggressive expansion was steadily alarming the Ottomans and the sharifs of Mecca, foreshadowing the confrontation that would ultimately bring about its destruction."},
  "electorate of hanover": {"1800":"In 1800, the electorate was ruled by George III, who had been Elector since 1760 while residing permanently in Britain and governing his German lands through his ministers in Hanover. Its formal status remained that of an Imperial electorate within the Holy Roman Empire, with the city of Hanover as its administrative seat. The state was caught between the great powers during the French Revolutionary Wars, having narrowly avoided involvement and maintaining an uneasy neutrality in these years. This precarious position soon collapsed, as a brief Prussian occupation in 1801 was followed by a French invasion on 26 May 1803. The Convention of Artlenburg on 5 July 1803 forced the disbandment of the Hanoverian army and delivered the electorate into French hands, foreshadowing its dissolution in 1806."},
  "emirate of sindh": {"1800":"In 1800, the Emirate of Sindh was ruled by its founding amir, Mir Fateh Ali Khan, from the capital at Hyderabad, in the final year before his death in 1801. Power was still shared under the Chauyari system among Fateh Ali and his surviving brothers, with cadet branches at Khairpur and Mirpur Khas holding their own territories. The emirate remained nominally subordinate to the Durrani Empire under Zaman Shah, but Afghan internal weakness left the Talpurs effectively independent in practice. Fateh Ali had by this time consolidated Talpur authority across the lower Indus and extended influence over neighbouring Baloch and frontier regions. His death the following year would pass leadership to his brother Mir Ghulam Ali Talpur, continuing the dynasty's joint-rule tradition."},
  "funj sultanate": {"1800":"In 1800, the Funj Sultanate was a fading power ruled in name by its Funj sultan at Sennar but governed in fact by the Hamaj regents, who held real authority. In 1800, the state was riven by chronic civil war among its urbanized factions, and effective control was collapsing back toward the Gezira plain between the Blue and White Niles. In 1800, its once-extensive outer provinces had already slipped away, with Kordofan lost to the Fur Sultanate and Dongola to the Shaykiyya in preceding decades. In 1800, the sultanate's decay left a fragmented realm that the regent Muhammad Adlan would only briefly stabilize after taking power in 1808. In 1800, the state still stood as an independent Islamic monarchy, roughly two decades before its conquest by the forces of Muhammad Ali of Egypt in 1821."},
  "free city of bremen": {"1800":"In 1800, Bremen was a self-governing Free Imperial City and one of the three surviving Hanseatic ports, its Senate steering a neutral, commerce-focused policy amid the wars of the French Revolution. Its wealth rested on Weser shipping and overseas trade, and neutrality allowed its merchants to profit as belligerent powers' commerce was disrupted. The republic was ruled by its patrician Senate and Bürgermeister, with civic affairs conducted from the Rathaus on the market square beneath the cathedral. Its formal sovereignty still derived from the Holy Roman Empire, whose institutions were by now under severe strain from Napoleon's advance. Within a few years this order would collapse, as the Empire dissolved in 1806 and France annexed the city in 1811, though its independence was restored after 1813."},
  "free city of hamburg": {"1800":"In 1800, Hamburg was a prosperous and independent Free Imperial City, the largest of the surviving imperial cities and one of Europe's busiest ports. Its government remained the traditional merchant Senate and citizenry, resisting the dynastic and territorial powers that surrounded it. The wars of the French Revolution had actually enriched the city, as neutral Hamburg captured much of the trade disrupted elsewhere and served as a hub for goods, finance, and émigrés. It still nominally belonged to the Holy Roman Empire, whose collapse and Napoleon's rise would soon threaten its autonomy and its commerce. Within a few years the dissolution of the Empire in 1806 and later French annexation would end this comfortable neutrality and bring economic ruin under the Continental System."},
  "ethiopian empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Ethiopian Empire was at the heart of the Zemene Mesafint, its emperor a captive figurehead in the walled palaces of Gondar. In that single year the throne changed hands between the puppet emperors Demetros and Tekle Giyorgis I, who were enthroned and deposed at the whim of rival warlords. Real power lay with the great regional lords, the Yejju rases who dominated Begemder and the imperial court and Ras Wolde Selassie, who ruled Tigray as a near-independent prince and championed Tekle Giyorgis I against the Yejju-backed Demetros. The realm was fragmented into rival provinces whose lords fought incessant civil wars, and imperial decrees carried little weight beyond the court. This paralysis at the centre defined Ethiopian politics until the reunification begun by Tewodros II half a century later."},
  "free city of lübeck": {"1800":"In 1800, Lübeck was a sovereign Imperial Free City on the Baltic, governed by its patrician Senate and Bürgermeister and still nominally a member of the Holy Roman Empire. Its economy rested on Baltic maritime trade, which had shown modest revival toward the end of the eighteenth century after generations of relative decline. The city remained politically neutral amid the wars of the French Revolution, profiting for a time as a trading intermediary. In 1801 Danish troops briefly occupied the town, but Lübeck preserved its freedom and self-governing status. Its independence would persist through the empire's dissolution in 1806 until the French annexation of 1811."},
  "grand duchy of tuscany": {"1800":"In 1800, the Grand Duchy of Tuscany was a state under military occupation, its rightful sovereign Ferdinand III still in exile in Vienna after fleeing the French invasion of 1799. In the previous year French troops had held Florence only from March to July 1799 before being driven out by the popular \"Viva Maria\" revolt and the Austro-Russian counter-offensive, leaving Austrian and allied forces in de facto control at the year's start. Napoleon's victory at Marengo on 14 June 1800 reversed the tide in Italy, and French forces again pushed south to occupy Tuscany over the following months. The grand duchy thus spent 1800 as a contested prize between the Habsburg and French war efforts rather than a functioning independent monarchy. Its fate was effectively sealed by the campaign, and within months the Treaty of Aranjuez (March 1801) would abolish it in favour of the French-sponsored Kingdom of Etruria."},
  "electorate of saxony": {"1800":"In 1800, the Electorate of Saxony was ruled by Frederick Augustus III, who had governed since 1763 and was widely esteemed for his frugal, orderly administration. Governed from Dresden, it remained a senior member of the Holy Roman Empire, its Catholic elector still presiding over a Lutheran population. Having been dragged into the War of the First Coalition against revolutionary France by the Empire's declaration of Reichskrieg in 1793, Saxony had withdrawn from the coalition in August 1796 and by 1800 held to a policy of prudent neutrality. This long peace allowed its economy, mining, textiles, and the great Leipzig trade fairs to prosper while much of Germany suffered war. The electorate would maintain this quiet course until 1806, when alliance with Prussia, French defeat of both, and the Treaty of Poznań transformed it into the Kingdom of Saxony."},
  "great lakes kingdoms": {"1800":"In 1800, Buganda was the ascendant power of the region, ruled by Kabaka Semakookiro from his royal capital at Kasangati and pressing its expansion against a declining Bunyoro. In 1800, Bunyoro-Kitara under Omukama Kyebambe III Nyamutukura remained large but was losing ground and territory to Buganda and to internal fragmentation. In 1800, the Kingdom of Rwanda under the Nyiginya dynasty was ruled by Mwami Mibambwe III Mutabazi II Sentabyo, whose death the following year would bring the boy-king Yuhi IV Gahindiro to the throne under a regency. In 1800, Burundi was entering its greatest phase of expansion under Mwami Ntare IV Rutaganzwa Rugamba, who roughly doubled the kingdom's territory through conquest and diplomacy. In 1800, Nkore was a smaller pastoral kingdom under its Bahinda Omugabe, one of several interlacustrine states whose sovereignty would last until the colonial partition at the century's end."},
  "habsburg monarchy": {"1800":"In 1800, the Habsburg Monarchy was ruled by Francis II, who was simultaneously Holy Roman Emperor, King of Bohemia, and King of Hungary, governing from Vienna. In that year it was still waging the War of the Second Coalition against Napoleonic France largely alongside Britain, Russia having abandoned the alliance early in 1800 as Tsar Paul I turned toward Napoleon. Its armies suffered decisive defeats at Marengo in June 1800 and at Hohenlinden in December 1800, which shattered the coalition's position in Italy and Germany. These reverses forced Francis to the negotiating table, leading to the Treaty of Lunéville in February 1801, which confirmed French dominance west of the Rhine and in northern Italy. The monarchy remained a sprawling multiethnic composite of Austrian, Bohemian, Hungarian, and other lands, still four years away from being reorganized as the Austrian Empire."},
  "helvetic republic": {"1800":"In 1800, the Helvetic Republic was in deep political crisis, governed from Bern as its seat since the capital had shifted from Aarau and Lucerne. On 7 January 1800 a coup d'état overthrew the Directory and deposed Frédéric-César de La Harpe, replacing directorial rule with an executive commission amid bitter feuding between unitarist and federalist factions. The centralized regime remained wholly dependent on French military backing and continued to lack legitimacy among a population resentful of conscription, requisitions, and the loss of cantonal self-rule. Switzerland in this year still bore the strains of the 1799 campaigns fought across its territory between French and Austro-Russian armies, which had left devastation and financial ruin. The unstable government lurched through further constitutional revisions, foreshadowing the collapse that would culminate in the 1802 civil war and Napoleon's 1803 Act of Mediation."},
  "hyderabad state": {"1800":"In 1800, Hyderabad State was ruled by Nizam Ali Khan, Asaf Jah II, who had reigned since 1762 and would rule until 1803. In 1800, the state was firmly within the British orbit following the subsidiary alliance signed on 1 September 1798, having earlier dismissed its French-officered corps at British insistence. In 1800, a supplementary treaty concluded on 12 October formalised the cession of the Ceded Districts to the Company as payment for the subsidiary British force stationed in the Nizam's territory. In 1800, the Nizam nonetheless retained internal sovereignty over a vast Deccan realm governed from Hyderabad, with the British Resident based at the court. In 1800, the state remained the foremost of the emerging princely states, its external and military autonomy curtailed but its dynasty and administration intact."},
  "hohenzollern principalities": {"1800":"In 1800, the two principalities were separate immediate members of the Holy Roman Empire, each ruled by a prince of the Catholic Swabian Hohenzollern branch. Hohenzollern-Hechingen was governed by Prince Hermann, who had succeeded his uncle in 1798 and ruled as a strict, businesslike patriarch enjoying a final high point of princely absolutism. Hohenzollern-Sigmaringen was ruled by Prince Anton Aloys, who had succeeded his father in 1785 and had fled to Vienna during the French Revolutionary Wars before returning in 1796. Both princes now faced the upheavals of the Napoleonic era, and Anton Aloys would soon lose his rich Dutch estates to France, receiving territory such as Glatt and secularized monasteries as compensation in 1802–1803. The Empire that guaranteed their status still stood in 1800, but its dissolution in 1806 and their absorption into the Confederation of the Rhine lay only a few years ahead."},
  "hausa kingdoms": {"1800":"In 1800, the Hausa Kingdoms were still independent city-states, each governed by its own sarki and electoral council rather than any unified crown. In 1800, Gobir stood as the most aggressive military power under the aging Sarki Nafata, who had begun imposing restrictions on the reformist preaching of the Fulani scholar Usman dan Fodio. In 1800, Kano and Katsina remained the great commercial centers, though Kano's earlier dominance had been eroded by cowrie-shell inflation and heavy taxation that shifted trade advantage toward Katsina. In 1800, the states were nominally Muslim but were denounced by dan Fodio's followers for syncretic practices, unjust taxation, and enslavement of fellow Muslims, tensions that were rapidly sharpening. In 1800, none of the rulers foresaw that within four years dan Fodio would proclaim a jihad that would sweep away their dynasties and forge the Sokoto Caliphate."},
  "asante empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Asante Empire was a powerful independent state centred on Kumasi and passing through a turbulent succession crisis. Osei Kwame Panyin, enstooled in 1777, had by this time been effectively destooled following disputes with the queen-mother Konadu Yaadom and his failure to appear for the Odwira festival, leaving the throne contested. The stool soon passed to the short-lived Opoku Fofie and then, about 1800 to 1804 depending on the source, to the vigorous Osei Bonsu, also called Osei Tutu Kwame. Despite the internal instability, the empire remained territorially intact and continued to profit from the gold and slave trades routed toward the British, Dutch, and Danish forts on the coast. Within a few years Osei Bonsu would launch his major campaigns against the Fante confederacy, culminating in the invasions and victories of 1806 to 1807."},
  "first french republic": {"1800":"In 1800, the French Republic was governed by the Consulate with Napoleon Bonaparte as First Consul, having taken power only months earlier in the coup of Brumaire. In February 1800 he moved his residence into the Tuileries Palace in Paris and pressed forward with administrative and financial reforms, founding the Banque de France that same year. The Republic remained at war with the Second Coalition, and Napoleon personally led an army across the Alps into Italy, defeating the Austrians at the Battle of Marengo on 14 June 1800. That victory, reinforced by Moreau's triumph at Hohenlinden in December, forced Austria toward the Treaty of Lunéville of early 1801. Peace negotiations with Britain were also underway, culminating in the Peace of Amiens signed in 1802."},
  "kingdom of mysore": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Mysore was ruled in name by the child maharaja Krishnaraja Wodeyar III, who had been enthroned the previous year, with actual governance in the hands of the Dewan Purnaiah acting as regent. The state functioned under a subsidiary alliance with the British East India Company, whose Resident, Barry Close, supervised its affairs and stationed Company troops within its borders. Having been reduced to a rump of Tipu Sultan's former dominions after the 1799 partition among the British, the Nizam of Hyderabad, and the Marathas, the kingdom's core lands were centered on Mysore and Seringapatam. Purnaiah used these years to restore order, rebuild finances, revive temple and religious endowments that had lapsed, and reorganize revenue administration after the upheavals of the war. The surrounding region remained unsettled, as the freebooter Dhondia Wagh raised a revolt in former Mysore territory that was crushed by British forces under Arthur Wellesley in 1800."},
  "principality of waldeck": {"1800":"In 1800, the principality was ruled by Friedrich Karl August, Prince of Waldeck and Pyrmont, who had reigned since 1763 and still governed Waldeck and Pyrmont as a single state. A career soldier who had served as a major-general in the Dutch army until 1794, he had earlier pursued ambitious modernization after visiting England in 1775, funding road-building, agriculture, wool and iron works, and a gymnasium at Korbach. These outlays, however, had driven the small state deep into debt, a burden he had tried to relieve by leasing troops abroad, including to Britain during the American War of Independence. As an immediate principality of the still-existing Holy Roman Empire, Waldeck retained its own sovereignty in 1800, its baroque capital at Arolsen the seat of the childless, unmarried prince. Within a few years its indebtedness would force him to hive off Pyrmont to his brother Georg in 1805, on the eve of the Empire's collapse and the principality's entry into the Confederation of the Rhine."},
  "tây sơn dynasty": {"1800":"In 1800, the Tây Sơn dynasty was ruled by Emperor Cảnh Thịnh (Nguyễn Quang Toản) from its capital at Phú Xuân, though the regime remained fractured by the court purges and defections that had followed Quang Trung's death. Throughout that year the Tây Sơn generals Trần Quang Diệu and Vũ Văn Dũng besieged the citadel of Quy Nhơn, held by Nguyễn Ánh's officer Võ Tánh, while occupying the surrounding coast and the strategic Thị Nại lagoon, yet they could not retake the fortress for the whole year. Nguyễn Ánh, unable to break the encirclement, kept his main forces in a holding posture near the front rather than pushing deeper north. The Tây Sơn still nominally controlled central and northern Vietnam, but their leadership was divided and their long-term position was eroding against Nguyễn Ánh's resurgent southern base. Within a year Phú Xuân itself would fall in July 1801, forcing Cảnh Thịnh to flee north, and by 1802 the dynasty would be extinguished entirely."},
  "viceroyalty of new spain": {"1800":"In 1800, New Spain was governed from Mexico City under King Charles IV of Spain, with the viceroyalty passing from Miguel José de Azanza to Félix Berenguer de Marquina, who assumed office on 30 April 1800. Berenguer de Marquina's tenure was largely uneventful and is chiefly remembered for its defensive military measures, the formation of the Regiment of Grenadiers, and the suppression of indigenous unrest such as the Indio Mariano rebellion of 1801. The viceroyalty remained the richest possession of the Spanish crown, its silver mines feeding both the treasury and the Manila galleon trade across the Pacific. Spain's entanglement in the wider Napoleonic-era wars in Europe disrupted transatlantic shipping and heightened pressures on colonial revenue and defense. Beneath the surface calm, Enlightenment ideas and creole discontent with peninsular privilege were building the tensions that would erupt into the independence movement a decade later."},
  "kingdom of naples and sicily": {"1800":"In 1800, Ferdinand IV of Naples and III of Sicily held both Bourbon crowns, having recovered the Neapolitan mainland after the fall of the Parthenopean Republic the previous year. The king and Queen Maria Carolina still resided in Palermo, where they had fled aboard Nelson's fleet in late 1798, so the court governed the reconquered kingdom from Sicily rather than from Naples. Cardinal Ruffo's royalist forces and their British allies had consolidated Bourbon control of the mainland, and a wave of trials and executions of former republicans continued to mark the restored regime. The two kingdoms remained constitutionally separate realms bound only by their common sovereign, firmly aligned against Revolutionary France within the anti-French coalitions. The royal family would not return to Naples itself until 1802, after the Peace of Amiens temporarily relieved French military pressure."},
  "sultanate of muscat and oman": {"1800":"In 1800, the state was ruled from Muscat by Sultan bin Ahmad, the fourth Al Bu Said ruler, who governed the coast while his brother Said held the Imamate in the interior at Rustaq. Its power rested on maritime trade across the Indian Ocean, with Muscat serving as a thriving entrepôt linking Arabia, Persia, India, and the East African coast. In this year Sultan bin Ahmad concluded a second treaty with the British East India Company, providing for a British agent to reside at Muscat and manage relations with other states. The realm also held distant possessions including Zanzibar and the Zanj coast in East Africa and the port of Gwadar on the Makran coast. At the same time it faced mounting pressure from Wahhabi forces advancing from central Arabia, who occupied Buraimi and besieged the governor of Sohar."},
  "kingdom of hawaii": {"1800":"In 1800, Kamehameha I ruled a nearly unified Hawaiian polity, having conquered Maui, Molokaʻi, Lānaʻi, and Oʻahu by 1795, with only Kauaʻi and Niʻihau still independent under the ruler Kaumualiʻi. His authority rested on decisive victories such as the 1795 battle of Nuʻuanu on Oʻahu and on Western firearms and advisors, notably the Englishman John Young and the Irishman Isaac Davis. The kingdom had no fixed capital in the European sense; the royal seat followed the king, who around this time held court on Hawaiʻi Island before shifting his center to Oʻahu and Honolulu Harbour in the years that followed to oversee the growing foreign shipping trade. The islands were increasingly drawn into the Pacific commerce in sandalwood and the provisioning of visiting ships, even as introduced diseases were driving a steep decline in the Native Hawaiian population. Kamehameha would complete the unification in 1810 when Kaumualiʻi ceded Kauaʻi peacefully, sparing the kingdom a final war."},
  "oyo empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Oyo Empire was a Yoruba imperial state in advancing decline, its central authority badly shaken by the recent forced suicide of Alaafin Awole. The throne passed through weak and contested successions, and provincial governors and tributaries increasingly ignored or defied the capital at Oyo-Ile. The rebellion of Afonja, the Aare Ona Kakanfo based at Ilorin who commanded much of Oyo's cavalry, was pulling the empire's military heart away from the Alaafin's control. Pressure from the Muslim north and the loss of tribute and trade revenue steadily eroded the imperial economy and army. Though still nominally sovereign over a wide swath of Yorubaland and its neighbours, Oyo in 1800 was fragmenting toward the collapse that would destroy its capital within a generation."},
  "kaarta": {"1800":"In 1800, Kaarta was an independent Bambara kingdom of the western Sahel governed by the Massassi (Coulibaly) clan from its capital at Diangounté. Its ruler in this period was Faama Desse Koro, who had succeeded Sira Bo after 1781, though his precise regnal dates are not securely recorded. Kaarta was locked in rivalry with the neighboring Bambara Empire of Segou, then at the height of its strength under Mansong Diarra, who ruled Segou from about 1790 to 1808. Desse Koro was defeated in battle by Mansong, marking a low point in Kaarta's fortunes as Segou pressed its campaigns against it. Despite this setback the kingdom endured as a distinct Bambara state and would recover its regional standing under Bodian Moriba a generation later."},
  "kingdom of cambodia": {"1800":"In 1800, Cambodia was a weak kingdom caught in an interregnum, its throne vacant of a crowned monarch since Ang Eng's death in 1796. In 1800, the boy-heir Ang Chan II remained under Siamese guardianship and had not yet been allowed to take the throne, while Prince Pok served as regent and governed the country. In 1800, the royal capital was Oudong, the seat of the Khmer court since the early seventeenth century. In 1800, Cambodia acknowledged the overlordship of both Siam and Vietnam, paying tribute to each and functioning as a buffer between the two expanding powers. In 1800, the provinces of Battambang and Siem Reap remained detached under Siamese control, having been ceded during Ang Eng's reign."},
  "sultanate of aussa": {"1800":"In 1800, the Sultanate of Aussa was ruled by Sultan Aydahis ibn Kadhafo Mahammad, who reigned from 1779 until 1801. The Mudaito dynasty he belonged to had held power for roughly two generations, and the state functioned as an independent Afar monarchy centered on its capital. During this decade its ruler organized the defense of the capital, reportedly recruiting matchlock-armed men from Aden in Yemen to repel attackers. Contemporary European accounts described the sultan as a brave and martial ruler whose armory included cannons and matchlocks. The sultanate stood outside any imperial control at this date, dominating the Afar lowlands as the foremost Afar power."},
  "kingdom of great britain": {"1800":"In 1800, Great Britain was ruled by King George III with William Pitt the Younger serving as Prime Minister and dominant political figure. In 1800, the kingdom was locked in the War of the Second Coalition against Revolutionary France, sustaining a continental struggle largely through naval power and subsidies to allies. In 1800, its Parliament passed the Act of Union with Ireland, and the Irish Parliament passed its counterpart, arranging the merger that would create the United Kingdom on 1 January 1801. In 1800, wartime taxation, harvest failures, and high grain prices strained the population, while Pitt's earlier introduction of income tax in 1799 helped finance the war effort. In 1800, the country stood at the leading edge of early industrialization, with growing textile manufacturing, coal and iron output, and expanding maritime commerce underpinning its global reach."},
  "maratha confederacy": {"1800":"In 1800, the Maratha Confederacy remained the largest indigenous power in India but was gravely weakened by internal division and rivalry among its chiefs. Baji Rao II held the office of Peshwa at Pune, though real authority increasingly rested with the ambitious general Daulat Rao Scindia. The death of Nana Fadnavis that same year stripped the confederacy of its last unifying statesman and left the houses of Scindia, Holkar, Bhonsle, and Gaekwad pursuing self-interested and mutually hostile policies. This disunity created the opening the British East India Company sought, as no single leader could coordinate the confederacy's still-formidable armies. Within two years Yashwant Rao Holkar would defeat the Peshwa at the Battle of Poona, driving Baji Rao II into the fateful alliance with the British that hastened the confederacy's collapse."},
  "kingdom of bhutan": {"1800":"In 1800, Bhutan was ruled by Druk Namgyel, the twenty-second Druk Desi, who held office from 1799 to 1803 under the enduring dual system. The state was internally unstable, with the office of Druk Desi weakened by short tenures, contested elections, and the growing autonomy of provincial penlops and dzongpöns. Following the 1774 peace treaty with the British East India Company after the Cooch Behar conflict, Britain had displaced Tibet as the chief external power on Bhutan's southern frontier, though relations remained cautious and distant. Bhutan continued to administer poorly demarcated tracts along the Bengal Duars, a source of friction that would later erupt into war. The government moved seasonally between its winter seat at Punakha and Thimphu, sustaining the Buddhist theocratic order the Zhabdrung had founded even as centralized control frayed."},
  "kanara": {"1800":"In 1800, Canara was a newly formed British collectorate on the south-western Indian coast, barely a year old under Company rule. Its first Collector, Captain Thomas Munro, administered the district from Mangalore and continued in that post until October 1800, imposing order and a fresh revenue settlement on territory only just wrested from Mysore. The population was still adjusting to the transfer of sovereignty from Tipu Sultan's regime to the East India Company, whose overarching authority in the region had been consolidated by Governor-General Richard Wellesley. As part of the Madras Presidency, the district answered to Company officials at Madras rather than to any indigenous ruler. It remained a single undivided Canara district, decades away from the 1859 split into North and South Canara."},
  "kong empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kong Empire was ruled by the fama Mori Maghari, who had succeeded Koumbi Ouattara and maintained Kong's prestige as a hub of trade and Islamic learning. In 1800, the state remained a loose confederation of Watara war-houses and Dyula merchant communities, controlling key trans-savanna routes carrying gold and kola nuts rather than a tightly unified realm. In 1800, the death of Mori Maghari in that very year is conventionally marked as the beginning of the empire's tribulations, as authority passed to weaker successors. In 1800, ethnic and religious groups within the empire were increasingly organizing resistance that eroded the central power of the Kong ruling house. In 1800, the empire nonetheless still held its core territory in the northeastern savanna and its walled capital continued to function as a flourishing commercial and scholarly center."},
  "oromo states": {"1800":"In 1800, the region was overwhelmingly Oromo country still ordered by the Gadaa system, with hereditary monarchy only beginning to crystallize at its northwestern edge. In 1800, Bofo, called Abba Gomol, was rising to power among the Limmu Oromo and, around 1800-1802, welding scattered clans into the Kingdom of Limmu-Ennarea from his capital at Sappa, having overrun the older Ennarea state whose Gonga-speaking ruling elite had taken refuge in Kaffa. In 1800, the other Gibe monarchies of Gumma, Gomma, Jimma, and Gera had not yet been founded, so no unified bloc of Oromo kingdoms existed and much of the surrounding highland remained governed by Gadaa councils rather than kings. In 1800, the reviving caravan trade in gold, coffee, ivory, and slaves was already drawing Muslim merchants into the Gibe basin and enriching the emerging chiefs who controlled its markets. In 1800, these communities lay beyond the reach of the Christian Ethiopian state to their north, which was itself fragmented in the decentralized Zemene Mesafint, leaving the Oromo of the Gibe fully autonomous."},
  "sikh confederacy": {"1800":"In 1800, the old confederacy of twelve independent misls had effectively ceased to function as a collective body, its authority passing to Ranjit Singh of the Sukerchakia Misl. In 1800, Ranjit Singh held Lahore, which he had seized the previous year and made his seat of power, though he still governed nominally as its Afghan-confirmed governor rather than as a sovereign. In 1800, he was actively subduing or allying with the remaining misls of central Punjab, backed by his mother-in-law Rani Sada Kaur of the Kanhaiya Misl. In 1800, the region remained a patchwork of Sikh-ruled territories not yet welded into a single administration, with the Cis-Sutlej and Phulkian chiefs still autonomous. In 1800, Ranjit Singh had not yet been formally proclaimed Maharaja, an event that would follow on Vaisakhi in April 1801."},
  "kingdom of imerina": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Imerina was ruled by Andrianampoinimerina, roughly midway through his reign of about 1787 to 1810. In 1800, he governed a reunified Imerina from Antananarivo, having moved his political capital there in 1794 while Ambohimanga remained the sacred royal town. In 1800, he pressed a program of consolidation and expansion, absorbing or pressuring neighboring highland peoples such as the Betsileo, Sihanaka, and Bezanozano while the coastal Sakalava resisted. In 1800, his administration rested on codified customary law, controlled markets with standardized measures, extensive irrigated rice cultivation, and a corvée-and-conscription system famously expressed in his call for an army of the \"hundred thousand.\" In 1800, he is credited with major building works at Antananarivo, including the reconstruction of the Besakana royal residence, marking the highland kingdom's rise as the paramount power on Madagascar."},
  "margraviate of baden": {"1800":"In 1800, Baden was a compact Margraviate ruled by the aged Charles Frederick from his purpose-built capital at Karlsruhe. Its lands lay scattered along the upper Rhine as one of the many small principalities of the Holy Roman Empire, hemmed in by larger neighbours. Charles Frederick's enlightened administration was already well established, having pursued legal reform, education, and agricultural improvement over decades of rule. The wars of the French Revolution had brought French armies to the Rhine, and Baden manoeuvred diplomatically to preserve and enlarge itself amid the collapse of the imperial order. Within three years these efforts would bear fruit, as the mediatisation of 1803 vastly expanded Baden's territory and raised it to an Electorate."},
  "swabian circle": {"1800":"In 1800, the Swabian Circle remained a working institution of the Holy Roman Empire, still binding together a patchwork of roughly ninety small territories in the southwest. In 1800, only the Duchy of Württemberg, the Margraviate of Baden, and the Prince-Bishopric of Augsburg carried real weight among its many minor members, while the co-directorship rested with the Bishop of Constance and the Duke of Württemberg. In 1800, its diet continued to meet at the imperial city of Ulm to organize contributions and troops, and the circle was caught up in the wars of the Second Coalition against Revolutionary France. In 1800, French victories brought fighting and occupation to Swabian lands, straining the circle's finances and defensive obligations. In 1800, the circle stood on the eve of the upheaval that the 1803 mediatization would bring, when most of its ecclesiastical states and free cities were absorbed by Württemberg and Baden."},
  "kingdom of prussia": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Prussia was ruled by King Frederick William III, who had succeeded to the throne in 1797. It held to a policy of armed neutrality in northern Germany that it had maintained since the 1795 Peace of Basel, staying out of the ongoing War of the Second Coalition against revolutionary France. In December 1800 it joined the Second League of Armed Neutrality alongside Russia, Denmark, and Sweden to resist British naval interference, a coalition that soon collapsed in 1801. Its government rested on an entrenched royal bureaucracy and a powerful professional army, though the reforms that would later modernize the state lay still ahead. This decade of neutrality spared much of central, eastern, and northern Germany from war until Prussia's catastrophic defeat by Napoleon in 1806."},
  "northern circars": {"1800":"In 1800, the Northern Circars were firmly under British East India Company administration as part of the Madras Presidency, with the Nizam of Hyderabad retaining only a nominal residual claim settled by annuity. The Chiefs and Councils that had earlier governed the tract had been abolished in 1794, and Company officials were moving toward a district-based collectorate system that would be formalized in 1802. Revenue policy in these years leaned on settlements with local zamindars, with permanent-settlement arrangements modeled on Bengal being attempted for hereditary landlords. The region remained peaceful under Company control, its acquisition having come largely through diplomacy and financial settlement rather than direct conquest. Masulipatam continued as the principal port and long-standing administrative town, while Guntur, incorporated only in 1788, had by now been fully integrated into the Circars."},
  "sultanate of darfur": {"1800":"In 1800, the Sultanate of Darfur was an independent Muslim state ruled by Sultan Abd al-Rahman al-Rashid of the Keira dynasty, at or near the peak of its power. In 1800, the sultan governed from the newly fixed capital at El Fasher, which he had established around 1790 in place of the dynasty's earlier itinerant royal camps. In 1800, the sultanate was engaged in wider diplomacy, having received the honorific title al-Rashid from the Ottoman sultan in 1792 and, in 1799, having written to congratulate Napoleon Bonaparte on his campaign in Egypt. In 1800, its wealth rested on the trans-Saharan caravan trade running north toward Egypt, exporting slaves, ivory, and other goods in exchange for manufactured wares. In 1800, the aging Abd al-Rahman was nearing the end of his reign, and he would die in 1801 and be succeeded by his son Muhammad al-Fadl."},
  "zaydi imamate": {"1800":"In 1800, the Zaydi Imamate was ruled from Sana'a by Imam al-Mansur Ali I, who had reigned since 1775. His government was visibly decaying, as the aging imam left day-to-day affairs to his ministers while court intrigue mounted and real power in Sana'a was held by his wazir Hasan al-Ulufi. The state still controlled the Zaydi highlands but faced the rapidly expanding Wahhabi movement pressing in from the north and the vulnerable Tihama coast. Within a few years, from 1803 onward, pro-Wahhabi forces under Sharif Hamud would seize the coastal lowlands, a loss that lay just ahead of this moment. The imamate thus stood in 1800 as a shrinking but still-functioning polity, its authority fraying at the edges even as Sana'a remained its recognized center."},
  "nova scotia": {"1800":"In 1800, Nova Scotia was a self-standing British colony administered from Halifax, its Loyalist-swollen society now a generation removed from the Revolution. Sir John Wentworth, appointed lieutenant governor in 1792 and made a baronet in 1795, presided over the executive while working with an elected House of Assembly. Halifax served as a major Royal Navy base and imperial garrison, giving the colony strategic weight during the wars against Revolutionary France. Wentworth's later years brought growing conflict with assembly leaders, notably William Cottnam Tonge, over who should control expenditure on roads and patronage. New Brunswick and Cape Breton, detached in 1784, remained separate colonies, so 1800 Nova Scotia was smaller than the province of a few decades earlier or later."},
  "mossi kingdoms": {"1800":"In 1800, the Mossi kingdoms were fully independent, comprising about twenty autonomous polities in the Volta basin with Ouagadougou, Yatenga, Tenkodogo, and Boussouma the most prominent. In 1800, the paramount Mogho Naba at Ouagadougou—most likely Naba Doulougou, whose reign is variously dated to the years around 1783-1802 or 1796-1825—held nominal suzerainty and arbitrated disputes among the central and southern kingdoms. In 1800, the northwestern kingdom of Yatenga remained effectively independent of Ouagadougou and a standing rival, so no single throne ruled all the Mossi. In 1800, Islam was gaining a foothold at court through Yarse Muslim traders, with a mosque and an imam permitted at Ouagadougou under Doulougou, even as the kings upheld their traditional religion and rites. In 1800, the kingdoms remained untouched by European rule, that conquest lying nearly a century in the future."},
  "kingdom of cochin": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Cochin was ruled by Rama Varma IX, popularly called Sakthan Thampuran, who reigned from 1790 until his death in 1805. It was a subsidiary and tributary state of the British East India Company under the treaty concluded with George Powney on 6 January 1791, having earlier been forced to pay tribute to Mysore. Sakthan Thampuran had shifted the seat of administration to Thrissur, where he resided at the Vadakkechira Palace and developed the town as the kingdom's economic and cultural centre. His reign was marked by administrative centralization, the suppression of overmighty feudal lords, and the reorganization of trade and temple affairs. The kingdom was internally consolidated but externally dependent, its foreign relations and territorial integrity now bound to British protection."},
  "kingdom of kongo": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Kongo was a fragmented shadow of its former self, nominally reunified but weakened by a century of dynastic conflict. In 1800, the throne was held by Henrique II Masaki ma Mpanzu, who reigned from 1794 to 1803 under a fragile arrangement dividing the succession among competing branches. In 1800, real authority was fractured, with provinces such as Soyo and Nsundi acting as de facto independent powers beyond the king's control. In 1800, the kingdom remained a Catholic monarchy oriented toward Portugal, and the transatlantic slave trade continued to drain and destabilize its population. In 1800, the seat of the diminished court remained the capital São Salvador, which had never regained the prominence lost during the civil-war destruction of the late seventeenth century."},
  "kingdom of dahomey": {"1800":"In 1800, Dahomey was ruled by King Adandozan, who had come to the throne in 1797 with the early years of his reign managed by a regency of elder statesmen. The kingdom remained a militarized slave-trading power centered on its capital at Abomey, exporting captives through the coastal port of Ouidah. It continued to owe tribute to the Oyo Empire, whose renewed strength soon constrained Adandozan's raiding campaigns against rival ports. Adandozan attempted to revive the flagging slave trade through military raids and, when those largely failed, turned to diplomatic pressure on European and Brazilian traders and to agricultural reforms. His harsh and increasingly unpopular rule sowed the divisions that would culminate in his overthrow by his brother Ghezo in 1818."},
  "principality of schaumburg-lippe": {"1800":"In 1800, Schaumburg-Lippe was still a county, not yet a principality, ruled nominally by the young Count Georg Wilhelm, who had succeeded as an infant in 1787. Because he was a minor, the county was governed by a regency; his mother Juliane of Hesse-Philippsthal had died in November 1799, after which Count Johann Ludwig von Wallmoden-Gimborn served as regent. The county remained an immediate fief of the Holy Roman Empire, its fragile autonomy having recently been defended before the imperial courts against encroachment by Hesse-Kassel. Its capital and princely residence was at Bückeburg, with Stadthagen as a secondary town. It would be another seven years before the county was elevated to a principality and Georg Wilhelm assumed full personal rule."},
  "sultanate of aïr": {"1800":"In 1800, the Sultanate of Aïr persisted as an autonomous Tuareg monarchy under its sultan at Agadez, but it was a much-diminished successor to the prosperous trading state of earlier centuries. Its economy still rested on the trans-Saharan caravan trade, particularly the salt and date routes linking Agadez to the Bilma and Fachi oases and the markets of Hausaland to the south. The sultan's authority remained limited and largely mediatory, exercised over often fractious Tuareg drum-groups rather than as a centralized state power. The eighteenth-century influx of northern Tuareg groups had left the region politically unsettled, deepening the decline that would leave Agadez a shadow of its former self by the time Heinrich Barth visited in 1850. No European power yet held sway over the region, French colonial control lying more than a century in the future."},
  "malay sultanates": {"1800":"In 1800, the peninsula and coastal Borneo were divided among these separate sultanates rather than any single kingdom, with no common ruler or capital. The premier line, Johor-Riau-Lingga under Sultan Mahmud Shah III, had moved its seat to Daik on Lingga in 1788 but was effectively governed by the Bugis Yang di-Pertuan Muda based in the Riau islands. Kedah, Kelantan and Terengganu lay under Siamese suzerainty, while Selangor and Perak remained shaped by Bugis and dynastic rivalries, and Brunei's authority over Borneo had contracted sharply. The British East India Company held Penang, ceded from Kedah in 1786, as a growing free port and naval station on the sultanates' northwestern flank. The stage was thus set for the nineteenth-century partition of this Malay world between British and Dutch spheres of influence."},
  "nguyễn domain": {"1800":"In 1800, Nguyễn Ánh ruled a consolidated southern realm centered on Gia Định (Saigon), controlling the Mekong delta and the coast up toward the contested central provinces. In that year his forces were locked in the drawn-out siege of Quy Nhơn against the Tây Sơn, whose armies had marched south to besiege the Bình Định citadel his general Võ Tánh held on the central coast. He commanded a formidable military of tens of thousands of troops and a large fleet, supplied through trade in delta rice and sugar for European weapons and materiel. He still held the title Nguyễn Vương rather than emperor, governing as a claimant restoring his family's legitimacy against the Tây Sơn regime in the north. Within two years these campaigns would culminate in the fall of Huế and Hanoi, reunification, and his enthronement as Gia Long."},
  "kingdom of sardinia": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Sardinia survived only as a de jure state, its Piedmontese and Savoyard mainland having been occupied by French forces since 1798 and formally reorganized toward annexation. In 1800, King Charles Emmanuel IV lived as an exile in central and southern Italy, having left the island of Sardinia in September 1799 for Florence, Rome, and Naples, while the island itself remained beyond French reach and was governed in his name by a viceroy. In 1800, the Battle of Marengo in June restored French control over Piedmont after a brief Austro-Russian occupation of Turin the previous year. In 1800, the king clung to the hope of a mainland restoration that Austrian and later French dominance repeatedly frustrated. In 1800, the wandering Savoyard court represented a dynasty in retreat, two years before Charles Emmanuel IV freely abdicated in favour of his brother Victor Emmanuel I."},
  "principality of lippe": {"1800":"In 1800, the Principality of Lippe was a small sovereign state of the Holy Roman Empire ruled by Prince Leopold I from his residence at Detmold. Because Leopold I had been declared incapacitated by a mental disorder in 1790, the affairs of the principality were managed under an arrangement of guardianship that had been conditionally eased in 1795. As one of the many minor principalities of Westphalia, Lippe belonged to the Lower Rhenish–Westphalian Circle and held imperial immediacy within the Empire. Its status as a principality, granted only in 1789, was still recent, and the ruling House of Lippe had already split into several branches with the main line seated at Detmold. Within a few years the wider order would be overturned, as Leopold I died in 1802 and the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806 pushed Lippe to join Napoleon's Confederation of the Rhine in 1807."},
  "kingdom of portugal": {"1800":"In 1800, Portugal was ruled in name by the incapacitated Queen Maria I, with her son Prince John governing as regent after formally assuming the title in 1799. The kingdom clung to its ancient alliance with Britain while resisting mounting pressure from Napoleonic France and its Spanish ally to close its ports to British trade. This diplomatic tightrope would break the following year in the brief War of the Oranges, when a Franco-Spanish invasion forced Portugal to cede Olivença to Spain. The court remained at Lisbon and continued to draw great wealth from Brazil, whose gold and colonial commerce underpinned royal finances. The metropolitan population stood at roughly three million, and the country's economy had been in relative decline since the mid-eighteenth century."},
  "portuguese india": {"1800":"In 1800, Portuguese India comprised the reduced coastal enclaves of Goa, Daman and Diu, administered as the Estado da Índia under a Portuguese governor. In 1800, a British detachment under the Anglo-Portuguese alliance had garrisoned Goa since 1799, guarding it against feared French seizure while the governor Francisco António da Veiga Cabral retained control of civil institutions. In 1800, the de jure capital remained Velha Goa (Old Goa), though decades of epidemic and decay had driven the government's functioning residence to Panjim (Nova Goa), where viceroys had lived since 1759. In 1800, the once-thriving city of Old Goa was largely depopulated and semi-abandoned, its administrative offices progressively relocating to Panjim over the following decades. In 1800, the territory was a modest remnant of a formerly vast maritime empire, sustained chiefly by its role as a Catholic and commercial foothold on India's western coast."},
  "wadai empire": {"1800":"In 1800, Wadai was an independent Muslim sultanate ruled from its walled capital at Wara by the Kolak dynasty. In 1800, the throne was held by Sultan Salih Derret, who reigned from about 1795 until 1803. In 1800, the state remained a middling regional power, hemmed between the stronger sultanate of Darfur and its tributary-rival Bagirmi, and had not yet undergone the expansion that would follow. In 1800, its prosperity rested on trans-Saharan caravan commerce, tribute, and slaving, with Wara's fortress-palace serving as the seat of government. In 1800, the dynastic tensions were already sharp, and within a few years Salih Derret's son Muhammad Sabun would seize power and transform Wadai into a far more assertive kingdom."},
  "rupert's land": {"1800":"In 1800, Rupert's Land remained a Hudson's Bay Company fur-trade domain rather than a governed state, with only a handful of Europeans stationed among Indigenous nations who conducted the bulk of the trade. Authority ran from the company's London governor and committee down to officers at coastal and inland posts, with York Factory serving as the principal depot and gateway to the interior. The company was locked in intense and often bitter competition with the North West Company, whose Montreal-based traders were expanding aggressively across the western interior. To meet this rivalry the Hudson's Bay Company was building more inland posts to intercept trade before it reached its competitors. No formal civil government or legislature existed, and daily life across the territory was shaped by the fur economy and relations with First Nations and emerging Métis communities."},
  "papal states": {"1800":"In 1800, the Papal States had just been resurrected after the collapse of the French-imposed Roman Republic and the death in exile of Pope Pius VI. In 1800, the newly elected Pius VII, chosen at a conclave held in Venice in March under Austrian protection, made his way to a Rome that had been recovered from French occupation. In 1800, the French Consulate under Napoleon formally acquiesced to the restoration, and the pope re-entered his capital in July to resume temporal rule. In 1800, Cardinal Ercole Consalvi was appointed Secretary of State and began reorganizing the shaken administration of the recovered territories. In 1800, however, the restored state remained fragile and dependent on the goodwill of France, a vulnerability that would culminate in renewed occupation and outright annexation within the decade."},
  "qajar persia": {"1800":"In 1800, Iran was ruled by Fath-Ali Shah Qajar, who had ascended the throne three years earlier and governed from the new capital at Tehran. The dynasty was still consolidating its hold, and the shah relied on royal princes and tribal governors to administer the provinces. Iran retained nominal authority over the khanates of the Caucasus, though Russian expansion toward Georgia was beginning to threaten this control, culminating in Russia's annexation of eastern Georgia by 1801. European powers were courting the Qajar court as the Napoleonic Wars unfolded, with Britain seeking to secure the approaches to India. The realm remained a traditional agrarian and pastoral society whose central government wielded limited direct power over distant regions."},
  "republic of lucca": {"1800":"In 1800, Lucca was a small aristocratic republic caught in the crossfire of the War of the Second Coalition, its centuries-old oligarchic constitution suspended after the French had overturned it in early 1799. In 1800, following an Austrian interlude, French forces reoccupied the city on 9 July and installed a provisional government associated with the commissioner Antoine Christophe Saliceti. In 1800, the traditional patrician bodies that had ruled through the Gonfaloniere and the Councils no longer functioned freely, the state being reshaped under French protectorate influence. In 1800, Lucca's fate hinged on the wider struggle between France and Austria for control of Tuscany and northern Italy, decided that year in France's favour. In 1800, the republic still nominally survived and would see a restored oligarchic constitution promulgated in 1801, only to be abolished by Napoleon in 1805."},
  "kingdom of spain": {"1800":"In 1800, Spain was ruled by the Bourbon king Charles IV, with government dominated by court favourites and the growing shadow of Napoleonic France. The able but controversial minister Mariano Luis de Urquijo served as First Secretary of State through most of the year until his dismissal that December, while the disgraced favourite Manuel de Godoy retained influence and would return to power in 1801. On 1 October the crown signed the Third Treaty of San Ildefonso with France, secretly agreeing to retrocede the Louisiana territory in exchange for promised compensation in Italy for the Duke of Parma. Spain remained bound to France as a junior partner in the ongoing war against Britain, its treasury strained and its fleet weakened after earlier naval defeats. Its immense American and Pacific empire still stood intact, but the metropolitan monarchy was drifting toward the crisis that would erupt in 1808."},
  "luba empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Luba Empire was ruled by the mulopwe Ilunga Sungu, whose reign of roughly 1780 to 1809 marked a peak of Luba power and expansion. In 1800, the state governed the savanna heartland around Lake Boya from its capital near Mwibele, projecting authority over a network of tributary chiefs and vassal frontier kingdoms. In 1800, its wealth rested on control of long-distance trade routes and monopolies over salt, copper, and iron passing through the Congo basin. In 1800, the sacred kingship remained bound to the Bambudye society and the ritual apparatus that legitimized the ruler as guardian of the land. In 1800, the empire had not yet felt the destabilizing East African slave and ivory raids that would later shatter it, standing instead as the preeminent power of the region."},
  "kingdom of sweden": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Sweden was ruled by the young King Gustav IV Adolf and still governed Finland as an integral eastern part of the realm. In this year the king summoned the Estates to Norrköping and confronted severe financial disorder inherited from his predecessor's Russian war, worsened by the crop failures of 1798 and 1799. Seeking to keep Sweden out of the Napoleonic conflict, Gustav IV Adolf joined the short-lived Second League of Armed Neutrality, whose founding convention of 16 December 1800 aligned Sweden with Russia and Denmark-Norway against British interference with neutral shipping. The kingdom was governed as an absolute monarchy under the framework Gustav III had established, with Stockholm as its capital and administrative heart. This precarious neutrality soon unravelled, foreshadowing the war that would cost Sweden all of Finland in 1809 and topple the king."},
  "konbaung dynasty": {"1800":"In 1800, the Konbaung dynasty was ruled by King Bodawpaya from his capital at Amarapura, which he had established as his royal seat in the early 1780s. The kingdom stood near its territorial height, having recently absorbed Arakan in 1784–1785 and consolidated control over Upper and Lower Burma. Bodawpaya presided over an ambitious, centralizing court, conducting kingdom-wide revenue and population surveys and undertaking massive religious projects such as the unfinished Mingun Pagoda. The absorption of Arakan had pushed the Burmese frontier up to the border of British-held Bengal, sowing the tensions and refugee flows that would later ignite the First Anglo-Burmese War. At this date the dynasty remained an independent and assertive regional power, its confrontation with British India still more than two decades in the future."},
  "kingdom of bagirmi": {"1800":"In 1800, Bagirmi stood as an independent Islamic sultanate ruled from Massenya by its Mbang, having recently shaken off tributary ties to Bornu. Its court presided over a Muslim ruling elite governing a population that still largely practiced indigenous religions, and its wealth rested heavily on slave-raiding against the non-Muslim peoples to its south. The state was hemmed in by two stronger powers, the older empire of Bornu to the west and the ascendant sultanate of Wadai to the east, and it maneuvered warily between them. This independence proved short-lived, for within roughly five years the Wadai ruler Sabun would sack Massenya, kill the Mbang, and force Bagirmi into vassalage. Thus 1800 marks a final interval of full sovereignty before the sultanate's long decline into tributary status."},
  "tokugawa shogunate": {"1800":"In 1800, the shogunate was led by Tokugawa Ienari, the eleventh shogun, who had taken office in 1787 and would rule until 1837 in the longest tenure of any Tokugawa shogun. In 1800, the conservative Kansei Reforms initiated by the chief councillor Matsudaira Sadanobu continued to shape policy even though Sadanobu himself had left office in 1793, promoting fiscal austerity, agricultural recovery, orthodox Neo-Confucianism, and censorship. In 1800, Japan remained under the sakoku isolation regime, with foreign trade confined largely to the Dutch and Chinese at Nagasaki, though Russian and other Western vessels were beginning to probe the northern frontiers. In 1800, the country was outwardly peaceful and Edo was among the world's largest cities, yet the samurai class and shogunal finances were increasingly strained while merchants prospered. In 1800, ultimate ceremonial authority still rested with the emperor at Kyoto, but real governing power lay with the bakufu at Edo Castle."},
  "rozvi empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Rozvi Empire was in visible decline, gripped by a catastrophic drought that struck around 1795–1800 and caused mass starvation across the plateau. The reigning mambo was Changamire Rupandamananga, nicknamed Rupengo, whose troubled reign coincided with the crisis. The famine triggered a series of civil wars that destabilized the state and persisted for at least the following decade. The empire also struggled to absorb or repel migrations of Tswana, Birwa, Hlengwe, and Karanga peoples moving through its territory. Despite these strains the Rozvi state remained intact and would endure for several more decades before the Mfecane invasions of the 1830s."},
  "kingdom of ireland": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Ireland was in personal union with Great Britain under King George III, with executive authority exercised through the Lord Lieutenant in Dublin. In 1800, the Irish Parliament in Dublin passed the Act of Union, its final major act, secured amid extensive bribery, patronage, and the granting of peerages to overcome opposition. In 1800, the country was still recovering from the bloody suppression of the 1798 rebellion of the United Irishmen and the abortive French landing at Killala. In 1800, political life remained dominated by the Protestant Ascendancy, while the promise of Catholic emancipation, dangled to win support for union, went unfulfilled because of the King's objections. In 1800, the kingdom stood on the eve of abolition, its separate parliament and statehood set to end at midnight on 31 December 1800."},
  "viceroyalty of new granada": {"1800":"In 1800, the Viceroyalty of New Granada was ruled by Viceroy Pedro Mendinueta y Múzquiz, who held office from 1797 to 1803. The colony was administered from Santa Fe de Bogotá as a mature and strategically important division of Spain's American empire. Royal revenues, buoyed by the tobacco and aguardiente monopolies, had leveled off at around three million pesos after 1800. Creole intellectual life was stirring, exemplified by the Royal Botanical Expedition and the scientific circle around José Celestino Mutis. Beneath the outward stability, resentment of Bourbon fiscal policy and peninsular privilege was mounting toward the crisis that would erupt after 1808."},
  "malabar": {"1800":"In 1800, Malabar was formally transferred from the Bombay Presidency to the Madras Presidency and administered from Calicut as a district of the Company's south Indian holdings. In 1800, the region remained deeply unsettled, as the Cotiote War against Kerala Varma Pazhassi Raja flared anew over control of the Wayanad highlands. In 1800, Company forces, later placed under officers including Arthur Wellesley, struggled to suppress guerrilla resistance across the Thalassery–Wayanad interior. In 1800, the once-powerful Zamorin of Calicut and other local rajas retained only nominal standing, their revenues and authority being absorbed into direct Company administration. In 1800, Malabar was thus a newly consolidated but turbulent frontier district of British India, its coastal ports and pepper trade prized by the Company even as rebellion persisted inland."},
  "viceroyalty of brazil": {"1800":"In 1800, Brazil was ruled from Rio de Janeiro by the viceroy Dom José Luís de Castro, 2nd Count of Resende, who had held the post since 1790. The colony remained a possession of the Portuguese crown under Queen Maria I, with Prince João acting as regent following her mental incapacity. The recently suppressed Bahia Conspiracy of 1798 still echoed as a warning of Enlightenment-inspired unrest, and colonial authorities kept a wary watch on dissent while enforcing the crown's trade monopoly. The economy leaned on plantation exports of sugar and cotton and on enslaved African labour, even as the great gold boom of Minas Gerais had passed its peak. Governance was fragmented across numerous captaincies reporting to the viceroy, whose direct authority was strongest in the south-central core around the capital."},
  "thuringian states": {"1800":"In 1800, the Thuringian lands were divided among seven small Ernestine duchies, still separate sovereign estates of the Holy Roman Empire six years before its dissolution. In 1800, Saxe-Weimar was governed by Duke Charles Augustus, who held it in personal union with Saxe-Eisenach and presided over the brilliant literary court that made Weimar the cultural capital of the German-speaking world. In 1800, the other duchies — Saxe-Gotha, Saxe-Altenburg, Saxe-Coburg-Saalfeld, Saxe-Meiningen, and Saxe-Hildburghausen — were each ruled by their own Wettin dukes, their borders an intricate mosaic produced by generations of partible inheritance. In 1800, these petty states were militarily insignificant and would soon be swept into Napoleon's orbit, acceding to the Confederation of the Rhine after 1806. In 1800, their combined territory and modest populations belied an outsized influence on European intellectual life radiating from the Weimar court."},
  "viceroyalty of peru": {"1800":"In 1800, the Viceroyalty of Peru was governed from Lima by Viceroy Ambrosio O'Higgins, 1st Marquess of Osorno, an Irish-born Spanish administrator who had risen through service in Chile before taking the viceregal office in 1796. His administration, cut short by his death in March 1801, focused on coastal defense against Britain—strengthening the fortifications of Callao amid the war declared in 1797—and on public works such as the new road linking Lima to Callao. The viceroyalty's territory had been sharply curtailed by the Bourbon Reforms, with the Río de la Plata lands gone since 1776 and Chile administered as a largely autonomous captaincy general, leaving Peru centered on its Andean and coastal heartland. Its society remained rigidly stratified between a Spanish and creole elite and a large Indigenous majority still burdened by tribute and labor obligations, with silver from mines like Cerro de Pasco anchoring the economy. Though outwardly stable and firmly loyal to the crown, the viceroyalty carried the unresolved tensions of the Túpac Amaru revolt of the previous generation, tensions that would resurface in the independence struggles of the following decades."},
  "saint-barthélemy": {"1800":"In 1800, Saint-Barthélemy was a Swedish free-port colony centred on Gustavia, governed at the turn of the year by Georg Henrik af Trolle before Hans Henrik Anckarheim took office in early 1801. Its neutral status let it thrive as a transshipment hub while the surrounding Caribbean was disrupted by the French Revolutionary Wars, drawing hundreds of merchant ships each year. The colony's economy rested on trade, warehousing, and enslaved labour rather than on sugar plantations, since the arid island could not support large-scale agriculture. Swedish authority was thin, exercised through a small garrison and colonial administration answerable to Stockholm. Within months of 1800, in March 1801, a British fleet would compel the outnumbered Swedish garrison to surrender, beginning a roughly sixteen-month British occupation."},
  "kingdom of nepal": {"1800":"In 1800, the throne was held by the infant king Girvan Yuddha Bikram Shah, who had reigned since his father Rana Bahadur Shah's abdication in March 1799. With Rana Bahadur's senior queen Rajrajeshwari away in Varanasi, the regency in Kathmandu was exercised by his junior queen, Subarnaprabha, amid a contentious court of Kajis in which Damodar Pande was the most influential figure. The deposed Rana Bahadur Shah, unable to reassert his power after most military officers sided with the courtiers, fled in May 1800 to the British-controlled city of Varanasi. The kingdom was still in an expansionist phase, holding recently conquered Kumaon and pressing its frontier westward toward Garhwal and into the Tarai lowlands. Kathmandu remained the royal capital, and the persistent factional rivalry of these years foreshadowed both the coming war with British India and the later ascendancy of Bhimsen Thapa."},
  "viceroyalty of the río de la plata": {"1800":"In 1800, the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata was an intact and fully functioning Spanish domain governed from Buenos Aires by Viceroy Gabriel de Avilés y del Fierro, the Marqués de Avilés, who had taken office in 1799. Its administration operated through the intendancy system, binding together the provinces of the Río de la Plata basin under Bourbon reformist governance. With Spain at war against Britain, the viceregal authorities focused on coastal defense and on regulating trade, including permitting neutral and foreign shipping at Buenos Aires while combating illicit commerce. The economy rested heavily on cattle ranching, hides, and the silver of Upper Peru, whose Potosí mining wealth flowed through the Atlantic port. The revolutionary crises of the British invasions and the May Revolution still lay several years ahead, leaving the viceroyalty outwardly stable and firmly under Spanish control."},
  "tuʻi tonga empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Tuʻi Tonga was Fuanunuiava, son of the earlier Tuʻi Tonga Paulaho, who had taken the title from his uncle Maʻulupekotofa around 1795 and would hold it until his death in 1810. In 1800, his role was overwhelmingly sacred and ceremonial, centered on religious obligations at the langi tomb complex and residence at Muʻa (Lapaha) on Tongatapu, with real political and military power lying elsewhere. In 1800, Tonga had just been thrown into turmoil by the 1799 assassination of the Tuʻi Kanokupolu Tukuʻaho, carried out by a faction of chiefs including Tupouniua, Finau ʻUlukālala II, and Fatafehi Fuanunuiava. In 1800, this opened a protracted civil war that set factions across Tongatapu, Haʻapai, and Vavaʻu against one another and left no single authority in control of the islands. In 1800, therefore, the \"Tuʻi Tonga Empire\" survived only as an ancient sacred title and its seat at Muʻa, no longer a functioning empire or a unified state."},
  "regency of tunis": {"1800":"In 1800, the Regency of Tunis was ruled by Hammuda ibn Ali, the capable and long-reigning fifth Husainid bey, who governed from the Bardo Palace outside Tunis. In 1800, the state was formally an Ottoman vassal but conducted its foreign and military affairs with near-complete autonomy from Constantinople. In 1800, its revenues drew on corsair raiding, which briefly revived amid the Napoleonic Wars, together with grain exports channelled through government monopolies. In 1800, tensions with the neighbouring Regency of Algiers were mounting, foreshadowing the Algerian invasions Hammuda would repel in 1807 and 1813. In 1800, Hammuda's authority remained firm, though he would later face and suppress a janissary revolt in 1811, disbanding that elite corps."},
  "regency of algiers": {"1800":"In 1800, the Regency of Algiers was ruled by Dey Mustafa Pasha, who had taken power in 1798 and governed from Algiers over a state that was de jure an Ottoman province but de facto independent. Its corsairs remained active across the Mediterranean, preying on European and later American shipping and extracting tribute and ransom from foreign powers. The dey's authority was constrained by the janissary Odjak, the guild of corsair sea captains, and largely autonomous provincial beys in Constantine, Oran, and Titteri. This period was marked by political instability and economic strain, and failed harvests would bring famine from 1803 to 1805. Mustafa Pasha survived plots against him in 1801 and 1804 before being assassinated by the Odjak in August 1805."},
  "spanish philippines": {"1800":"In 1800, the Captaincy General of the Philippines was governed by Rafael María de Aguilar y Ponce de León, who had held office since 1793 and would become the longest-serving Spanish governor of the colony. The territory remained administratively dependent on the Viceroyalty of New Spain, with Manila serving as its seat of government, commerce, and ecclesiastical authority. Aguilar's Enlightenment-influenced administration prioritized defense, reinforcing fortifications and, in that very year, establishing a Naval Command to monitor foreign vessels entering the archipelago. Spanish authority was concentrated in Luzon and the Visayas, while the Muslim sultanates of Mindanao and Sulu remained largely beyond effective colonial control. The Manila galleon trade with Acapulco still operated, though its long dominance was beginning to wane amid the wider disruptions of the Napoleonic era in Europe."},
  "regency of tripoli": {"1800":"In 1800, the Regency of Tripoli was ruled by Yusuf Karamanli, who had held power since 1795 and governed as an autonomous pasha under nominal Ottoman suzerainty. Its economy still depended heavily on corsairing and the tribute European and American governments paid to protect their shipping from Tripolitan raiders. The regency had signed the Treaty of Tripoli with the United States in 1796, but relations were deteriorating as Yusuf pressed for larger payments. Within a year these tensions would erupt into the First Barbary War, which Yusuf effectively opened in May 1801 by having the flagpole at the American consulate cut down. The state was thus a small but assertive Barbary power, wealthy from maritime coercion yet increasingly exposed to the naval strength of rising Western nations."},
  "joseon": {"1800":"In 1800, the reform-minded King Jeongjo died suddenly of an abscess, cutting short a reign noted for scholarship, the Kyujanggak royal library, and efforts to balance the court factions. He was succeeded by his ten-year-old son Sunjo, so effective power passed to the Grand Queen Dowager Jeongsun, who ruled as regent on the young king's behalf. Aligning with the conservative Noron faction, the regency moved swiftly against political rivals and Catholic converts, setting the stage for the Sinyu Catholic Persecution that erupted the following year in 1801. The kingdom remained a tributary of Qing China under the sadae framework while continuing its guarded, isolationist posture toward the wider world. This transition also marked the beginning of a long era of in-law clan domination, as powerful lineages such as the Andong Kim increasingly controlled the court around the boy-king."},
  "zanzibar": {"1800":"In 1800, Zanzibar was a dependency of the Al Bu Sa'id Sultanate of Oman, then ruled from Muscat by Sultan bin Ahmad, and administered locally by an Omani governor from Zanzibar Town. The island served as the principal Busaidi base and entrepot on the East African coast, its commerce increasingly funneled through Indian merchants and financiers. Busaidi authority extended over Unguja, Pemba, Kilwa, and Lamu, but the rival Mazrui family still held Mombasa in defiance of the Omani sultan. The clove-plantation economy that would later define the island had not yet developed, and the coast's wealth rested chiefly on the trade in slaves, ivory, and goods passing between the interior and the wider Indian Ocean world. The sovereign Sultanate of Zanzibar did not yet exist, that separation from Oman lying more than half a century in the future."},
  "lunda empire": {"1800":"In 1800, the Lunda Empire was an independent and powerful African state governed by the Mwata Yamvo, with Nawej II a Ditend beginning his long reign around this time. In 1800, the court resided at the great royal capital of Musumba, a fortified center of paved courtyards, earthen walls, and thousands of retainers from which the king ruled a wide network of tributary chiefs. In 1800, the empire's prosperity rested on its monopolistic control of caravan trade, exporting ivory and captives westward to Portuguese and Luso-African traders and receiving cloth, guns, and other goods in return. In 1800, the Lunda system of provincial governors and tribute collectors held together a vast confederation, while satellite kingdoms like that of the Mwata Kazembe recognized the Lunda origin of their own ruling houses. In 1800, the Chokwe who would later shatter the empire were still largely subordinate hunters and clients, so Lunda authority over the region remained essentially intact and unchallenged by European powers."},
  "spanish louisiana": {"1800":"In 1800, Spanish Louisiana remained under Spanish administration governed from New Orleans, with the Marquess of Casa Calvo serving as interim governor after Manuel Gayoso de Lemos died in 1799. In 1800, on October 1, Spain and Napoleonic France secretly signed the Third Treaty of San Ildefonso, agreeing to retrocede the colony to France in exchange for Italian territory. In 1800, this transfer stayed hidden and unexecuted, so Spanish officials, law, and garrisons continued to run the province day to day. In 1800, New Orleans thrived as a busy river and Gulf port, its trade increasingly bound up with the expanding United States upriver. In 1800, the colony faced growing pressure from American settlers pressing westward and from disputes over navigation rights and the deposit at New Orleans."},
  "rajput states": {"1800":"In 1800, Rajputana was a patchwork of separate Rajput kingdoms rather than one state, each ruled by its own maharaja and locked in mutual rivalry. Jaipur was ruled by Sawai Pratap Singh, Marwar (Jodhpur) by Bhim Singh, and Mewar (Udaipur) by its own Bhim Singh of the Sisodia line. The Marathas under Daulat Rao Sindhia and Yashwant Rao Holkar dominated the region, exacting heavy tributes and periodically ravaging the countryside, while Pindari bands added to the devastation. The states had by this date appealed to the British East India Company for protection, but the Company's policy of non-interference meant those requests were refused. Their courts were beset by succession disputes and financial exhaustion, leaving them unable to resist Maratha extortion in the years around 1800."},
  "sultanate of brunei": {"1800":"In 1800, Brunei was an independent sultanate ruled by Sultan Muhammad Tajuddin, whose reign spanned the turn of the century. By this date its once-vast maritime empire had shrunk to control of northwestern Borneo, with outlying claims contested by the rival Sultanate of Sulu. The court maintained the traditional apparatus of a Malay monarchy centered on the sultan and his senior nobles, and Muhammad Tajuddin pursued diplomacy abroad, sending envoys to China to promote Brunei's trade and to the Spanish authorities in Manila. Its economy still rested on regional maritime commerce, tribute from dependencies, and the export of forest and jungle produce. European colonial encroachment and coastal piracy already pressed on the state, foreshadowing the sharper territorial losses that would come after 1841."},
  "kingdom of kandy": {"1800":"In 1800, the Kingdom of Kandy stood as the last independent native state on the island, ruled by the young Nayak king Sri Vikrama Rajasinha, who had been crowned in 1798 at about eighteen. Its coastal lowlands were by then held by the British East India Company, which had displaced the Dutch in 1796 and administered the maritime provinces under Governor Frederick North. Real power at court was contested between the king and his chief minister, the Adigar Pilima Talawe, whose intrigues shaped Kandyan policy toward the British. Tensions with the Company over trade and detained subjects were mounting toward open conflict, which broke out in the First Kandyan War of 1803. The kingdom's rugged interior, its guardianship of the Tooth Relic, and the divided loyalties of its Kandyan aristocracy defined its precarious survival in these years."},
  "lao kingdoms": {"1800":"In 1800, the three Lao kingdoms all stood as tributary vassals of Siam under the newly established Chakri dynasty in Bangkok. Luang Prabang was ruled by King Anurutha, who had been held hostage in Bangkok and only permitted to return to reign in 1792 under Siamese overlordship. Vientiane was governed by King Inthavong, who had succeeded his deposed brother Nanthasen in 1795 and ruled as a loyal Siamese tributary. Champasak in the south was under King Fay Na, installed in 1791 and likewise subordinate to Bangkok, which controlled the succession and demanded tribute from all three courts. Each king retained internal authority over his own realm, but real sovereignty lay with Siam, and the future rebel Anouvong—then serving under Inthavong—had not yet risen to the Vientiane throne."},
  "sultanate of morocco": {"1800":"In 1800, Morocco was an independent sovereign sultanate ruled by Moulay Slimane of the Alaouite dynasty, who had held the throne since 1792. In 1800, his authority extended southward as the inhabitants of the Tuat oases agreed to pay taxes to the sultan, strengthening the reach and revenue of the Makhzen. In 1800, Slimane pursued a policy of centralization, having recently recovered Oujda and the eastern provinces from the Turks in 1798 and fixed the border at the Wadi Kiss. In 1800, he had restricted trade with the European powers after reversing his father's overseas commerce policy, amid tensions with Spain and Portugal, while maintaining cordial relations with the young United States. In 1800, Fez served as his principal capital, from which the court and army governed a realm of largely autonomous tribes."},
  "madras presidency": {"1800":"In 1800, the Presidency of Fort St George was governed by Edward Clive, who served as Governor of Madras from 1798 to 1803. It had just emerged victorious from the Fourth Anglo-Mysore War of 1799, in which the storming of Seringapatam ended the reign of Tipu Sultan and removed the Company's most formidable southern adversary. In this year the Nizam of Hyderabad ceded the districts of Rayalaseema, the so-called Ceded Districts, to the Company in return for the maintenance of British troops under the subsidiary alliance system. The Nawab of Arcot still nominally held the Carnatic, though his effective independence was on the verge of extinction and his territory would be annexed the following year in 1801. The presidency thus stood as the dominant British power across the Coromandel coast and much of the Deccan interior, administered from Fort St George at Madras."},
  "kingdom of travancore": {"1800":"In 1800, Travancore was ruled by the young Maharaja Balarama Varma, who had ascended the throne in February 1798 as a teenager. In 1800, effective administrative power lay largely with the Dalawa (chief minister), with Velu Thampi rising to prominence at court amid the intrigues of the young ruler's minority. In 1800, the kingdom was bound to the British East India Company by the subsidiary treaty concluded in 1795, obliging it to maintain a Company force and pay a subsidy. In 1800, the seat of government was Thiruvananthapuram, to which the capital had been transferred from Padmanabhapuram in 1795, though the older fortified palace remained an important residence. In 1800, mounting subsidy arrears and friction with the Company Resident were building the tensions that would culminate in the fuller Subsidiary Alliance of 1805 and Velu Thampi's revolt at the decade's end."}
};

/* 1700-era per-state year paragraphs (deep-merged so existing years are untouched). */
(function(Y){var A={"kingdom of france":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of France was ruled by Louis XIV, then near the height of his personal reign, with his court and government seated at the Palace of Versailles. On 1 November 1700 Charles II of Spain died childless, leaving a will that bequeathed the entire Spanish inheritance to Louis XIV's grandson, Philip, Duke of Anjou. After deliberation, Louis accepted the inheritance on his grandson's behalf, and Philip was proclaimed Philip V of Spain in mid-November, raising the prospect of Bourbon dominance over both France and Spain. This acceptance alarmed the other European powers, above all Austria, England, and the Dutch Republic, who formed a Grand Alliance against a united Bourbon bloc. The dispute over the succession triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, which opened in 1701 and would dominate the final phase of Louis XIV's reign."},"kingdom of spain":{"1700":"In 1700, the Spanish monarchy was ruled by the ailing and childless Charles II, the last Habsburg king, whose long decline had left the succession the central question of European diplomacy. Persuaded by his advisers, notably Cardinal Portocarrero, he willed the undivided monarchy to Philip of Anjou, grandson of Louis XIV of France, before dying on 1 November 1700 at the age of thirty-eight. Philip was proclaimed King Philip V on 16 November 1700, inaugurating Bourbon rule over Spain and its empire. The prospect of a Franco-Spanish dynastic union alarmed the other great powers, and within months England, the Dutch Republic, and Emperor Leopold I, who backed the rival Habsburg Archduke Charles, began forming the Grand Alliance. These tensions ignited the War of the Spanish Succession the following year, opening a long struggle whose Iberian theatre would leave lasting divisions within Spain."},"kingdom of portugal":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Portugal was ruled by King Pedro II of the House of Braganza, who had reigned since 1683 and was steadily centralizing royal power at the expense of the old nobility. The kingdom stood at peace and secure in its independence, guaranteed by the 1668 Treaty of Lisbon and buttressed by a long-standing alliance with England. The recent discovery of gold in the Brazilian interior of Minas Gerais was beginning to funnel new wealth into the crown's finances and reshape the Atlantic economy. Portugal's diplomacy at this moment leaned cautiously toward France and Spain, with Louis XIV's grandson newly installed as Philip V in Madrid. Within a few years this alignment would reverse through the Methuen treaties of 1703, drawing Portugal into the Grand Alliance and the War of the Spanish Succession."},"kingdom of england":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of England was ruled by William III of Orange, who had reigned alone since the death of his co-monarch and wife Mary II in 1694, following the Glorious Revolution that had established a constitutional settlement grounded in the Bill of Rights of 1689. England held the Kingdom of Ireland in personal union under William and shared its monarch with the separate Kingdom of Scotland, while Parliament exercised growing authority over taxation, the army, and the succession. On 30 July 1700 Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, the only surviving child of the heir presumptive Princess Anne, died at the age of eleven, throwing the Protestant succession into crisis and prompting Parliament the following year to pass the Act of Settlement, which vested the succession in Sophia, Electress of Hanover, and her Protestant heirs. Abroad, the death of the childless Charles II of Spain in November 1700 and the acceptance by Louis XIV of the Spanish throne for his grandson Philip of Anjou threatened to upset the European balance of power. These developments led William to work toward a renewed Grand Alliance against France, setting the stage for the War of the Spanish Succession that would break out in 1701."},"kingdom of scotland":{"1700":"In 1700, Scotland was ruled by King William II, who reigned simultaneously as William III of England under the post-1603 union of crowns, while remaining governed by its own Parliament and Privy Council at Edinburgh. The nation was reeling from the \"seven ill years\" of famine in the late 1690s and, above all, from the collapse of the Darien scheme, the Company of Scotland's attempt to plant the colony of New Caledonia on the Isthmus of Panama. The second and final Darien expedition capitulated to a besieging Spanish force and abandoned the settlement in the spring of 1700, wiping out an enormous share of Scotland's mobile capital. William's refusal to lend English or Dutch support to the venture deepened Scottish resentment, and organised addresses to Parliament protested the government's failure to back the colony. This economic ruin and political grievance intensified pressure toward an incorporating union with England, which was ultimately concluded in 1707 under William's successor, Queen Anne."},"dutch republic":{"1700":"In 1700, the Dutch Republic was led by stadtholder William III of Orange, who since 1689 was simultaneously King of England, Scotland, and Ireland, an arrangement binding Dutch and English foreign policy closely together. The Republic remained one of Europe's foremost commercial and naval powers, though its economic primacy was beginning to be challenged and the strain of decades of war against France weighed heavily on its finances. The death of the childless Spanish king Charles II in November 1700 triggered the succession crisis that would become the War of the Spanish Succession, prompting William to organize resistance to French ambitions. Dutch, English, and Austrian negotiators concluded the Treaty of The Hague in 1701, reconstituting the Grand Alliance against Louis XIV of France. William III died in March 1702 shortly after the alliance formed, and because he left no heir the provinces of Holland, Zeeland, and Utrecht left the stadtholderate vacant, beginning the Second Stadtholderless Period."},"holy roman empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Holy Roman Empire was headed by Emperor Leopold I of the House of Habsburg, who had reigned since 1658 and also ruled the Austrian hereditary lands, Bohemia, and Hungary. The Empire remained a fragmented confederation of roughly three hundred states whose common affairs were deliberated by the Perpetual Imperial Diet, which had sat continuously at Regensburg since 1663. That year saw a pivotal succession crisis when the childless Habsburg king Charles II of Spain died in November, bequeathing the entire Spanish inheritance to Philip of Anjou, a grandson of Louis XIV of France. Leopold refused to accept this settlement and pressed the rival claim of his son Archduke Charles, setting the stage for the War of the Spanish Succession that erupted in 1701. In the same period Leopold, needing military support, agreed to recognize the Elector of Brandenburg as King in Prussia, a title assumed at Königsberg in January 1701."},"habsburg monarchy":{"1700":"In 1700, the Habsburg Monarchy was ruled from Vienna by Emperor Leopold I, who had reigned since 1657 over the composite realm of the Austrian hereditary lands, the Bohemian crownlands, and the Kingdom of Hungary. The monarchy had just emerged victorious from the Great Turkish War, and the Treaty of Karlowitz in January 1699 confirmed its recovery of nearly all of Hungary, Transylvania, Croatia, and Slavonia from the Ottoman Empire after Prince Eugene of Savoy's decisive victory at Zenta in 1697. These gains established the dynasty as the dominant power in Central Europe and doubled the effective size of its Hungarian domains. The death of the childless Charles II of Spain in November 1700, who bequeathed his entire inheritance to Louis XIV's grandson Philip of Anjou, shattered hopes of a peaceful partition and set Leopold to press the rival Habsburg claim on behalf of his son, Archduke Charles. This dispute drew the monarchy into the War of the Spanish Succession, whose opening campaigns in northern Italy began in 1701, committing Vienna to a long struggle against Bourbon France."},"brandenburg-prussia":{"1700":"In 1700, Brandenburg-Prussia was governed from Berlin by Elector Frederick III of the House of Hohenzollern, who had ruled since 1688. That November, he secured the Crown Treaty of 16 November 1700, in which Emperor Leopold I approved his elevation to royal rank in exchange for a Prussian alliance and troops in the coming War of the Spanish Succession. The state remained a scattered composite of Brandenburg, Ducal Prussia, and Rhenish and other exclaves, defended by the professional standing army inherited from the Great Elector. Frederick cultivated a lavish court in the French style and supported learning, having founded the Academy of Arts (1696) and the Academy of Sciences (1700). Just after this map year, on 18 January 1701, he crowned himself King Frederick I \"in Prussia\" at Königsberg, converting the electorate into the Kingdom of Prussia."},"polish–lithuanian commonwealth":{"1700":"In 1700, the Commonwealth was ruled by King Augustus II the Strong, who had been elected in 1697 while also reigning as Elector of Saxony. Although Augustus launched an invasion of Swedish Livonia and besieged Riga at the start of the year, he did so chiefly as Elector of Saxony, and the Commonwealth itself remained formally neutral as the Great Northern War opened against Sweden's young king Charles XII. The Polish–Lithuanian Sejm and Senate were deeply reluctant to be drawn into the conflict, reflecting the political fragmentation and weakness of the elective monarchy. That same year Lithuania was convulsed by civil war, as the Sapieha magnate family was decisively defeated by a coalition of rival nobles at the Battle of Olkieniki in November 1700. These strains presaged the Swedish invasion of the following years, which would see Augustus dethroned and replaced by Stanisław Leszczyński in 1704."},"tsardom of russia":{"1700":"In 1700, the Tsardom of Russia was ruled by Tsar Peter I, later known as Peter the Great, who governed from Moscow as St. Petersburg had not yet been founded. That year Russia entered the Great Northern War, joining Denmark-Norway and Saxony-Poland in a coalition against the Swedish Empire of the young Charles XII. Russian forces invaded Swedish Estonia and laid siege to the fortress of Narva in the autumn. On 30 November 1700 the numerically superior Russian army was routed at the Battle of Narva by a much smaller Swedish force under Charles XII, losing its artillery train and suffering heavy casualties. The disaster spurred Peter to accelerate his sweeping military, administrative, and cultural reforms aimed at modernizing the state along Western European lines."},"kingdom of sweden":{"1700":"In 1700, Sweden was an absolute monarchy at the peak of its imperial power, ruled by the eighteen-year-old Charles XII, who had inherited the crown in 1697 and the unchecked royal authority built up by his father Charles XI. Its Baltic empire encompassed present-day Finland, Estonia, Livonia, Ingria, and German territories such as Swedish Pomerania and Bremen-Verden, governed from Stockholm. That year a hostile coalition of Denmark-Norway, Saxony-Poland-Lithuania, and Russia attacked the young king's dominions, opening the Great Northern War. Charles swiftly forced Denmark-Norway out of the alliance with the Peace of Travendal in August, securing his ally Holstein-Gottorp. In November he marched to relieve besieged Narva and routed a Russian army several times the size of his own, a stunning victory that cemented his reputation as a warrior-king."},"denmark–norway":{"1700":"In 1700, Denmark–Norway was ruled by King Frederick IV of the House of Oldenburg, who had acceded on his father Christian V's death in August 1699 and was anointed at Frederiksborg in April 1700. As part of an anti-Swedish coalition with Russia and Saxony-Poland, Danish forces opened the Great Northern War in March by invading Sweden's ally Holstein-Gottorp and besieging its fortresses. The young Swedish king Charles XII responded with a bold counterstroke, using Anglo-Dutch naval support to land an army on the island of Zealand and threaten Copenhagen directly. Caught undefended, Frederick IV was compelled to sign the Peace of Travendal on 18 August 1700, forcing Denmark–Norway out of the war, obliging it to restore Holstein-Gottorp and pay a war indemnity. Withdrawn from the conflict, Frederick spent the following years reforming the army into a militia raised from the peasantry and did not re-enter the war until after Sweden's catastrophic defeat at Poltava in 1709."},"swiss confederation":{"1700":"In 1700, the Swiss Confederation was a league of thirteen cantons together with numerous allied and subject territories, still without any single ruler or capital and coordinated only through the periodic Tagsatzung. Its politics were paralyzed by the confessional split between Catholic and Protestant cantons, which had begun holding largely separate councils and left the common diet deadlocked. The cantons were governed internally by entrenched patrician and guild oligarchies characteristic of the ancien régime, and many maintained close ties with Louis XIV's France, to whom they supplied mercenary regiments. Tensions in the Toggenburg valley under the Prince-Abbot of St. Gall were building toward open conflict, which erupted in the Second War of Villmergen in 1712 and ended with a decisive Protestant, Zürich- and Bern-led victory that shifted the confederacy's balance of power. Abroad the Confederation held to its policy of armed neutrality even as the War of the Spanish Succession engulfed surrounding Europe."},"papal states":{"1700":"In 1700, the Papal States were ruled by Pope Innocent XII, the reforming pontiff who had abolished the office of cardinal-nephew, until his death on 27 September of that year. The vacancy opened a conclave that sat from October into November and elected Cardinal Giovanni Francesco Albani, who took the name Clement XI on 23 November 1700. That same year Rome hosted a great Jubilee, or Holy Year, drawing pilgrims to the city even as the state struggled with grain shortages and the demographic stagnation that had gripped it since the previous century. On 1 November 1700 King Charles II of Spain died childless, and the resulting dispute over his inheritance soon plunged Europe and the Italian peninsula into the War of the Spanish Succession. Governed as an elective theocratic monarchy from Rome, the papacy sought to preserve its neutrality but found its central-Italian territory dangerously exposed as Habsburg and Bourbon armies prepared to contest the peninsula."},"republic of venice":{"1700":"In 1700, the Republic of Venice was ruled at the start of the year by Doge Silvestro Valier, the 109th doge, who died on 7 July 1700 and was succeeded by Alvise II Mocenigo, elected on 17 July 1700. The republic had recently concluded the long Morean War against the Ottoman Empire, and by the Treaty of Karlowitz of January 1699 it retained the Morea (the Peloponnese), which it organized as the \"Kingdom of the Morea,\" along with Aegina and gains in Dalmatia. Despite this territorial expansion, many Venetians felt the acquisitions poorly compensated for the war's enormous cost in lives and money, and the state remained in structural decline. Facing the outbreak of the War of the Spanish Succession, Venice adhered firmly to a policy of neutrality, rebuffing both French and Habsburg efforts to draw it into alliance. Behind this diplomatic caution the republic continued to live in famed splendour, even as its Mediterranean power and commercial primacy ebbed."},"republic of genoa":{"1700":"In 1700, the Republic of Genoa was governed by Doge Girolamo De Mari, who held the customary style of \"King of Corsica,\" while effective authority lay with the patrician oligarchy and the great families of the Genoese aristocracy. The state was a wealthy but politically declining maritime republic, still a significant banking centre tied closely to Spanish and Bourbon finance, yet long past its era of Mediterranean naval dominance. Its position had been made precarious by the French bombardment of the city in 1684 and the doge's humiliating apology to Louis XIV at Versailles in 1685, leaving Genoa firmly within the French sphere of influence. The death of the childless King Charles II of Spain in November 1700 triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, and Genoa proclaimed a formal neutrality that it struggled to defend as rival armies crossed its territory. That neutrality was compromised in practice by Bourbon pressure, with the government permitting the passage of French battalions through Genoese lands even as it sought to keep the republic out of the wider conflict."},"kingdom of naples":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Naples was a viceroyalty of the Spanish Empire, governed from Naples by the viceroy Luis Francisco de la Cerda y Aragón, 9th Duke of Medinaceli. On 1 November 1700 the childless Habsburg king Charles II of Spain died, bequeathing his dominions—including Naples—to the French Bourbon prince Philip V, a succession that helped precipitate the War of the Spanish Succession. Many Neapolitan nobles resented the transfer of allegiance to the Bourbons and favored the rival Austrian Habsburg claimant, fostering pro-Austrian sentiment in the kingdom. This discontent erupted in 1701 in the Conspiracy of Macchia, an aristocratic uprising aimed at handing the kingdom to the Austrian line, which the Duke of Medinaceli suppressed. The kingdom remained under Spanish Bourbon control at this point, but it would be conquered by Austrian Imperial forces in 1707 during the ongoing war."},"kingdom of sicily":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Sicily was ruled by Charles II of Spain, the last Habsburg king of Spain, and governed on the island by the viceroy Pedro Manuel Colón de Portugal, 7th Duke of Veragua, from his seat at Palermo. The kingdom was a distinct realm within the composite Spanish monarchy, administered separately from the neighbouring Kingdom of Naples and still recovering from the catastrophic 1693 Val di Noto earthquake, whose reconstruction was producing the Sicilian Baroque. On 1 November 1700 the childless Charles II died in Madrid, bequeathing the entire Spanish inheritance, including Sicily, to Philip of Anjou, who became Philip V of the House of Bourbon. This disputed succession ignited the War of the Spanish Succession, pitting the Bourbon claimant against the Austrian Habsburg archduke Charles and their respective allies. Sicily remained under Bourbon-Spanish administration during these opening years of the conflict, only to be ceded to the House of Savoy in 1713 by the Treaty of Utrecht."},"duchy of savoy":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Savoy was ruled from Turin by Duke Victor Amadeus II, who had reigned since 1675 and was pursuing a program of administrative centralization and military strengthening. At the turn of the century the death of the childless Spanish king Charles II and the disputed Bourbon succession drew the duchy into the diplomatic manoeuvring that preceded the War of the Spanish Succession. Savoy was then aligned with France, and in 1701 Victor Amadeus II formally allied with Louis XIV, a bond sealed by the marriage of his daughter Maria Luisa to the new Bourbon king of Spain, Philip V. His true ambition, however, was the neighbouring Duchy of Milan, and mounting French distrust of his loyalty foreshadowed the rupture to come. That break arrived in October 1703, when Victor Amadeus II abandoned France for the Grand Alliance, a switch that soon exposed his lands to French invasion and the celebrated 1706 siege of Turin."},"kingdom of sardinia":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Sardinia was a Spanish possession governed by a viceroy from Cagliari and still bound to the Spanish crown at the death of the childless Habsburg king Charles II on 1 November of that year. Charles's will bequeathed the entire Spanish inheritance, Sardinia included, to Philip of Anjou, who became King Philip V, while Emperor Leopold I advanced a rival Habsburg claim to the Italian possessions. Sardinia's Spanish governors initially remained loyal to the new Bourbon regime, and an early pro-Habsburg stirring on the island was suppressed. The dispute over the succession escalated into the War of the Spanish Succession, which would soon draw the island into the wider European conflict. In 1708 a British fleet would capture Cagliari and hand the kingdom to the Habsburg claimant, but in 1700 itself the island remained quietly under Bourbon-Spanish control."},"duchy of milan":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Milan was a possession of the Spanish crown, governed at Milan by Prince Charles Henry de Lorraine-Vaudémont, who had held the post since 1698. Its nominal sovereign was Charles II of Spain, the last Habsburg king of Spain, until his death in November 1700 without an heir. Charles had willed the entire Spanish inheritance to Philip of Anjou, grandson of Louis XIV, while Emperor Leopold I advanced the rival claim of his son, Archduke Charles of Austria, making the wealthy and strategically vital duchy a central prize in the looming struggle. The resulting War of the Spanish Succession broke out in 1701, and imperial forces under Prince Eugene of Savoy campaigned in Lombardy against the Franco-Spanish garrisons. At the turn of the century the duchy remained a prosperous Lombard state burdened by heavy Spanish wartime taxation, its fate soon to be decided by the fall of Milan to Austrian arms in 1706."},"duchy of modena":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Modena and Reggio was ruled by Duke Rinaldo d'Este, who had left a cardinalate to succeed his nephew Francesco II in 1694. Having married Charlotte Felicitas of Brunswick-Lüneburg in 1696, Rinaldo cultivated ties to the German princely houses and the Habsburgs in hope of protection for his exposed state. The duchy was a minor power in the Po valley, financially strained and militarily weak, and increasingly caught between France and Austria as the childless Spanish king Charles II's death in November 1700 set the stage for a European succession war. When the War of the Spanish Succession erupted in 1701–1702, Rinaldo declared neutrality, but this failed to spare Modena, which French troops occupied while he fled to Bologna. He would not be restored to his capital until 1707, after German forces expelled the French, a settlement that later brought him the Duchy of Mirandola while costing him Comacchio."},"duchy of parma and piacenza":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Parma and Piacenza was ruled by Francesco Farnese, the seventh Farnese duke, who had succeeded his father Ranuccio II in 1694 at the age of sixteen. He had inherited a state left deeply in debt by his predecessor's extravagant court and had responded with austerity, dismissing servants, musicians, and entertainers and curbing lavish court expenditure. The death of the childless Charles II of Spain in 1700 triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, which soon spilled into northern Italy and threatened the small, landlocked duchy. Anxious to keep foreign armies off his lands, Francesco adopted a policy of strict neutrality, though Imperial forces under Prince Eugene of Savoy nonetheless moved through and occupied parts of the Farnese territories. The Habsburg emperor promised compensation for these intrusions but later reneged, instead asserting that Parma was an Imperial fief, leaving the young duke in a weak and exposed diplomatic position."},"republic of lucca":{"1700":"In 1700, the Republic of Lucca was a small, independent oligarchic city-state governed not by a single prince but by the collegial Anziani, or Council of Elders, presided over by a Gonfaloniere who, like his colleagues, served only a brief two-month term to prevent any one family's dominance. Its ruling class had been sealed shut by the constitutional reform of 1628, which registered a closed hereditary patriciate of a few hundred noble families in an official roll and reserved all offices and the seats of the General Council to them. Hemmed in by the Medici Grand Duchy of Tuscany under Cosimo III, the republic clung to strict neutrality and cautious diplomacy, and a friction with Tuscany around this time reportedly obliged it to disburse heavy sums to secure Spanish and Imperial protection. As the great powers drifted toward the War of the Spanish Succession, which erupted in 1701 and drew armies into northern Italy, Lucca guarded its treasured \"Libertas\" by staying out of the fighting and relying on its fortified walls and careful statecraft rather than arms. Its economy still rested on the silk manufacture and banking that had long made the city famous, though this trade was gradually eroding under competition from Lyon and other rising centers."},"republic of geneva":{"1700":"In 1700, the Republic of Geneva was an independent, self-governing Calvinist city-state led not by a prince but by its four Syndics and the patrician Small Council, with no single ruler above them. The city was a prosperous commercial and banking centre and a stronghold of Reformed Protestantism, still absorbing the economic and cultural impact of Huguenot refugees who had passed through or settled after Louis XIV's revocation of the Edict of Nantes in 1685, notably strengthening its watchmaking trade. It remained an ally of the Protestant Swiss cantons of Bern and Zürich while staying formally outside the Confederation, and it warily guarded its independence against neighbouring Catholic France and Savoy. Beneath its stability, resentment was growing among the citizenry against the entrenched oligarchy's monopoly on power, tensions that would erupt in the 1707 movement led by the lawyer Pierre Fatio, who demanded a greater role for the General Council and was executed for it. The wider War of the Spanish Succession, which broke out in 1701, heightened the strategic anxieties of the small republic wedged between France and Savoy."},"medici grand duchy of tuscany":{"1700":"In 1700, the Grand Duchy of Tuscany was ruled from Florence by Cosimo III de' Medici, whose long reign had brought severe economic decline, crushing taxes, a decayed customs system, and stern religious and moral legislation. The death of the childless Charles II of Spain in November 1700 triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, in which Cosimo III kept Tuscany officially neutral while remaining a nominal Spanish vassal for the Sienese fief. He recognized Philip of Anjou as the new king of Spain and sought to protect his exposed state from the surrounding great-power conflict. At home, the Grand Duke faced a deepening succession crisis, for neither his elder son Ferdinando nor his other children had produced heirs, and his efforts to secure the line through Gian Gastone's marriage and his daughter Anna Maria Luisa proved fruitless. The court's piety and rigidity, combined with demographic contraction from earlier plagues and continuing fiscal exhaustion, left Tuscany one of the poorer and more inward-looking states of Europe as the new century began."},"ottoman empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Ottoman Empire was ruled by Sultan Mustafa II, who was recovering from the disastrous Great Turkish War that had ended the previous year. The Treaty of Karlowitz, signed in January 1699, had forced the empire to cede Hungary and Transylvania to Habsburg Austria, the Morea and most of Dalmatia to Venice, and Podolia to Poland, marking its first major territorial losses after centuries of expansion in Europe. In 1700 the accompanying Treaty of Constantinople ceded the fortress of Azov to Peter the Great's Russia, sealing the empire's retreat on its northern frontier. Under the grand vizier Amcazade Köprülü Hüseyin Pasha, the government pursued fiscal and military reforms, reducing wartime taxes on essentials such as tobacco, coffee, soap, and cooking oil while attempting to purge and retrain the janissary corps. The sultan spent much of this period residing at Edirne rather than the capital, a growing source of resentment that would culminate in his deposition during the Edirne Incident of 1703."},"qing dynasty":{"1700":"In 1700, the Qing empire was ruled by the Kangxi Emperor, then in his mid-forties and nearly four decades into his sixty-one-year reign, governing from Peking. The dynasty had entered a durable peace after crushing the Revolt of the Three Feudatories in 1681 and annexing the Zheng regime's Taiwan in 1683, consolidating Manchu control over China proper, Manchuria, and the newly submitted Khalkha Mongols. The Treaty of Nerchinsk with Russia in 1689 had fixed the northeastern frontier, and the defeat of the Dzungar leader Galdan at Jao Modo in 1696, followed by his death in 1697, secured Outer Mongolia, though the Dzungars remained a rival power in the west. Kangxi presided over an era of recovery and cultural patronage, even as the lingering Kangxi Depression in silver and grain prices shaped the rural economy. The empire had not yet incorporated Xinjiang or established firm authority over Tibet, both of which came in the following decades."},"mughal empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Mughal Empire was ruled by its sixth emperor, Aurangzeb (Alamgir I), then in his eighties and near the height of the empire's territorial reach across the subcontinent. Though Shahjahanabad (Delhi) remained the empire's nominal capital and dynastic seat, Aurangzeb had resided in the Deccan since 1681, running his government from a vast mobile camp centered on Aurangabad while waging his prolonged war against the Marathas. The Deccan campaigns strained the empire's finances and armies even as its maps looked most impressive, and Aurangzeb's court spent these years besieging Maratha hill forts. In March 1700 the Maratha ruler Rajaram died, leaving his infant son Shivaji II under the regency of his widow Tarabai, who continued the resistance rather than collapsing. Mughal forces pressed the war, capturing the fortress of Satara after a long siege in April 1700, yet Maratha guerrilla raids persisted and would ultimately outlast Aurangzeb, who died in 1707."},"safavid empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Safavid Empire was ruled from Isfahan by Shah Sultan Husayn, who had acceded in 1694 and was a pious, pleasure-loving monarch with little interest in governing. The Shia clergy held commanding influence at court, their ascendancy consolidated under the recently deceased Mohammad Baqir Majlisi, and it shaped a rigid religious policy hostile to Sunnis, Sufis, Zoroastrians, and other minorities. The court's extravagance depleted the treasury while the frontier provinces grew restive and poorly defended. Baluch raiders had penetrated toward Kerman, prompting the appointment of the Georgian prince Gorgin Khan as governor to restore order in the southeast. These strains foreshadowed the Ghilzai Afghan revolt at Kandahar that would erupt within the decade and ultimately bring down the dynasty."},"tokugawa shogunate":{"1700":"In 1700, the shogunate was ruled from Edo by the fifth shogun, Tokugawa Tsunayoshi, while Emperor Higashiyama reigned as a ceremonial figurehead at Kyoto. Tsunayoshi increasingly delegated affairs to his grand chamberlain Yanagisawa Yoshiyasu and was notorious for the Laws of Compassion, the animal-protection edicts that earned him the nickname the \"Dog Shogun.\" The country was in the midst of the Genroku era, a peak of urban prosperity, kabuki and puppet theater, ukiyo-e printmaking, and the writing of Ihara Saikaku, Chikamatsu Monzaemon, and Matsuo Bashō. The sakoku isolation regime remained firmly in force, confining foreign trade to supervised Dutch and Chinese contact at Nagasaki and to Korea and the Ryukyus. The years immediately following saw the Akō incident of 1701–1703, in which the forty-seven rōnin avenged their lord, and the devastating Great Genroku earthquake that struck Edo in 1703."},"joseon":{"1700":"In 1700, Joseon was ruled by King Sukjong (r. 1674–1720) from the capital Hanseong, presiding over a long era of external peace as a tributary of Qing China recovering from the earlier Manchu invasions. Court life was dominated by violent factional strife, and after the Gapsul Hwanguk of 1694 the Western faction's Noron group held power, having restored Queen Inhyeon and driven out the Southerners. The following year brought the reign's climactic crisis: Queen Inhyeon died in 1701, and the king, blaming his former consort Jang Hui-bin for cursing the queen to death, had Jang executed by poison. This Sinsa Hwanguk of 1701 shattered the Southern faction, entrenching Noron dominance and deepening the succession rivalry between Crown Prince Yi Yun and Prince Yeoning. Beneath the court intrigue the country enjoyed relative stability and agrarian recovery, though tensions over the northern frontier with Qing would soon lead to the 1712 demarcation of the Yalu–Tumen boundary at Mount Baekdu."},"đại việt":{"1700":"In 1700, Đại Việt was nominally ruled by the figurehead emperor Lê Hy Tông at Thăng Long, though genuine authority lay with the two lordly houses. In the north the veteran Trịnh lord Trịnh Căn governed Đàng Ngoài (Tonkin) from the same capital, while in the south Nguyễn Phúc Chu ruled the increasingly autonomous Đàng Trong (Cochinchina) from Phú Xuân near Huế. The land was at peace, the Trịnh–Nguyễn wars having ended in 1672, and the two domains coexisted as effectively separate states behind fortified frontier lines. The Nguyễn were the era's dynamic force, having subjugated Champa by 1693 and, in 1698, organizing the Saigon–Gia Định region under Nguyễn Hữu Cảnh as they pressed into the Mekong Delta. European trade was in retreat, with the Dutch East India Company winding down its dealings with the Trịnh around this time, and Lê Hy Tông would abdicate in favor of his son in 1705."},"ayutthaya kingdom":{"1700":"In 1700, the Ayutthaya Kingdom was ruled by King Phetracha, founder of the Ban Phlu Luang dynasty, who had seized the throne in the revolution of 1688 and expelled French military and political influence. Having come to power as a usurper, Phetracha spent much of his reign suppressing revolts against his legitimacy, and around 1699–1700 he was still committing substantial forces to subdue the lingering rebellions of the governors of Nakhon Ratchasima (Khorat) and Nakhon Si Thammarat (Ligor). The kingdom remained a prosperous regional power and a busy trade emporium, maintaining cordial relations and trade monopolies with the Dutch even after the rupture with France. Tensions were meanwhile mounting over the succession, centered on the king's ambitious son and viceroy Luang Sorasak, who would seize power on Phetracha's death. Phetracha died in February 1703 and was succeeded by Sorasak, who took the reign name Suriyenthrathibodi and is remembered as the \"Tiger King.\""},"kingdom of cambodia":{"1700":"In 1700, the Khmer kingdom was governed from Oudong and was convulsed by a fresh round of dynastic strife and foreign intervention. Chey Chettha IV, who had returned to the throne in 1696, faced a Vietnamese invasion by the Nguyễn lords under Nguyễn Hữu Cảnh, whose forces struck at Phnom Penh. The uparaja (vice-king) Ang Em surrendered to the Vietnamese and was installed as king with their backing, while Chey Chettha IV attempted to expel the invaders but was defeated. This episode was part of the relentless Nguyễn advance down the Mekong delta, which was steadily absorbing formerly Khmer land and choking Cambodia's access to maritime trade. Squeezed between Vietnamese pressure from the east and Ayutthayan Siam from the west, the throne changed hands rapidly in these years, with Chey Chettha IV surrendering and being restored the following year as rival princes courted competing foreign patrons."},"kingdom of lan xang":{"1700":"In 1700, the throne of Lan Xang was newly held by Sai Ong Hue, who took the regnal name Setthathirath II after seizing Vientiane. A nephew of the late Sourigna Vongsa returning from long exile in Vietnamese-controlled Huế, he had attacked the capital in 1698 and, with the aid of Vietnamese forces, ousted the interim ruler Nan Tharat before formally proclaiming himself king in this year. Though the realm was still nominally united under Vientiane, his legitimacy was contested and the kingdom remained wracked by the succession strife that had followed Sourigna Vongsa's death in 1694. Rival claimants, especially the exiled grandsons Kingkitsarat and Inthasom sheltering in Sipsong Panna, refused to accept his rule and prepared to press their own claims from the north. Within a few years these tensions would erupt into open partition, but in 1700 the kingdom still stood as a single, if fragile, polity centered on Vientiane."},"toungoo dynasty":{"1700":"In 1700, the Restored Toungoo kingdom was ruled from Ava by King Sanay Min, who had come to the throne in 1698 following the death of his father Minye Kyawhtin. Sanay, like his father, was an ineffectual ruler, and the dynasty was in a phase of stagnation with central authority steadily weakening over its outlying provinces and Shan and frontier dependencies. The realm remained largely at peace and free of major wars in this period, but the underlying decline of royal control and the drift toward court-centred \"palace rule\" continued. His court maintained trading vessels and diplomatic contacts abroad, including exchanges with the Mughal Empire, and absorbed refugees fleeing the declining Kingdom of Mrauk U in Arakan. The structural weaknesses of this era would deepen over subsequent decades and culminate in the dynasty's overthrow by the Mon Restored Hanthawaddy Kingdom in 1752."},"kingdom of mrauk u":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Mrauk U was in deep political turmoil, and the throne itself changed hands that year as Naradipati's reign ended on 17 June and Sanda Wimala I was installed on 18 June 1700. The kingdom was in near-anarchy following the loss of Chittagong to the Mughal Empire in 1666, which had cut off its most lucrative Bengal revenues and trade. This period saw a rapid succession of short and often violent reigns, with roughly ten kings ruling in the four decades before 1710, several lasting only months. Royal authority had fragmented amid factional struggles among nobles and the disruptive influence of foreign palace guards and mercenaries, and Sanda Wimala I himself would later be driven out by rebels and die in exile in Bengal. Stability was not restored until Sanda Wizaya seized power around 1710 and briefly revived Arakanese military strength."},"lan na":{"1700":"In 1700, Lan Na was a vassal under Burmese (Toungoo) overlordship, having lost its independence in 1558, with Chiang Mai as its seat of government. The ruler at Chiang Mai was Cheputarai, a Burmese-appointed vassal king who reigned from 1675 to 1707 and whose name may derive from that of a Burmese prince, reflecting how Burma governed Lan Na through installed rulers. This fell within the period historians describe as Chiang Mai's third spell under Burmese rule, from 1631 to 1727, and Thai chroniclers often characterise these decades as a stagnant \"Dark Age\" marked by depopulation and cultural decline. The kingdom was internally fragmented among semi-autonomous muang, with heavy taxation and weak central authority sowing the discontent that would erupt in the Chiang Mai revolt of 1727. No major war or treaty is recorded at Chiang Mai in 1700 itself; the polity remained a quiet, subordinate frontier holding of the declining Toungoo empire."},"shan states":{"1700":"In 1700, the Shan states were a scattered array of Tai principalities owing tributary allegiance to the Restored Toungoo (Nyaungyan) dynasty of Burma, then ruled from Ava by King Sanay Min, who had succeeded his father in 1698. Each principality remained under its own hereditary saopha, retaining internal autonomy while sending tribute to the Burmese court, so that no single ruler or capital governed the region as a whole. Sanay Min, like his father, proved an ineffectual monarch, and Burmese central authority was entering a period of gradual decline that would leave the frontier increasingly unsupervised. The northernmost Shan states—among them Mogaung, Bhamo, Hsenwi, Kengtung, and Sipsongpanna—had long paid dual tribute to both Burma and Qing China, and in the decades after 1700 their saophas increasingly leaned toward the more powerful Qing. This drift culminated in the 1730s, when many of these border states were annexed by the Qing dynasty while the weakening Toungoo court was unable to respond, but around 1700 itself the region remained a nominally Burmese-tributary borderland at relative peace."},"kingdom of bhutan":{"1700":"In 1700, Bhutan was governed under the dual Chösi system by the Druk Desi Gedun Chomphel, who held the temporal office from about 1695 to 1701 while the Je Khenpo led the monastic body and the Zhabdrung authority survived only as contested reincarnations. The recent death of Gyalse Tenzin Rabgye, the fourth Druk Desi and the last figure to wield both spiritual and temporal power together, had left the state increasingly dominated by its secular administrators and the rivalries of the regional penlops and dzongpons. In that year Bhutan again invaded Sikkim, its second such campaign after an earlier incursion around 1680, extending Drukpa pressure along its western frontier. The state continued to guard against Tibetan and Mongol hostility, though the major Tibetan-Mongol invasion that Bhutan repulsed came later, in 1714, rather than at the turn of the century. Government radiated from the great dzongs, above all Punakha Dzong, which served as the seat of the Druk Desi and the winter residence of the central monastic community."},"tibet":{"1700":"In 1700, real power in Tibet rested with the regent (desi) Sangye Gyatso, who ruled at Lhasa in the name of the Dalai Lama and had governed since 1679. The controversial Sixth Dalai Lama, Tsangyang Gyatso, whom Sangye Gyatso had publicly installed in 1697 after long concealing the Fifth Dalai Lama's death, nominally reigned but was known for poetry and worldly pursuits rather than monastic discipline. The Ganden Phodrang remained a Buddhist theocracy backed by the Khoshut Mongols, though the khanate's authority had waned and Sangye Gyatso cultivated ties with the Dzungars to counterbalance it. Tension was mounting with the ambitious Khoshut prince Lhazang, a grandson of Güshi Khan who resented the regent's dominance and the diminished standing of his house. These strains would erupt within a few years, once Lhazang seized the Khoshut throne, leading to the regent's killing in 1705 and the deposition of the Sixth Dalai Lama in 1706."},"kingdom of kandy":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Kandy was ruled by Vimaladharmasuriya II, a peaceable king who had succeeded his father Rajasinghe II in 1687 and reigned from his highland capital at Kandy. The kingdom remained the last independent Sinhalese state, secure behind its mountainous interior while the Dutch East India Company controlled the surrounding lowland coasts and dominated the island's foreign trade. Though the Dutch held the littoral, their attempts to subdue the interior militarily had failed, and relations centred on commerce rather than open war. The king was a notable patron of Theravada Buddhism, having sought monks from across the Bay of Bengal to restore the lapsed higher-ordination lineage and having rebuilt the Temple of the Tooth Relic beside his palace as a three-storeyed shrine. Tensions over trade were building toward the frontier dispute of 1701, when Kandy closed its borders with Dutch territory to channel exports through the ports of Puttalam and Kottiyar, stripping the Company of its grip on the lucrative areca-nut trade."},"dutch ceylon":{"1700":"In 1700, Dutch Ceylon was administered from Colombo by Governor Gerrit de Heere, who had held office since 1697 and would remain until his death in 1702. The Company controlled the cinnamon-rich coastal belt around Colombo, Galle, and Jaffna, enforcing its export monopoly, while the independent Kingdom of Kandy under King Vimaladharmasuriya II held the interior. Relations with Kandy were tense over trade, and in 1701 a commercial dispute erupted when the Kandyans closed their borders with Dutch territory to divert commerce through the ports of Puttalam and Kottiyar, costing the VOC its control of the areca-nut trade. The Dutch retaliated, and the standoff continued until around 1707, when the Kandyan borders reopened and the two rival ports were closed. During these years the VOC also promoted the systematic cultivation and disciplined harvesting of cinnamon along the coast to safeguard its most valuable revenue."},"sultanate of brunei":{"1700":"In 1700, Brunei was ruled by Sultan Nasruddin, who had proclaimed himself sultan in 1690 on the death of his uncle Sultan Muhyiddin, the victor of the recent civil war. The realm was still recovering from the devastating succession conflict of roughly 1660 to 1673, and the court governed from the stilt-built water capital of Kampong Ayer on the Brunei River. Nasruddin worked to restore stability, maintaining the long-standing trade ties with Manila that dated to Sultan Bolkiah's era, issuing pitis coinage to aid commerce, and relying on the counsel of the Minangkabau nobleman Dato Godam, who had arrived around 1691. His authority was nonetheless contested by the ambitious Pengiran Temenggong Muhammad Shamsuddin, whose growing power and rumored designs on the throne troubled the sultan and the people until the rival was eventually eliminated by poison. Much reduced from its sixteenth-century zenith, the sultanate at this date held a diminished Bornean domain beset by internal rivalries, piracy, and mounting European commercial pressure."},"malay sultanates":{"1700":"In 1700, the leading Malay sultanate of Johor was ruled by Sultan Abdul Jalil Shah IV, the former Bendahara who had been proclaimed at Kota Tinggi in September 1699 after the assassination of Sultan Mahmud Shah II ended the old royal line descended from Malacca. His accession triggered a lasting legitimacy crisis, since he sprang from the administrative Bendahara family rather than the sacred Malacca-Srivijaya dynasty, and it provoked factional revolts against his rule. Around this time Johor's itinerant court was shifting away from Kota Tinggi toward the Pancur and Riau area, where its ports thrived as free-trade entrepôts on the Strait of Malacca handling tin, pepper, gambier, and forest goods. Elsewhere the wider Malay-Muslim world remained a patchwork of separate courts, with Perak, Kedah, and Kelantan on the peninsula and the aging sultanate of Brunei presiding over a slowly declining Bornean domain. These were maritime trading states bound by Islam, the Malay language, and dynastic marriage rather than by any single overlord, and the destabilizing arrival of Bugis power-brokers and the Minangkabau claimant Raja Kecil still lay a few years ahead."},"spanish philippines":{"1700":"In 1700, the Captaincy General of the Philippines was governed from Manila by Governor and Captain-General Fausto Cruzat y Góngora, who had held office since 1690 and remained one of the most capable Spanish administrators of the era. Ruling as a dependency of the Viceroyalty of New Spain, he had overhauled the colony's finances, settled its debts to the treasury in Mexico City, and pushed the islands toward self-sufficiency, having issued new governing ordinances in 1696 that curbed official corruption and mandated annual provincial inspections. The colony's lifeblood remained the annual Manila galleon trade, which carried Chinese silks and Asian goods across the Pacific to Acapulco in exchange for Mexican silver. Catholic religious orders continued to dominate provincial and parish life as the encomienda system was giving way to provinces administered by alcaldes mayores. Cruzat y Góngora served until December 1701, when he was succeeded by Domingo Zabálburu de Echávarri and departed for Spain, dying aboard a returning galleon in 1702."},"dutch east india company":{"1700":"In 1700, the Dutch East India Company was near its commercial zenith yet already facing the early erosion of its spice monopoly as demand for Moluccan cloves and nutmeg softened. Its affairs in Asia were directed by Governor-General Willem van Outhoorn, who governed from the Castle of Batavia and served from 1691 to 1704. The company held a firm grip on the clove and nutmeg trade of Ambon and the Banda Islands and maintained forts and factories across the Indonesian archipelago, Ceylon, India, the Cape, and Japan. During this period the VOC pressed efforts to establish coffee cultivation in Java, which would grow into a major commercial crop, while its Asian workforce numbered in the tens of thousands. Van Outhoorn's administration was later criticized for weak leadership, rising corruption, and nepotism, and tensions with the Mataram succession foreshadowed the Javanese wars that would embroil the company in the following decades."},"kingdom of middag":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Middag persisted as a paramount aboriginal confederation on Taiwan's central-western plains under the early Qing administration that had annexed the island in 1683. Its villages, centered on the Dadu (Middag) area between the Dajia River and Lukang, remained under a supra-tribal leadership that Qing officials such as Huang Shujing would soon record as still functioning in the Dadu district. The polity was no longer a military power as in the Dutch and Zheng eras, but retained internal autonomy over its Papora and allied communities. Growing Han Chinese immigration and reclamation of the fertile Dadu plains were placing mounting pressure on its lands and labor. This slow encroachment set the stage for the resistance of 1731–1732 that would end the confederation a generation later."},"khanate of khiva":{"1700":"In 1700, the Khanate of Khiva was ruled by Shah Niyaz Khan, an Arabshahid installed under the overlordship of Bukhara, to which Khiva had been a vassal since about 1695. That same year Shah Niyaz sent an embassy and letter to Tsar Peter the Great of Russia, offering his submission and seeking protection against the marauding Turkmen and Kazakh tribes, an overture that first stirred Russian interest in Central Asia. The khanate at this time was politically fragile, its central authority undermined by autonomous tribal chiefs and recurrent Bukharan interference, while its overlord Subhan Quli Khan of Bukhara reigned until his death in 1702. The state's economy still rested on irrigated farming of the Amu Darya oasis, the taxing of caravans, and slave-raiding on Persian and Russian populations. This uneasy courtship with Russia collapsed within a generation, culminating in 1717 when the Khivans massacred Prince Bekovich-Cherkassky's Russian expedition."},"kazakh khanate":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kazakh Khanate was ruled by Tauke Khan, whose reign (c. 1680–1715/1718) is often seen as the last period of relative unity across the three zhuz. Tauke governed from Turkestan (Hazrat-e Turkestan), the caravan city on the Syr Darya that served as the khans' winter seat and religious center around the Khoja Ahmed Yasawi mausoleum. His administration relied on regular councils of biys (tribal judges) and the customary legal code known as the Jeti Zhargy, and he sought to keep the Senior, Middle, and Junior zhuz coordinated in the face of external threats. To the east, the Buddhist Dzungar (Oirat) Khanate pressed hard on Kazakh grazing lands and towns, continuing the conflict that had flared in the 1680s over Sairam and Tashkent and that would culminate in the disastrous invasions of the 1720s. Around 1700 the khanate remained a functioning if increasingly fragile confederation, its cohesion beginning to fray as the individual zhuz pursued more independent policies."},"central asian khanates":{"1700":"In 1700, the settled oasis khanates of Transoxiana were dominated by the Khanate of Bukhara, ruled by Subhan Quli Khan of the Ashtarkhanid dynasty—also called the Janid or Toqay-Timurid line, the last Chinggisid house to hold Bukhara. Central authority was already eroding, as effective power drained from the khan toward the Uzbek tribal emirs, above all the rising Manghit aristocracy who would come to govern in the khans’ name after 1712. The khanate’s economy rested on irrigated agriculture fed by the Zeravshan River and its ancient canal network around the Bukhara oasis, supplemented by long-distance caravan commerce along the old Silk Road routes linking Persia, India, Russia, and the steppe. Relations with neighbours were tense and often hostile: the Khanate of Khiva to the northwest launched repeated raids and campaigns, the Kazakh hordes pressed and periodically ravaged the Transoxianan heartland, and Sunni Bukhara remained religiously and politically estranged from Shiʿite Safavid Persia over the disputed frontier of Khorasan. To the east the rising Buddhist Dzungar Khanate added further pressure on Central Asia, deepening the insecurity that accompanied Bukhara’s slow political disintegration in the decades after Subhan Quli Khan’s death in 1702."},"imamate of oman":{"1700":"In 1700, the Imamate of Oman was ruled by Imam Saif bin Sultan (r. 1692–1711), the fourth Ya'rubid imam, from his residence at the castle of Rustaq. His reign marked the height of Ya'rubid power, coming just two years after his forces completed the 33-month siege of Mombasa and captured Fort Jesus from the Portuguese in December 1698, bringing the Swahili coast of Kenya and Tanzania, together with Zanzibar and Pemba, under Omani control. Around this time Oman consolidated its position as a rising Indian Ocean naval power, harassing Portuguese shipping and trade across the western Indian Ocean. Domestically, Saif bin Sultan invested heavily in agriculture and infrastructure, constructing aflaj irrigation systems and planting extensive date palms in the Al Batinah region to draw interior tribes toward the coast. Contemporary Omani historians recalled that at no time was Oman so renowned, powerful, or prosperous as under his rule, and he added the Burj al-Riah wind tower to his stronghold at Rustaq."},"sultanate of morocco":{"1700":"In 1700, the 'Alawi sultanate was ruled by Moulay Ismail, who governed from his purpose-built imperial capital at Meknes rather than the older seat of Fez, driving forward the vast palace, granary, and fortification complex whose walls stretched for tens of kilometres. His authority rested on the centralized 'Abid al-Bukhari, a standing army of enslaved and Haratin soldiers loyal to the throne rather than to the tribes, which allowed him to hold the whole country under a single ruler for the first time under his dynasty. Having already recovered the Atlantic ports of Larache and Asilah from Spain in earlier campaigns, his forces maintained the grinding blockade and siege of Spanish-held Ceuta that had begun in 1694 and would drag on for the rest of his reign. On his eastern frontier he pressed against Ottoman Algeria, taking the Beylik of Mascara around 1699, an aggressive posture that would end in a heavy Moroccan defeat at the Chelif River in 1701. Around this time the realm was one of the strongest Muslim states of the western Mediterranean, its writ reaching from the Mediterranean coast toward the Sahara and the Senegal river, while its corsairs and captive-taking made Morocco a persistent concern for European powers."},"ethiopian empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Ethiopian Empire was ruled by Emperor Iyasu I, called \"the Great,\" the last commanding monarch of the Gondarine golden age, who governed from the permanent castle-capital of Gondar founded by his grandfather Fasilides. His reign was marked by frequent but generally victorious campaigns to defend the southern frontier against Oromo incursions and by close attention to administration, including numerous theological and legislative councils convened in Gondar and a reform of customs and tax duties in the late 1690s. The French physician Charles Jacques Poncet, who reached Gondar in July 1699 and stayed until September 1700, attended the emperor and one of his sons, and Iyasu cultivated diplomatic contacts abroad, including overtures toward Louis XIV of France. Gondar itself flourished as a center of church-building, manuscript illumination, and religious scholarship, drawing farmers, soldiers, students, Muslim traders, and Beta Israel craftspeople. Royal authority remained strong at this date, though the dynastic instability that would culminate in Iyasu's murder in 1706 and the later Era of the Princes was already latent."},"sultanate of darfur":{"1700":"In 1700, the Sultanate of Darfur was ruled by Sultan Ahmad Bukr of the Keira dynasty, who had come to power in the 1680s and would reign until the early 1720s. He was actively enlarging the state, subduing the kingdom of Dar Qimr in the west and drawing the Zaghawa nomads of the north into the realm through conquest and marital alliances. The court remained itinerant, moving with the sultan as a mobile \"fashir\" through the highlands in and around the Jebel Marra massif rather than sitting at any permanent capital, since el-Fasher was not founded as a fixed seat until the 1790s. Ahmad Bukr strengthened the kingdom's administration and Islamic character while pushing its frontiers outward toward the rival sultanates of Wadai to the west and the Funj to the east. His expansion brought Darfur into growing competition with Wadai, whose sultan Ya'qub campaigned against him, setting the stage for the long regional rivalries of the eighteenth century."},"wadai empire":{"1700":"In 1700, Wadai was ruled from its capital at Wara by the kolak Ya'qub 'Arus, who reigned from 1681 to 1707. A Maba-led Muslim sultanate east of Lake Chad, it profited from its position on the Saharan caravan routes linking Bornu and Darfur. Ya'qub is credited with throwing off Wadai's long-standing tributary subordination to the powerful sultanate of Darfur to the east, asserting the state's independence. His campaigns against Darfur, then ruled by Sultan Ahmad Bakr, pressed deep into enemy territory but were checked by Darfur's alliance with Bagirmi and its access to Ottoman-supplied firearms. Islam remained the official religion of the ruling elite while much of the wider population continued to follow traditional beliefs."},"bornu empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Bornu Empire was ruled from Ngazargamu by the Sayfawa mai Dunama VII Martemarambi, who had succeeded Idris V around the turn of the century and reigned until roughly 1717. The empire remained a substantial Muslim Sahelian power controlling trade routes west of Lake Chad, but it was well past its sixteenth-century peak under Idris Alooma and had been in gradual decline since the mid-1600s. Its position was strained by recurring drought linked to the Little Ice Age's effect on Lake Chad, by famines in the latter part of the seventeenth century, and by pressure from Tuareg raiders to the north. Bornu's former dominance over the trans-Saharan trade was increasingly eroded as rival powers such as the Hausa city-states and the Wadai Sultanate opened competing routes and asserted their own commercial strength. Even so, Ngazargamu endured as a major fortified trading and Islamic scholarly center, and the empire retained its broad territorial framework in the central Sudan through this period of quiet consolidation rather than expansion."},"hausa kingdoms":{"1700":"In 1700, the Hausa city-states of the central Sudan stood as independent walled polities, each under its own sarki, having reasserted freedom from Bornu, Songhai, and Kebbi over the preceding decades. Katsina had emerged as the preeminent state, eclipsing Kano as the chief commercial hub of the region and drawing caravans and Muslim scholars who favored it over the declining centers of the Niger bend, and around the turn of the century its throne passed from Muhammadu Toya Rero II to Muhammadu Wari II. Kano remained a thriving craft and textile center under increasing fiscal strain, its sultans raising taxes to the point that Tuareg and traders were drifting away, shortly before Muhammad Sharefa took its throne in 1703. The devastating incursions of the Kwararafa (Jukun), who had exiled a Kano ruler in the 1650s and sacked Katsina, Zazzau, and Bornu's capital around 1680, had begun to recede as that power declined, while the roughly 1650 perpetual peace between Kano and Katsina still held. Gobir in the far north served chiefly as a frontier bulwark against Tuareg and other invaders and had not yet achieved the militarized dominance it would seize later in the eighteenth century."},"mossi kingdoms":{"1700":"In 1700, the paramount Mossi kingdom of Ouagadougou was ruled by the Mogho Naba Zombré, whose unusually long reign is conventionally dated from 1681 to 1744. Zombré is remembered for fixing the royal seat permanently at Wogodogo (Ouagadougou), whereas earlier the court had shifted with each ruler around the Oubritenga heartland. His era saw the beginnings of administrative centralization, as the Naba placed new functions in the hands of palace officials drawn from outside the hereditary chiefly lineages to check rebellious territorial chiefs. The northwestern kingdom of Yatenga, the great rival to Ouagadougou, remained effectively independent and in this period experienced a rapid turnover of rulers that weakened its central authority, well before the consolidating reforms of Naaba Kango later in the century. The Mossi realms as a whole retained their non-Muslim political and religious order, having long since ended their earlier wars with Songhai, while Muslim Dyula and Hausa traders operated in the market towns without displacing the traditional kingship."},"oyo empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Oyo Empire was a rising Yoruba power in its apogee of roughly 1650 to 1750, ruled by an Alaafin from the walled capital of Oyo-Ile in the northern savanna. Its strength rested on a formidable cavalry, horses obtained through northern trade, which was devastating on open grassland and had allowed Oyo to begin raiding southward toward the coast from about 1682. Royal power was constitutionally balanced by the Oyo Mesi council under the Bashorun and by the Ogboni society, an arrangement that repeatedly forced Alaafins to abdicate or take their own lives during this era. Which individual Alaafin held the throne in exactly 1700 is uncertain, as pre-nineteenth-century Oyo chronology drawn from Samuel Johnson's traditions is speculative and disputed among sources. The great trials of strength with Dahomey and the securing of a coastal outlet still lay in the decades ahead, so around 1700 Oyo was an expanding but not yet fully imperial hegemon over the states between the Volta and the Niger."},"kingdom of benin":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Benin was ruled by Oba Ewuakpe, whose accession the historian Jacob Egharevba dates to around this year, though some scholars place it a decade earlier. His reign opened amid severe internal crisis, as the Edo people and many chiefs withdrew their support, refusing to attend palace ceremonies, supply food, or provide labor, in part in outrage at mass killings he ordered at his mother's funeral. Abandoned in Benin City, Ewuakpe was forced to retreat to Ikoka, his mother's village, while rival chiefs asserted their power. This unrest formed part of the wider civil wars of roughly 1689 to 1721, during which a rebel leader sacked Benin City, and central royal authority was only partly restored through negotiated settlements. The turmoil culminated after Ewuakpe's death in a disputed succession between his sons Ozuere and Akenzua, resolved in Akenzua I's favor around 1713."},"kingdom of kongo":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Kongo was deep in the succession war that had raged since the catastrophic defeat at Mbwila in 1665, splintered among rival claimants who each ruled from fortified mountain strongholds. Pedro IV Água Rosada of the Kinlaza-aligned Água Rosada house held the fortress atop Mount Kibangu, in the Serra do Canda east of São Salvador, and could not occupy the ruined capital, while the Kimpanzu king João II refused to recognize any rival and controlled his own domains. The old capital of São Salvador (M'banza Kongo), abandoned in 1678, still lay largely in ruins and depopulated, so no single royal court governed the realm. Provincial magnates such as the powerful counts of Soyo acted with near-total independence, and warfare, famine, and the slave trade continued to drain the countryside. These conditions set the stage for the Antonian movement of the prophetess Beatriz Kimpa Vita, who marched into the deserted capital around 1704, and for Pedro IV's eventual reoccupation and reunification of the kingdom in 1709."},"lunda empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Lunda Empire was ruled from its royal capital, the musumba in the Nkalaany (Kalanyi) valley, by the Mwata Yamvo Nawej, remembered as the state's first well-attested sovereign, who had taken power around 1695. Nawej strengthened the young monarchy by creating enduring court offices, including the queen-mother title Rukonkesh and the positions Swan Mulond and Swan Mulop that helped regulate succession within the ruling lineage. His reign was marked by campaigns against neighbouring peoples, including the building of a fortress in Sala Mpasu country, though the frontier remained contested and an invasion by the neighbouring Kanyok kingdom would eventually cost him his life. The empire at this time was a compact but consolidating power on the high central-African plateau, ordered as a centralized core surrounded by tribute-paying provinces and a fringe of allied Lunda-culture kingdoms. Its wealth already rested on controlling long-distance trade in ivory, salt, copper, and captives, forging the routes that would soon tie the interior to Portuguese Angola on the Atlantic and to merchant networks reaching toward the Indian Ocean."},"luba empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Luba Empire was a still-modest state centered on the Upemba Depression grasslands of what is now Katanga, ruled by a sacred mulopwe from the capital at Mwibele near Lake Boya. Scholarly reconstructions from oral tradition, chiefly Thomas Reefe's chronology, place the generation of Kadilo (with Ndaye Mwine Nkombe, ca. 1690–1750) in power at this time, marking the beginning of the kingdom's first major territorial expansion. Under Kadilo the Luba began absorbing neighboring polities, including the Kingdom of Kikondja and other Luba-speaking chiefdoms, and the court frequently relocated to better exploit tributary resources. The kingship's authority rested on the Bambudye society and a system of tribute rather than standing armies, while the ruling elite controlled regional exchange in salt blocks, copper ingots, iron tools, and raffia cloth along the Lualaba river networks. The far-reaching long-distance trade and dramatic imperial growth associated with later rulers such as Ilunga Sungu still lay decades in the future, so around 1700 the polity remained a rising regional power rather than the savanna's dominant empire."},"rozvi empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Rozvi Empire had passed to an unnamed successor of its founder Changamire Dombo, who had died around 1695–1696, though the identity of this mambo is not securely documented. The young state was at the height of its power on the Zimbabwe plateau, having recently driven Portuguese traders and missionaries off the interior after attacks such as the sacking of the Dambarare market in 1693. Ruling from the stone-walled zimbabwe at Danamombe, the Changamire commanded a formidable military and controlled the gold and cattle wealth of the former Butua kingdom in the southwest. In 1702 the Rozvi struck northward into Mutapa, backing Samutumbu Nyamhandu against the Portuguese-supported Mwenemutapa Chirimbe, who was briefly reinstated with Portuguese aid before Rozvi influence prevailed. Through these interventions the empire consolidated its dominance over rival Shona polities and its reputation as the paramount power of the south-central African interior."},"kingdom of imerina":{"1700":"In 1700, the Kingdom of Imerina was ruled by Andriamasinavalona, whose reign of roughly 1675 to 1710 marked the realm's high point of unity, prosperity, and territorial extent in the central highlands. He governed from Antananarivo, the hill capital he had renamed from Analamanga, and had organized his domain into six provinces (toko) centered on strongholds such as Ambohimanga, Alasora, Ambohidratrimo, and Fihaonana. The kingdom in this period was largely at peace and agriculturally productive, its power radiating over the rice-growing districts within a short radius of the capital rather than across the wider island. Late in his reign, however, Andriamasinavalona resolved to divide the kingdom among four favored sons, a decision that would fracture the realm into rival principalities upon his death around 1710. That partition had not yet taken effect in 1700, so the state still stood whole, though the seeds of the roughly seventy-seven-year civil war that followed were being sown."},"sakalava kingdoms":{"1700":"In 1700, the Sakalava were divided into the two dominant kingdoms of Menabe in the west and Boina in the north, together commanding much of western and northern Madagascar. The northern kingdom of Boina had recently been founded by Andriamandisoarivo, a son of Andriandahifotsy, who had pushed north to the Betsiboka region and Boina Bay after breaking away from the Menabe line. These were cattle-herding states whose royal power rested on control of the coastal trade, exchanging enslaved captives taken in raids on neighbouring peoples for firearms and manufactured goods brought by European and Arab-Swahili merchants. The northern coast at this time also hosted European pirate settlements, and Sakalava chiefs drew on this trade to arm their expanding armies. Ruling from shifting royal towns rather than a single capital, the Sakalava were on the eve of their period of greatest power, which Boina's king Toakafo would consolidate over the northern third of the island within the following two decades."},"portuguese mozambique":{"1700":"In 1700, Portuguese Mozambique was a chain of coastal captaincies and Zambezi prazo estates administered under the Estado da Índia from the fortified Island of Mozambique, with authority ultimately resting with the Portuguese crown through the viceroy at Goa. The colony was in visible retreat: Fort Jesus at Mombasa had fallen to the Omani forces of Saif bin Sultan in December 1698, ending Portuguese dominance of the northern Swahili coast and pushing Portuguese attention southward toward the Mozambique and Zambezi region. On the interior plateau the Rozvi under Changamire Dombo had destroyed the key gold-trading fair of Dambarare in 1693 and driven the Portuguese out of the Manica region and the Mutapa state by 1695, ending Portuguese political control of the Zimbabwe plateau. As a result the Portuguese were largely confined to the coast and the lower Zambezi, where trade increasingly funneled through the interior-oriented prazo networks rather than the lost maritime hubs to the north. The settler and Luso-African prazeiro elite dominated local society, but the colony would not be separated into an autonomous captaincy-general independent of Goa until 1752."},"portuguese guinea":{"1700":"In 1700, Portugal's foothold on the Upper Guinea coast, under King Pedro II and administered through Cape Verde with Santiago as its distant capital, amounted to little more than the fortified trading town of Cacheu amid powerful independent African states such as the Papel, the kingdom of Kaabu, and Kassa. The Portuguese presence rested on the lançados, Cape Verdean and Portuguese traders and exiles who had settled among the local peoples and drove the export slave trade, routinely defying the crown's supposed commercial monopoly. The Cacheu and Cape Verde Company, chartered in 1690, was struggling against competition from Spanish-American slavers between 1696 and 1703 and would collapse entirely in 1706. The nearby captaincy of Bissau, whose fort dated to the late 1680s, was failing in these years and was abandoned soon after when its captain-major was captured and killed by the local king, leaving Cacheu the sole significant Portuguese seat until the 1750s. Real power over the interior and the terms of trade lay with the African rulers, to whom the Portuguese paid duties and depended on for the captives and goods passing through their forts."},"new france":{"1700":"In 1700, New France was governed by Louis-Hector de Callière as governor general, seated at Quebec, having succeeded Frontenac after his death in 1698. The colony stood near the height of its fortunes, with the long Beaver Wars against the Iroquois winding down toward the Great Peace of Montreal, formally signed in August 1701, which secured a broad settlement among the French, their Indigenous allies, and the Five Nations. Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville had founded Louisiana in 1699, establishing Fort Maurepas near Biloxi to block English expansion and anchor French claims at the mouth of the Mississippi. The fur trade remained the colony's economic mainstay, though the French court restricted the interior trade and posts around this period to curb a glut of beaver pelts. The onset of the War of the Spanish Succession in 1701 soon renewed colonial conflict with the English, spilling into North America as Queen Anne's War from 1702."},"viceroyalty of new spain":{"1700":"In 1700, the Viceroyalty of New Spain was governed from Mexico City by Viceroy José Sarmiento de Valladares, who had held the office since December 1696 and remained a committed supporter of the ruling House of Habsburg. The colony was still recovering from the severe famine of 1697, during which the viceroy had ordered maize and wheat stockpiled in public granaries, and in 1700 he organized a night watch of constables across the wards of the capital to curb crime. Its economy rested on silver from Zacatecas and Guanajuato, though annual output had fallen well below its early-seventeenth-century peak, and the Manila galleon continued to link Acapulco to the Philippines. On November 1, 1700, the childless King Charles II died in Madrid, ending the Spanish Habsburg line, but news of his death did not reach New Spain until early 1701. The disputed succession soon ignited the War of the Spanish Succession, and because Sarmiento was known as a Habsburg loyalist while the Bourbons secured the throne, he was removed from office and recalled to Spain in 1701."},"viceroyalty of peru":{"1700":"In 1700, the Viceroyalty of Peru was governed from Lima by Melchor Portocarrero Lasso de la Vega, 3rd Count of Monclova, a capable administrator who had held the office since 1689 and would remain until his death in 1705. At its greatest extent it still embraced most of Spanish South America, and its economy rested on Andean silver, though the great mine of Potosí had passed its early-seventeenth-century peak and its output and population were in long decline. The death of the childless Habsburg king Charles II on 1 November 1700 ended the dynasty that had ruled Spain and its empire since the conquest, and the crown passed to the Bourbon Philip V, a succession that soon plunged Europe into the War of the Spanish Succession. The change of dynasty had little immediate effect in Lima, where royal authority, the mita labor draft, and the trade monopoly centered on the Pacific fleets continued much as before. Persistent concern over foreign interlopers and the vulnerability of the coast meant Monclova devoted attention to colonial defenses, even as French merchants soon began trading in Pacific ports under the new Franco-Spanish alignment."},"state of brazil":{"1700":"In 1700, the State of Brazil was governed by Dom João de Lencastre, Governor-General since 1694 and seated at Salvador da Bahia, the colonial capital. The colony's economy still rested on the Atlantic sugar trade of the northeastern coast and the labor of enslaved Africans, though its sugar dominance had been eroded by competition from the Caribbean. The gold strikes made in the highlands of Minas Gerais during the 1690s were igniting a rush that drew thousands of migrants and enslaved people into the interior, straining royal control and provoking rivalries that would soon erupt in the War of the Emboabas. Under Lencastre the Crown suppressed the last of the runaway-slave quilombos in the wake of the destruction of Palmares, improved Bahia's fortifications, and advanced the Salvador mint. Portugal itself was on the eve of joining the War of the Spanish Succession, which would expose Brazil's ports, above all Rio de Janeiro, to later French naval raids."},"province of new york":{"1700":"In 1700, the Province of New York was governed by Richard Coote, 1st Earl of Bellomont, a royal appointee who also held the governorships of Massachusetts Bay and New Hampshire and who had spent much of the preceding year in New England before returning to New York City. Bellomont had arrived in 1698 charged with rooting out official corruption, enforcing the Navigation Acts, and suppressing the piracy that had flourished under his predecessors, and by 1700 he had arrested Captain William Kidd, whom he had earlier sponsored, and shipped him to London for trial. The colony was still recovering from the deep factional divisions left by Leisler's Rebellion, and Bellomont aligned with the Leislerian faction, having championed the reversal of Jacob Leisler's attainder and approved a proper reburial of his remains. Bellomont conducted diplomacy with the Iroquois at Albany, whose neutrality was strategically vital between the English and New France, but he fell ill and died in New York City on 5 March 1700/1 (Old Style), whereupon Lieutenant Governor John Nanfan assumed administration until Lord Cornbury arrived in 1702. New York City remained the seat of government, a diverse trading port still shaped by its Dutch heritage and dominated by a small circle of wealthy landholding and mercantile families."},"province of massachusetts bay":{"1700":"In 1700, the Province of Massachusetts Bay was under the royal governorship of Richard Coote, 1st Earl of Bellomont, who also held the governorships of New York and New Hampshire and was frequently absent from Boston. During Bellomont's absence from mid-1700, Lieutenant Governor William Stoughton — a former chief judge of the Salem witch trials — served as acting governor, exercising executive authority until early 1701. The colony was still recovering from the social trauma of the 1692 witch trials and was engaged in an uneasy peace following King William's War, which had ended with the Treaty of Ryswick in 1697. Government continued to be seated in Boston, with tension between the crown-appointed executive and the elected General Court over issues such as the governor's salary and control of currency. Puritan Congregationalism remained dominant in civic and religious life, and the province stood on the eve of renewed conflict with New France, Queen Anne's War, which would erupt in 1702."},"colony of virginia":{"1700":"In 1700, Virginia was an English royal colony governed by Francis Nicholson, who had been appointed governor in 1698. The seat of government had just been moved from the decayed and fire-damaged Jamestown to the newly laid-out town of Williamsburg, formerly Middle Plantation, renamed in 1699 in honor of King William III. Nicholson supervised the planning of the new capital, which grew alongside the College of William and Mary, chartered in 1693. The colony remained a tobacco-and-plantation society whose reliance on enslaved African labor was deepening following the erosion of the Royal African Company's monopoly, and Virginia was the most populous of England's mainland American colonies. Its planter elite, organized through the House of Burgesses and county courts, consolidated its social and political dominance during these years."},"province of carolina":{"1700":"In 1700, the Province of Carolina was a single proprietary colony governed from Charles Town, with a deputy governor overseeing the distant northern Albemarle settlements. Governor Joseph Blake, a leader of the Dissenter faction, died in office in September 1700 and was succeeded by James Moore, an Anglican allied with the Goose Creek Men, shifting political power toward the Anglican faction. In the northern region, Henderson Walker served as acting deputy governor over the Albemarle settlements. The colony's economy centered on Charles Town's booming trade in deerskins and enslaved Native Americans, alongside the rapid rise of rice cultivation worked by enslaved Africans in the lowcountry. Tensions over establishing the Anglican church, factional rivalry, and looming imperial conflict with Spanish Florida shaped the colony's affairs as the new century began, with Moore soon leading a failed 1702 expedition against St. Augustine."},"spanish florida":{"1700":"In 1700, Spanish Florida was a fragile presidio colony centred on St. Augustine, sheltered by the recently completed Castillo de San Marcos and administered through Havana. It was governed by José de Zúñiga y la Cerda, who had taken office as governor and captain general the previous year and now presided over a garrison town surrounded by a weakening chain of Franciscan missions. The colony stood on the eve of open conflict as the War of the Spanish Succession, known in the Americas as Queen Anne's War, drew England and Spain into hostilities. In November and December 1702, Carolina governor James Moore led an expedition that razed the town of St. Augustine, whose inhabitants and soldiers sheltered within the coquina fort until a relief fleet from Havana forced the English to withdraw. The following years brought further devastation, as Moore's raids of 1704 destroyed the Apalachee missions and reduced Spain's hold to the immediate area around St. Augustine."},"spanish cuba":{"1700":"In 1700, Cuba was a Spanish captaincy general governed from Havana, whose great harbour fortresses and landward defences made it the key naval bastion of the Spanish Caribbean. The island's governor and captain general exercised military and civil authority under the distant oversight of the Audiencia of Santo Domingo. The year coincided with the death of the childless Charles II of Spain and the accession of the Bourbon Philip V, which soon plunged the empire into the War of the Spanish Succession. That conflict disrupted the transatlantic convoys, forcing the treasure fleets that rendezvoused at Havana to sail far less frequently and with greater risk. Cuba remained a modest, defense-oriented colony whose economy was constrained by restrictive Spanish trade laws, well before the sugar and slavery boom of the later eighteenth century."},"spanish santo domingo":{"1700":"In 1700, Spanish Santo Domingo was governed by Severino de Manzaneda, who served as governor and captain general from 1699 to 1702. The colony was a poor and thinly populated Spanish possession on eastern Hispaniola, its economy resting on cattle ranching and illicit trade after generations of decline and depopulation outside the capital. Just three years earlier, the 1697 Treaty of Ryswick had confirmed the loss of the island's western third to France as the colony of Saint-Domingue, and tensions and border frictions with the growing French colony persisted. In November 1700 the last Habsburg king, Charles II, died and was succeeded by the Bourbon Philip V, a dynastic change that would soon draw Spain into the War of the Spanish Succession and bring gradual reforms affecting the colony. Santo Domingo remained overshadowed by its French neighbor, whose plantation economy was steadily growing while the Spanish side stagnated in relative isolation."},"dutch surinam":{"1700":"In 1700, Dutch Surinam was governed by Paulus van der Veen, who held the governorship from 1696 until 1707 on behalf of the Society of Suriname. The colony was administered from Paramaribo, the coastal capital and principal port through which its plantation produce was shipped to the Dutch Republic. Its economy was expanding rapidly, with the number of sugar, cotton, and indigo plantations and the enslaved African population both climbing steeply in the surrounding decades. Enslaved people continually escaped the plantations into the forested interior, forming Maroon groups whose raids on estates were a persistent security concern for the planters and colonial authorities. Van der Veen's administration also pursued schemes such as engaging German prospectors to search the interior for minerals, reflecting Dutch hopes of finding new sources of wealth beyond agriculture."},"essequibo":{"1700":"In 1700, Essequibo was a small, sparsely settled Dutch West India Company colony administered from Fort Kyk-Over-Al on its island at the confluence of the Essequibo, Mazaruni and Cuyuni rivers. The colony was led by commander Samuel Beekman, who governed from 1690 to 1707 and under whose command the surveyor Abraham Maas produced the oldest surviving survey map of the Dutch river settlement. Settlement remained concentrated along the upper river rather than the coast, with only a handful of plantations worked by a modest enslaved African workforce. The chief export crops of the period were annatto dye, tobacco, indigo and cacao, while large-scale sugar planting and the coffee cultivation that later transformed the colony had not yet taken hold. The Zeelandic administration continued cautious expansion under Company monopoly, and no major war disrupted the colony in these years, though it lay within a contested frontier claimed by Spain to the west."},"french guiana":{"1700":"In 1700, French Guiana was a small, struggling royal colony of Louis XIV, administered by a crown-appointed governor from its capital at Cayenne. The settlement clustered along the coast and lower rivers between the Dutch Guiana colonies to the west, across the Maroni, and the Portuguese-claimed lands to the east and south toward the Amazon. Its economy rested on modest sugar, indigo, and Cayenne-pepper plantations worked by enslaved Africans, whose numbers still amounted to only a couple of thousand after decades of slow growth. French control, contested by the Dutch as recently as their 1676 reoccupation, had by now been firmly consolidated, though the colony remained sparsely populated and economically marginal compared to France's richer Caribbean sugar islands. Within a year the outbreak of the War of the Spanish Succession would again expose the vulnerable colony to European rivalries in the Americas."},"tuʻi tonga empire":{"1700":"In 1700, the Tuʻi Tonga reigned as Tonga's sacred paramount from the walled royal centre of Muʻa (Lapaha), beside the lagoon on eastern Tongatapu, but held mainly ritual and religious authority rather than worldly power. Everyday temporal government rested with the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua and, increasingly, the ascendant Tuʻi Kanokupolu line, so the archipelago was administered through this uneasy three-title arrangement rather than by a single overlord. The empire's earlier overseas hegemony over Samoa, Fiji, and other island chiefdoms had long since collapsed, leaving effective authority confined to the Tongan islands themselves, though the elaborate ʻinasi tribute rituals and the sacred prestige of the Tuʻi Tonga endured. Tonga at this time was comparatively peaceful, with no sustained European presence, the fleeting visits of Schouten and Le Maire in 1616 and Abel Tasman in 1643 having left no lasting mark and Cook's arrival still more than seven decades away. The bitter succession wars that would engulf Tonga lay in the future, beginning only after the assassination of the Tuʻi Kanokupolu Tukuʻaho in 1799."}};for(var k in A){Y[k]=Y[k]||{};for(var y in A[k])Y[k][y]=A[k][y];}})(window.COUNTRY_YEARS);

/* 1700-era year paragraphs for the same (deep-merged). */
(function(Y){var A={"ainu":{"1700":"In 1700, the Ainu of Ezo lived in the shadow of their defeat in Shakushain's revolt three decades earlier, retaining only a nominal autonomy after being forced to swear allegiance to the Matsumae domain. They had no single leader or capital, remaining organized into scattered kotan villages under local headmen across Hokkaido, Sakhalin, and the Kuril Islands. Following the revolt, the Matsumae had established dozens of new trading posts and tightened their monopoly, leaving many Ainu communities economically dependent and, in some cases, on the verge of famine. Impoverished Ainu were increasingly drawn into exploitative labor arrangements at Japanese fisheries, while acting as intermediaries in trade linking Japan, the Amur region, and the Qing world. Epidemic disease, including smallpox, was already thinning a population whose social and political independence was steadily giving way to Matsumae control."},"akan states":{"1700":"In 1700, the Akan interior was dominated by the militarized gold states of Denkyira and Akwamu, while Osei Tutu was consolidating a new Asante confederacy from his capital at Kumasi. Denkyira, under its ruler Ntim Gyakari, remained the overlord of much of the Gold Coast interior, exacting heavy tribute from subject states including the Asante towns. Akwamu, having taken Accra in 1681, controlled much of the eastern seaboard and its trade with European forts. The Asante union, bound together by the sacred Golden Stool and the collaboration of Osei Tutu and the priest Okomfo Anokye, was preparing to challenge Denkyiran domination. This confrontation culminated the following year at the Battle of Feyiase in 1701, where Asante decisively defeated Denkyira and Ntim Gyakari was killed, launching Asante's rise as the leading Akan power."},"amazon hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the Indigenous peoples of the Amazon basin remained a mosaic of independent villages and ethnic groups with no central authority, largely beyond direct Portuguese or Spanish administration but increasingly pressured at their margins. Portuguese slavers and bandeirantes operating from Belém do Pará, founded in 1616, raided upriver along the Solimões and its tributaries to capture Indigenous laborers, while Spanish Jesuits advanced from the west. The Jesuit missionary Samuel Fritz, who founded missions among the Omagua and other peoples from 1686 and would soon become superior of the Mainas missions, spent these years advising vulnerable riverine communities to retreat and regroup upstream to evade Portuguese slave-raiding, amid disputes over the contested Portuguese-Spanish frontier. Epidemic disease, especially smallpox, together with forced labor and raiding, drove catastrophic depopulation across the mission districts of the upper Amazon. Deep in the interior forests, however, most peoples in 1700 still lived autonomously in their own villages, practicing horticulture, hunting, and fishing well outside effective European control."},"andean hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the eastern Andean slopes and montaña remained under the control of autonomous indigenous groups — Asháninka (Campa), Machiguenga, Piro, Amuesha and others — rather than any Spanish administration, with no ruler, capital, or unified authority over the region. The Franciscan missions first planted in the 1630s around Quimirí and the Cerro de la Sal had largely lapsed or been abandoned by this date, so around 1700 the frontier zone lay between mission waves with only a fragile, intermittent Spanish presence. The renewed Franciscan drive into the Chanchamayo valley and Cerro de la Sal would not begin until 1709, and the coordinating Convent of Santa Rosa de Ocopa was established only in 1725. Salt Mountain (Cerro de la Sal), a key regional trade and salt-mining site, continued to anchor indigenous exchange networks that operated independently of colonial oversight. The great mid-century upheaval — Juan Santos Atahualpa's rebellion of 1742 that expelled the missions and secured lasting independence — still lay decades in the future, leaving circa 1700 a period of scattered, unconsolidated contact on an overwhelmingly self-governing frontier."},"arctic peoples":{"1700":"In 1700, the Inuit, Yup'ik, and Aleut peoples lived as independent, self-governing communities with no overarching ruler, state, or capital, organized instead around family bands led by experienced hunters and elders. They subsisted amid the Little Ice Age climate on seals, walrus, whales, caribou, and fish, adapting to colder conditions that in many regions had reduced open-water whaling in favor of ringed seals taken at breathing holes and greater reliance on land game. Most groups remained beyond regular European contact: the Norse presence in Greenland had long since vanished, whalers touched only the Labrador coast and Davis Strait seasonally, and the Aleutians would not encounter Russians until Vitus Bering's voyage of 1741. Their communities continued to use the kayak, umiak, dog sled, and harpoon that had defined the Thule tradition, trading and sometimes raiding among neighboring bands across the Arctic. The year fell within a long period of relative isolation and cultural continuity, before the disease and colonial upheaval that would follow eighteenth-century contact."},"australian aboriginal hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the Aboriginal peoples of Australia lived as hundreds of independent nations and clans across the entire continent, with no central ruler, capital, or unified government, decades before any European settlement. Authority in each group lay with elders and was grounded in kinship, Dreaming law, and custodianship of specific territories rather than in any state apparatus. Along the northern coasts, Makassan fishermen from Sulawesi were beginning their seasonal trepang (sea cucumber) voyages, a trade conventionally dated to about 1720 but likely underway earlier, which brought dugout canoes, metal tools, tobacco, and loanwords to Yolngu and other northern peoples. Elsewhere, contact with Europeans remained fleeting, limited to Dutch coastal charting of \"New Holland\" through the 1600s and William Dampier's brief landings on the north-west coast in 1688 and 1699. Life across the continent otherwise continued along long-established seasonal and ceremonial patterns, entirely self-governing and unaffected by the colonisation that would begin only with the First Fleet in 1788."},"belize":{"1700":"In 1700, the Bay Settlement was an informal, legally ambiguous cluster of predominantly English logwood cutters along the Bay of Honduras coast, on land Spain still claimed as its own. There was no colonial governor or Crown administration; the \"Baymen,\" many of them former buccaneers who had turned to timber after treaties suppressing piracy in the mid-17th century, governed their own affairs loosely through public agreement. The community was scattered among the cayes and the mouths of rivers such as the Belize and Hondo, with no single seat of government or fortified capital. Spain regarded the cutters as interlopers and periodically threatened or raided the coast, though no permanent Spanish garrison controlled the area, and the great wave of formal Spanish expulsions of the Baymen would not begin until 1717. The settlement's activity centered wholly on felling and exporting logwood for the European dye trade, its long-term status still unresolved and decades away from any recognized concession."},"delagoa bay":{"1700":"In 1700, Delagoa Bay was an open, contested trading anchorage under no firm European sovereignty, its shores controlled by autonomous Tsonga (Tonga) chiefdoms. Portuguese traders operated intermittent stations in the Espírito Santo estuary, but their forts were feeble and frequently unable to withstand local pressure, while Dutch and other ships called to barter for ivory. The Dutch East India Company had not yet founded its factory here — Fort Lijdzaamheid would only be built in 1721 and abandoned by 1730 — so around 1700 European presence was transient and commercial rather than territorial. Local chiefs held the decisive authority, granting or denying trade access and supplying the ivory and captives that drew foreign vessels. The bay in this period functioned as a way station in the wider Indian Ocean trade rather than as a governed colony of any European crown."},"finnmark":{"1700":"In 1700, Finnmark was the northernmost amt of Denmark–Norway, ruled by the Oldenburg king Frederick IV, who had acceded to the throne of the absolutist dual monarchy in 1699. The province had no fixed land border, and its inland Sámi were still subject to overlapping taxation claims from the Danish-Norwegian, Swedish, and Russian crowns in the disputed common districts. Around this time the Lutheran church intensified its efforts to convert and discipline the Sámi, with Isaac Olsen beginning his work as a teacher and preacher in eastern Finnmark from about 1703, a campaign later organized on a large scale by Thomas von Westen after 1716. The notorious Finnmark witch trials, which had executed dozens of people at Vardø over the course of the century, had effectively wound down by the 1690s. The outbreak of the Great Northern War in 1700 drew Denmark–Norway into conflict with Sweden, though the fighting itself lay far to the south of this remote Arctic frontier."},"fivizzano":{"1700":"In 1700, Fivizzano was a Tuscan vicariate in the Lunigiana under Grand Duke Cosimo III de' Medici, who had reigned over the Grand Duchy of Tuscany since 1670. It functioned as a detached Florentine enclave, separated from the main body of Tuscany by the intervening Duchy of Massa and the surrounding Genoese, Estense, and Malaspina territories. The walled town remained the administrative seat of its surrounding rural district, prosperous by local standards and recently embellished by Cosimo III's 1683 fountain in the Piazza Medicea. Cosimo III's long reign was marked by economic stagnation, heavy taxation, and religious rigor, and by 1700 the anxious question of the Medici succession loomed, since his sons produced no heirs. The broader Italian peninsula stood on the eve of the War of the Spanish Succession, whose upheavals would soon draw Tuscany and the small states of Lunigiana into the wider conflict over the Spanish inheritance."},"franche-comté":{"1700":"In 1700, Franche-Comté was a fully integrated province of the Kingdom of France under Louis XIV, some two decades after its cession by the Treaty of Nijmegen in 1678. Its provincial Parlement, university, and administrative institutions sat at Besançon, which had replaced Dole as the capital following the transfer of the Parlement in 1676. Royal authority was exercised through an intendant and a military governor, the office of governor being held by the ducal house of Duras, while the frontier was heavily fortified by Vauban at Besançon and Belfort. Anti-French sentiment among the local population lingered from the wars of conquest, though the province was being steadily assimilated into the French administrative and fiscal system. As the century turned, the outbreak of the War of the Spanish Succession in 1701 again made the province a strategic eastern border region facing the Holy Roman Empire."},"great plains nations":{"1700":"In 1700, the Great Plains were home to dozens of independent nations with no common government, ruler, or capital, and the mounted bison-hunting culture later associated with them was only beginning to form. The horse, introduced by the Spanish and dispersed widely after the 1680 Pueblo Revolt scattered thousands of animals northward through trade and raiding, was spreading up the plains but had not yet reached most northern peoples, with the Shoshone of Wyoming obtaining horses around this time and the Blackfoot not acquiring them until the 1730s. The Comanche were emerging from the Eastern Shoshone and pushing southeast onto the southern plains still largely as pedestrian hunters, first appearing in Spanish records raiding New Mexico in 1706. The Lakota and other Sioux, pushed westward from the woodlands by conflict with the Ojibwe and Cree during the later seventeenth century, were moving onto the plains, while village peoples such as the Pawnee, Mandan, Hidatsa, and Arikara continued farming maize, beans, and squash along the river bottoms and hunting bison on foot. Around this date the great transformation into the classic horse-and-bison culture was thus in its earliest stages, still decades from the fully mounted societies that would dominate the plains by 1770."},"guanches":{"1700":"In 1700, the Guanches no longer existed as an independent people, the Canary Islands having been fully incorporated into the Crown of Castile since the conquest was completed in 1496. The archipelago was a long-settled Spanish territory governed by royally appointed officials on each island, with the last speakers of the Guanche language dying out around this time and the indigenous population having been largely killed, enslaved, or absorbed into a mixed Canarian society. The islands' economy centered on the export of sweet Malvasia wine, known in England as sack or malmsey, though the boom in that trade was declining by about 1700 amid tariff disputes and Portuguese competition. Politically, the year fell at the end of the reign of the last Habsburg king, Charles II of Spain, whose death in November 1700 brought the Bourbon Philip V to the throne and precipitated the War of the Spanish Succession. Any surviving Guanche heritage persisted only as elements of Canarian custom, place-names, and vocabulary rather than as a living, self-governing people."},"hadramaut":{"1700":"In 1700, Hadramaut had no single sovereign and was governed as a mosaic of local Kathiri and other tribal sultans, Yafaʿi warlords, and influential sayyid families rather than one centralized state. The once-dominant Kathiri Sultanate had long passed its peak, its power eroded by internal civil wars and the intrusion of the Yafaʿi, who held western Hadramaut from a base at al-Qatn, while the Kathiri clung to inland strongholds around Seiyun, Tarim, and Shibam. The sayyid or sharif aristocracy of Tarim continued to exercise wide spiritual and social authority and to mediate among the feuding tribes, giving the fractious region a measure of religious cohesion. Portuguese coastal ambitions had earlier been repulsed, and the wider region lay under nominal Ottoman and Yemeni-highland influence, but day-to-day control rested with local rulers, and the ports of al-Shihr and al-Mukalla kept Hadramaut tied into Indian Ocean commerce and its emerging merchant and scholarly diaspora. Precise ruler names and events for this specific year are poorly documented, and within a generation the first Kathiri state would collapse around 1730 amid continued Yafaʿi and Quʿayti pressure."},"hindu kingdoms":{"1700":"In 1700, the leading Hindu power of this bloc, the Maratha state, was thrown into crisis by the death of Chhatrapati Rajaram I at Sinhagad in March, whereupon his widow Tarabai proclaimed their infant son Shivaji II as ruler and made herself regent. Tarabai took personal command of the war effort, and contemporary historians such as Jadunath Sarkar credited her administrative genius and resolve with holding the Maratha cause together through this emergency. The aged Mughal emperor Aurangzeb was still personally campaigning in the Deccan, and in April 1700 his forces captured the fort of Satara after a months-long siege, part of a grinding war that wore down his own army over more than two decades. Rather than collapsing, the Marathas under Tarabai kept up mobile raids and even pushed eastward into Mughal-held territory, so that the war remained unresolved. Meanwhile the Rajput states largely held their autonomy under nominal Mughal overlordship and the southern Nayaka kingdoms of Madurai and Thanjavur persisted amid mounting internal disorder and pressure from Mughal-appointed powers."},"imamate of aussa":{"1700":"In 1700, the Imamate of Aussa was a declining Muslim state in the lower Awash valley, its authority eroded since the end of Imam Umar al-Din bin Adam's reign around 1672. Its ruling imams struggled to hold together a fractious realm riven by conflict among Harla, Arab, and local Afar groups. Persistent Oromo pressure and the rising power of the Afar Mudaito clan continued to sap the imamate's strength in this period. The exact identity of the reigning imam in 1700 is not securely documented, falling between the recorded figure of Umar al-Din and the last imam Salman, who died in 1750. The state remained centered on the oasis capital of Aussa but was on a trajectory toward the Mudaito takeover that would culminate in 1734."},"lombardy":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Milan was a possession of the Spanish crown, its nominal sovereign being the ailing and childless King Charles II of Spain, who died on 1 November 1700. Day-to-day rule was exercised on the crown's behalf by a Spanish governor seated at Milan, while the duchy remained a rich and heavily fortified prize coveted by both the Bourbon and Habsburg claimants to the Spanish inheritance. Charles II's death triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, with his will naming Louis XIV's grandson Philip of Anjou, proclaimed King Philip V on 16 November 1700, as heir to the entire Spanish monarchy including Milan. This outcome was fiercely contested by the Austrian Habsburgs, whose earlier partition schemes had assigned Milan to Archduke Charles. Within months the duchy became the opening theater of the war, as an Austrian army under Prince Eugene of Savoy crossed into Milanese territory in 1701."},"luxembourg":{"1700":"In 1700, the Duchy of Luxembourg was a province of the Spanish Netherlands, held by King Charles II of Spain as Duke until his death on 1 November of that year. It had only recently been restored to the Spanish Habsburgs by the Treaty of Ryswick in 1697, France having occupied it since Vauban's siege of 1684 and greatly strengthened its fortress in the interim. Administration ran from Brussels under the Spanish crown, with Luxembourg City and its fortifications the anchor of Spanish power on the empire's exposed western frontier. The childless death of Charles II triggered the War of the Spanish Succession, and under his will the Spanish inheritance, including the Southern Netherlands, passed to Philip of Anjou, grandson of Louis XIV. Over the following years the duchy became caught up in the wider conflict that would ultimately transfer it, with the rest of the Southern Netherlands, from Spanish to Austrian Habsburg rule by the treaties of Utrecht and Rastatt of 1713–1714."},"mahra":{"1700":"In 1700, the Mahra Sultanate was an autonomous tribal sultanate of the Mahri people, its rulers of the Banu Afrar line governing from the coastal town of Qishn on the mainland and holding the island of Socotra. The sultanate controlled the Arabian Sea littoral east of Hadhramaut, subsisting on fishing, pastoralism, frankincense and aloe, and the maritime trade that passed its ports. It had long since reverted to Mahri control after the brief Portuguese occupation of Socotra ended in 1511, and Ottoman power had by this period receded from the region, leaving its harbors free of imperial levies. The old Christian community of Socotra, a relic of earlier centuries, had died out during the 1600s, and the archipelago's population was by now Muslim. The specific reigning sultan of this era is not securely documented in the surviving record, and the polity faced only intermittent friction with neighboring Hadrami powers such as the Kathiri over inland oases and caravan routes."},"mali":{"1700":"In 1700, the former Mali heartland along the upper Niger had no single ruler and was divided among competing Bamana chiefdoms and Mandinka remnants rather than governed as one state. The Keita dynasty of the old Mali Empire survived only as local chiefs based at Kangaba, having lost its imperial authority after Niani was razed around 1670. The early Bambara kingdom that Kaladian Coulibaly had built at Segou had already fragmented following his death around 1660, so Segou in this period was a contested and unconsolidated town rather than the seat of an empire. No centralized power yet dominated the region: the transformative Bamana state under Biton Coulibaly would not be founded until 1712, and the Bambara kingdom of Kaarta to the west was likewise still a minor, loosely organized polity. The years around 1700 therefore represent an interregnum of small warring chiefdoms across the upper Niger, in the decades between the collapse of Mali and the rise of the consolidated Segou and Kaarta empires."},"maori":{"1700":"In 1700, the Māori were wholly independent, having had no sustained contact with Europeans since Abel Tasman's fleeting and hostile encounter of 1642 and nearly seventy years before James Cook's voyage of 1769. There was no paramount ruler; authority was dispersed among many autonomous iwi and hapū, each governed by its own rangatira drawing on whakapapa and mana. Society was in its mature \"Classic\" phase, with hilltop and headland pā fortifications, terraced garden systems, seasonal resource exploitation, and finely worked pounamu and carved canoes. Inter-tribal warfare, alliance-making, and competition for territory and prestige were recurring features of life, as illustrated by the heavily fortified volcanic-cone pā of the Tāmaki (Auckland) isthmus occupied through this period. No single dated political event defines the year, since Māori history around 1700 is reconstructed from archaeology and oral tradition rather than written records, and the islands remained beyond the reach of any outside power."},"nogai horde":{"1700":"In 1700, there was no longer a single unified Nogai Horde but a set of fragmented Nogai groups scattered across the western steppe, having been driven from their old Volga–Yaik homeland by the Kalmyks earlier in the century. The principal western hordes — the Budjak, Yedisan, Jamboyluk, and Yedishkul, together with the Kuban Nogais — grazed the steppes north of the Black Sea and the Sea of Azov and were nominally subject to the Crimean Khanate rather than to any Nogai bey of their own. These nomads supplied cavalry and raiders for the Crimean khans, under whose loose authority the several Nogai groups were held in this period. Squeezed between the Kalmyks to the east, the Crimean Tatars and Ottomans to the south, and an expanding Russia to the north, the Nogais suffered repeated attacks, including Kalmyk raids launched as agents of Russia. The old capital of Saraychik had long been destroyed, and the surviving Nogais lived as dependent, mobile pastoralists with no central authority uniting them."},"northeastern woodlands nations":{"1700":"In 1700, the northeastern woodlands were dominated by the Haudenosaunee (Iroquois) Confederacy of the Five Nations, which had spent the seventeenth century waging the Beaver Wars against the French and their Indigenous allies. The Confederacy governed itself through the Grand Council at Onondaga rather than a single ruler, but by this date it was severely weakened, its fighting strength having fallen from roughly 2,250 warriors in 1689 to about 1,230 by 1698 through war, epidemic disease, and defections. The Huron-Wendat had already been destroyed and dispersed as an independent confederacy in 1649, while the Algonquian Wabanaki peoples of the northeast, including the Abenaki, allied with New France against English colonial expansion. Facing demographic collapse and the loss of reliable English military support, the Iroquois turned to diplomacy, and in 1701 concluded the Great Peace of Montreal with Governor Louis-Hector de Callière and some 1,300 representatives of thirty-nine nations, pledging neutrality in future Franco-English wars. Thus around 1700 these nations stood between the competing French and English empires, exhausted by the Beaver Wars yet still a decisive force in the balance of colonial North America."},"oromo":{"1700":"In 1700, the Oromo remained a decentralized people with no single ruler or capital, their affairs still governed by the Gadaa age-grade system and organized around competing clans and confederations across the Ethiopian highlands and neighboring lowlands. The main phase of the great migrations had largely subsided, and Oromo groups such as the Mecha, Tulama, and Barentu were settling and consolidating control over the lands they had occupied during the previous century and a half. In the Ethiopian Empire, Emperor Iyasu I \"the Great\" (reigned 1682–1706) both campaigned against Oromo groups and recruited and settled others, encouraging their conversion to Christianity and elevating a Christianized Oromo elite into high military and provincial office. Around this time Iyasu even married his daughter to an Oromo leader, marking the growing integration of powerful Oromo individuals into the imperial nobility, a trend that would culminate in the later dominance of the Yejju Oromo. Meanwhile, in the southwest the settled Oromo of the Gibe region were beginning the long transition from Gadaa republics toward the hereditary monarchies—Jimma, Limmu-Ennarea, Gera, Gomma, and Gumma—that would fully crystallize only in the following century."},"pampas cultures":{"1700":"In 1700, the peoples of the Pampas remained stateless and independent, ranging the grasslands south of the Río de la Plata in autonomous bands beyond effective Spanish control from the small port of Buenos Aires. There was no single ruler; leadership rested with band headmen and, increasingly, with war chiefs whose prominence was rising as mounted raiding grew. The horse, which had diffused into northern Patagonia by around 1620, had by the late seventeenth century made the Puelche and neighboring groups equestrian, and around 1700 this transformation was deepening, reshaping subsistence, mobility, and social organization. The process of Araucanization was underway, as Mapuche expansion from across the Andes spread the Mapudungun language, horsemanship, and trading and raiding networks eastward into the plains. By this time the older Querandí and Het groupings were increasingly merged into the broader mounted population later known collectively as the \"Pampas\" peoples."},"papous":{"1700":"In 1700, the peoples of New Guinea remained essentially independent of any outside power, organised into hundreds of self-governing villages and clans with no overarching ruler, capital or central government. Their economy rested on shifting and wetland horticulture of taro, yams and sago together with pig husbandry, while status flowed to \"big-men\" who commanded prestige through ceremonial exchange rather than dynastic succession. This period coincides with the disputed but widely reconstructed arrival of the South American sweet potato, spread via Portuguese and Malay traders through the Moluccas, which archaeologists and oral historians associate with an \"Ipomoean Revolution\" that intensified highland agriculture and pig-keeping around this date. Contact with the outside world was marginal and coastal, limited to sporadic trade in bird-of-paradise plumes, sea cucumbers, aromatic gums and slaves with Bugis, Seramese and Tidore-linked seafarers, with the interior highlands entirely unknown to outsiders. No wars, treaties or successions of the kind recorded for centralised states apply, as sovereignty in 1700 was fragmented among innumerable independent communities."},"patagonian shellfish and marine mammal hunters":{"1700":"In 1700, the peoples of Patagonia and Tierra del Fuego remained wholly independent, having experienced only sporadic contact with passing European expeditions and no colonization or foreign rule. The mainland Tehuelche had by this date been transformed by the horse, adopted from Spanish sources after about 1570, which vastly extended their range for hunting guanaco and rhea and reshaped their band mobility and social organization. On the Isla Grande de Tierra del Fuego the Selk'nam continued as terrestrial guanaco hunters within their haruwen family territories, while the Yámana and Kawésqar plied the Beagle Channel and southern archipelago in bark canoes, the women diving for shellfish and the men harpooning sea lions. There was no ruler, treaty, or state event to record, as these were stateless societies governed by kinship, custom, and shamanic authority rather than by any centralized government. The only European presence in the far south around this time was the occasional ship rounding Cape Horn or passing through the Strait of Magellan, leaving the region in the undisputed occupation of its Indigenous inhabitants."},"polynesians":{"1700":"In 1700, the Polynesian peoples remained almost entirely outside sustained European contact, organized as they had been for centuries into many independent island chiefdoms rather than a single polity with one ruler. In Tonga the ancient Tuʻi Tonga line still held sacred paramountcy and continued to receive the ʻinasi first-fruits tribute — a custom Captain Cook would witness in the 1770s — while everyday governance rested increasingly with the Tuʻi Kanokupolu and other secular chiefly lines. The Society Islands, Samoa, Hawaii, the Marquesas, and the Cook Islands were each divided among competing ariʻi and aliʻi chiefdoms whose fortunes shifted through warfare, marriage alliances, and religious rank, with no island-wide monarchy yet established. On Rapa Nui, moai carving was winding down amid deforestation and resource strain, and the island's population had fallen well below its earlier peak by the time Jacob Roggeveen sighted it in 1722. In New Zealand the Māori were fully settled as iwi and hapū tribal groupings across both islands, wholly unvisited by Europeans since Abel Tasman's brief and hostile 1642 encounter, and would not be contacted again until James Cook's arrival in 1769."},"pontremoli":{"1700":"In 1700, Pontremoli was not an independent state but a subordinate town of the Grand Duchy of Tuscany, which had acquired it in 1650, a few years after King Philip IV of Spain relinquished it and Genoa briefly held it. The Grand Duchy was ruled by Cosimo III de' Medici, whose long reign was marked by economic stagnation, heavy taxation, and religious severity across Tuscan territories. For Pontremoli itself, membership in the stable Medici state had brought a period of relative peace and prosperity, and the town continued to embellish itself with signorial palaces and churches. It remained a fortified administrative center guarding the Cisa pass in the Lunigiana, still hemmed in by the many small Apennine states — the Malaspina fiefs and other minor lordships — that fragmented the region. The wider succession crisis looming over the childless Medici line, which would eventually pass Tuscany to the House of Lorraine, did not yet directly disturb the town's routine of trade and local government."},"republic of the seven zenden":{"1700":"In 1700, the Republic of the Seven Zenden was governed by its Diet of the seven tithings under a Landeshauptmann, with the aged Adrian V von Riedmatten serving as prince-bishop of Sion. The bishop's temporal authority had long been subordinated to the communes, so real power lay with the district assemblies and their delegates meeting at Sion. As a Catholic associate of the Old Swiss Confederacy, the Republic largely kept out of the wider European conflicts brewing at the turn of the century, maintaining internal stability under its established constitution. Adrian V died on 20 May 1701, and Franz Joseph Supersaxo was chosen to succeed him as prince-bishop, continuing to rule until 1734. Throughout this period the seven tithings continued to administer the subject lands of Lower Valais while defending their communal self-rule against any revival of episcopal or foreign claims."},"savanna hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the North American interior labeled here as \"Savanna hunter-gatherers\" was home to dozens of independent Indigenous nations rather than any single ruler or government, with leadership held locally by band chiefs, war leaders, and councils. Along the Missouri and neighboring river valleys, semi-sedentary farming peoples such as the Mandan, Hidatsa, Pawnee, Arikara, and Wichita lived in substantial earth-lodge and grass-lodge villages, raising maize, beans, and squash while hunting bison seasonally. Out on the open grasslands, more mobile hunting bands followed the great bison herds, and the recently spread horse — moving north through Indigenous trade and capture, greatly accelerated by the release of Spanish livestock after the 1680 Pueblo Revolt — was beginning to transform mobility, hunting, and warfare. This period also saw significant population movement, as groups pressed by intertribal conflict and pressures from the east migrated onto the Plains, while European diseases spreading ahead of direct contact had already begun to reduce many communities. No treaties, dynastic successions, or centralized events define the region in 1700; its history around this date is one of gradual cultural transformation and the early adoption of the horse rather than the rise or fall of a state."},"shuar":{"1700":"In 1700, the Shuar lived as an autonomous Jivaroan people in the forested eastern Andean slopes and upper Amazon of present-day southeastern Ecuador and northern Peru, entirely outside effective Spanish control. They had no ruler, king, or central government; authority rested with individual household heads and with respected warriors (kakaram) who led only during raids, so no single figure governed the people. This condition followed directly from the great revolt of 1599, in which allied Jivaroan warriors destroyed the Spanish towns of Logroño and Sevilla del Oro and expelled colonial administration from their lands. Through the seventeenth century and into 1700 the Shuar remained effectively unconquered, engaging in internal feuding, head-hunting warfare, and only sporadic, cautious trade or contact with missionaries and colonists at the fringes of their territory. No major treaty, dynastic succession, or centralized political event marked this period, as the Shuar had no institutions through which such events could occur, and their independence would persist until sustained missionary and state incursion much later."},"siberian peoples":{"1700":"In 1700, the Chukchi, Koryak, and Itelmen remained largely independent stateless peoples with no single ruler, governing themselves through kin groups and local leaders across Chukotka and the Kamchatka Peninsula. The Russian conquest of Kamchatka had just begun under the Cossack Vladimir Atlasov, whose 1697–1699 expedition from Anadyrsk subdued Itelmen settlements by force, seized hostages, and established the Upper Kamchatka ostrog to enforce yasak fur tribute. Because only sable was accepted and these tundra-dwelling herders and sea-mammal hunters were not forest fur-trappers, the tribute demand caused great hardship and fueled fierce resistance. The Chukchi to the north were still being largely left alone by the Russians, who found them warlike and their lands unprofitable, and sustained conflict with them would intensify in the following decades. Major Itelmen and Koryak uprisings were imminent — a large revolt in 1706–1707 would destroy several Russian outposts — while the Chukchi would repeatedly defeat Russian forces and were never fully subjugated by arms."},"songhai":{"1700":"In 1700, no unified Songhai state existed, the former empire having been destroyed by the Moroccan invasion of 1591, and the label marks its old Niger-bend heartland now divided among successor powers. The core cities of Timbuktu, Gao, and Djenné were held by the Arma, descendants of the Moroccan expeditionary soldiers, who ruled the Pashalik of Timbuktu as a self-governing regime that recited the Friday sermon in the name of the Moroccan sultan but was in practice independent of Marrakesh. The pashalik was gripped by acute political instability, with the office of pasha rotating rapidly among rival Arma factions; reigns had collapsed to an average of about eleven months, and in 1697 a pasha had been elected and deposed on the same day. Downriver in Dendi, the surviving branch of the Askia dynasty maintained a smaller Songhai successor kingdom from its capital at Lulami, where Askia Hanga began a long reign around 1700. Across the region, Arma authority was contracting under pressure from Tuareg, Fulani, and Bambara neighbors, and the old imperial unity of the Niger bend was gone."},"southeastern woodlands nations":{"1700":"In 1700, the Southeastern Woodlands nations existed as many separate polities with no common ruler, each governed by its own town councils and war and peace chiefs. The Cherokee occupied the southern Appalachians, the Muscogee (Creek) the Georgia and Alabama river valleys, the Choctaw and Chickasaw the Mississippi interior, the Catawba the Carolina piedmont, and the Natchez the lower Mississippi. This was the height of the Carolina-driven Indian slave trade and the booming deerskin trade run out of Charles Town, which armed groups such as the Chickasaw and Creek to raid neighbors for captives sold to the West Indies. The founding of French Louisiana at Biloxi in 1699 opened a second European front, drawing the Choctaw toward the French while the Chickasaw leaned English, entrenching the \"play-off\" diplomacy between rival colonies. Recurring smallpox epidemics and slave-raiding were already collapsing smaller coastal and piedmont peoples, foreshadowing the Yamasee War that would erupt within fifteen years and the devastating Cherokee smallpox epidemic that followed a generation later."},"subarctic forest hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the boreal-forest hunter-gatherer bands lived under no single ruler, remaining dispersed autonomous family groups whose leaders held influence only by consent and skill. Across the North American Subarctic, the fur trade radiating from Hudson's Bay Company posts founded after 1670 was steadily drawing Cree, Ojibwe, and Dene groups into trapping and trading, while the rival French posts of the interior competed for the same pelts. Armed and provisioned by trade with the Hudson's Bay Company, Woodland and Swampy Cree were expanding northward and westward into territories of Dene peoples such as the Chipewyan, intensifying intergroup conflict in the years around 1700. European trade goods and epidemic diseases had already moved along Indigenous exchange networks well ahead of the traders themselves, unsettling long-standing patterns of life. In the Siberian taiga the parallel Evenki, Khanty, Yukaghir, and related peoples were by this date largely under Russian tribute (yasak) demands following the seventeenth-century conquest of Siberia, their numbers already declining from disease and exactions."},"subarctic nations":{"1700":"In 1700, the Subarctic peoples remained independent, decentralized band societies with no overarching government, ruler or capital, their affairs directed locally by band leaders and hunting-camp heads. The Innu (Montagnais) of the eastern boreal forest had by then been trading furs with the French for roughly a century, an alliance sealed between Champlain and Chief Anadabijou in 1603 and funneled through Tadoussac and the Saguenay corridor toward James Bay. On Hudson and James Bays, Cree bands had become the dominant intermediaries of the English fur trade, controlling the waterways and often keeping the interior Chipewyan and other Dene away from the coastal posts. This period fell within the Anglo-French wars over the bay: Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville had captured the key post of York Factory in 1697 after the Battle of Hudson's Bay, and the French held it (as Fort Bourbon) until the 1713 Treaty of Utrecht, so much of the trade around 1700 passed through French hands. The western Dene, including the Chipewyan, still had only limited direct access to European goods, a situation that changed only after about 1717 with the Cree-Chipewyan peace and the growth of trade at the Churchill River."},"tasmanian hunter-gatherers":{"1700":"In 1700, the Palawa of Tasmania lived entirely beyond the reach of Europeans and had no single ruler, the island being home to autonomous hunter-gatherer bands spread across its coasts, forests, and highlands. Their societies continued a way of life that had persisted in isolation since Bass Strait severed the island from the mainland thousands of years before, organised around clans and kin-based leadership rather than kings or governments. Daily life turned on the seasonal round of hunting, fishing, shellfish gathering, and firestick management of the land, with material culture and language traditions unique to the island. No documented external event marked the year for them: Abel Tasman had merely sighted and named the coast in 1642 without contacting the inhabitants, and no sustained European presence yet existed. Their world in 1700 was thus one of continuity and self-governing local communities, still more than a century before the British settlement of 1803 that would devastate them."},"western north american nations":{"1700":"In 1700, the region was a patchwork of independent Indigenous nations with no common ruler, government, or capital. The Rio Grande Pueblos had been reconquered by Diego de Vargas after the 1680 Pueblo Revolt and the campaigns of 1692–1696, so most Pueblo towns were again under nominal Spanish authority within the province of Santa Fe de Nuevo México, though Spanish policy had shifted toward accommodation. On the northern periphery the Navajo (Diné) of Dinétah were increasingly adopting Puebloan farming, weaving, and livestock, while Apache bands raided and traded across the Southwest and southern Plains. In the Great Basin and Plateau the horse had begun to spread from Pueblo herds released in 1680, and by around 1700 the Northern and Eastern Shoshone and the Ute were acquiring mounts, with a Shoshone offshoot beginning the migration that would become the Comanche. The California and interior Plateau peoples such as the Nez Perce remained largely beyond direct European reach, continuing foraging, fishing, and village life little changed by colonization at this date."},"wolof states":{"1700":"In 1700, the Senegambian coast was divided among the successor kingdoms of the former Jolof Empire, with no single overlord uniting them. The most powerful ruler of the moment was Lat Sukaabe Fall, who had seized Cayor in 1697 and held it in personal union with Baol as both damel and teigne, backed by his ceddo warriors and his maternal Geej dynasty. He pursued a policy of centralizing royal authority over trade and resisting European commercial pressure, and around this time he detained André Brue, director of the French Senegal Company, releasing him only after payment. To the north the brak ruled Waalo along the lower Senegal River, while the rump kingdom of Jolof survived landlocked in the interior. The Serer kingdoms of Sine and Saloum held ground to the south, and all of these states traded enslaved people, gum arabic, and hides through the French posts at Saint-Louis and Gorée and with English traders nearby."}};for(var kk in A){Y[kk]=Y[kk]||{};for(var yy in A[kk])Y[kk][yy]=A[kk][yy];}})(window.COUNTRY_YEARS);

(function(Y){var A={"spanish netherlands":{"1700":"In 1700, the Spanish Netherlands were still ruled in the name of the childless and dying Charles II of Spain, the last Spanish Habsburg. His death that November and the disputed Bourbon succession made the provinces an immediate battleground of the War of the Spanish Succession. French armies moved in early, seizing the barrier fortresses that Dutch garrisons had occupied under earlier treaties. Brussels remained the administrative centre even as French, Dutch, and Austrian forces contested control of the countryside. The eventual peace settlements of 1713 to 1714 would transfer the territory from Spanish to Austrian Habsburg rule."}};for(var kk in A){Y[kk]=Y[kk]||{};for(var yy in A[kk])Y[kk][yy]=A[kk][yy];}})(window.COUNTRY_YEARS);


/* 1600-era info-box data (Atlas timeline) — added by the 1600 era build. */
(function(){var T=window.COUNTRY_YEARS=window.COUNTRY_YEARS||{},A={"kingdom of france":{"1600":"In 1600, France was ruled by King Henri IV of the House of Bourbon from his capital at Paris. Having secured the throne through his conversion to Catholicism and pacified the Wars of Religion with the Edict of Nantes of 1598, he had brought a fragile peace to the realm. In this year he waged the brief Franco-Savoyard War against Duke Charles Emmanuel I of Savoy, which concluded in the Treaty of Lyon in 1601 and gained France Bresse, Bugey, Gex, and Valromey. Following the annulment of his marriage to Marguerite de Valois, he wed Marie de' Medici, the ceremony taking place by proxy in Florence in October 1600. His chief minister the Duke of Sully was rebuilding royal finances and infrastructure as the kingdom recovered from decades of civil war."},"kingdom of england":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of England was ruled by the aging Queen Elizabeth I of the House of Tudor from London, in the closing years of her long reign. She held the crown of the neighbouring Kingdom of Ireland in personal union, where the Nine Years' War against Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone, was raging, with Lord Mountjoy grinding down the Irish confederacy after the disgrace of the Earl of Essex following his failed 1599 campaign. England remained locked in the long Anglo-Spanish War, and in this period the East India Company received its royal charter on 31 December 1600. With the childless queen nearing the end of her life, the succession question loomed, and secret understandings were forming around James VI of Scotland. Wales was fully incorporated into the English realm, while the wider Elizabethan cultural flowering continued in the age of Shakespeare."},"kingdom of scotland":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Scotland was ruled by King James VI of the House of Stuart from Edinburgh. The previous year he had printed his treatise on kingship, Basilikon Doron, and he positioned himself as the most credible heir to the childless Elizabeth I of England. On 5 August 1600 he survived the mysterious Gowrie Conspiracy, in which the Earl of Gowrie and his brother were killed in an alleged plot against the king at Perth. Scotland remained an independent kingdom with its own parliament and the established Presbyterian Kirk, though James contended with the power of the reformed church. He would succeed to the English throne three years later in 1603, uniting the crowns."},"habsburg spain":{"1600":"In 1600, Habsburg Spain was ruled by King Philip III from his capital at Madrid, though the court would relocate to Valladolid the following year. Real power lay with his favourite, Francisco Gómez de Sandoval, Duke of Lerma, who steered the exhausted monarchy toward disengagement and peace. Spain remained at war with the Dutch rebels in the Eighty Years' War and with Elizabethan England, while also backing the Irish against the English crown. The treasury was severely strained after decades of conflict and repeated bankruptcies under Philip II, who had died in 1598. Lerma's policy of retrenchment would soon yield the peace with England in 1604 and the Twelve Years' Truce with the Dutch in 1609."},"kingdom of portugal":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Portugal was ruled by King Philip II of Portugal, who was simultaneously Philip III of Spain, within the Iberian Union of the Philippine dynasty. The kingdom kept its separate institutions and was administered from Lisbon through a viceroy or governors ruling in the absent king's name. Portugal retained its own laws, cortes, and coinage under the guarantees of the 1581 Cortes of Tomar, and Portuguese officials continued to staff its offices at home and overseas. Its far-flung maritime empire, from Brazil to Goa and beyond, was increasingly exposed to attacks by the Dutch and English, rivals of the Spanish crown to which Portugal was now bound. The Casa da Índia in Lisbon still regulated the lucrative spice fleets of the Carreira da Índia, though Dutch competition in Asian waters was beginning to mount."},"dutch republic":{"1600":"In 1600, the Dutch Republic was a young confederation of seven northern provinces in open revolt against Habsburg Spain, with States-General and the province of Holland dominant and no single monarch. Executive military leadership lay with Stadtholder Maurice of Nassau, while Johan van Oldenbarnevelt served as the leading statesman as Land's Advocate of Holland. In July 1600 Maurice won the Battle of Nieuwpoort in Flanders against the army of the Spanish Netherlands, though the campaign fell short of its strategic aims. The Republic's trade and finance were surging, and the Dutch East India Company would be chartered two years later in 1602. The de facto seat of government was The Hague, where the States-General and the Prince of Orange resided."},"spanish netherlands":{"1600":"In 1600, the Spanish (Southern) Netherlands were the Habsburg-held provinces governed as the sovereign appanage of the Archdukes Albert of Austria and Isabella Clara Eugenia, who had assumed rule in 1598 under Philip II's cession, from their court at Brussels. Their army under Archduke Albert fought Maurice of Nassau at the Battle of Nieuwpoort in July 1600, where the Spanish-Habsburg forces were defeated in the field. The territory remained locked in the Eighty Years' War against the northern Dutch Republic, its sovereignty conditional on reversion to Spain should the archducal couple die childless. Antwerp, though still a major city, had declined after its 1585 fall and blockade of the Scheldt, shifting commercial primacy northward. Real military and financial direction continued to flow from Madrid despite the nominal archducal autonomy."},"holy roman empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Holy Roman Empire was ruled by Emperor Rudolf II of the House of Habsburg, who kept his imperial residence at Prague rather than Vienna. Rudolf, a noted patron of the arts and sciences, hosted Tycho Brahe as Imperial Mathematician and would take on Johannes Kepler, but he suffered a severe mental collapse around 1599–1600 and increasingly withdrew from governance. His dismissal of Protestant counselors in 1599 and reliance on zealous Catholic advisers sharpened the confessional tensions that would culminate in later crises. The Empire remained a decentralized patchwork of hundreds of principalities, free cities, and ecclesiastical states bound loosely under the elected emperor. Growing friction with his brother Matthias and rebellion in Hungary lay just ahead, foreshadowing the Brothers' Quarrel and the road to the Thirty Years' War."},"polish–lithuanian commonwealth":{"1600":"In 1600, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth was ruled by the elected king Sigismund III Vasa of the House of Vasa, who had transferred the royal court from Kraków to Warsaw around 1596. As a hereditary king of Sweden as well, Sigismund's Catholic policies and absence provoked conflict, and 1600 saw the outbreak of open war with Sweden over Livonia. The realm was an elective monarchy constrained by a powerful noble Sejm and the szlachta's Golden Liberty, spanning a vast multi-ethnic and multi-confessional territory. Its magnate families wielded enormous regional power, and the Commonwealth stood as one of the largest states in Europe. Warsaw functioned as the practical seat of government while Kraków remained the coronation city."},"tsardom of russia":{"1600":"In 1600, the Tsardom of Russia was ruled from Moscow by Tsar Boris Godunov, elected in 1598 after the extinction of the Rurikid main line with the death of Fyodor I. Godunov was an able administrator who reformed the courts, sent students to be educated in western Europe, and pursued cautious diplomacy, but the boyar aristocracy resented his elevation. The year stood on the eve of catastrophe, as the great famine of 1601–1603 would soon kill roughly a third of the population and shatter his legitimacy. The pretender False Dmitry, claiming to be the dead Tsarevich Dmitry, would invade with Polish and Cossack backing in 1604. Godunov's reign is conventionally regarded as the opening of the Time of Troubles that engulfed Russia after his sudden death in 1605."},"kingdom of sweden":{"1600":"In 1600, Sweden was governed from Stockholm by Duke Charles of Södermanland, whom the Riksdag at Linköping in February had recognized as sovereign under the title Charles IX after formally confirming the deposition of the absent Catholic king Sigismund III Vasa, who also held the Polish throne. Charles consolidated his hold in March 1600 with the Linköping Bloodbath, the public beheading of leading nobles who had backed Sigismund. The dynastic dispute over the Swedish crown spilled into the Baltic, and the Polish–Swedish War over control of Livonia and Estonia opened in 1600. Charles ruled in fact as king though he would not formally accept the royal title and be crowned until 1604 and 1607. The realm at this date also encompassed Finland and was contesting the eastern Baltic provinces with the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth."},"denmark–norway":{"1600":"In 1600, the twin kingdoms of Denmark and Norway were ruled from Copenhagen by King Christian IV, who had begun his personal reign in 1596 after a regency following his father Frederick II's death. The composite monarchy also controlled Iceland, the Faroes, Greenland claims, and the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein, and levied the lucrative Sound Dues on shipping passing the Øresund. Christian IV, ambitious and energetic, was investing in the navy, towns, and building projects and asserting Danish claims along the northern Norwegian and Arctic coasts against Sweden. The kingdom was at peace in 1600, before the Kalmar War against Sweden broke out in 1611. Copenhagen was the seat of the royal court and administration for the whole realm."},"republic of venice":{"1600":"In 1600, the Most Serene Republic of Venice was headed by Doge Marino Grimani, elected in 1595 and reigning until his death in 1605, its government run by the patrician Great Council, Senate, and Council of Ten from the Doge's Palace in Venice. The Republic still held a maritime empire across the Adriatic and eastern Mediterranean, including Crete, the Ionian Islands, Dalmatia, and Istria, though its Levant trade faced growing competition and Ottoman pressure. Under Grimani, Venice passed laws from 1601 curbing papal and clerical privileges, sharpening a jurisdictional quarrel with Rome that would erupt into Pope Paul V's interdict in 1606. The city remained a leading centre of commerce, printing, glassmaking, and the arts. Venice guarded its independence between the Habsburg powers and the Papacy while managing its overseas possessions."},"republic of genoa":{"1600":"In 1600, the Republic of Genoa was led by Doge Lorenzo Sauli, elected in 1599 to the two-year term fixed by Andrea Doria's 1528 constitution, with the state run by an oligarchy of noble merchant-banking families. Genoa was closely tied to Habsburg Spain as its banker and naval partner, and this was the height of what Fernand Braudel called the 'age of the Genoese', when the city's financiers handled the silver of the Spanish crown. The Republic held Corsica and a strip of the Ligurian coast, with the capital and chief port at Genoa. Its wealth rested more on international finance and shipping than on territory, its bankers dominating the fairs that moved Spanish American silver through Europe. The dogeship rotated among the aristocratic families under the enduring influence of the Doria and the broader Spanish alliance."},"medici grand duchy of tuscany":{"1600":"In 1600, the Grand Duchy of Tuscany was ruled from Florence by Grand Duke Ferdinando I de' Medici, who had governed since 1587 after leaving a cardinalate. That year his court hosted the celebrated proxy marriage of his niece Marie de' Medici to King Henri IV of France, solemnised at Florence Cathedral in October 1600 and marked by lavish festivities that included Jacopo Peri's opera Euridice, one of the earliest operas. Ferdinando used Medici banking wealth and the French match to strengthen Tuscany's diplomatic standing and reduce dependence on Spain. The Grand Duchy encompassed Florence, Siena, and much of Tuscany, and Ferdinando promoted the port of Livorno as a free-trade harbour and improved agriculture and infrastructure. The Medici court remained a leading patron of art, science, and music."},"duchy of savoy":{"1600":"In 1600, the Duchy of Savoy was ruled by Duke Charles Emmanuel I from his capital at Turin, the realm's centre of gravity having shifted across the Alps into Piedmont. The duke was at war with France, King Henry IV having declared the Franco-Savoyard War in August 1600 over the disputed Marquisate of Saluzzo, which Savoy had occupied since the late 1580s. French forces overran Savoy's trans-alpine possessions of Bresse, Bugey, Gex and Valromey during the campaign. The conflict was settled by the Treaty of Lyon on 17 January 1601, under which Savoy ceded those western territories and paid an indemnity to France but was granted Saluzzo in exchange. Charles Emmanuel, an ambitious and restless prince, continued to manoeuvre between France and Habsburg Spain in pursuit of territorial gain."},"duchy of milan":{"1600":"In 1600, the Duchy of Milan was a possession of the Spanish Habsburg crown under King Philip III, governed on his behalf from the city of Milan. The governor was Pedro Enríquez de Acevedo, Count of Fuentes, an experienced soldier who took up the post in 1600 and would hold it until his death in 1610. As Spanish governor he combined military command with civil administration in a duchy that had been under Spanish control since 1535. Strategically vital as the anchor of the Spanish Road linking Spain's Italian and Netherlandish holdings, Milan served as a key military base and recruiting ground, and Fuentes pursued an aggressive policy against the Protestant Grisons on its northern frontier. The city of Milan held around 120,000 inhabitants, with roughly a million people across the duchy as a whole."},"kingdom of naples":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Naples was ruled as a Spanish viceroyalty on behalf of King Philip III, with its government seated in the city of Naples. The viceroy was Fernando Ruiz de Castro, 6th Count of Lemos, who held office from 1599 to 1601 and in 1600 commissioned the new Royal Palace of Naples, designed by Domenico Fontana. Governance ran through the Collateral Council presided over by the viceroy, alongside judicial and financial councils. The kingdom was the most populous of Spain's holdings outside Castile, with the capital alone approaching a quarter of a million inhabitants and the realm around three million. Heavy Spanish fiscal demands and reliance on the Neapolitan aristocracy shaped a kingdom that supplied the Spanish crown with revenue and soldiers."},"kingdom of sicily":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Sicily was governed as a Spanish viceroyalty under King Philip III, with its administration seated at Palermo. The viceroy was Bernardino de Cárdenas, 3rd Duke of Maqueda, who held the office from 1598 to 1601 and undertook major urban works in Palermo. Attached to the Crown of Aragon since the medieval period, the island retained its own parliament and considerable institutional autonomy under Spanish rule. Sicily served as a vital grain exporter and a frontline naval base against the Ottomans and Barbary corsairs in the central Mediterranean. Its coasts were guarded by a chain of watchtowers and fortified ports against raiding."},"kingdom of sardinia":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Sardinia was ruled as a Spanish viceroyalty within the Crown of Aragon under King Philip III, with the viceroy Antonio Coloma, Count of Elda, resident at Cagliari. Retaining its own parliament and administration, the kingdom preserved a distinct status rather than being absorbed into the Kingdom of Aragon. The island was frequently targeted by Barbary corsairs amid the ongoing Habsburg–Ottoman conflict, prompting the construction from the later sixteenth century of a network of coastal defensive towers. Its economy rested chiefly on grain, livestock and salt, with the ports of Cagliari and Alghero as its main outlets. Governance leaned heavily on the local feudal nobility, and the island remained a relatively peripheral and lightly populated part of the Spanish Monarchy."},"swiss confederation":{"1600":"In 1600, the Old Swiss Confederation was a loose league of thirteen sovereign cantons bound by overlapping alliance treaties, with no single capital and no permanent central government beyond the periodic federal Diet (Tagsatzung) that met at Baden. It was deeply split along confessional lines between Protestant cantons such as Zürich and Bern and Catholic cantons such as Lucerne and the Inner Swiss states, a divide that had hardened after the Reformation. Though nominally still part of the Holy Roman Empire, the Confederation was effectively autonomous and pursued a policy of neutrality while its cantons hired out mercenaries to foreign powers. In these years Geneva, an allied city rather than a full member, was under continued pressure from Catholic Savoy, whose forces would attempt the famous night assault of the Escalade in December 1602. The confederal system functioned through congresses of delegates and shared administration of subject territories rather than a unified state."},"republic of the seven zenden":{"1600":"In 1600, the Republic of the Seven Zenden governed the Valais as a confederation of seven districts (zenden) strung along the upper Rhône valley, associated with the Swiss Confederation but not a full member. Sion served as its principal seat, where the Prince-Bishop of Sion retained nominal sovereign dignity while real power had increasingly passed to the assembly of the zenden and the elected grand bailiff (Landeshauptmann). The territory was religiously contested in these decades, with a strong Protestant current in the upper valley confronting a Catholic majority and Counter-Reformation pressure. The lower Valais below Sion was held as a subject land administered by the seven upper districts rather than governed as an equal. Its politics turned on the balance between episcopal authority, the district communes, and rival aristocratic families such as the Supersaxo and de Riedmatten."},"papal states":{"1600":"In 1600, the Papal States were ruled by Pope Clement VIII (Ippolito Aldobrandini) from Rome, and the year was celebrated as a Holy Year Jubilee that drew an estimated several million pilgrims to the city. Only two years earlier, in 1598, Clement had incorporated the Duchy of Ferrara into the Papal States after the Este line failed, significantly enlarging papal territory in the north. On 17 February 1600 the philosopher Giordano Bruno was burned at the stake in the Campo de' Fiori after his condemnation by the Roman Inquisition. Clement was also active in wider European affairs, having brokered the 1598 Peace of Vervins between Spain and France and reconciled the papacy with Henry IV of France. The pontiff governed both as a temporal sovereign over central Italy and as head of the Catholic Church during the height of the Counter-Reformation."},"duchy of prussia":{"1600":"In 1600, the Duchy of Prussia was nominally ruled by Duke Albert Frederick of Hohenzollern, but he had long been mentally incapacitated, and the government was exercised by a regent, George Frederick of Brandenburg-Ansbach, from the capital at Königsberg. The duchy remained a fief of the Polish crown, held under the suzerainty of King Sigismund III Vasa. As Albert Frederick had no surviving son, the succession question loomed large, and the Brandenburg Hohenzollerns pressed their claim to inherit the fief through marriage ties. It was a Lutheran state and one of the earliest secular Protestant principalities in Europe. The regency of George Frederick, who himself died in 1603, worked to secure orderly administration and to preserve the family's rights over the eventual inheritance of the duchy."},"crimean khanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Crimean Khanate was ruled by Ghazi II Giray, in the course of his second reign, which had begun in 1597 and would last until his death in 1607. He governed from the capital at Bakhchisarai as a vassal of the Ottoman sultan Mehmed III, while retaining considerable independence in the khanate's own steppe diplomacy and warfare. Ghazi II Giray had earned Ottoman confidence through service in the Ottoman–Safavid War and was noted as a cultured ruler, poet, and musician as well as a capable military commander. In these years his forces were repeatedly called upon to support Ottoman campaigns, including operations connected to the Long Turkish War against the Habsburgs in Hungary. He also had to manage rivalries within the extensive Giray dynasty and pressures along the frontier with Poland-Lithuania and the Cossacks."},"ottoman empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Ottoman Empire was ruled by Sultan Mehmed III from Constantinople, who had come to the throne in 1595 and controversially had his nineteen brothers executed to secure the succession. The empire was locked in the Long Turkish War against Habsburg Austria, and in 1596 Mehmed personally led the army to a major victory at the Battle of Mezőkeresztes in Hungary. Simultaneously the Celali rebellions were spreading across Anatolia, as disbanded soldiers and overtaxed peasants rose against the central government. In the east, tensions with Safavid Persia under Shah Abbas I were building toward renewed war. The empire remained a dominant power spanning the Balkans, Anatolia, the Levant, Egypt, and North Africa, though internal strain was mounting."},"safavid empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Safavid Empire was ruled by Shah Abbas I, who had moved the capital to Isfahan around 1598 and was transforming it into a magnificent imperial city. Abbas had earlier accepted a humiliating peace with the Ottomans in 1590 to free himself to crush the Uzbeks in the east, and by 1598 he had retaken Herat and Mashhad. He was in the midst of far-reaching military reforms, building a standing army of ghulam slave-soldiers equipped with firearms to reduce dependence on the Qizilbash tribal cavalry. English adventurers, including Anthony and Robert Sherley, arrived at his court around this time to encourage an anti-Ottoman alliance. The realm centered on the Iranian plateau and stretched across Persia toward the Caucasus and Central Asian frontiers."},"kazakh khanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kazakh Khanate occupied the steppes of Central Asia and was ruled by Tevekkel Khan (Tauekel), who had consolidated power and campaigned aggressively against the Shaybanid Uzbeks to the south. Around 1598 Tevekkel launched a major invasion of Transoxiana, seizing Tashkent, Samarkand, and other cities but failing to take Bukhara, then retreating to Tashkent where he died of wounds sustained in the fighting. He was succeeded by his brother Esim Khan (Ishim), under whom Tashkent came under lasting Kazakh control. The khanate remained a confederation of nomadic tribes organized into hordes, with the town of Turkestan and its Yasawi shrine serving as a political and religious center. Its economy rested on pastoral nomadism and control of caravan routes across the steppe."},"khanate of khiva":{"1600":"In 1600, the Khanate of Khiva was ruled by the Arabshahid dynasty of the Khwarazm region, a branch of the Shaybanid Uzbeks descended from Genghis Khan. The state was chronically unstable, fragmented among rival princes and subject to raids, and had recently endured periods of domination by the neighboring Bukharan khanate. The Amu Darya's shifting course was undermining the older capital of Urgench, prompting a gradual transfer of the seat of power toward Khiva over these decades. The khanate's population was a mix of settled oasis farmers and Turkmen and Uzbek nomads, with an economy built on irrigation agriculture, trade, and the slave markets for which the region became notorious. It remained a peripheral but persistent power in the Khwarazm oasis south of the Aral Sea."},"nogai horde":{"1600":"In 1600, the Nogai Horde was a fractured nomadic confederation of the steppes north of the Caspian and Aral seas, already split since 1557 into the Greater Nogai Horde on the Volga–Ural steppe and the Lesser Nogai Horde in the North Caucasus. Weakened by internal feuds, famine, and mounting Kalmyk pressure from the east, the Nogais were increasingly drawn into the orbit of Muscovy, to whom many of their mirzas swore nominal allegiance. The Greater Horde nominally centered on its winter seat at Saraychik on the Yaik (Ural) River, a caravan town that had earlier been sacked by Cossacks. The Nogais lived as pastoral nomads herding horses and sheep, raiding neighbors and supplying horses to Russian and Central Asian markets. Their power was in steep decline as Russian expansion and Kalmyk migrations closed in on the steppe."},"oman":{"1600":"In 1600, interior Oman was under the Ibadi Nabhani dynasty, whose rule the sources describe as temporarily restored around this year, with tribal and religious authority dispersed among the confederations of the interior. The coast, including the port of Muscat, had been held by the Portuguese Estado da Índia since 1515 and lay outside this rule. Omani politics in these years were marked by chronic rivalry between the Nabhani maliks and advocates of a restored elected Ibadi imamate, with towns such as Nizwa and Rustaq passing back and forth. This fragmentation left the country without unified leadership on the eve of the Yaruba revival. The situation persisted until 1624, when the election of Imam Nasir bin Murshid began the reunification of Oman and the eventual expulsion of the Portuguese."},"mahra":{"1600":"In 1600, Mahra was ruled by the Banu Afrar (Afrari) dynasty of sultans, whose core lay at the coastal town of Qishn and extended to the island of Socotra. No single named ruler of the year is securely attested in the available record, the dynasty's early lineage being sparsely documented. The Portuguese had briefly seized Socotra in 1507 but abandoned it by 1511, leaving the Mahri sultans in control of the island and the mainland coast thereafter. The polity remained a maritime, tribally organized sultanate on the eastern Yemeni coast, largely autonomous of the Zaydi and Kathiri powers to its west. This arrangement of a Qishn-and-Socotra sultanate under the Banu Afrar endured, with interruptions, for centuries afterward."},"hadramaut":{"1600":"In 1600, the Hadramaut interior was dominated by the Kathiri Sultanate of the Al Kathir tribe, seated in the Wadi Hadramaut towns of Tarim and Seiyun. The period was one of endemic tribal warfare, as the Kathiri sultans relied heavily on Yafi'i mercenary soldiers from the highlands to hold their oasis strongholds. No single ruler of the year is securely attested, and authority was contested among tribal factions across the valley and the coastal towns of Shihr and Mukalla. The Portuguese and other Indian Ocean powers touched the coast but did not govern the interior wadi. This fractured order of Kathiri sultans, Yafi'i soldiery, and rival coastal tribes would persist and shift over the following centuries."},"gharra":{"1600":"In 1600, this southeastern-Arabian locality lay within the zone of Mahri and Dhofari tribal peoples along the coast and hinterland east of Hadramaut. No sultan, capital, or governing regime for a distinct 'Gharra' polity is securely attested for the year, and it is best understood as a tribal community rather than a state. The surrounding coast was frequented by Portuguese and other Indian Ocean shipping but not administered by them inland. Regional authority, such as it was, rested with neighbouring tribal sultanates like the Banu Afrar of Mahra. Any specific ruler or event for this entity in 1600 is not responsibly sourceable."},"central asian khanates":{"1600":"In 1600, this Siberian expanse was in the final stage of the Russian conquest, its former ruler Khan Kuchum of Sibir having been decisively defeated near the Ob in 1598 and driven into exile among the Nogai. No unified indigenous state governed the region; authority was fragmenting as surviving Tatar princes either submitted to the Tsar or dispersed. The Tsardom of Russia consolidated its hold through a network of stockaded forts, including Tyumen founded in 1586, Tobolsk in 1587, and Tara in 1594. Tobolsk served as the effective Russian administrative center for the newly subjugated lands. The settled oasis khanate of Bukhara, which lay far to the south, is not represented within this map's polygon."},"mughal empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Mughal Empire was ruled by the third emperor, Akbar, who governed from Agra after the court had returned there from Fatehpur Sikri and Lahore by 1598. Akbar was at the height of his power, having consolidated an efficient centralized administration built on the mansabdari ranking system, the zabt revenue settlement, and a policy of religious conciliation. In these years his energies were absorbed by the Deccan campaigns to the south, where Mughal armies besieged and captured the fort of Ahmadnagar in August 1600 and Akbar's son Prince Daniyal and Abul Fazl operated in the region. At the same time the emperor faced the rebellion of his eldest son, Prince Salim, the future Jahangir, who set up a semi-independent court at Allahabad around 1600. Akbar reigned until his death in 1605, when Salim succeeded him as Jahangir."},"vijayanagara empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the reduced Vijayanagara Empire was ruled by the Aravidu emperor Venkata II, also known as Venkatapati Raya, who reigned from 1586 to 1614. His capital was Chandragiri in the Rayalaseema uplands, to which the court had shifted around 1592 after the loss of the old imperial city; he would move his seat to Vellore only around 1606. Venkata II was an energetic ruler who worked to hold together the empire's remaining southern territories and to keep the assertive nayakas of Madurai, Tanjore, and Gingee in check. Around 1601 he faced a serious revolt when the rebel Lingama Nayaka of Vellore was backed by these southern nayakas, a rising his forces suppressed though his authority in the deep south stayed weak. A relative lull in pressure from the Muslim sultanates to the north allowed him to prevent further disintegration of central authority during this period."},"ahmadnagar sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Ahmadnagar Sultanate was in acute crisis as Mughal armies under Prince Daniyal pressed its heartland and captured the fort of Ahmadnagar on 18 August 1600. The regent Chand Bibi, who had earlier organized the defence of the capital, had been killed by her own disaffected officers in April 1600, after which the disorganized garrison could not hold the citadel and the young sultan Bahadur Nizam Shah was taken prisoner. Rather than collapse, the sultanate's resistance was carried on by the Habshi minister Malik Ambar, who in 1600 proclaimed a new ruler, Murtaza Nizam Shah II, and rallied the state from bases away from the fallen capital. Malik Ambar operated from strongholds such as Paranda and later the region around Khadki, building up a cavalry army and mobile guerrilla forces to harry the Mughals. The Nizam Shahi state thus survived 1600 as a resistance polity with no single fixed capital, its fortunes bound to Malik Ambar's leadership."},"bijapur sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Sultanate of Bijapur was ruled by Ibrahim Adil Shah II, who reigned from 1580 to 1627, from his capital at Bijapur in the western Deccan. His long reign is regarded as the golden age of the Adil Shahi dynasty, marked by prosperity, religious tolerance, and lavish patronage of the arts, with the sultan himself a noted musician and poet. Around this time Bijapur was extending its influence southward toward Mysore even as the wider Deccan was destabilized by the advancing Mughals. In the immediately preceding years Bijapur had, together with Golconda, sent forces to help Ahmadnagar resist the Mughal advance, but it avoided the direct conquest that befell its neighbour. Bijapur thus entered the seventeenth century as the strongest and most culturally brilliant of the surviving Deccan sultanates."},"golconda sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Sultanate of Golconda was ruled by its fifth sultan, Muhammad Quli Qutb Shah, who reigned from 1580 to 1612. His court was by now centred on Hyderabad, the new city he had founded in 1591 on the banks of the Musi River beside the older fortress of Golconda, and which he adorned with the Charminar and other monuments. His reign is considered a high point of the Qutb Shahi dynasty, distinguished by prosperity from the region's diamond trade and by his own literary output in Dakhini Urdu, Persian, and Telugu. In the surrounding years Golconda had joined Bijapur in sending forces to support Ahmadnagar against the encroaching Mughals, though its own core territory remained secure. Golconda thus stood in 1600 as a rich and culturally vibrant sultanate, still a generation away from direct Mughal pressure."},"bidar sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Bidar Sultanate was ruled by Amir Barid II of the Barid Shahi dynasty from its capital at Bidar in the central Deccan. He had come to power in 1591 after a disputed succession, displacing the infant Ali Barid II following the death of the previous sultan Qasim Barid II. The small state remained hemmed in by the far larger Deccan sultanates of Bijapur and Golconda and was increasingly fragile. To the north, the Mughal emperor Akbar was actively campaigning in the Deccan and captured Ahmadnagar in August 1600, heightening the pressure on all the region's Muslim states. Bidar's rulers survived chiefly through the strength of their fortress and cautious diplomacy rather than military power."},"rajput states":{"1600":"In 1600, most of the Rajput kingdoms were Mughal vassals allied to the emperor Akbar, whose court at Agra drew heavily on Rajput commanders such as those of Amber and Marwar. The principal exception was Mewar under Maharana Amar Singh I of the Sisodia dynasty, who had succeeded his father Pratap in 1597 and continued the fight for independence from the Udaipur region. In that period Akbar dispatched an army under Prince Salim against Mewar, but Amar Singh's forces resisted and inflicted reverses on the Mughals in the hill country. The other major houses, including Amber under Man Singh and the Rathores of Marwar, served the empire and campaigned on its behalf as far as Bengal and the Deccan. Rajputana thus stood divided between imperial collaboration and the lingering defiance of Mewar."},"bengal":{"1600":"In 1600, Bengal was largely a province, or subah, of the Mughal Empire, but its eastern deltaic heartland of Bhati remained outside firm imperial control. Following the death of the great resistance leader Isa Khan in 1599, his son Musa Khan led the Baro-Bhuyan zamindars from their base at Sonargaon in continued defiance of the Mughals. The riverine terrain and the confederacy's river fleet allowed them to hold out against imperial armies for another decade. Elsewhere the province was administered on behalf of the emperor Akbar, whose authority steadily expanded through the region. Musa Khan's resistance would finally be crushed by the Mughal governor Islam Khan around 1610 to 1611."},"orissa":{"1600":"In 1600, most of Orissa had been under Mughal rule since Akbar's general Man Singh completed its conquest between 1590 and 1592, and the region was administered as part of the Bengal subah. The surviving indigenous power was the Gajapati raja Ramachandra Deva of Khurda, who had submitted to Mughal authority and been recognised as a vassal and legitimate heir of the Odishan Gajapatis. From his seat at Khurda he retained control of the sacred Jagannath temple at Puri and its ceremonial prerogatives. The Mughal provincial administration of the coastal plain was centred on Cuttack, the old regional capital. Orissa thus combined direct imperial governance with the persistence of a religiously prestigious local dynasty."},"islamic and hindu states":{"1600":"In 1600, the north-central Indian region covered by this catch-all label lay overwhelmingly within the Mughal Empire under the emperor Akbar, who ruled from Agra. There was no single independent state of this name; instead the zone comprised directly administered Mughal provinces alongside a mosaic of subordinate Hindu and Muslim chiefs. Akbar's revenue and administrative reforms had by this date integrated much of the Gangetic and central plains into a unified imperial framework. Local Rajput and other rulers within it generally held their lands as vassals rather than as sovereigns. The label is therefore best read as a general descriptive grouping overlapping the Mughal heartland rather than as a separate polity."},"ming dynasty":{"1600":"In 1600, the Ming empire was ruled by the Wanli Emperor from the capital at Beijing, though he had by this date largely withdrawn from routine administration in a prolonged standoff with his officials. The costly Three Great Campaigns had just concluded, including the suppression of the Bozhou (Yang Yinglong) rebellion in the southwest in 1600 and the earlier defense of Korea, which ended with the Japanese withdrawal in 1598. Wanli's insistence on naming a favored younger son as heir had provoked the bitter succession dispute known as the case over the crown prince, straining the court. Eunuch mining and tax commissioners dispatched to the provinces stirred widespread urban unrest and resentment against the throne. The realm remained outwardly the wealthiest and most populous state on earth, even as fiscal and administrative weaknesses that would later prove fatal were deepening."},"joseon":{"1600":"In 1600, Joseon Korea was ruled by King Seonjo from the capital at Hanseong, then in the difficult aftermath of the Japanese invasions. The Imjin War had ended in 1598 with the withdrawal of Japanese forces following the death of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, leaving the peninsula devastated by seven years of fighting. The naval victories of Admiral Yi Sun-sin, who had been killed at the Battle of Noryang in 1598, were already central to how the war was remembered. The kingdom faced enormous reconstruction: ruined farmland and cities, sharply reduced population and revenue, and damaged palaces in the capital. Court politics remained shaped by factional rivalry among the literati even as the dynasty set about rebuilding."},"japan":{"1600":"In 1600, Japan was formally an empire under Emperor Go-Yōzei in the imperial capital of Kyoto, but real power was disputed among the great lords following the death of Toyotomi Hideyoshi in 1598. Governance was nominally in the hands of a council of regents acting for Hideyoshi's young heir Toyotomi Hideyori, based at Osaka Castle, but rivalries quickly split the realm. On 21 October 1600 the decisive Battle of Sekigahara pitted Tokugawa Ieyasu's eastern coalition against the western alliance led by Ishida Mitsunari, ending in a sweeping victory for Ieyasu. This triumph made Ieyasu, whose base was at Edo, the effective master of Japan, though he had not yet received the title of shogun. The formal Tokugawa shogunate would not be established until 1603, so 1600 stands at the very hinge between the Momoyama age and the coming Edo order."},"kingdom of tsang":{"1600":"In 1600, central Tibet's most powerful secular ruler was the Tsangpa king Karma Tensung, who governed from the fortress of Samdrubtse at Shigatse in the Tsang region. He had succeeded his father, the dynasty's founder Karma Tseten, who died in 1599, and his reign saw considerable expansion of Tsangpa authority across southern, western, and northern Tibet. The plateau as a whole remained politically fragmented, with the Tsangpa contending against other lords and against the growing influence of the Gelug school centered on the Dalai Lamas near Lhasa. Sectarian rivalry between the Tsangpa's Karma Kagyu allies and the Gelug order was a defining tension of the age. No single unified Tibetan state existed, and the Ganden Phodrang government that would later rule from Lhasa lay decades in the future."},"đại việt":{"1600":"In 1600, Đại Việt was nominally ruled by the restored Lê dynasty from Thăng Long, with the young Emperor Lê Kính Tông on the throne, but real power lay with the Trịnh lord Trịnh Tùng who dominated the court. The Lê had been restored after the overthrow of the usurping Mạc, though the Mạc still clung to a rump domain in the far north around Cao Bằng. Beneath the fiction of a single Lê realm, the country was splitting between two warlord houses that both claimed to serve the emperor. In this very year Nguyễn Hoàng, who governed the southern provinces around Thuận Hóa and Quảng Nam, slipped away from Trịnh control in the north to consolidate his own autonomous base in the south. This deepening Trịnh–Nguyễn division set the stage for the long north–south rivalry that would divide Đại Việt for generations."},"ayutthaya kingdom":{"1600":"In 1600, the Ayutthaya Kingdom was ruled by King Naresuan, who governed from the capital at Ayutthaya on the Chao Phraya river. Naresuan had thrown off Toungoo Burmese overlordship and was pressing his advantage against a collapsing Burma, whose imperial capital Pegu had just been looted and burned by Toungoo and Arakanese forces at the end of 1599. Naresuan led an army into Burma in 1600 and besieged Toungoo, and Ayutthaya reached its greatest territorial extent of the period, drawing Lan Na and Cambodia into its orbit. The kingdom prospered as a maritime trading hub, with growing Portuguese, Dutch, and other foreign contact at its port. Naresuan continued to consolidate his gains until his death in 1605."},"lan na":{"1600":"In 1600, Lan Na was centred on Chiang Mai under Nawrahta Minsaw, who had ruled the kingdom through the collapse of the First Toungoo Empire and asserted its autonomy as Burmese power disintegrated. The kingdom stood in a precarious position between a collapsing Burma to the west and the ascendant Siam of Naresuan to the south. It was moving into the Siamese orbit rather than any Burmese one, and Chiang Mai formally submitted to Naresuan's overlordship around 1602. Internally Lan Na remained fragmented and weakened after decades of Burmese domination that had begun in 1558. Within a decade and a half it would fall back under Burmese suzerainty as the Restored Toungoo dynasty recovered."},"kingdom of lan xang":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Lan Xang was ruled by King Voravongsa II, who had taken the throne in 1596, with his capital at Vientiane on the Mekong. The realm was recovering from decades of Burmese interference and succession turmoil that had followed the death of Setthathirath, having regained effective independence under Nokeo Koumane in 1591. Voravongsa II presided over a comparatively stable period, holding together the Lao mueang along the middle Mekong including Luang Prabang to the north. The landlocked kingdom sat astride important overland trade routes linking Siam, the Khmer lands, and Yunnan. Voravongsa II's reign extended to about 1622."},"kingdom of cambodia":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Cambodia was a weakened successor state to Angkor, its court seated at Srei Santhor after the Siamese sack of Longvek in 1594 had broken the previous capital. The monarchy was destabilised and its succession contested in these years, following the deposition of Satha I and the ensuing chaos of foreign intervention. Iberian adventurers out of Spanish Manila, led by Blas Ruiz and Diego Veloso, had seized influence over the Khmer court in the late 1590s, an episode that ended violently around 1599–1600. Cambodia was squeezed between an ascendant Siam under Naresuan to the west and a rising Vietnamese presence to the east. The capital would shift again toward Oudong by 1618 as the post-Angkor court kept relocating."},"toungoo dynasty":{"1600":"In 1600, the Toungoo realm was in the hands of Nyaungyan Min, founder of the Restored (Nyaungyan) Toungoo dynasty, who had seized Ava in late 1599 and ruled Upper Burma from that dry-zone capital. The First Toungoo Empire built by Bayinnaung had utterly collapsed, and its old capital Pegu had just been looted and burned by Arakanese and Toungoo forces. Nyaungyan set about reconsolidating the fractured Burmese heartland, systematically recovering the nearer Shan states such as Nyaungshwe in these years. His restored kingdom was for now a smaller, more manageable polity centred on the dry zone rather than the sprawling empire of his predecessors. This reunification effort, continued after his death in 1605 by his son Anaukpetlun, laid the foundation for the recovery of much of the former empire."},"kingdom of pegu":{"1600":"In 1600, the once-glittering capital of Pegu lay in ruins, having been surrendered by King Nanda Bayin on 19 December 1599 and then looted and burned by Arakanese forces the following month. Nanda Bayin himself had been carried off as a prisoner to Toungoo, where he would be killed late in 1600, while his brother Nyaungyan Min withdrew to Ava in Upper Burma and was recognised there as king. Lower Burma had fragmented into a violent contest among the Arakanese, the breakaway lord of Toungoo, and the Siamese who had seized the Tenasserim coast. The Portuguese adventurer Filipe de Brito e Nicote was establishing himself at the port of Syriam, from where he would soon dominate the delta's trade. No stable central authority ruled Pegu, and the region remained depopulated and chaotic in the immediate aftermath of the kingdom's collapse."},"aceh sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, Aceh was ruled by Sultan Alauddin Ri'ayat Syah Sayyid al-Mukammal, who reigned from 1589 to 1604 from the capital at Banda Aceh (Kutaraja). His reign coincided with the first arrival of northern European traders in the Malacca Strait, and relations with them were turbulent: the Dutch commander Cornelis de Houtman had been killed and his brother captured during a clash in 1599. In November 1600 the Dutch commander Van Caerden was received cordially and some Dutch prisoners were released, opening steadier contact with the Netherlands. The sultanate remained a formidable pepper-trading power hostile to the Portuguese at Malacca and maintained its reputation as a bastion of Islam. Alauddin's court was remembered in Acehnese chronicle as pious and prosperous, setting the stage for the empire's peak under his successors."},"johor sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, Johor was ruled by Sultan Alauddin Riayat Shah III, who had come to the throne in 1597 and reigned until 1615. His court was based at Batu Sawar on the Johor River, the earlier capital of Johor Lama having been sacked by the Portuguese in 1587. The sultanate remained caught in the enduring rivalry with Portuguese Malacca to the north and the aggressive Aceh Sultanate across the strait, both of which had repeatedly ravaged its territory. In these years Johor began cautiously exploring an alliance with the newly arrived Dutch against the Portuguese, a policy that would be formalised in treaties a few years later. The kingdom controlled the southern peninsula and the archipelago at the mouth of the strait, sustaining itself through its riverine trade."},"malay and bornean sultanates":{"1600":"In 1600, this region of Borneo and the nearby islands was divided among several Muslim sultanates rather than governed from any single capital. The foremost, Brunei, was ruled by Sultan Abdul Jalilul Akbar, who had succeeded his father Muhammad Hasan in 1598; Brunei had been reduced from its earlier imperial reach after the Spanish assault of the 1578 Castilian War and was consolidating as a smaller riverine power. Other courts such as the Sultanate of Banjar in the southeast persisted as autonomous trading states, some drawing cultural influence from Java. These sultanates competed and traded across the archipelago while the arrival of Dutch and Spanish shipping began to reshape regional commerce. No overarching authority united them, and each maintained its own sultan, capital, and sphere of influence."},"kingdom of kandy":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Kandy in the central highlands of Ceylon was ruled by Vimaladharmasuriya I, who reigned from 1592 to 1604 from his capital at Kandy (Senkadagala). A former Portuguese convert turned defender of Sinhalese independence, he had decisively defeated a major Portuguese invasion at the Battle of Danture in 1594, securing his mountain kingdom's autonomy. He revived Theravada Buddhism on the island by importing ordained monks from Lower Burma and enshrined the sacred Tooth Relic in a newly built two-storey Temple of the Tooth beside his palace. Around him the Portuguese controlled the maritime lowlands of the island, and the Tamil Kingdom of Jaffna held the north, leaving Kandy as the last independent Sinhalese realm. A further Portuguese offensive was repelled at the Battle of Balana in 1602, confirming the kingdom's reputation as an unconquered highland stronghold."},"saadi sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, Morocco was ruled from Marrakesh by the Saadi sultan Ahmad al-Mansur, whose reign stood at its zenith of prestige and wealth. Revenues from the trans-Saharan gold trade and sugar exports funded a splendid court and the completion of the El Badi Palace. That same year al-Mansur dispatched his secretary Abd al-Wahid ben Messaoud as an envoy to the court of Elizabeth I of England to explore an anti-Spanish alliance. The sultanate's power was reinforced by its conquest of the Songhai lands across the Sahara after Tondibi in 1591, which channeled fresh gold northward. Al-Mansur would die of plague in 1603, after which his sons plunged the dynasty into a ruinous war of succession."},"pashalik of timbuktu":{"1600":"In 1600, the middle-Niger cities of Timbuktu, Gao, and Djenné were governed by the Moroccan-installed Arma regime centered on Timbuktu, in the aftermath of Songhai's destruction at Tondibi in 1591. The pashalik still nominally acknowledged Sultan Ahmad al-Mansur of Marrakesh, though real authority lay with its pashas and the Arma soldiery. The region remained unsettled, with Arma garrisons struggling to consolidate control while the surviving Songhai dynasty maintained a rival kingdom of Dendi to the south along the Niger. Timbuktu's famed scholarly community had suffered from the conquest, and leading jurists such as Ahmad Baba had been deported to Marrakesh. Trans-Saharan gold and salt commerce continued, but the once-great imperial order of the Niger bend had given way to a fractured, militarized administration."},"bornu empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Bornu Empire west of Lake Chad stood at or near its zenith, ruled from the walled capital of Ngazargamu. The empire had reached its greatest extent under Mai Idris Alooma, whose reign in the later sixteenth century brought military reforms, firearms, and Turkish musketeers alongside vigorous promotion of Islamic law. Alooma's death is variously dated to the years around 1600, and his reign or its immediate aftermath left a powerful, well-organized state at the height of its influence over Hausaland, the Sahara caravan routes, and neighboring peoples. Bornu controlled the vital trans-Saharan trade to Tripoli, exchanging enslaved people and other goods for horses and firearms. The empire remained a dominant power of the central Sudan, its court famed for administrative order and Islamic learning."},"hausa kingdoms":{"1600":"In 1600, the Hausa lands consisted of a set of independent, walled city-states rather than a single unified realm, each ruled by its own sarki, with no common capital. The leading cities included Kano, Katsina, Zazzau (Zaria), Gobir, Rano, Daura, and Biram, which competed and traded with one another and with their neighbors. Kano and Katsina flourished as centers of the trans-Saharan trade, textiles, leatherwork, and Islamic scholarship, drawing merchants and scholars from across the Sudan. During this period many of the Hausa states paid tribute to or were dominated by the powerful Bornu Empire to their east. Frequent warfare among the city-states, and raids for captives, characterized the political life of the region."},"wolof states":{"1600":"In 1600, the region of the lower Senegal was divided among the successor Wolof and Serer states left by the disintegration of the Jolof Empire, with no single capital over the whole area. After Cayor's victory at the Battle of Danki around 1549, the tributary kingdoms of Cayor, Baol, Waalo, Sine, and Saloum had broken away, reducing Jolof to a landlocked inland rump under its Burba. Cayor, with direct access to Atlantic trade and no dependence on the Burba, had grown into the most powerful of the coastal states. By this date the imperial authority of the Burba Jolof over these kingdoms had effectively collapsed, and they operated as sovereign polities. Trade with Portuguese and other European merchants along the coast, including in captives, hides, and gum, shaped the fortunes of the seaboard kingdoms."},"kingdom of kongo":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Kongo was ruled by the manikongo Álvaro II from the capital São Salvador, the Christianized name of M'banza-Kongo. The kingdom was a centralized Christian monarchy, its elite Catholic since the reign of Afonso I earlier in the century, and it maintained active diplomatic ties with Portugal and the Papacy. Álvaro II sought to reduce dependence on Portuguese Angola to the south and pursued a direct relationship with Rome, an effort that culminated in the famous embassy of Antonio Emanuele Ne Vunda dispatched in his reign. Relations with the neighboring Portuguese colony of Luanda, founded in 1575, were increasingly strained over the slave trade and territorial encroachment. The realm remained prosperous and comparatively stable at this date, still decades before the disastrous defeat at Mbwila in 1665 that shattered royal authority."},"kingdom of benin":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Benin was ruled by the Oba Ehengbuda from its capital at Benin City, a large walled settlement in the West African forest zone. The kingdom was near the peak of its power, having expanded significantly under the warrior-obas of the sixteenth century, and it traded briskly with Portuguese and later Dutch merchants in pepper, ivory, cloth, and enslaved people. Benin City was renowned for its earthworks, guild-organized bronze and ivory casting, and a court hierarchy centered on the divine kingship of the Oba. Ehengbuda is traditionally remembered as the last oba to personally lead armies in the field and is associated with reforms to court ritual and the war chiefs. European visitors of this era described the capital as an impressive, orderly city comparable to major towns of their own continent."},"oyo empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Oyo Empire was centered on its capital Oyo-Ile (Old Oyo, also called Katunga) in the northern Yoruba savanna. The state was recovering and consolidating after an earlier period of disruption and displacement, having re-established the metropolitan capital and rebuilt its cavalry-based military strength. Government combined the sacred kingship of the Alaafin with the powerful council of state chiefs known as the Oyo Mesi, headed by the Basorun, who checked royal authority. Oyo's open grassland location allowed it to field cavalry, giving it a decisive advantage over the forest kingdoms to its south and enabling the expansion of tribute networks. The empire was on the threshold of the great territorial growth that would make it the dominant power of the Yoruba region in the following century."},"akan states":{"1600":"In 1600, the Akan states were not a single polity but a cluster of independent kingdoms, city-states, and trading chiefdoms across the forest and coastal zone of present-day Ghana and eastern Côte d'Ivoire. Prominent among them were forest states such as Bono (Bono Manso) and Denkyira, alongside numerous smaller Akan polities that had grown wealthy from the gold trade. Gold from Akan lands drew Portuguese, and increasingly Dutch, traders to coastal forts, most notably São Jorge da Mina (Elmina). No paramount authority united these states, which competed and traded with one another and with the Europeans on the coast. The rise of Denkyira and, later, the Asante confederacy that would dominate the region lay still ahead in the seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries."},"mossi kingdoms":{"1600":"In 1600, the Mossi kingdoms were a set of related states in the Volta River basin of present-day Burkina Faso, the most important being Ouagadougou, Yatenga, and Tenkodogo. Each was ruled by its own sovereign—the ruler of Ouagadougou bearing the title Mogho Naba—claiming descent from the legendary founding figures of the Mossi. These cavalry-based kingdoms had a strong tradition of resisting incorporation by the Sahelian empires to their north and had earlier raided Songhai territory, though by this date the Songhai Empire itself had collapsed after the Moroccan invasion of 1591. The Mossi maintained a distinct political and religious culture, largely resisting Islam among the ruling class while engaging in regional trade in the Niger bend zone. They remained a durable regional power, their kingdoms persisting into the colonial period."},"ethiopian empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Ethiopian Empire was ruled by the child-emperor Yaqob (throne name Malak Sagad II), a young son of the late Sarsa Dengel who had died in 1597. Real power lay with his regent, Ras Athanatewos, governor of Begemder, who dominated the boy-sovereign for the early years of the reign. The Solomonic court had no fixed capital and remained itinerant, moving between seasonal royal camps, though a fortified stone royal residence at Guzara near Lake Tana had recently been built and served as a favored seat, as Gondar would not be founded until 1636. The realm's political center had by this time shifted decisively northward from Shewa into the Begemder and Lake Tana region. These years were marked by court intrigue, factional rivalry among great lords, and continuing pressure from Oromo migrations into the highlands, with Yaqob only later throwing off his regent's control."},"adal sultanate":{"1600":"In 1600, the Adal Sultanate no longer existed as a unified state, having fragmented after its capital was moved from Harar to the oasis of Aussa in 1577. Its former heartland was now split between the walled Muslim city-state of Harar, ruled by local emirs and Walashma descendants, and the Imamate of Aussa in the Awash valley and Danakil lowlands. Harar, the notional capital shown here, survived as an isolated but enduring center of Islamic scholarship and trade behind its walls. Both remnant polities were under heavy and growing pressure from Oromo expansion across the region. There was no single sultan commanding the old Adal territory, and the label reflects the source map rather than a coherent 1600 state."},"tunjur kingdom":{"1600":"In 1600, the region of Darfur and eastward into Wadai was ruled by the Tunjur kingdom, a Muslim dynasty of partly Nubian descent that dominated the trans-Saharan trade routes of the eastern Sahel. Its rulers held court from stone-built royal centers, the early capital of Uri and later Ain Farah, from which they exercised overlordship across a wide and loosely integrated territory. The kingdom stood at its height in this period, before the political changes that would reshape the region within a generation. To the east its authority extended over the Wadai lands, where a Maba-led Islamic revolt would only later overthrow Tunjur rule around 1635. To the west it would in turn be superseded by the Fur Keira dynasty of Darfur around the 1650s."},"wadai":{"1600":"In 1600, there was no unified Wadai sultanate, as the Islamic state of that name would not be founded until around 1635 by the Maba leader Abd al-Karim. The region east of Lake Chad instead lay under the overlordship of the Tunjur kingdom, whose Muslim rulers dominated the eastern Sahel from Darfur. Local Maba and other communities inhabited the area as tributary or loosely subject groups rather than as an organized polity of their own. There was accordingly no single Wadai ruler or fixed capital in this year. The territory shown reflects the region that would later become the Wadai Sultanate, not an existing 1600 state."},"kingdom of bagirmi":{"1600":"In 1600, the Kingdom of Bagirmi was ruled by its mbang (sovereign) from the capital at Massenya, southeast of Lake Chad. The reign of Abdullah IV, dated roughly 1568 to 1608, spans this year, and it was under him that the ruling class formally adopted Islam and the kingdom took on the character of a sultanate. The court at Massenya developed Islamic judicial and administrative practices as the state consolidated. Bagirmi supported itself through farming and through participation in the slave and caravan trade of the central Sudan. It remained a modest but organized central-Saharan polity, positioned between the larger powers of Kanem-Bornu to the west and the emerging states to the east."},"mutapa empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Mutapa Empire was ruled by Mwenemutapa Gatsi Rusere, who had succeeded to the throne around 1589 and reigned from the royal court in the highlands south of the Zambezi valley. Portuguese traders and Dominican and Jesuit missionaries operated at inland fairs such as Massapa and Luanze, and Lisbon's agents pressed steadily for gold-mining rights and political influence over the court. The kingdom still profited from exporting gold and ivory, but its autonomy was eroding under this mounting Portuguese pressure. Gatsi Rusere would soon face rebellions and a debilitating civil war that led him around 1607 to cede mineral rights to the Portuguese in exchange for military support. In these years the state remained sovereign but was drifting toward the dependency that would hollow it out over the following decades."},"luba empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the young Luba state in the Upemba Depression of the Katanga region was ruled from Mwibele, near Lake Boya, in the era of its legendary founder-king Kongolo Mwamba and his successor Kalala Ilunga. Luba oral tradition places the kingdom's consolidation in the late sixteenth century, so around 1600 the polity was still in its formative dynastic phase rather than the extensive empire it later became. The sacred kingship (bulopwe) and the associated court institutions that would define the Luba political model were being established in this period. The state's wealth rested on the rich fishing, farming, and metalworking economy of the Upemba lakes and on control of regional trade in salt, iron, and copper. From this nucleus the Luba would expand over the following century into one of the major powers of Central Africa."},"lunda":{"1600":"In 1600, there was no unified Lunda empire; the Ruund people of the Kalanyi and upper Kasai region lived in a cluster of pre-imperial chiefdoms without a single overarching ruler or capital. This period corresponds in Lunda oral tradition to the era of the queen Lueji and the arrival of the Luba hunter-prince Chibinda Ilunga, whose marriage is remembered as the origin of centralized sacred kingship among the Lunda. The consolidation of the paramount Mwant Yav title and the founding of the imperial capital at Musumba still lay in the future, several decades after 1600. Society at this stage was organized around local chiefs, kin-based communities, and an economy of farming, fishing, hunting, and regional trade in salt, iron, and copper. The centralized Lunda Empire that would dominate Central Africa was only beginning to take shape."},"swahili city-states":{"1600":"In 1600, the Swahili city-states were fragmented autonomous towns living under heavy Portuguese pressure along the East African coast, with no single ruler or capital uniting them. Portugal had made Mombasa a stronghold, completing the great fortress of Fort Jesus in 1593, and used its ally Malindi to police the coast while extracting tribute and controlling trade. Kilwa, once the leading gold entrepot, had long declined, and towns such as Mombasa, Pate, and the Lamu archipelago chafed under Portuguese overlordship. Local sultans retained their thrones and Islamic urban life continued, but real maritime and commercial dominance had passed to the Estado da India. Resentment simmered across the coast, foreshadowing the revolts and eventual Omani intervention that would end Portuguese control later in the century."},"madagascar":{"1600":"In 1600, non-Merina Madagascar was not a single state but a mosaic of Malagasy kingdoms, chiefdoms, and clan groups, with no island-wide ruler or capital. In the west the Sakalava were emerging under the Maroserana dynasty, whose Menabe kingdom around the Morondava River would be consolidated over the following decades. Along the east coast lived the ancestors of the Betsimisaraka and other peoples, still organized as small independent chiefdoms rather than the confederation that would form only in the early eighteenth century. Coastal communities traded cattle, rice, and enslaved people with Arab, Swahili, and European visitors, while inland dynasties ruled through cattle wealth and ancestral ritual authority. The powerful Sakalava kingdoms of Menabe and Boina, and the later Betsimisaraka union, were still in their formative or future stages at this date."},"kingdom of imerina":{"1600":"In 1600, the small highland Kingdom of Imerina in central Madagascar was ruled by Ralambo, whose reign is traditionally dated to roughly the late 16th and early 17th centuries. His seat lay at Ambohidrabiby, one of the sacred hills of Imerina, to which he had moved from his earlier capital at Alasora, the seat of his father Andriamanelo. Ralambo is remembered in Merina oral tradition for expanding the kingdom's authority, for being the first to apply the name Imerina to the central highlands, and for introducing customs such as the fandroana royal bath festival and the eating of zebu beef. The polity remained a compact cluster of fortified hilltop villages rather than a large territorial state, surrounded by rival Vazimba and other highland groups. Antananarivo had not yet been founded; it would be established around 1610 by Ralambo's son Andrianjaka after he captured the hill of Analamanga."},"viceroyalty of new spain":{"1600":"In 1600, the Viceroyalty of New Spain was governed from Mexico City by Gaspar de Zúñiga y Acevedo, 5th Count of Monterrey, who served as viceroy from 1595 to 1603 under King Philip III. His administration oversaw the northward push of the Spanish frontier, having authorized Juan de Oñate's 1598 expedition that established the colony of New Mexico. Monterrey also strengthened Caribbean and Gulf coastal defenses after privateer raids, relocating the port of Veracruz to a more defensible site. Mexico City was the political, ecclesiastical, and commercial heart of Spanish North America, and silver from mines such as Zacatecas flowed through it toward Seville. Monterrey would leave in 1603 to become viceroy of Peru, succeeded in New Spain by the Marquess of Montesclaros."},"viceroyalty of peru":{"1600":"In 1600, the Andes were governed not by the Inca — whose empire had fallen to Francisco Pizarro in 1533 — but by the Spanish Viceroyalty of Peru, ruled from Lima by Viceroy Luis de Velasco, 1st Marquess of Salinas (1596–1604), under King Philip III. Velasco's administration consolidated the mita labor system that funneled indigenous workers to the vast silver mines of Potosí, then among the richest in the world. Lima, the 'City of Kings' founded by Pizarro in 1535, was the seat of the viceroy, the Real Audiencia, and an archbishopric, and served as the hub for the treasure fleets carrying silver to Spain. The viceroyalty nominally embraced almost all of Spanish South America, though effective control was concentrated in the Andean core, coast, and mining zones. Velasco would depart in 1604 to become viceroy of New Spain, exchanging posts with the Count of Monterrey."},"spanish cuba":{"1600":"In 1600, Cuba was a Spanish governorate administered from Havana by Governor Juan Maldonado Barnuevo, who held office from 1595 to 1602 and combined civil and military command over the island. Cuba was still legally subordinate to the Captaincy General of Santo Domingo and would not be raised to its own Captaincy General until 1607. Havana had become the essential rendezvous and provisioning point for the Spanish treasure fleets, which gathered there before the Atlantic crossing, making the port a magnet for English, French, and Dutch privateers. In response, the Crown was heavily fortifying the harbor, with works such as the Castillo de los Tres Reyes del Morro then under construction. The island's economy rested on servicing the fleets, cattle ranching, and small-scale agriculture rather than the plantation sugar economy of later centuries."},"spanish santo domingo":{"1600":"In 1600, Santo Domingo, on the island of Hispaniola, was the seat of the Real Audiencia and Captaincy General of Santo Domingo, the oldest permanent European seat of government in the Americas and the head of Spanish authority in the Caribbean. Its president also served as governor and captain-general, exercising jurisdiction over Hispaniola, Puerto Rico, and the mainland Venezuelan coasts. By this date, however, Santo Domingo had declined sharply, eclipsed by the wealthier viceroyalties of Mexico and Peru and reduced to one of the lowest-ranking audiencias. The city and colony suffered from depopulation, contraband trade with foreign rivals along the island's northern and western coasts, and neglect by the Crown. Within a few years these smuggling havens would prompt the drastic devastaciones of 1605–1606, when Spain forcibly depopulated western Hispaniola — indirectly opening the way for later French settlement of Saint-Domingue."},"tuʻi tonga empire":{"1600":"In 1600, the Tuʻi Tonga Empire was a maritime chiefdom-state centred on the island of Tongatapu, with its ceremonial seat at the royal complex of Muʻa on the shore of the Fanga ʻUta lagoon. The paramount title of Tuʻi Tonga was held within the ancient lineage, though by this period much of the practical political and administrative authority had already devolved to the junior Tuʻi Haʻa Takalaua line and its own delegated Tuʻi Kanokupolu title. The empire's earlier maritime reach across western Polynesia — into Samoa, ʻUvea, Futuna, and Niue — had contracted well before this date, leaving influence rather than firm control over distant islands. Society remained organised around the langi stone burial mounds of the sacred chiefs and a tributary network funnelling goods to the Tuʻi Tonga. No European contact had yet occurred, the first Dutch encounters — Schouten and Le Maire in 1616 — lying some fifteen years in the future."},"shan states":{"1600":"In 1600, the Shan states were a patchwork of Tai-speaking principalities (möng) spread across the highlands of what are now northern and eastern Myanmar and adjacent borderlands, each ruled by its own hereditary saopha (sawbwa) rather than by any single overlord. They had no common capital; power was dispersed among rival seats such as Hsipaw, Hsenwi, Mong Nai, Kengtung, and others. Following the collapse of the First Toungoo Empire's overextension after Bayinnaung's death in 1581, the region was highly unstable, with the Burmese realm fragmenting and Shan chiefs asserting autonomy or shifting allegiances. Ava and the northern polities were contested through the 1590s and early 1600s, and Nyaungyan Min was campaigning to reconsolidate Upper Burma and bring the nearer Shan möng back under Toungoo suzerainty. The principalities thus stood between reasserted Burmese pressure and their own persistent local autonomy."},"oromo":{"1600":"In 1600, the Oromo were expanding pastoralist and agro-pastoralist peoples organised under the Gadaa age-grade system rather than under any centralised state or single ruler. Their sixteenth-century population movements — traditionally reckoned from the 1520s onward — were near their height, pushing north and west out of the southern Ethiopian region into the highlands of the Christian Solomonic empire and the Muslim sultanates weakened by the earlier wars of Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi. Authority rested with the periodically elected Abbaa Gadaa and assemblies of each confederacy, so there was no capital and no dynasty. During this period the Ethiopian emperor Sarsa Dengel, and after his death in 1597 the contested successions leading toward Susenyos, repeatedly campaigned against advancing Oromo groups with limited lasting success. The various Oromo confederacies thus operated as autonomous, mobile political communities across a broad and shifting frontier."},"maori":{"1600":"In 1600, the Māori of Aotearoa (New Zealand) lived as numerous independent iwi and hapū — tribes and sub-tribes — with no overarching state, monarch, or capital. Political and economic life was organised around descent groups led by rangatira and, in matters of tapu and mana, by tohunga, with fortified pā serving as strongholds during frequent inter-group conflict. This period fell within the later phase of the archaeologically defined Classic Māori culture, after the extinction of the moa and the shift toward horticulture based on kūmara, fishing, and fowling supplemented by seasonal foraging. There had been no European contact; Abel Tasman's brief and hostile 1642 encounter still lay decades away, and sustained contact would not come until James Cook in 1769. Māori society therefore continued to develop entirely on its own terms across the North and South Islands."}};for(var k in A){T[k]=Object.assign(T[k]||{},A[k]);}})();
